{It’s all connected! I’ve searched for harmony in the course just as I search for harmony on the chessboard. You’ll learn some stuff in the first chapters that you’ll come to appreciate as you move further. I have chosen some particular systems in the Spanish opening and I’ll explore them in depth and show you my vision. Instead, a Lifetime Repertoire approach would mean answering all the questions and covering all the possibilities. A never-ending task to produce and study!} 1. e4 {I was a 1.e4 player from my childhood and I'm a 1.e4 player at heart, though I have occasionally played 1.d4 during my career as a top player.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {This is the starting position of the Spanish. We'll focus on some systems that are based on understanding rather than move-per-move knowledge.} a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 (4... d6 5. O-O {The Steinitz will also make its appearance, and I'll give you some guidelines about this move order and 5.c3 . It's up to you to see what fits you best.}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 {The starting position of the course. Let me introduce the two main stops in our journey.} Z0 ({•} 9... Nb8 {The Breyer is the section I'm proudest of.} 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 {White's thematic idea. The knight goes to g3 to protect the e4-pawn.} Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 {White is at a crossroads. I tried} 15. a4 {but didn't like it. My favorite system is 15.b3 , as I explain in the course. I have included four World-class level files on the Breyer with the best options for both sides. There, I show you my own preparation against this system, and some new discoveries made with the assistance of modern engines during the creation of this course. 15...Bg7 The main line. 16.d5 The logical follow-up, in pure Cemento Spirit! 16...Rc8 Always the most unpleasant move for me, but we'll also see 16...Nb6 stopping White's c4 and preparing to undermine the center. 17.Rb1 My good old friend! 17...c6 18.c4 White gets the desired structure. I have called 15...d5 16.Bg5 'the Wild Affair' and you'll understand why when you see the special file devoted to it. 16...h6 17.Bh4 g5 18.Nxg5 hxg5 19.Bxg5 So many legendary stories about these lines! • 9...Bb7 10.d4 Re8 11.Nbd2 Bf8 The Zaitsev Variation. I'll discuss different moves and how small details make all the difference, for example in the 12.a3 line. Or how Magnus Carlsen masters the position after 12.Bc2 from both sides of the board. After 12...g6 13.d5 Nb8 , with the knight on b8, the Zaitsev takes a Breyer flavor, whereas I see 12.a4 Na5 as a Zaitsev-Chigorin, as Black has adopted a Zaitsev setup, but the knight on a5 is in the Chigorin spirit. I strongly advise you to accompany the text with the videos. I have put my soul into the recordings and offered extra insights, stories connected to the games, the process behind my analysis, my feelings about the moves… I’m sure you will find the course extremely useful, not as an opening repertoire, but as a guide to chess strategy. Modern theory is in constant evolution, novelties come and go, but the fundamentals stay. Enjoy the journey, and let me know how you feel about the course. I want to hear from you!}) *

