1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas (move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 d6 {The Steinitz variation has recently again gained popularity. I believe the main reason is that it is perfectly suitable for online rapid/blitz events, but in my mind, in classical chess, it can only be used as a surprise weapon. In the days when this game was played at the top level, Shakhriyar Mamedyarov was the only player ready to use it on a regular basis. Using it as a regular weapon worked for some time, but I believe after the game I'll show you in this course, Shakh has lost interest in playing it. I have always looked at the Steinitz Variation as a dream come true from White`s perspective, not because it is any bad, but much more that it gives White a lot of freedom! Especially when comparing it with variations like the Marshall/Berlin, which drives the White players crazy. Facing the Steinitz variation is like pure pleasure.} 5. O-O Bd7 ({Inviting the complications with} 5... Bg4 {, discussed here. [/variation/37928673/#/5/b/0.0] As always, many move orders often lead to the same tabiya positions, but every move order also allows some special variation. It is our responsibility to make up our minds what we prefer and to make sure we know why!}) {Shakh's weapon, aiming to play the system position strategy! The other option is to go for the kamikaze approach with 5...Bg4, which forces White to know his stuff, but if he does, then I guess Black is risking a lot.} 6. d4 ({Knowing that the main reason why Shakhkriyar liked to play this line is that he enjoyed playing the tabiya position after the slow} 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 {, it was all the more logical that I am trying to force him out of his comfort zone!}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 b5 8. Nxc6 Bxc6 9. Bb3 Nf6 {Very important moment. White can only play for advantage with very precise play!} 10. c4 $1 {The key move, which we analyzed with my trainer and father-in-law, Arshak, immediately after my game with Mamedyarov from Wijk 2006! I was dreaming of getting a second chance, and after patiently waiting for 2 years, the time finally came. The point of the 10.c4 move order is that since the e4-pawn is not hanging, we use this little tactic to get more control in the center.} Be7 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Re1 {White has successfully achieved the first step. I have stabilized the center, and thanks to the c4, e4, Nc3, and Bb3 construction, I have an excellent grip on the center.} Re8 {The most logical move. The funny thing is that my opponent already had two games with this position against Shirov in 2007, which is why I felt that the odds of me getting it were very low. The good thing was that both of these games ended in a draw, so there was still hope that Shakh believed in this line.} 13. Bf4 {My preparation with Arshak was always based on this move. White is playing for maximum central control. We already have a space advantage; our primary aim should be not to give Black any counterplay.} Rb8 {Shakh's improvement is very logical: defending the b5-pawn and aiming for the strategically desired ...Nd7 and ...Bf6 regrouping.} 14. Qc2 $1 {I am very pleased with this move. The point is that our prep with Arshak was not really move-per-move based; it was more like we tried to understand the position. It is obvious that knowing the spirit of the position helped me make the right decisions over the board! One important factor is to keep the tension in the center and to be ready to meet the idea that Black is intending. A total restricting policy! Leko-Mamedyarov [/variation/37928673] is deeply analyzed in the Steinitz Chapter, [/course/229376/9] where I also explore some alternatives and nuances in the early moves.} *

