1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 {The start of the Classical Spanish. White has achieved perfect harmony. With the last move, 9.h3, we have made all the necessary preparatory moves. White is ready to play d2-d4, occupying the center without needing to worry about the annoying pin with ...Bc8-g4, which would put immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. From here on, we will be focusing on learning as many useful middlegame ideas/move orders in different variations as possible by studying my most instructive games related to this topic. This is one of my absolute favorite opening positions!} Z0 ({• For the Breyer System, introduced by} 9... Nb8 {, see here. [/variation/38016592] • For the Zaitsev System, introduced by}) (9... Bb7 {, see here. [/variation/38014149] • From the Breyer or the Zaitsev, Black can take the fight into Benoni structures. See here. [/variation/38013544] • The}) (9... Nd7 {System is explored here. [/variation/38014511] • For the Chigorin System, introduced by}) (9... Na5 {, see here. [/variation/38013665]}) *

