1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Nb8 {The Breyer variation. This opening variation is named after the legendary Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, one of the main pioneers of the Hypermodern chess Era. The Hypermodern school of chess had the completely fresh concept of not fighting for the center directly. Instead, it prioritized harmonious piece placement first (fianchettoing the bishops was a vital part of the concept) and only then challenged the opponent's center. This new approach has brought a lot of fresh wind (the spirit of the 1920s) into the world of chess, thus enriching the history of chess and the game itself. Unfortunately, he died very young, at the age of only 28, in 1921. This has been a terrible loss not only for Hungarian chess but also for the whole chess community. This variation is based on perfect harmony. Black first loses some time with his knight, but it will be beautifully regrouped to d7. Black is looking forward to challenging White´s center slowly after developing all the other pieces (...Bc8-b7, ...Rf8-e8, followed by ...Be7-f8-g7). It is known to promise a very big strategic battle with all pieces on the board. No surprise that it became one of the favorite opening variations of legendary World Champion Boris Spassky, and also Magnus Carlsen, on his way to the top, has always loved to play it. Often, top GMs refer to any thematic ...Nc6-b8 move in any 1.e4 e5 opening as the 'Breyer spirit'! In the course, I'll show you three instructive games where I faced the Breyer System and samples of very deep preparation against it so you can see how opening study works at the highest level.} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 {Now we see the main point of Black's play. Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.} 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} c5 {This is a tricky move order, but if we know the strategic idea behind it, we can very easily handle it. We'll see in my game vs. Panchanathan how Black's idea backfired like a boomerang because I knew my stuff!} 12. Bc2 $1 {Keeping the tension and not falling into Black's strategic trap with d4-d5. It is also common knowledge that if we have the center (like here with pawns e4-d4 vs. e5-d6), we should keep the tension as long as it is possible and usually only change the status quo if we gain other strategic benefits.} cxd4 13. cxd4 exd4 14. Nxd4 Bb7 {Black would be fine if he had one extra move with ...Re8 to be ready to follow with ...Be7-f8! The only little problem is that it is White to move, and in fact, White has the very strong response 15. a4! which refutes Black's concept!} 15. a4 $1 {Black actually faces concrete problems here. The d4-knight puts pressure on the b5pawn, and once it moves, that will enable White's other knight on d2 to join the party via the vulnerable c4-square. We can conclude that thanks to the timely a2-a4 move, suddenly both White's knights become very mobile! Panchanathan's position was quickly falling apart. You can see all the nuances in the model game Leko-Panchanathan [/variation/37823704/#/1/w], Isle of Man 2017.} *

