1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Nb8 {The Breyer variation. This opening variation is named after the legendary Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, one of the main pioneers of the Hypermodern chess Era. The Hypermodern school of chess had the completely fresh concept of not fighting for the center directly. Instead, it prioritized harmonious piece placement first (fianchettoing the bishops was a vital part of the concept) and only then challenged the opponent's center. This new approach has brought a lot of fresh wind (the spirit of the 1920s) into the world of chess, thus enriching the history of chess and the game itself. Unfortunately, he died very young, at the age of only 28, in 1921. This has been a terrible loss not only for Hungarian chess but also for the whole chess community. This variation is based on perfect harmony. Black first loses some time with his knight, but it will be beautifully regrouped to d7. Black is looking forward to challenging White´s center slowly after developing all the other pieces (...Bc8-b7, ...Rf8-e8, followed by ...Be7-f8-g7). It is known to promise a very big strategic battle with all pieces on the board. No surprise that it became one of the favorite opening variations of legendary World Champion Boris Spassky, and also Magnus Carlsen, on his way to the top, has always loved to play it. Often, top GMs refer to any thematic ...Nc6-b8 move in any 1.e4 e5 opening as the 'Breyer spirit'! In the course, I'll show you three instructive games where I faced the Breyer System and samples of very deep preparation against it so you can see how opening study works at the highest level.} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 {Now we see the main point of Black´s play. Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.} 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now the white bishop is not aiming at f7, it is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4 pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now, we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7 (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!). The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides in the main line} 15. a4 {, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my}) (15. b3 {System instead. That´s where my heart is!}) 15... d5 16. Bg5 $3 {The bomb! Brilliant prep by Team Judit Polgar for her match with Boris Spassky in 1993, This move, setting up a piece sacrifice, put ...d5 out of business for more than a decade!} h6 17. Bh4 {The point of White's play!} g5 {This move is in deep crisis. However, it will be our main topic in the 15. b3 d5 'Wild Affair' [/variation/38397300] section due to some amazing tactical lines! I was shocked to discover that, according to modern super engines, the so-called 'losing move' ( 17...dxe4!? is probably holding.} 18. Nxg5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 exd4 {Suddenly, young Mamedyarov tried to resurrect the line in 2006 against no one else than Judit! In fact, in a period of good two weeks, he beat Judit and drew with such attacking monsters like Shirov and Grischuk! It is incredible what stories chess history can write! For a very long time, computers could not refute this line by themselves! My trainer, Amador Rodriguez, made a real contribution to killing it!} 20. e5 $3 {The key move of White's piece sac. Now modern engines are giving all the critical lines in a fraction of a second for which we had to work like crazy...The concept is obvious: White sacrifices the e-pawn in order to make sure that Black's b7-bishop stays buried. We'll stop here at this introduction, but prep went really deep. In the course, I'll show you here [/variation/38397300] our 1999 solution and what modern engines have to say.} *

