ainst it so you can see how opening study works at the highest level.} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 {Now we see the main point of Black's play. Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.} 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now the white bishop is not aiming at f7, it is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4 pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now, we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7. (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!) The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides in the main line} 15. a4 {, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my}) (15. b3 {System instead. That´s where my heart is!}) 15... Bg7 ({The most natural move but, as we'll see, not the only one. Now, clearly Black is threatening to push ...d6-d5 next, if given the chance. The popular} 15... a5 {and the passive}) (15... c6 {are the subject of a small file on the sidelines [/variation/38442922] against 15. b3. Not critical, but White needs to know how to react.}) 16. d5 $1 {We will NOT allow Black to break the center anymore with ...d6-d5. By closing down the center, we are also fighting against the fianchettoed bishops! We are fighting the whole Hypermodern Chess spirit!} Qe7 $5 {A very interesting handling of this position. I believe it was Sasikiran's invention. The idea looks simple, but in fact it is the starting move of a very deep concept! First of all, Black protects the d6-pawn, so is ready to push ...c7-c6 immediately, without determining the position of the d7-knight. Then the next step is to play ...Rec8 followed by ...a6-a5. Obviously, White will push c3-c4, so Black hopes to trade both pawns with ...b5xc4 and ...c6xd5 and install the d7-knight on c5; if Black is then even given the time to achieve ...Ba6 as well, that would be the ultra dream! One more extra idea that Black has is to move the queen to f8, not really for defensive purposes, but much more is Black than aiming at a timely ...Bg7-h6 trade of the dark-squared bishops. Strategically a brilliant concept! The big question is how should White fight it!} 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rec8 {The key position! Something extraordinary happened here: a phone call changed everything! I'll tell you all about it and we'll study the finesses of the position in my model game vs. Nigel Short.} 19. Rc1 $3 {This super deep prophylactic move is just the beginning. See Leko-Short. [/variation/37806095]} *

