ainst it so you can see how opening study works at the highest level.} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 {Now we see the main point of Black's play. Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.} 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now the white bishop is not aiming at f7, it is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4 pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now, we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7. (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!) The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides in the main line} 15. a4 {, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my}) (15. b3 {System instead. That´s where my heart is!}) 15... Bg7 ({The most natural move but, as we'll see, not the only one. Now, clearly Black is threatening to push ...d6-d5 next, if given the chance. The popular} 15... a5 {and the passive}) (15... c6 {are the subject of a small file on the sidelines [/variation/38442922] against 15. b3. Not critical, but White needs to know how to react.}) 16. d5 $1 {We will NOT allow Black to break the center anymore with ...d6-d5. By closing down the center, we are also fighting against the fianchettoed bishops! We are fighting the whole Hypermodern Chess spirit!} Nb6 {By now a typical move in the Breyer variation, introduced by none other than the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky after having suffered enough in this variation in his match with Judit Polgar. Finally, for the last game, he came up with this idea which worked to perfection. Black wants to undermine White's center with ...c7-c6; if Black succeeds in forcing White to release the tension with dxc6, Black will achieve everything he dreams about with all his pieces coming to life!} 17. Rb1 $3 {This super important prophylactic was a game-changer! That is why the 16...Nb6 move lost its attraction. Due to the pin on the b7-bishop, White is able to stabilize the center and also gets out of any potential tricks on the long diagonal.} (17. Be3 Rc8 18. Qe2 c6 19. c4 cxd5 20. cxd5 Nbxd5 $3 21. exd5 Nxd5 {is Spassky's stunning positional piece sacrifice, which had an earth-shattering impact back in 1993!}) 17... c6 18. c4 $1 {This is now possible. Thanks to the previous little move, White is able to keep his powerful pawn chain intact and does not need to worry about the knight sac on d5. This also means that in the long term, the knight on b6 will really be misplaced...} Qc7 19. Bd3 {Now, White has beautifully stabilized the center and can slowly improve the position. See my model game [/variation/37803576/#/1/w] against Beliavsky in the Bled Olympiad 2002.} *

