1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Bb7 {The Zaitsev variation usually leads to a very complex battle. It is more complicated compared with the Breyer and requires much more concrete opening knowledge. It is not an opening variation that can be played on autopilot. It suits players who are ready to invest a lot of time in studying all kinds of long, complicated variations with many different structures. The ideas are easy to understand. Black first develops the bishop and follows it up with ...Re8.} 10. d4 Re8 {This is the real starting position of the Zaitsev variation. Black keeps the tension in the center and is planning to play ...Bf8 next. It is really fascinating that this opening variation only got developed in the 70`s, but by none other than Karpov's long time trainer Igor Zaitsev. We can speak about a very modern and ambitious opening variation. The absolute main idea of Black is to pressure the e4-pawn as quickly as possible and not to allow White to carry out the Nb1-d2-f1-g3 maneuver, which we see in so many other Classical Spanish variations. Obviously, it comes at the cost of weakening the f7-pawn early on, but it is easy to see that White is unable to exploit it.} 11. Nbd2 (11. Ng5 {is not really an attacking move, as Black can parry the threat easily with ...Rf8. It is often used as a famous Zaitsev draw (one of the big drawbacks if we consider using it as a fighting weapon facing weaker opposition!), but repeating just once is a common strategy by players who are known to be getting into time-trouble, myself included...} Rf8 12. Nf3 {White has nothing better than to retreat.} Re8 13. Nbd2 {Now, we continue.}) 11... Bf8 12. Bc2 ({The start of the Zaitsev tabiya. White has a very big choice here. Here, we can already better see the problem White is faced with. The knight can`t move to f1 due to ...exd4, and the e4-pawn will fall. That is why the absolute main moves are} 12. a4 {,}) (12. a3 {, and}) (12. d5 {, apart from}) (12. Bc2 {.}) {White´s main idea is to push d4-d5 and be ready to cement the pawn structure with b2-b3 followed by c3-c4.} 12... g6 {This is usually the main move. This position is discussed in the Firouzja-Carlsen [/variation/37952165/#/1/w], Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914/#/1/w] and Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252/#/1/w] games.} 13. d5 {Sticking to the plan started with Bb3-c2. White blocks the center now that he is ready to protect it with the already mentioned b2-b3, c3-c4 moves.} Ne7 14. c4 ({See Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914/#/1/w], Dresden 2008.} 14. Nf1 $5 {was Carlsen-Navara, [/variation/38038252] played 5-6 days after our game. Magnus had to be well aware of it.}) *

