1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 {We will take a look at a few examples where, from a Breyer or Zaitsev, Black decides to take the fight towards Spanish/Benoni structures.} Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 exd4 {Around 2015 this artificiallly looking double-edged option started to get popular thanks to efforts by such greats as Peter Svidler and Bu Xiangzhi. For a while, Black was getting the desired results, but then came the following game (pearl) from Sasha Grischuk!} 12. cxd4 Nd7 {This is Black's idea. Black gives up the center but hopes to achieve good counterplay in the resulting Benoni structure. The plan is to play ...Na5, ...Bf6, followed by ...c5 and play on the dark squares. Once again, the real problem is the b7-bishop!} 13. Nf1 Na5 14. Bc2 Bf6 {White has tons of different move orders, it is very easy to get lost in them!} 15. Ng3 {I give the exclamation mark because of the deep concept that Grischuk had in mind by playing this knight move right away! The first reaction could easily be like, why do we force or provoke g6, which seems to be very useful for Black? The next question is: Why do we want our knight on g3? All will be answered in the Grischuk-Alekseenko [/variation/37956740] game.} *

