1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} ({•} 3... Nf6 {The Berlin is not the topic of this course but, as we'll see, it can lead to Classical Spanish structures.} 4. d3 d6 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now we reached a typical main line of the Classical Spanish 6.d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves.} b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12.Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go, but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 {This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas(move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! We've landed on the Zaitsev. [/variation/38014149/#/12/b]}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 ({For the Steinitz variation} 4... d6 {, see here [/variation/38014575].}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 ({•} 6. d3 d6 {This Spanish can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Nd7 {At first, this is a rather strange-looking move as Black moves a developed piece once again, but it is, in fact, an important variation. Very important not to dismiss or underestimate such lines! The most important thing is to understand what Black wants to achieve and act accordingly. Black's main idea is pretty obvious: to place the knight on b6, and the e7 bishop will go to f6. However, even this should be divided into two different chapters because Black has two different setups. Important to highlight that this variation entered the world stage in the 1940`s when Smyslov started to play it. Quickly, many great stars followed the trend. The list is enormous: Najdorf, Ragozin, Lilienthal, Tolush, and later even Botvinnik, Tal, Petrosian, Keres, and Bronstein have tried it out. Showing that, in general, it is a fascinating regrouping that caught the attention of all the top stars of that Era.} 10. d4 {White occupies the centre and waits for Black to show his cards.} Nb6 ({This is the line that was developed later at the end of 1950´s. The original intention was} 10... Bf6 {.}) 11. Nbd2 Bf6 12. Nf1 {White was in time to transfer the knight to f1 in time! This is very important because like this White can handle the pressure on the d4-pawn without problems.} Re8 {This old forgotten line was prepared by Fressinet together with the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky, especially for Cannes 2002! In the very first game, when Fressinet used this line, it yielded him a surprisingly easy draw vs Topalov! Only now, when preparing the material for my first ever Chessable course, did I notice that this move was favored by none other than Efim Geller in the 1960s, the most famous theoretician among the Soviet elite players.} 13. Bc2 $5 {In my quick prep before the game, I was attracted to this move as I considered it the most flexible. I never, in my wildest dreams, expected Fressinet to repeat this line, but just in case, I wanted to be ready. See Leko-Fressinet. [/variation/37959965]} *

