11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Nd7 {At first, this is a rather strange-looking move as Black moves a developed piece once again, but it is, in fact, an important variation. Very important not to dismiss or underestimate such lines! The most important thing is to understand what Black wants to achieve and act accordingly. Black's main idea is pretty obvious: to place the knight on b6, and the e7-bishop will go to f6. However, even this should be divided into two different chapters because Black has two different setups. Important to highlight that this variation entered the world stage in the 1940s when Smyslov started to play it. Quickly, many great stars followed the trend. The list is enormous: Najdorf, Ragozin, Lilienthal, Tolush, and later even Botvinnik, Tal, Petrosian, Keres, and Bronstein have tried it out. Showing that, in general, it is a fascinating regrouping that caught the attention of all the top stars of that Era.} 10. d4 {White occupies the centre and waits for Black to show his cards.} Bf6 {The official main line of the 9...Nd7 variation. Black immediately puts pressure on the d4-pawn hindering the typical Nbd2 development, but in this case, White has time to do something else...} 11. a4 $1 {White immediately goes after the vulnerable Black queenside and uses that black had no time to place the knight on b6 yet! See the model game Leko-Pinter. [/variation/37984007]} *

