11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {and again, we've landed in the Zaitsev [/variation/38014149/#/12/b].}) 6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the Classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. That's the benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6.d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!) 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O 9. h3 Na5 {The Chigorin variation has been developed immediately at the very beginning of the 20th century. Probably, the temptation of moving the knight with a tempo, allowing pushing the c-pawn forward to c5, thus enabling Black to protect the vulnerable e5-pawn with ...Qc7, was the reason why it became so popular. Right now, it is considered that it is a possibility, but it is one of those opening variations that White enjoys playing. The point is that there is no pressure on White, and by knowing the natural moves/opening ideas, White will always get a nice playable position. Of course, as with every opening variation also, here there are some important basic ideas we have to know.} 10. Bc2 c5 {Black follows his strategy.} 11. d4 {White occupies the centre.} Qc7 {Keeping the tension is considered the most reliable line for Black.} 12. Nbd2 ({The move that I have been using all my life. With fresh eyes,} 12. d5 $5 {is very sympathetic for White! Especially when we consider that the direction that happened in the MVL-Caruana St. Louis blitz 2023 game stands pretty well for Black.}) 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Nc6 {By now, I believe that this is Black's most reliable line in the Chigorin. Luckily, before this game. Black immediately puts pressure on the d4-pawn.} 14. Nb3 {The absolute main line. We'll see all the details in Leko-Adams, [/variation/38117838] Tilburg 1998.} *

