1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1.e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} 4. Ba4 d6 5. O-O {Inviting the complications with 5...Bg4. As always, many move orders often lead to the same tabiya positions, but every move order also allows some special variation. It is our responsibility to make up our minds what we prefer and to make sure we know why!} (5. c3 Bd7 {If Black wants to play a typical system position, then this is the logical choice.} 6. O-O g6 7. d4 Bg7 {Is also one of the ways to reach this tabiya position. Just like as if after 5.O-O Bd7, White would play 6.c3 instead of 6.d4, which I played in my game!}) ({The extra possibility for Black in this move order is} 5. c3 f5 $5 6. exf5 Bxf5 7. O-O Bd3 8. Re1 Be7 {This line has a lot of modern theory. In my time, when I played this line with White in the middle of the 90s, things were much more simpler...} 9. Bc2 Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Nf6 11. d4 {and now after} e4 12. Ng5 d5 13. f3 $1 {This pawn break is key!} h6 14. Nh3 O-O 15. Nd2 $1 exf3 16. Nxf3 {This was considered to be pleasant for White and I managed to win a model game vs legendary Arthur Jussupow in this line.} Qd7 17. Qg6 {and now} Qe8 $1 {is the recent way to hold! After 17...Qg4 18.Qxg4 Nxg4 19.Nf4 Rfd8 20.Ne6 Rd7 21.Bf4 Rc8 22.Re2 b6 23.Rae1 I had a nice advantage in the game [/variation/38709571] Leko-Jussupow, Vienna 1996.�}) *

