6... h5 $1 {This piece sacrifice is the idea. What's White's correct reaction?} 7. d4 $1 {White immediately starts action in the center to get ready to capture the bishop on g4 at the right moment.} (7. hxg4 $2 {would be a horrible mistake inviting trouble on the h-file...} hxg4 8. Ne1 $2 Qh4 {just mates.}) 7... b5 (7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 exd4 {Grabbing the pawn like this is certainly not in the spirit of Black`s play.} 9. c3 {White plays simple chess with fantastic compensation.}) 8. Bb3 Nxd4 {The only idea; otherwise, nothing makes sense.} 9. hxg4 $1 {Now is the time to take the piece.} hxg4 10. Ng5 $1 {The key move and the point behind 7.d4 opening up the c1-h6 diagonal for the bishop. I have never believed in this line for Black after taking my time to study it at the end of the 90s.} Z0 (10... Nh6 {Only move. This is where crazy things start to happen. One fresh example can be used as a good starting point for further study.} 11. Bd5 $1 c6 12. c3 $1 {Very direct way of confronting Black`s variation.} cxd5 13. cxd4 Be7 14. Qd2 $3 {This is one of those moves that needs to be part of White`s preparation.} dxe4 15. Nc3 Nf5 16. Ngxe4 {and now} Bf8 $1 {is the critical move when Black is fighting for his life, and maybe he succeeds, maybe not... 16...Nxd4 17.Ng3! f5 18.Qd3 O-O 19.Nd5 and White went on to win easily in the Cheparinov -Kovalev, Sharjah 2023 game.}) *

