13... Nf6 {How to continue with White?} 14. Re1 $1 {This was my main attempt before the game.} ({Svidler played the less critical} 14. e5 dxe5 15. Qxe5+ Qe7 16. Qc3 b4 17. Qf3 Rb8 18. Bf4 Bg7 19. Nd2 O-O 20. Bxc7 Rbe8 {and Black had no problems in the game Svidler -Van Foreest, Malmo 2023.}) 14... Bg7 15. e5 dxe5 16. Rxe5+ $1 {This was my key idea, and it is still a novelty! What is going on? The theory is supposed to be developing...} ({It is more natural to play} 16. Qxe5+ {but here, Black has a great trick, as we'll see in the next exercise.}) 16... Be6 17. Qc6+ (17. Qc6+ Kf8 {Here, White has many tempting options playing for long-term compensation.} 18. Rxe6 $5 {The positional exchange sac was my favorite!} fxe6 19. Nc3 {and let's see how Black should defend.}) *

