9... Nf6 {Very important moment. White can only play for advantage with very precise play!} 10. c4 $1 {Key move, which we analyzed with Arshak immediately after my game with Mamedyarov from Wijk 2006! I was dreaming of getting a second chance, and after patiently waiting for 2 years, the time finally came. The point of the 10.c4 move order is that since the e4-pawn is not hanging we use this little tactic to get more control in the center.} ({In my earlier game I played the routine} 10. Nc3 {but after} Be7 11. Re1 O-O {Black has no real worries Leko-Mamedyarov Wijk aan Zee 2006 and later it also happened in MVL-Mamedyarov game.}) ({Ivanchuk has once tried} 10. f3 {in an old game against the German legend Dr. Robert Hübner.} Be7 11. c4 {here Black missed the chance to play} bxc4 12. Bxc4 d5 $1 {and Black equalizes after successfully breaking the center.}) 10... Be7 (10... Nxe4 $2 {loses to many things, the simplest being} 11. Re1 Be7 12. Qf3 {winning material.}) 11. Nc3 O-O ({The e4 pawn is still taboo.} 11... Nxe4 $2 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Qd4 {with a double attack and the Black king will have nowhere to go after Qxg7 happens.}) 12. Re1 {White has successfully achieved the first step. I have stabilized the center, and thanks to the c4, e4, Nc3, and Bb3 construction, I have an excellent grip on the center.} Re8 {The most logical move. The funny thing is that my opponent already had two games for this position against Shirov in 2007, which is why I felt that the odds of me getting it were very low. The good thing was that both of these games ended in a draw, so there was still hope that Shakh believed in this line.} ({Later Black has also tried to improve by going} 12... Nd7 $5 13. Be3 Bf6 14. Qc2 $5 {An interesting idea by Svidler.} Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxe4 16. Rac1 {and Black quickly collapsed in the Svidler-Stevic 2015 game, but for example, modern engines only give a small edge to White.}) 13. Bf4 $1 {Our preparation with Arshak was always based on this move. White is playing for maximum central control. We already have space advantage; our primary aim should be not to give Black any counterplay.} (13. Qf3 b4 $1 14. Nd5 a5 15. a4 Nd7 16. Be3 Bf6 $1 {Black got everything he could hope for with sufficient counterplay in Shirov-Mamedyarov Tal Memorial 2007}) 13... Rb8 {Shakh's improvement is very logical. Defending the b5 pawn and aiming for the strategically desired Nd7, Bf6 regrouping.} ({In their second game in Tal blitz 2007 right after the classical tournament, Black played} 13... Nd7 $6 {but after} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Qh5 $1 {Black faced instant problems.}) ({If} 13... Bf8 {White can play} 14. Qf3 {because now the bishop is already committed to f8 (there is no more ...Nd7 + ...Bf6 plan). 14.Bg5!? is also possible.}) 14. Qc2 $1 {I am very pleased with this move. The point is that our prep with Arshak was not really move-per-move based; it was more like we tried to understand the position. It is obvious that knowing the spirit of the position helped me make the right decisions over the board! One important factor is to keep the tension in the center and to be ready to meet the idea that Black is intending. A totally restricting policy!} *

