15... Nd7 {The move in the spirit. The knight is heading towards the c5-square. How do we play now?} 16. Be3 $1 {Yes, we follow the restricting strategy! Important not to allow Black anything which could give him good mood!} ({There was a forced possibility with} 16. Ba4 {Seemingly great to trade our 'bad bishop,' but this gives Black chances to calculate lines, which leads to move-per-move play. Since we have the control and the upper hand, we only go for force lines if we are really profiting!} Bxa4 17. Qxa4 Bf6 $1 {( 17...Nc5 18.Qc6 Nd3 is also possible.)} 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $1 {This gives Black excellent drawing chances.} 19. Qxd7 Qxf4 {and if} 20. Qxc7 Rbc8 21. Qd7 Red8 {the attack on the c4-pawn forces a repetition:} 22. Qe7 Re8 {or 20.b3! 20...Rxe4 21.g3! when White keeps some pressure, but Black should hold. 21...Qe5 22.Rxe4 Qxa1+ 23.Kg2 Rf8 24.Qxc7 Qxa2 is too drawish.}) 16... Bf8 17. f3 $1 {Again just following the standard plan. The keyword is: 'Stability'!} ({There was a tempting option of opening a front on the queenside with} 17. a3 {but after} bxa3 18. Rxa3 Nc5 $1 {Black is ready to sacrifice the weak a6-pawn in order to change the character of the position.} 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. Rxa6 Re6 $1 {and suddenly Black's pieces have purpose!} 21. Ra3 Bd6 $1 {Black jumps out!} 22. f4 g5 $1 {immediately challenging White's central pawns.} 23. e5 gxf4 $1 {with total chaos!}) 17... Nc5 {This can be met energetically.} (17... Ba8 $6 {The start of an unfortunate plan, but the suffocative strategy has clearly had an effect on my opponent. And humanly, how long can we tolerate the monster knight on d5?}) ({Maybe doing nothing with} 17... a5 18. Rad1 Qc8 {was best, but we all know how difficult it is to do nothing when we feel under pressure!} 19. Bd4 {White is simply better.}) 18. Bxc5 $1 {With the intention to react quickly.} dxc5 19. f4 $1 {Covering the dark squares is also very sad for Black!} *

