1. e4 {This has always been my main move.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {Around the age of 12, I learned the Spanish Opening from the White side. The chance of getting a complex fight with all the pieces on the board with a lot of maneuvering has fascinated me right from the start. It has also been said by everybody that as a 1. e4 player, if you want to learn to play real chess, then you have to master the Ruy Lopez to perfection! When starting out, it might look scary that Black has so many systems, but step by step, one can get easily familiar with all the opening lines. The variations are mostly based on move orders and understanding the arising middlegame positions. This helps to start, and later, we can always deepen our knowledge by studying concrete move-per-move lines in real depth or simply looking at instructive games.} a6 {When I learned the Spanish, luckily the Berlin defense was not yet established as a blocker!} 4. Ba4 d6 {The Steinitz variation has recently again gained popularity. I believe the main reason is that it is perfectly suitable for online rapid/blitz events, but in my mind, in classical chess, it can only be used as a surprise weapon. In the days when this game was played at the top level, Mamedyarov was the only player ready to use it on a regular basis. Using it as a regular weapon worked for some time, but I believe after this game, Shakh has lost interest in playing it. I have always looked at the Steinitz Variation as a dream come true from White`s perspective, not because it is any bad, but much more that it gives White a lot of freedom! Especially when comparing it with variations like the Marshall/Berlin, which drives the White players crazy. Facing the Steinitz variation is like pure pleasure.} 5. O-O {Inviting the complications with 5...Bg4. As always, many move orders often lead to the same tabiya positions, but every move order also allows some special variation. It is our responsibility to make up our minds what we prefer and to make sure we know why!} (5. c3 Bd7 {If Black wants to play a typical system position, then this is the logical choice.} 6. O-O g6 7. d4 Bg7 {Is also one of the ways to reach this tabiya position. Just like as if after 5. O-O Bd7, White would play 6. c3 instead of 6. d4, which I played in my game!}) ({The extra possibility for Black in this move order is} 5. c3 f5 $5 6. exf5 Bxf5 7. O-O Bd3 8. Re1 Be7 {This line has a lot of modern theory. In my time when I played this line with White in the middle of the 90´s things were much more simpler...} 9. Bc2 Bxc2 10. Qxc2 Nf6 11. d4 {and now after} e4 12. Ng5 d5 13. f3 $1 {This pawn break is key!} h6 14. Nh3 O-O 15. Nd2 $1 exf3 16. Nxf3 {Was considered to be pleasant for White and I have managed to win a model game vs legendary Arthur Jussupow in this line.} Qd7 17. Qg6 Qg4 {17...Qe8! is the recent way to hold!} 18. Qxg4 Nxg4 19. Nf4 Rfd8 20. Ne6 Rd7 21. Bf4 Rc8 22. Re2 b6 23. Rae1 {with a nice advantage in the game [/variation/38709571] Leko-Jussupow, Vienna 1996.�}) 5... Bd7 {My opponent sticks to his weapon, aiming to play the system position strategy!} ({The other option is to go for the kamikaze approach with} 5... Bg4 {which forces White to know his stuff, but if he does then I guess Black is risking a lot...} 6. h3 h5 $1 {This piece sacrifice is the idea. Now} 7. hxg4 $2 {would be a horrible mistake inviting trouble on the h-file...} hxg4 8. Ne1 $2 Qh4 {just mates. 7.d4! White immediately starts action in the center to get ready to capture the bishop on g4 at the right moment. A) 7...Bxf3 Grabbing the pawn like this is certainly not in the spirit of Black`s play. 8.Qxf3 exd4 ( 8...b5? 9.Bb3 Nxd4? would be too naive... 10.Qxf7# ) 9.c3 White plays simple chess with fantastic compensation. 9...dxc3? Black is way underdeveloped here. 10.Nxc3 Nf6 11.e5 dxe5 12.Bxc6+ bxc6 13.Qxc6+ Nd7 White has many winning moves here due to the pin and the lead in development. 14.Rd1 or 14.Bg5 . If 9...Qf6 10.Qd1 Tranquilo! The problems remain for Black... 10...b5 11.Bb3 Nge7 12.a4 $16 with big problems coming... B) 7...b5 8.Bb3 Nxd4 The only idea; otherwise, nothing makes sense. 9.hxg4! Now is the time to take the piece. 9...hxg4 10.Ng5! The key move and the point behind 7. d4 opening up the c1-h6 diagonal for the bishop. I have never believed in this line for Black after taking my time to study it at the end of the 90s. Before, I was simply happy with my 5. c3 choice and thought it to be unnecessary to deal with this crazy line for no reason! However, when things really started developing in the 5. c3 line, and it turned out not to be so easy at all to get an advantage against a well-prepared opponent, then I knew that the time had come to check out what was going on with the 5. O-O move order. Now, the only move is 10...Nh6 and this is where crazy things start to happen. One fresh example can be used as a good starting point for further study. 11.Bd5! c6 12.c3! Very direct way of confronting Black`s variation. 12...cxd5 13.cxd4 Be7 14.Qd2!! This is one of those moves that needs to be part of White`s preparation. 14...dxe4 15.Nc3 Nf5 16.Ngxe4 Nxd4 16...Bf8! Is the critical move when Black is fighting for his life and maybe he succeeds, maybe not... 17.Ng3! f5 18.Qd3 O-O ( 18...f4 19.Qg6 ) 19.Nd5 and White went on to win easily in the Cheparinov-Kovalev Sharjah 2023 game. [/variation/38709572]�}) 6. d4 $5 ({Now I am the one using the extra possibility thanks to the 5.O-O move order! Knowing that the main reason why Shakhkriyar likes to play this line is that he enjoys playing the tabiya position after the slow} 6. c3 g6 7. d4 Bg7 {it is all the more logical that I am trying to force him out of his comfort zone!}) ({The traditional move} 6. c3 {leads to the already mentioned tabiya position} g6 7. d4 Bg7 8. Re1 Nf6 9. h3 O-O {when} 10. Nbd2 exd4 11. cxd4 Nb4 $1 {is one of the ideas and 10.Bc2!? Re8 can be considered a modern starting position of this line with a lot of high-level games. It is a rich position worth studying with both colors.}) 6... exd4 {My opponent has exclusively used this move, and it was clearly the main field of preparation when facing Shakh those days.} ({Last year there was a high-level theoretical duel in this line which went} 6... b5 $5 7. Bb3 Nxd4 8. Nxd4 exd4 {Now we reach a typical tricky position, which amused me as a kid when I first learned that Black can eventually trap White's bishop if White is not careful.} 9. c3 $1 {This pawn sacrifice is the point of White's play. Black is not yet developed, so he needs to be very well-prepared if willing to enter this line. 9.Qxd4? c5 The motif we all learn as kids. 10.Qd5 c4 and White can resign.} dxc3 {Now White has two options. Both are dangerous for Black, but objectively, none of them is a killer. In any case, I felt that I was ready to test my opponent and would have made up my mind over the board between the following possibilities: A)} 10. Qh5 {The main challenge} g6 11. Qd5 Be6 12. Qc6+ Bd7 13. Qxc3 Nf6 14. Re1 $1 {This was my main attempt before the game. (In the mentioned recent game, Svidler played the less critical 14.e5 dxe5 15.Qxe5+ Qe7 16.Qc3 b4 17.Qf3 Rb8 18.Bf4 Bg7 19.Nd2 O-O 20.Bxc7 Rbe8= and Black had no problems in the game [/variation/38709573] Svidler -Van Foreest, Malmo 2023. �)} Bg7 15. e5 dxe5 16. Rxe5+ $1 {This was my key idea, and it is still a novelty! What is going on? The theory is supposed to be developing... It is more natural to play 16.Qxe5+ but here, Black has a great trick! What is that trick? 16...Be6! 17.Bxe6 O-O!! Yes, this is a cold shower! 18.Bb3 Re8 19.Qc3 Ng4! and suddenly White has to fight for his life to survive.} Be6 17. Qc6+ Kf8 {Here, White has many tempting options playing for long-term compensation. A1)} 18. Rxe6 $5 {The positional exchange sac was my favorite!} fxe6 19. Nc3 {How should Black defend?} Qe8 $1 {Key defensive move!} 20. Qf3 {I stopped here and thought that if Black is ready to play like this, I am up for the challenge! White has beautiful compensation for the exchange. How to defend like an engine here with Black?} h6 $3 {Engines are cold-blooded! It is the only move; otherwise, Black loses.} 21. Bf4 Kg8 22. Re1 Kh7 {There are some spectacular lines here, but Black holds in all of them!} 23. Bxh6 $5 Bxh6 24. Rxe6 {What to play now with Black?} Rf8 $3 25. Rxe8 Raxe8 {Suddenly, Black gets serious counterplay! Or 23.Rxe6 Qd7 24.Bxh6 Rae8! 25.Be3 Rxe6 26.Qh3+ Nh5 27.Bxe6 Qd3 28.g4 Bxc3! Getting access to the ...Qe4 check idea! 29.gxh5 Qb1+ 30.Kg2 Qe4+ probably ends with perpetual check. A2) 18.Nc3 Bxb3 19.axb3 b4! Thanks to this move, Black can force things! Both 20.Qc5+ Qd6 and 20.Nd5 Nxd5 21.Rxd5 Qe8! should hold! A3) 18.Bd2 The engine's other move, but I was never impressed... 18...Bxb3 19.axb3 Kg8 20.Rxa6 ( 20.Rxb5 h6! Black gets out) 20...Rxa6 21.Qxa6 h5 22.Qxb5 Kh7= $13 Suddenly, Black is too active! B) 10.Nxc3 Nf6 11.Qe2!? I was surprised to see that this is still a novelty even today! (White would love to play 11.f4 immediately, but here Black has the clever 11...Be6! which is just unclear. ) 11...Be7 12.f4 O-O 13.e5 Ne8 14.Be3 I am not famous for sacrificing pawns, but this is looking very dangerous for Black. Instead, 12...Be6 13.Bxe6 fxe6 14.e5 dxe5 15.fxe5 Nd5 16.Ne4 maybe holdable, but also scary. 10.Qd5 Be6 11.Qc6+ Bd7 12.Qxc3 Nf6 13.Re1 Be7 14.e5 dxe5 15.Qxe5 Be6 16.Bxe6 fxe6 17.Qxe6 Qd7 is safe for Black.}) 7. Nxd4 ({Modern engines also suggest} 7. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 8. Qxd4 {but I have always difficulty giving up my light squared bishop just like this... Black can play} f6 {intending ...Ne7-...Ng6 or 8...Ne7 and Black's central pawns control important squares.}) 7... b5 {The dynamic possibility. Everything else from my opponent would have been a huge surprise.} ({The reason why modern engines suggest 7.Bxc6 is that they are not sure how much advantage White has after} 7... Nxd4 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd4 Nf6 {However, humanly, it is enough to look at the position, and we already see that it is so much more fun to be White here. Since it is very passive, it is certainly not Mamedyarov's style!} 10. Nc3 Be7 11. Rd1 $5 {or 11.b3 O-O 12.Bb2 c6 $14 Sad move, but Black needs to stop Nc3-d5 at all cost. It is not as bad as it looks, but clearly White enjoys squeezing positions like this.}) 8. Nxc6 ({This is the point!} 8. Bb3 $2 {With this move White would fall into the children trap!} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 c5 10. Qd5 c4 {.}) 8... Bxc6 9. Bb3 Nf6 {Very important moment. White can only play for advantage with very precise play!} 10. c4 $1 {Key move, which we analyzed with Arshak immediately after my game with Mamedyarov from Wijk 2006! I was dreaming of getting a second chance, and after patiently waiting for 2 years, the time has finally come. The point of the 10.c4 move order is that since the e4 pawn is not hanging we use this little tactic to get more control in the center.} ({In my earlier game, I played the routine} 10. Nc3 {but after} Be7 11. Re1 O-O {Black had no real worries in the game [/variation/38709574] Leko-Mamedyarov, Wijk aan Zee 2006�, and later it also happened in the MVL-Mamedyarov game. [/variation/38709575]� Note that 10...Nxe4 loses to 11.Nxe4 Bxe4 12.Re1 and f3.}) ({Ivanchuk has once tried} 10. f3 {in an old game [/variation/38709576] vs. German legend Dr. Robert Hübner.�} Be7 11. c4 {here Black missed the chance to play} bxc4 12. Bxc4 d5 $1 {and Black equalizes after successfully breaking the center.} 13. exd5 {and both} Nxd5 {and 13...Bxd5 are okay.}) 10... Be7 (10... Nxe4 $2 {loses to many things, the simplest being} 11. Re1 Be7 12. Qf3 {winning material.} O-O 13. Rxe4 Bxe4 {( 13...f5? 14.cxb5+ and White captures the bishop thanks to the discovered check.)} 14. Qxe4 Re8 15. Qc2 Bf6 16. Bd2 {is enough to solve the back-rank issues.}) 11. Nc3 O-O ({The e4 pawn is still taboo:} 11... Nxe4 $2 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Qd4 {with double attack and the black king will have nowhere to go after Qxg7 happens.}) 12. Re1 {White has successfully achieved the first step. I have stabilized the center, and thanks to the c4, e4, Nc3, and Bb3 construction, I have an excellent grip on the center.} Re8 {The most logical move. The funny thing is that my opponent already had two games for this position against Shirov in 2007, which is why I felt that the odds of me getting it were very low. The good thing was that both of these games ended in a draw, so there was still hope that Shakh believed in this line.} ({Later Black has also tried to improve by going} 12... Nd7 $5 13. Be3 Bf6 14. Qc2 $5 {Interesting idea by Svidler} Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Bxe4 16. Rac1 {and Black quickly collapsed in the Svidler-Stevic 2015 game, [/variation/38709577]� but for example, modern engines only give a small edge to White.}) 13. Bf4 $1 {Our preparation with Arshak was always based on this move. White is playing for maximum central control. We already have space advantage; our primary aim should be not to give Black any counterplay.} (13. Qf3 b4 $1 14. Nd5 a5 15. a4 Nd7 16. Be3 Bf6 $1 {Black got everything he could hope for with sufficient counterplay in the game [/variation/38709578] Shirov-Mamedyarov, Tal Memorial 2007.�}) 13... Rb8 {Shakh's improvement is very logical. Defending the b5 pawn and aiming for the strategically desired ...Nd7, ...Bf6 regrouping.} ({In their second game [/variation/38709579]� in Moscow, Wch blitz 2007, right after the Tal Memorial classical tournament, Black played} 13... Nd7 $6 {but after} 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Qh5 $1 {Black faced instant problems.}) ({If} 13... Bf8 {, White can play} 14. Qf3 {because now the bishop is already committed to f8 (there is no more ...Nd7, ...Bf6 plan). 14.Bg5!? is also possible.}) 14. Qc2 $1 {I am very pleased with this move. The point is that our prep with Arshak was not really move-per-move based; it was more like we tried to understand the position. It is obvious that knowing the spirit of the position helped me make the right decisions over the board! One important factor is to keep the tension in the center and to be ready to meet the idea that Black is intending. A total restricting policy!} b4 ({Not a happy choice, and clearly, this move was played out of desperation. The problem of Shakhriyar was that he very well understood that after the natural} 14... Nd7 {I had planned the very annoying} 15. cxb5 $1 {My spirit was to keep the tension until I could make concrete benefits; now the time is here.} axb5 {and now comes the point} 16. Bd5 $1 {which puts a lot of direct pressure on Black. The more automatic 16.Nd5 would allow 16...Nc5! which is OK for Black.} Bb7 $5 {is possible, while 16...Bxd5 17.Nxd5 looks horrible. 17...Nc5 protecting c7. 18.Rad1 Ne6 19.Bg3 followed by f4 and e5.}) (14... Bf8 {can be met by} 15. Rad1 {or the stronger 15.Bg5! Be7 16.Rad1 Nd7 17.Be3 and Black has similar problems. Or 17.cxb5 axb5 18.Bd5!? , a lovely extra tactical possibility! 18...Bb7!= but 18...Bxd5 runs into 19.Bxe7 .}) 15. Nd5 Nd7 {The move in the spirit. The knight is heading towards the c5-square.} (15... Nxd5 $5 {Surprisingly, the engine says that this is not so bad, but humanly, this is absolutely 'No go territory'!} 16. cxd5 Bb5 {one really needs to be an engine not to care about how ugly this looks, but with ...Bf6 coming, Black has chances to compensate for the bad structure...} 17. Rac1 Bf6 {when c7 is targeted but so is b2.} 18. h3 $1 {First White should create 'luft' before deciding what to do next. Instead, 18.Qd2 a5 19.Bc4 g5!! Wow, this is clearly computer chess... 20.Bg3 a4!! $132 with the idea of ...a3. Luckily, I played Mamedyarov and not an engine...}) 16. Be3 $1 {Yes, we follow the restricting strategy! Important not to allow Black anything which could give him good mood!} ({There was a forced possibility with} 16. Ba4 {Seemingly great to trade our 'bad bishop,' but this gives Black chances to calculate lines, which leads to move-per-move play. Since we have the control and the upper hand, we only go for force lines if we are really profiting!} Bxa4 17. Qxa4 Bf6 $1 {( 17...Nc5 18.Qc6 Nd3 is also possible.)} 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $1 {This gives Black excellent drawing chances.} 19. Qxd7 Qxf4 {and if} 20. Qxc7 Rbc8 21. Qd7 Red8 {the attack on the c4-pawn forces a repetition:} 22. Qe7 Re8 {or 20.b3! 20...Rxe4 21.g3! when White keeps some pressure, but Black should hold. 21...Qe5 22.Rxe4 Qxa1+ 23.Kg2 Rf8 24.Qxc7 Qxa2 is too drawish.}) 16... Bf8 17. f3 $1 {Again just following the standard plan. The keyword is: 'Stability'!} ({There was a tempting option opening a front on the queenside with} 17. a3 {but after} bxa3 18. Rxa3 Nc5 $1 {Black is ready to sacrifice the weak a6-pawn in order to change the character of the position.} 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. Rxa6 {(Important to highlight that the same strategy does not work now! 20.f4? Bxd5! 21.cxd5 c4! and Black wins material!)} Re6 $1 {and suddenly Black's pieces have purpose!} 21. Ra3 Bd6 $1 {Black jumps out!} 22. f4 g5 $1 {immediately challenging White's central pawns} 23. e5 gxf4 $1 {with total chaos!} 24. Qc3 Qh4 $132 {24.Nf6+? is bad due to different reasons 24...Rxf6 25.exf6 Qxf6 $17 or 24...Qxf6!? 25.exf6 Rxe1+ 26.Kf2 Re6! ( 26...Rbe8 27.Ba4! Walking back to the hotel from the Chessable office, I immediately discovered this move, because I had those lines which I was not completely sure about in my head! Yes, I am a chess player...) 27.Qf5 Be4! 28.Qg5+ Bg6 $17}) 17... Ba8 $6 {The start of an unfortunate plan, but the suffocative strategy has clearly had an effect on my opponent. And humanly, how long can we tolerate the monster knight on d5?} (17... Nc5 {can be met energetically with} 18. Bxc5 $1 {with the intention to react quickly after} dxc5 {with} 19. f4 $1 {Covering the dark squares is also very sad for Black! Now there is no way to break out of the grip!} Bxd5 20. cxd5 {White's bishop is stronger than Black's, and White has ideas like Rad1 and e4-e5.}) ({Maybe doing nothing with} 17... a5 18. Rad1 Qc8 {was best, but we all know how difficult it is to do nothing when we feel under pressure!} 19. Bd4 {White is simply better.}) 18. Rad1 {All of White's pieces are perfectly placed.} c6 {Logical follow-up of the previous move.} 19. Nf4 Qc7 {Black is hoping to have time to stabilize with moves like ...a5, ...g6, ...Rbd8, and ...Bb7, and it might not be so easy to break Black's construction. So, White is obviously better, but what could be an effective way to increase the pressure before Black stabilizes?} 20. Nd3 $1 {I love this move so much! In my mind, I keep the memory of this being the decisive move of the game. All the funnier that engines don't even put it into the top 3 category! Engines' chess is something completely different....} ({Clearly I was tempted to play} 20. c5 $5 {immediately, but after} Nxc5 21. Bxc5 dxc5 {White has nice compensation, but there is no need to rush things. The computer highlights that here} 22. g3 $3 {keeping the tension is apparently very strong move, but this is too sophisticated...}) 20... a5 {Whatever Black was doing, the sleeping beast on b3 would be awakened!} (20... Ne5 21. c5 $1 Nxd3 22. Rxd3 dxc5 23. Red1 {Total domination on the d-file.}) ({If} 20... c5 {then of course} 21. Ba4 {followed by Nd3-f4 and the d5-square is 'eternal'.}) 21. c5 $1 {Black is just lost.} Bb7 (21... Rbd8 {runs into} 22. Bg5 $1) (21... Nxc5 22. Nxc5 dxc5 23. Bxc5 Bxc5+ 24. Qxc5 Rb5 25. Qd6 {The position is also losing in the endgame.} Qxd6 26. Rxd6 Kf8 27. Red1 {Black is completely paralyzed, and White is in no rush to cash in, can just slowly increase the pressure. 27.Rd7 Rb7! is in fact the engine's cool defense!}) 22. Bf4 $1 {I sensed that instead of suffering, Shakh is trying to kick out with a quick ...Ba6 idea, and I have prepared a nasty surprise...} Ba6 $6 {Falling into my nice little trick, but we are anyway talking about a horrible position.} (22... Ne5 {would have prolonged the battle, but the torture would remain.} 23. cxd6 Bxd6 24. Nxe5 Bxe5 25. Bxe5 Rxe5 26. f4 Re7 27. e5 c5 28. Rd6 {I agree with computer's +2.30 evaluation.} Qxd6 $2 29. exd6 Rxe1+ 30. Kf2 Rbe8 31. d7 {.}) 23. cxd6 Bxd6 24. Bxd6 Qxd6 {What was my prepared nasty trick?} 25. Ne5 $1 {Great feeling to play a move like this. Now the white rook enters the 7th rank with decisive impact!} Qxe5 26. Rxd7 Red8 27. Red1 {White has total domination. Mamedyarov has had enough of this torture and simply resigned the game. Finishing the tournament with such a stylish strategic win gave me very good emotions, and as an added bonus, it won me the daily Best Game Prize!} 1-0

