1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. The benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6. d2-d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!). 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O ({This is the automatic move and honestly, I have never seen anyone playing any other move here. But it makes sense to mention to those who are not yet familiar with the classical Spanish positions that we are certainly not afraid of the pin with} 8... Bg4 $2 {in fact I consider this as a huge strategical mistake. After} 9. h3 Bh5 10. d3 {Here Black is already getting into trouble! Since the center is closed, the pin is doing absolutely no harm to White; it is much more of a potential target. White has the natural Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver coming (often well-timed g2-g4 ideas are also strong), after which Black´s h5-bishop will be completely sidelined from the battle on g6. After that, the b3-bishop will become an even bigger monster! That is the reason why no serious player plays the early 8...Bg4.}) 9. h3 {The start of the Classical Spanish. White has achieved perfect harmony. With the last move, 9. h3, we have made all the necessary preparatory moves. White is ready to play d2-d4, occupying the center without needing to worry about the annoying pin with ...Bc8-g4, which would put immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. From here on, we will be focusing on learning as many useful middlegame ideas/move orders in different variations as possible by studying my most instructive games related to this topic. One of my absolute favorite opening positions!} Nb8 {My opponent is known to be a great expert of all the classical Spanish systems, so it was impossible to guess which opening variation he would choose. For this game, he opted for the Breyer variation. This opening variation is named after the legendary Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, one of the main pioneers of the Hypermodern chess Era. The Hypermodern school of chess had the completely fresh concept of not fighting for the center directly. Instead, it prioritized harmonious piece placement first (fianchettoing the bishops was a vital part of the concept) and only then challenged the opponent's center. This new approach has brought a lot of fresh wind (the spirit of the 1920s) into the world of chess, thus enriching the history of chess and the game itself. Unfortunately, he died very young, at the age of only 28, in 1921. This has been a terrible loss not only for Hungarian chess but also for the whole chess community. This variation is based on perfect harmony. Black first loses some time with his knight, but it will be beautifully regrouped to d7. Black is looking forward to challenging White´s center slowly after developing all the other pieces (...Bc8-b7, ...Rf8-e8, followed by ...Be7-f8-g7). It is known to promise a very big strategic battle with all pieces on the board. No surprise that it became one of the favorite opening variations of legendary World Champion Boris Spassky and also Magnus Carlsen on his way to the top has always loved to play it. Often, top GMs refer to any thematic ...Nc6-b8 move in any 1. e4 e5 opening as the 'Breyer spirit'!} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 ({Now we see the main point of Black´s play. With} 10... Nbd7 {Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.}) 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} ({Very important to highlight how much the move order matters and why it is essential to understand what and why we are doing! It would be fatal to mix up the moves with} 11... Re8 $2 {due to the simple and typical tactic} 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6 {winning the black queen and the game.}) 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4-pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7. (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!) The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. The reason why} 15. b3 {never got any appreciation earlier was that everyone probably wrongly assumed that} d5 {just kills it. But after the brilliant novelty by Judit in her match with Spassky when she came up with the prepared stunning piece sacrificing idea} 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 {, things have dramatically changed! The point is that if Black is unable to push ...d6-d5 at this very moment this case, he is confronted with the White threat of going d4-d5 because, after the typical breaking move, ...c7-c6, white can cement the pawn chain by going c3-c4. Leading to a completely different type of play. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! 15.a4 is considered the eternal main line, but somehow I was never really attracted to it, probably because 15. b3 served me extremely well, so there was no reason to change anything. 15...c5 Challenging the center. 16.d5 c4 and here we reach the absolute main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black gets the c5-square for his knight; yes, the bishop on b7 is buried, but black has ideas like ...Ra8-b8 followed by the ...Bb7-c8 regrouping. Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my 15. b3 System instead. That's where my heart is!}) 15... Bg7 {The most natural move, now clearly Black is threatening to push ...d6-d5 next, if given the chance.} (15... d5 16. Bg5 $1 {The bomb! Brilliant prep by Team Judit Polgar for her match with Boris Spassky in 1993.} h6 17. Bh4 $3 {I will be covering all the amazing lines and stories behind it in a separate theoretical file! [/variation/38384139] 16.exd5 Nxd5 17.dxe5 Nxc3 18.Qd3 Nd5 19.Bg5 Qc8 $132 Happened with an unclear position. Black even ended up winning this game [/variation/38709580] in Polgar, J-Beliavsky, Munich 1991 � thus confirming the assumption that 15. b3 is harmless...}) 16. d5 $1 {The answer is a clear, NO! We will not allow Black to break the center anymore with ...d6-d5. By closing down the center, we are also fighting against the fianchettoed bishops! We are fighting the whole Hypermodern Chess spirit!} Nb6 {By now, a typical move in the Breyer variation introduced by none other than the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky after having suffered enough in this variation in his match with Judit Polgar. Finally, for the last game, he came up with this idea, which worked to perfection. The brilliant main idea we will see later. For the moment, Black wants to undermine White's center with ...c7-c6; if Black succeeds in forcing White to release the tension with dxc6 that case Black will achieve everything he dreams about with all his pieces coming to life!} *

