16... Nb6 {) A typical move in the Breyer variation introduced by none other than the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky after having suffered enough in this variation in his match with Judit Polgar. Black wants to undermine White's center, but I came up with an important prophylaxis to improve on White's play. How to counter Black's central counterplay idea?} 17. Rb1 $3 {Super important prophylaxis! Due to the pin on the b7-bishop, White is able to stabilize the center and also gets out of any potential tricks on the long diagonal. This was a game-changer, that is why the 16...Nb6 move lost its attraction.} c6 {White is ready for this now.} 18. c4 $1 {Thanks to the previous little move, this is now possible. White is able to keep his powerful pawn chain intact and does not need to worry about the knight sac on d5. This also means that, in the long term, the knight on b6 will really be misplaced...} Qc7 {Now, the same sacrifice is out of the question as White is absolutely ready for it.} (18... cxd5 $6 19. cxd5 Nbxd5 20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Bd2 $16 {and there is no follow-up here.}) (18... bxc4 $6 19. bxc4 Nxc4 $2 20. Rxb7) 19. Bd3 {Now, White has beautifully stabilized the center and can slowly improve the position.} *

