{White has consolidated the center. One of Black's main ideas is to use the c5-square for a knight. Important question: which knight?} 19... Nbd7 $1 {) Obviously, one of Black's knights needs to aim for the perfect c5-square. Since this knight has nothing to do on b6 anymore, while the colleague on f6 should stay to guard the kingside, after the game, the answer is clear: this is the knight that should be moved! My game against Beliavsky went} (19... Nfd7 $2 {This turns out to be a really unfortunate move, but as two big Breyer experts like Peter Wells and Alexander Beliavsky have both opted for it shows that this was very much considered a typical reaction back then.} 20. Be3 $1 {This was the new plan introduced in the Sherzer-Wells game in the Hungarian League 1995, which continued} Rec8 21. Qd2 {Systematic play, no need for the fancy: 1-0 (14) Sherzer,A (2490)-Wells,P (2530) Hungary 1995. Great inspiration for White players facing the Breyer! 20...Nc5 The official novelty, but I guess it was more of a case that Beliavsky was not familiar with the dangers of his position; otherwise, obviously, he would have improved earlier. 21.Bf1 The bishop is beautifully hiding on f1 and, at the same time, protecting the vital c4 pawn and making sure that the pawn chain remains intact! This is also a big difference compared with 19...Nbd7-c5 when this move would not be possible due to the hanging e4-pawn! Small details with a huge impact!! Now, the knight on b6 is a real problematic piece.}) 20. Be3 bxc4 $5 {In general, Black should only open up the queenside if there is a concrete idea behind it. Otherwise, it would simply favor White! Please think about what could be White's benefit!} (20... Nc5 21. Rc1 $1 {This is a clever way to force Black to show his cards about what he intends to do with the queenside pawn structure. It is a complex, big struggle, but I prefer to play with White...}) 21. bxc4 {I am instantly highlighting one of the big bonus ideas for White after Black released the tension with ...b5xc4.} cxd5 22. cxd5 Bxd5 $1 {The only justification! This motif keeps on returning in different scenarios! Shows that this is a typical idea that we always have to keep in mind... Here is a sample continuation:} (22... Bxd5 $1 23. exd5 e4 24. Rc1 Qb7 25. Nxe4 Nxe4 26. Bxe4 Rxe4 27. Qc2 {eyeing the rook and the c6-square.} Nc5 $5 {is possible, 27...Qxd5 28.Red1 Qf5 29.Rxd6 $16 is good for White, and after 27...Nf6 28.Red1 , White still keeps some pressure thanks to the Qc6 idea!}) *

