21... Nbd7 $2 {This move runs into direct problems. In fact, White even has two options to punish it. Let's think: what could be the problem?} 22. b4 $1 {This is the brutal way!} (22. cxb5 {is the strategic way.} cxb5 {is strategically just bad.} 23. Rc1 b4 {Now, going for kingside attack with} 24. h4 $5 {is also an option! Rec8 25.h5 Qd8 26.Nh2 with Ng4 and Qf3 coming, while 24.a3 a5 25.axb4 axb4 26.Bb5! is another typical way of getting the upper hand on the queenside in these structures! 22...axb5 23.b4! We see it again: White only gives up his pawn chain to gain concrete results! 23...Na4 24.Rc1+- Picturesque position: due to the pin on the c-file, Black loses material! Or 23...Na6 24.dxc6 Bxc6 25.a4! Reb8 26.Rc1+- winning. Kamikaze but not enough is 23...Nxe4 24.Nxe4 cxd5 25.Rc1 Qb8 26.Neg5!? or 26.Nc3 d4 27.Bxd4 exd4 28.Rxe8+ Qxe8 29.Nxb5 with a clear advantage.}) 22... Na4 23. Rc1 $1 {With concrete problems on the c-file!} Nb2 (23... Qb8 24. Qd2 {with just a very bad position.}) 24. Qd2 Nxc4 25. Bxc4 bxc4 26. Rxc4 $16 {White will double up on the c-file, with huge pressure.} *

