23... a5 $5 {) Black intends ...Ba6. I feel this was more natural than the game continuation. How can White counter Black's plans? Time for some really serious tests!} 24. Bh6 {What should Black do now?} Ba6 {First question: what happens if Black plays this?} (24... Bxh6 {This invites the attack.} 25. Qxh6 f6 26. h4 $1 {Following Carlsen's motto: Attacking without sacrificing.} Reb8 27. h5 Nf8 28. Nh4 Qg7 29. Qd2 {or 26...Rab8 27.h5 Nf8 28.Nh4! Qg7 29.Qd2 and Black is overloaded.}) (24... Bf8 $14 {This is some insane computer suggestion limiting the damage, but obviously, such moves will never cross our human brain...}) 25. Nf5 $1 {Yes, then we use the typical tactical motif! It's very important that Black is unable to ignore this knight jump.} Bf6 {This runs into a standard motif.} (25... Bxh6 26. Nxh6+ Kg7 27. Ng4 {Black's kingside is too weak.} f6 28. h4 {Free attack!}) (25... gxf5 $2 26. Qg5 {with mate to follow.}) 26. dxc6 $1 {Again, the famous motif Ljubo explained to me: we only play like this when it brings us some direct benefit!} Qxc6 27. Nxd6 {White dominates the board.} *

