25... Ba6 {This is my main question: how to proceed here with White?} 26. Bxa6 $1 {First creating unbalance between Black's rooks.} (26. Nf5 {Now it is an empty shot.} Bf6 {there is no follow-up.}) (26. h4 Bxf1 27. Rxf1 Nf6 $1 {and suddenly Black has perfect harmony!}) (26. Bb5 Bxb5 27. Rxb5 Reb8 28. Rxb8+ Rxb8 {There is no attack left, and it's also too late for switching back to positional play.} 29. Be3 Qb6 {with counterplay.}) (26. Be3 $5 {is possible, but it is slightly less effective than the other move order. But understanding the idea is clearly rewarded with a high five as well!}) 26... Rxa6 {Here comes the key move.} 27. Be3 $14 {The key move. Whoever found this idea gets a huge high five!! This is my spirit: every single small detail counts! To be fair, it is not a small detail at all; in my opinion, this is now almost a technically winning position for White! So, what has happened in the last few moves? Let me try to break it down step by step! 1. With 24.Bh6, we have set up the tactical shot with Nf5, which kind of forced/provoked Black to include the ...cxd5 move. 2. This opened up some more files on the queenside but, even more importantly, has weakened the light squares. Plus, the c4 and b5-squares are suddenly available for White's knights! 3. This means that, by creating pressure on the kingside with 24.Bh6, we ended up making huge achievements on the queenside! 4. When we realize that we do not have to play for an attack, then it immediately becomes clear that, in this case, we should keep our dark-squared bishop! It is obviously much more valuable than its colleague on g7 when the battle moves to the queenside.} Rb8 {This is a sample line. The engine prefers} (27... h5 $1 28. Qc2 Rc8 $1 {A slightly mysterious move to me, as I can't really see what changed and why this is so important... Again, once the computer plays it, it is already possible to understand that the main idea is to be ready to hinder White from bringing the f3-knight all the way to c4!} 29. Nd2 {I still see the same benefits as described in the model line. White simply lets the music play and continues in the same spirit.}) 28. Qc2 $1 Rab6 29. Nd2 $1 {And Black is in a lot of trouble. I found it very instructive and like a beautifully colorful rainbow with three different aspects. 1. Forcing Black to play the strategically undesirable ...cxd5 trade due to the Nf5 tactical threat. 2. After achieving our strategic aim, we can simply switch back to the queenside and massage a lovely advantage by playing Bh6-e3, avoiding the exchange of the dark-squared bishops! 3. When Black wants to outsmart us by trying to exchange all bishops, then we have the Re1-e3 rook lift going for a direct attack against Black's king! Combining all elements is my absolute favorite chess theme!} *

