31... f6 {How to execute White's kingside attack?} 32. Re3 $1 {When knowing the ideas, this is already very simple...} Re7 {An important moment because suddenly White has two very tempting options to sacrifice. It is always important to keep a cool head when making the last crucial decision!} (32... Bb5 33. hxg6 hxg6 34. Nh5) 33. hxg6 {When complications are not necessary, it's better to keep it simple! It was not too late to get carried away and miss a great defensive resource from Black!} (33. Nf5 gxf5 {Clearly, I wanted to make 33.Nf5 work with} 34. Rg3+ {Again, this is a fantastic exercise for calculation, so please use the great opportunity in our next exercise! 34.Qxf6! This is computerish and despite the fact that it is good for White this is clearly not the way we want to go... 34...Rf7 35.Rg3+ Ng6 36.Qh4! Rg7 37.hxg6 hxg6 This does not look like mate, so a human intuition can easily stop here... 38.Qh6! Engine's brutality, simply no feelings at all... 38...Nxe4 39.Rxg6 Rxg6 40.Qxg6+ Kf8 41.f3+- and wins, while after 38...Kf7 39.exf5 Bxf5 40.Ne3 , it's not clear how long Black can survive this.}) 33... hxg6 {What next?} 34. Nh5 $1 {Also, here we get the chance to sac the knight, and I found it even more stylish!} gxh5 (34... Rf7 35. Rg3 Bb5 36. Rxg6+ $5 {This is spectacular. 36.Ne3 Bxf1 37.Kxf1 is, of course, good enough.} Nxg6 37. Qxg6+ Kf8 {This is, again, something for serious calculation. How to win this? You can test your calculation skills in another exercise.}) 35. Rg3+ Bg4 {Black avoids mate, but the position is hopeless.} (35... Kf7 36. Qxh5+ {leads to direct checkmate.}) 36. Qxh5 $1 {Simple, but it's aesthetically pleasing to finish a combination with such a quiet little move.} Nxe4 {Now both captures win.} 37. Qxg4+ (37. Rxg4+ Ng5 38. Qh6 $1 Nfh7 39. Bd3) 37... Ng5 38. Ne3 $1 e4 39. Qf4 Z0 ({My opponent had had enough and resigned due to} 39... Nfh7 40. Ng4 {.}) *

