1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. The benefit of 6.Re1 compared with 6. d2-d3 (which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!). 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O ({This is the automatic move and honestly, I have never seen anyone playing any other move here. But it makes sense to mention to those who are not yet familiar with the classical Spanish positions that we are certainly not afraid of the pin with} 8... Bg4 $2 {in fact I consider this as a huge strategical mistake. After} 9. h3 Bh5 10. d3 {Here Black is already getting into trouble! Since the center is closed, the pin is doing absolutely no harm to White; it is much more of a potential target. White has the natural Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver coming (often well-timed g2-g4 ideas are also strong), after which Black´s h5-bishop will be completely sidelined from the battle on g6. After that, the b3-bishop will become an even bigger monster! That is the reason why no serious player plays the early 8...Bg4.}) 9. h3 {The start of the Classical Spanish. White has achieved perfect harmony. With the last move, 9. h3, we have made all the necessary preparatory moves. White is ready to play d2-d4, occupying the center without needing to worry about the annoying pin with ...Bc8-g4, which would put immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. From here on, we will be focusing on learning as many useful middlegame ideas/move orders in different variations as possible by studying my most instructive games related to this topic. One of my absolute favorite opening positions!} Nb8 {My opponent is known to be a great expert of all the classical Spanish systems, so it was impossible to guess which opening variation he would choose. For this game, he opted for the Breyer variation. This opening variation is named after the legendary Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, one of the main pioneers of the Hypermodern chess Era. The Hypermodern school of chess had the completely fresh concept of not fighting for the center directly. Instead, it prioritized harmonious piece placement first (fianchettoing the bishops was a vital part of the concept) and only then challenged the opponent's center. This new approach has brought a lot of fresh wind (the spirit of the 1920s) into the world of chess, thus enriching the history of chess and the game itself. Unfortunately, he died very young, at the age of only 28, in 1921. This has been a terrible loss not only for Hungarian chess but also for the whole chess community. This variation is based on perfect harmony. Black first loses some time with his knight, but it will be beautifully regrouped to d7. Black is looking forward to challenging White´s center slowly after developing all the other pieces (...Bc8-b7, ...Rf8-e8, followed by ...Be7-f8-g7). It is known to promise a very big strategic battle with all pieces on the board. No surprise that it became one of the favorite opening variations of legendary World Champion Boris Spassky and also Magnus Carlsen on his way to the top has always loved to play it. Often, top GMs refer to any thematic ...Nc6-b8 move in any 1. e4 e5 opening as the 'Breyer spirit'!} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 ({Now we see the main point of Black´s play. With} 10... Nbd7 {Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.}) 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} ({Very important to highlight how much the move order matters and why it is essential to understand what and why we are doing! It would be fatal to mix up the moves with} 11... Re8 $2 {due to the simple and typical tactic} 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6 {winning the black queen and the game.}) 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4-pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7. (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!) The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. The reason why} 15. b3 {never got any appreciation earlier was that everyone probably wrongly assumed that} d5 {just kills it. But after the brilliant novelty by Judit in her match with Spassky when she came up with the prepared stunning piece sacrificing idea} 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 {, things have dramatically changed! The point is that if Black is unable to push ...d6-d5 at this very moment this case, he is confronted with the White threat of going d4-d5 because, after the typical breaking move, ...c7-c6, white can cement the pawn chain by going c3-c4. Leading to a completely different type of play. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! 15.a4 is considered the eternal main line, but somehow I was never really attracted to it, probably because 15. b3 served me extremely well, so there was no reason to change anything. 15...c5 Challenging the center. 16.d5 c4 and here we reach the absolute main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black gets the c5-square for his knight; yes, the bishop on b7 is buried, but black has ideas like ...Ra8-b8 followed by the ...Bb7-c8 regrouping. Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my 15. b3 System instead. That's where my heart is!}) 15... Bg7 {The most natural move, now clearly Black is threatening to push ...d6-d5 next, if given the chance.} (15... d5 16. Bg5 $1 {The bomb! Brilliant prep by Team Judit Polgar for her match with Boris Spassky in 1993.} h6 17. Bh4 $3 {I will be covering all the amazing lines and stories behind it in a separate theoretical file! [/variation/38384139] 16.exd5 Nxd5 17.dxe5 Nxc3 18.Qd3 Nd5 19.Bg5 Qc8 $132 Happened with an unclear position. Black even ended up winning this game [/variation/38709580] in Polgar, J-Beliavsky, Munich 1991 � thus confirming the assumption that 15. b3 is harmless...}) 16. d5 $1 {The answer is a clear, NO! We will not allow Black to break the center anymore with ...d6-d5. By closing down the center, we are also fighting against the fianchettoed bishops! We are fighting the whole Hypermodern Chess spirit!} Nb6 {By now, a typical move in the Breyer variation introduced by none other than the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky after having suffered enough in this variation in his match with Judit Polgar. Finally, for the last game, he came up with this idea, which worked to perfection. The brilliant main idea we will see later. For the moment, Black wants to undermine White's center with ...c7-c6; if Black succeeds in forcing White to release the tension with dxc6 that case Black will achieve everything he dreams about with all his pieces coming to life!} 17. Rb1 $3 {Super important prophylaxis! Due to the pin on the b7, bishop White is able to stabilize the center and also gets out of any potential tricks on the long diagonal. It was a game-changer, that is why the 16...Nb6 move lost its attraction.} (17. Be3 Rc8 18. Qe2 c6 19. c4 cxd5 20. cxd5 Nbxd5 $3 {This is what Spassky had in mind when choosing 16...Nb6. What a stunning positional piece sacrifice; this had an earth-shattering impact back in 1993!} 21. exd5 Nxd5 {I was exactly 13 years old when this happened in a game [/variation/38709581] of the legendary Polgar,J- Spassky Match in Budapest 1993. � It is one of those eternal moments!}) 17... c6 18. c4 $1 {Thanks to the previous little move, this is now possible. White is able to keep his powerful pawn chain intact and does not need to worry about the knight sac on d5. This also means that, in the long term, the knight on b6 will really be misplaced...} Qc7 ({Now the same sacrifice is out of question as White is absolutely ready for it.} 18... cxd5 $6 19. cxd5 Nbxd5 20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Bd2 $16 {and there is no follow-up here.}) (18... bxc4 $6 19. bxc4 Nxc4 $2 20. Rxb7) 19. Bd3 {Now White has beautifully stabilized the center and can slowly improve the position.} Nfd7 $2 {This turns out to be a really unfortunate move, but as two big Breyer experts like Peter Wells and Alexander Beliavsky have both opted for it shows that this was very much considered a typical reaction back then (See the notes to the Unzicker-Donner game in the next move!). But after both Peter's and Alexander's kings got under serious attack, it is no surprise that recently, Black players switched to the more solid 19...Nbd7 move!} (19... Nbd7 $1 {Obviously, one of Black's knights needs to aim for the perfect c5-square. Since this knight has nothing to do on b6 anymore, while the colleague on f6 should stay to guard the kingside so, after the game, the answer is clear: this is the knight that should be moved!} 20. Be3 {and now: A)} bxc4 $5 {In general, Black should only open up the queenside if there is a concrete idea behind it. Otherwise, it would simply favor White! Please think about what could be White's benefit!} 21. bxc4 {I am instantly highlighting one of the big bonus ideas for White after Black released the tension with b5xc4.} cxd5 22. cxd5 Bxd5 $1 {The only justification! This motif keeps on returning in different scenarios! Shows that this is a typical idea that we always have to keep in mind...} 23. exd5 e4 24. Rc1 Qb7 25. Nxe4 Nxe4 26. Bxe4 Rxe4 27. Qc2 Nc5 $5 {or 27...Qxd5 28.Red1 Qf5 29.Rxd6 $16 or 27...Nf6 28.Red1 and White still keeps some pressure thanks to the Qc6 idea! B) 20...Nc5 and if 21.Bc2 a5 here Black can target the c4-pawn quickly! Instead, 21.Rc1! is a clever way to force Black to show his cards what he intends to do with the queenside pawn structure. It is a complex, big struggle, but I prefer to be with White... 21...Nxd3 Never easy to evaluate correctly. After improvising during the recording, I decided to update it a bit... In general, if Black decides to close the queenside, it is important for him to trade these pieces. White has the space advantage, so fewer pieces mean an easier regrouping for Black! I have discovered quite some important details!! 22.Qxd3 b4 23.Qd2 This is what the engine suggests as the main alternative. 23...a5!? is possible but after 23...c5 , how to play this position in a really smart way? B1) 24.Rf1 a5 25.Bh6 ( 25.Ne1 is generally a really nice idea, to transfer the knight to the ideal d3-square in these structures!, but here Black has a strong response in 25...h5! with counterplay against the e4-pawn.) 25...Qe7 26.Bxg7 Kxg7 27.Ne1 a4 28.Nd3 axb3 29.axb3 Ra3 30.Rb1 Bc8 31.f4 exf4 32.Rxf4 Nd7 is solid enough! B2) 24.a4!? Closing the queenside like this always deserves attention. Now White slowly focuses on creating play on the kingside. 24...bxa3? 25.Ra1 $16 . B3) 24.a3! a5 25.Ra1 Combining play on both sides is the engine's main suggestion and one has to say that it is a clever idea! 25...Reb8 26.Ra2 Bc8 27.Rea1 Qb7 with a long maneuvering game, but it is White who is calling the shots...}) 20. Be3 $1 {This was the new plan introduced in Sherzer-Wells in the Hungarian League 1995. To make it all the more dramatic, this game had actually been played next to me! Knowing that Alex was part of Judit Polgar's team, helping prepare for her match and also assisting her against the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky in Budapest in 1993, it is easy to understand where this idea came from...It was obviously born after analyzing game 10, which was the last game of the match! Now, it is easy. We just read the computer evaluation, which states +0.70...} ({It is pretty amazing that this position was reached already in 1960 by two legends. However, the outcome of that game fooled the chess world for over 35 years! This is how chess theory developed or got stuck in the old days without computers! The game continued...} 20. Bd2 bxc4 21. bxc4 a5 22. Qb3 Reb8 23. Qa3 {Targeting both d6 and a5. This is also an instructive strategical idea, but with all of Black's pieces focused on the queenside, it is now not so effective if Black finds the right way. A)} a4 $6 24. Be3 Nc5 $1 {Impressive play! Under pressure, Black found an impressive idea that got the opponent out of balance.} 25. Bxc5 dxc5 26. d6 $6 {(Now, with engines on, it is easy to say that White should have played 26.Nf1! and the complications after 26...cxd5 27.cxd5 c4! 28.Rec1! Bf8 29.Qc3 Ba6 30.Ne3 Bd6 31.Bf1 are exactly working out in White's favor.)} Qd8 {and} 27. Red1 $1 {was strong but the game went 27.Qxc5 Nd7 28.Qa3 Qa5= $13 Beautiful dark squared strategical concept which impressed everyone and nobody searched in this direction afterward for a while... 29.Red1 with a draw agreed already in the game [/variation/38709583] Unzicker, W-Donner, J, Leipzig 1960.� Obviously, White felt that Black had wonderful compensation and preferred to end the game immediately with a well-timed draw offer. I always love to see how old games are maybe not anymore perfect according to computers, but they have so much soul and can still teach us so much! B) 23...Ba6! Now not 24.Bxa5? cxd5! but 24.Rec1 Nc5 25.Bf1 Nba4!= and this is probably what both Peter and Alexander had in mind by going 19...Nfd7. Here, Black has nothing to fear! 26.Be3 Rxb1 27.Rxb1 Rb8 28.Rxb8+ Qxb8 29.dxc6 Qc7 .}) 20... Nc5 {The official novelty, but I guess it was more of a case that Beliavsky was not familiar with the dangers of his position; otherwise, obviously, he would have improved earlier.} (20... Rec8 21. Qd2 {Systematic play. (No need for the fancy 21.a4!? which strategically would only confuse human players! In general, I am not a fan of this move in these structures, but here the engine has a very concrete idea in mind which is the justification! 21...bxa4 22.bxa4 a5 23.Qb3! is the engine's point and suddenly it makes perfect sense, but in this structure pushing a2-a4 without a very specific reason could easily be a strategic mistake, so be careful! 23...Ra6 24.c5 or 23...c5 24.Ne2 $14 and the knight will go to b5.)} bxc4 22. bxc4 Na4 {aiming at the c5-square.} 23. Bh6 $1 {Starting the kingside attack, now that all of Black's pieces are focused on the queenside.} f6 $6 {Pure panic! ( 23...Nac5 24.Nf5 looks very strong, but... 24...Bf6! is a defensive motive which one should keep in mind! 25.Ne3 White is better, but this is clearly the lesser evil.)} 24. Nh4 $5 Nac5 {and since White is in the driver's seat, there is no need to play for the beauty prize with} 25. Ngf5 $5 {but 25.Be2 Nf8 26.Be3!? makes a lot of sense. Black has defended the kingside but, by doing so, has done some long-term weakening with f7-f6... This gives White the right idea: Why would I change my good bishop for the bad one? 26...Nfd7 27.Bg4 Very nice systematic play. The pin along the h3-c8 diagonal is deadly, especially with the ...f7-f6 weakening! 27...Rcb8 28.Red1 Smart move provoking the undesirable ...cxd5! 28...cxd5?! After this, Black´s position is just collapsing. 29.cxd5 Bc8 I decided to replace the 29...Rc8 move. Obviously, Chessbase has it wrong in the database, as I realized during the recording! One confusion that I can imagine is that Rook's shortcut is B (bástya) in Hungarian! This is the only Sherlock Holmes solution I could come up with... 30.Rbc1! The c-file opened up for White after ...c6xd5! 30...Qb6 31.Be6+ Kh8 32.Bh6 Bxh6 33.Nxg6+! lovely finish to this great game [/variation/38709582] by White 1-0 Sherzer,A (2490) -Wells,P (2530) Hungary 1995.� Great inspiration for White players facing the Breyer!}) 21. Bf1 {The bishop is beautifully hiding on f1 and, at the same time, protecting the vital c4-pawn making sure that the pawn chain remains intact! This is also a big difference compared with 19...Nbd7-c5 when this move would not be possible due to the hanging e4-pawn! Small details with a huge impact!! Now, the knight on b6 is a real problematic piece.} bxc4 {Black is definitely not happy to release the tension (we already know that this is in White's favor), but after...} (21... Nbd7 $2 {This move runs into direct problems. In fact, White even has two options to punish it. Let's think: what could be the problem? A)} 22. b4 $1 {This is the brutal way!} Na4 23. Rc1 $1 {with concrete problems on the c-file!} Nb2 {(Or 23...Qb8 24.Qd2 with just a very bad position.)} 24. Qd2 Nxc4 25. Bxc4 bxc4 26. Rxc4 {and White will double up on the c-file with pressure. B) 22.cxb5 The strategic way. B1) 22...cxb5 is strategically just bad. 23.Rc1 b4 24.a3 ( 24.h4!? Going for kingside attack is also an option! 24...Rec8 25.h5 Qd8 26.Nh2 with Ng4 and Qf3 coming.) 24...a5 25.axb4 axb4 26.Bb5! Another typical way of getting the upper hand on the queenside in these structures! B2) 22...axb5 23.b4! We see it again: White only gives up his pawn chain to gain concrete results! 23...Na4 24.Rc1+- Picturesque position: due to the pin on the c-file, Black loses material! 23...Na6 24.dxc6 Bxc6 25.a4! Reb8 26.Rc1+- 23...Nxe4 Kamikaze, but not enough. 24.Nxe4 cxd5 25.Rc1 Qb8 26.Neg5!? or 26.Nc3 d4 27.Bxd4 exd4 28.Rxe8+ Qxe8 29.Nxb5 with a clear advantage.}) 22. bxc4 Nbd7 {Very important strategical position. White has many different plans to choose from. I feel that most probably I was clearly affected by the Sherzer-Wells model game, but I have also seen no reason not to do it. After all, there is a clear logic behind it: while Black is packed on the queenside and needs a lot of moves like ...a5, ...Ba6, or ...Reb8, and ...Bc8 to do something with his b7-bishop, why not target the slightly abandoned Black king...} 23. Qd2 ({A)} 23. h4 $5 {Starting direct action on the kingside was also possible, but I feel that it is a bit early for such a committal decision} a5 24. h5 Ba6 25. Nh2 Reb8 {and now} 26. Qc2 $5 {is possible. It's consequent to continue the 'attack' with 26.Ng4 but it is important to pay attention to the opponents' possibilities as well! 26...Rxb1! This is a problem: Black distracts the White queen and gains time to create counterplay on the queenside. 27.Qxb1 cxd5 28.cxd5 Rb8 29.Qc1 Bxf1 30.Rxf1 Qb6 and now 31.Bh6 can be answered by 31...Nf6!}) ({B) There was also a very attractive purely positional idea by slowly regrouping all the pieces to the queenside with} 23. Nd2 $5 {but the problem that I see with this idea is, is White really in time to get everything done?} Reb8 {allows White to improve the position:} 24. Qc2 $1 Bc8 25. Ne2 a5 26. Nc3 {or 24...a5 25.Ne2! Ba6 26.Nc3 White is in time to achieve the desired regrouping and Black will have trouble finding any plan. 23...a5! 24.Nb3 (Modern engines want to play 24.Qc2 , but I have an issue with this! 24...Ba6! This is the reason why Black had to start with 23...a5. 25.Ne2 Insisting, but now Black can change the character of the game! 25...cxd5! A very well-timed capture on d5 because now White is forced to play the humanly unattractive exd5... 26.exd5 f5 Honestly, I am shocked by the computer's evaluation because I would think that Black can never be worse, and with White, this is absolutely no-go territory! I wanted to highlight this: no matter how strong the engines are, one should not blindly follow them!) 24...Ba6!? Black can try to provoke White here... 25.dxc6 I would prefer not to go for a pawn hunt like this! 25...Qxc6 26.Nxa5 Qc7 White might have won a pawn, but it also helped Black get a nice position with active pieces and a spoiled White pawn structure! This is certainly not my cement spirit!}) 23... Rab8 ({HIGHLIGHT!! Somehow I feel that} 23... a5 $5 {followed by ...Ba6 was more natural. Actually, here we can witness some incredible strategical finesses. Time for some really serious tests!} 24. Bh6 {What should Black do now?} Bf8 $14 {is some insane computer suggestion limiting the damage, but obviously, such moves will never cross our human brain... Let’s see the human alternatives: A) First question: what happens if Black plays 24...Ba6 25.Nf5! Yes, then we use the typical tactical motif! 25...gxf5? is obviously met by 26.Qg5 with mate to follow. 25...Bxh6 (Very important that Black is unable to ignore the Nf5 move because 25...Bf6 runs into 26.dxc6! Again, the famous motif: we only play like this when it brings direct benefit! 26...Qxc6 27.Nxd6+- ) 26.Nxh6+ Kg7 27.Ng4 Black's kingside is too weak. 27...f6 28.h4 Free attack. B) 24...Bxh6 25.Qxh6 This invites the attack. 25...f6 26.h4! Following Carlsen's motto: Attacking without sacrificing. 26...Reb8 27.h5 Nf8 28.Nh4 Qg7 29.Qd2 or 26...Rab8 27.h5 Nf8 28.Nh4! Qg7 29.Qd2 and Black is overloaded. C) 24...cxd5 25.cxd5 and here: C1) 25...Ba6 This is my main question: how to proceed here with White? Now 26.Nf5 is an empty shot, as after 26...Bf6 , there is no follow-up. If 26.h4 Bxf1 27.Rxf1 Nf6! , suddenly Black has perfect harmony! 26.Bb5 Bxb5 27.Rxb5 Reb8 28.Rxb8+ Rxb8 There is no attack left, and it's also too late for switching back to positional play. 29.Be3 Qb6 with counterplay. The immediate 26.Be3!? is possible, but it is slightly less effective than the other move order. But understanding the idea is clearly rewarded with a high five as well! 26.Bxa6! First creating unbalance between Black's rooks. 26...Rxa6 27.Be3 $14 The key move. Whoever found this idea gets a huge high five!! This is my spirit: every single small detail counts! To be fair, it is not a small detail at all; in my opinion, this is now almost a technically winning position for White! So, what has happened in the last few moves? Let me try to break it down step by step! 1. With 24. Bh6, we have set up the tactical shot with Nf5, which kind of forced/provoked Black to include the ...cxd5 move. 2. This opened up some more files on the queenside but, even more importantly, has weakened the light squares. Plus, the c4 and b5-squares are suddenly available for White's knights! 3. This means that, by creating pressure on the kingside with 24. Bh6, we ended up making huge achievements on the queenside! 4. When we realize that we do not have to play for an attack, then it immediately becomes clear that, in this case, we should keep our dark-squared bishop! It is obviously much more valuable than its colleague on g7 when the battle moves to the queenside. Now, the engine prefers 27...h5! 28.Qc2 Rc8! A slightly mysterious move to me, as I can't really see what changed and why this is so important... Again, once the computer plays it, it is already possible to understand that the main idea is to be ready to hinder White from bringing the f3-knight all the way to c4! 29.Nd2 I still see the same benefits as described in the model line. White simply lets the music play and continues in the same spirit. A model line is 27...Rb8 28.Qc2! Rab6 29.Nd2! And Black is in a lot of trouble. C2) Finally, let’s see 25...Bxh6 26.Qxh6 Ba6 Here comes an important sub-question: What to do here with White? Not 27.Nh4 Kh8 $14 but 27.Re3!! The rook is joining the battle on the 3rd rank with devastating effect! ( 27.Bxa6 Rxa6 28.Nh5? is too much talent! In a clearly better position, there's no need for such attitude! 28...gxh5 29.Re3 Nf8 30.Nh4 Ng6 31.Nf5 f6 Black is in time to defend against the mating attack. 28.Re3 is possible as well, but here, Black has better chances of defending. 28...Nf8 White is obviously better, but the same attacking ideas do not work here! 29.h4!? still offers a steady advantage. 29.Nh4 f6 and now 30.Ngf5! , but if instead 30.Nh5? Qf7 , here we see a big difference, namely, the rook from a6 defends the d6-pawn, so the same Nf5 idea does not work here! 31.Nf5? is simply met by 31...Kh8 $17 and suddenly it turns out that White has misplayed everything!) 27...Nf8 28.Nh4 Simple chess. We are still threatening with either Ngf5 or Nh5 sac... ( 28.Nf5!? gxf5 29.Nh4!! f4 30.Nf5 f6 31.Qxf6 h6 32.Rc3 Bxf1 33.Kxf1 Ra7 34.Rbb3!! is some insane computer line which is absolutely unnecessary, but I had to show it because it was so beautiful...) 28...Kh8 runs into 29.Ngf5 , and 28...f6 29.Nh5 Qf7 30.Nf5! is a lovely position! 30...gxh5 31.Nxd6 or 30...gxf5 and now White can choose between different finishes. 31.Rg3+ Kh8 32.Rg7 Qxh5 33.Qxh5 Kxg7 34.Bxa6+- Winning because the bishop is taboo! Also 31.Nxf6+ Kh8 32.Nxe8 Rxe8 33.Qxd6 wins. I found everything very instructive and like a beautifully colorful rainbow with three different aspects. 1. Forcing Black to play the strategically undesirable ...cxd5 trade due to the Nf5 tactical threat. 2. After achieving our strategic aim, we can simply switch back to the queenside and massage a lovely advantage by playing Bh6-e3, avoiding the exchange of the dark-squared bishops! 3. When Black wants to outsmart us by trying to exchange all bishops, then we have the Re1-e3 rook lift going for a direct attack against Black's king! Combining all elements is my absolute favorite chess theme!}) 24. Bh6 $1 {Continuing the plan. Now again, the Nf5 idea is looming in the air.} Bxh6 (24... Nf8 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Qg5 $1 {with all the weak dark squares it looks horrible.}) 25. Qxh6 Nf8 {Black is planning to cover the dark squares on the kingside with ...f7-f6. It is always very important to understand what resources our opponent has in mind so that we are getting ready for it both over the board and also psychologically.} 26. h4 {A very natural attacking move. I faced some problems here because there were too many other attractive good options as well. But finally, I decided to be practical and play the most systematic way without going for any direct sacrifices.} ({A)} 26. Re3 $5 {One of the other attractive alternatives. As we know from the other line we looked at, this is a very dangerous idea. A1)} Bc8 27. Rxb8 Qxb8 {Important to think here, as White has a great idea!!} 28. Ng5 $3 {Pretty bombastic! There is even this motif, something that we rarely see. Now, White is threatening to sac the knight with Nh5, and Black is completely helpless. Here we see why it was so important to distract Black's queen from the 7th rank! ( 28.Qg5!? intending Nh5 is interesting, while 28.Nh5!? gxh5 29.Ng5!! is the same winning idea.)} cxd5 29. Nh5 $1 gxh5 30. Rg3 {there is no escape for Black's king. A2) 26...Ba8 27.Rxb8 Rxb8 28.Nh4 f6 29.Nhf5! Qf7 30.Nxd6 Qg7 31.Qh4 Rd8 32.Ndf5 gxf5 33.Nxf5 Ng6 34.Qh5 Qf8 35.Rg3= $13 but Black should avoid 29...gxf5 30.Nxf5 Ng6 31.h4! cxd5 32.cxd5 Nxe4 33.h5 Nf4 34.Rxe4 Qf7 35.Re3! Kh8 36.Rg3 Rg8 37.Rxg8+ Kxg8 38.g3 Nxh5 39.Bc4+-}) ({B)} 26. Nh4 $5 {Also very interesting, but since White can attack without sacrificing anything, there is no need to give Black practical chances! Often, finding only moves to survive is much more preferable for the defending side than to keep defending a simply bad position without perspective.} f6 27. Nhf5 gxf5 28. Nxf5 Ng6 29. h4 $1 {and here, with computer assistance, White can enjoy playing for compensation, but over the board, this only gives Black hopes to confuse both sides.} Qf7 30. h5 Nf4 31. g3 Nxh5 32. Be2 Ng7 33. Nxd6 Qe7 34. Nxe8 Rxe8 35. Bg4 Bc8 36. Bxc8 Rxc8 37. Rb6 $16 {29...cxd5 30.h5 Nh4!! Wow, this is what I am talking about! ( 30...Nf4 31.Qxf6 or the fancy 31.Re3!? Nxe4 32.Rbb3! White rooks wants to reach g3!) 31.Nxh4 d4! suddenly it is a huge mess and first time in this game my heart is more with Black! Or 30.cxd5! Rf8 31.h5 Nf4 32.g3 Nfd3 33.Re2! but apart from engines I am not sure who can keep up the overview here...}) ({C)} 26. Nh2 $2 Bc8 $1 {is solid for Black.}) 26... cxd5 $6 {In a higher sense this is already the losing inaccuracy! As we will see later in the game, this trade with ...cxd5 cxd5 will also clearly favor White here as well... But the drawback is kind of still unforeseeable!} (26... Bc8 $1 {was the way to go.} 27. Rxb8 Qxb8 28. h5 Qc7 29. Nd2 $1 {keeping all options open, and now: A)} Qe7 $5 {. B) 29...a5 30.Re3 f6 31.hxg6 hxg6 32.Nh5! Qf7 33.Rg3 or 33.Be2 C) 29...f6 30.Nb3 with clear advantage as Black is unable to hold the c5-outpost. D) 29...Nfd7!? Trying to get the knight to f6. Now not 30.Re3 Nf6! and suddenly nothing works! 30.dxc6!! Again, the famous quote from Ljubojevic: only play like this if there is concrete benefit!! D1) 30...Nb8 31.Re3 Nxc6 32.Nf5+- wins. D2) 30...Nf6 31.Nf5! ( 31.Qg5 Qe7 32.hxg6 hxg6 33.Nf5 Bxf5 34.exf5 Kg7 35.fxg6 fxg6 36.Nf3 $16 or 36.Nb3 ) If 31...Bxf5 32.exf5 Nxh5 33.Re3 Qxc6 34.g4 Nf6 35.Rh3 Qd7 36.Be2+- White has a winning attack, and after 31...Nxh5 32.Ne3 Qxc6 33.Nd5 Nd7 34.Nf3 Ndf6 35.Ng5 Be6 comes the wonderful little touch 36.Be2!! Black is overloaded with the defense. 36...Bxd5 37.exd5 and Bxh5 is next. D3) 30...Qxc6 31.Re3! with terrific attack. 31...Nf6 32.Be2! and again Nf5 is coming.}) 27. cxd5 Bc8 {Let's try to think about what has changed with the insertion of ...cxd5, cxd5 moves!} 28. Rxb8 $1 {First step. It is always important to force the Black queen to lose time!} Qxb8 29. h5 Qc7 30. Nd2 $3 {Here we see the drawback of the ...cxd5 trade. Suddenly, the c4-square is available for the knight, from which it puts tremendous pressure on the d6-pawn. It is my favorite move of the game. The rest plays like a beautiful melody!} Bd7 {Black's bishop tries to reach the b5-square to control c4, but it is one move too late!} 31. Nc4 $1 f6 (31... Bb5 {Again, a good moment to think! How to proceed?} 32. Nf5 $3 {As usual, when we play a great strategic game, the tactics come to us!} gxf5 33. Nxd6) 32. Re3 $1 {When knowing the ideas, this is already very simple...} Re7 {An important moment because suddenly White has two very tempting options to sacrifice. It is always important to keep a cool head when making the last crucial decision!} (32... Bb5 33. hxg6 hxg6 34. Nh5) 33. hxg6 {When complications are not necessary, it's better to keep it simple!} ({It was not too late to get carried away and miss a great defensive resource from Black!} 33. Nf5 gxf5 34. Qxf6 $1 {This is computerish and despite the fact that it is good for White this is clearly not the way we want to go... (Clearly, I wanted to make 33.Nf5 work with 34.Rg3+ Again, this is a fantastic exercise for calculation, so please use the great opportunity! 34...Kf7 35.Rg7+ Ke8 36.Qxf6 Instead of resigning, Black has a great defense! 36...Be6!! When I saw this during the game, I immediately made up my mind to stick to the simple option without any fancy business!)} Rf7 35. Rg3+ Ng6 36. Qh4 $1 Rg7 37. hxg6 hxg6 {This does not look like mate, so a human intuition can easily stop here...} 38. Qh6 $1 {Engine's brutality, simply no feelings at all...} Nxe4 39. Rxg6 Rxg6 40. Qxg6+ Kf8 41. f3 {and wins, while after 38...Kf7 39.exf5 Bxf5 40.Ne3 , it's not clear how long Black can survive this.}) 33... hxg6 34. Nh5 $1 {Also, here we get the chance to sac the knight, and I found it even more stylish!} gxh5 (34... Rf7 35. Rg3 Bb5 36. Rxg6+ $5 {This is spectacular. ( 36.Ne3 Bxf1 37.Kxf1 is, of course, good enough.)} Nxg6 37. Qxg6+ Kf8 {This is, again, something for serious calculation. How to win this?} 38. Ne3 $3 Bxf1 39. Nxf6 {This is the quiet key move.} Bxg2 $5 {fails to} 40. Nf5 {, while after 39...Bb5 40.Qh6+ Rg7 41.Nf5 Qf7 42.Qh8+ Rg8 43.Nxg8 Qxg8 44.Qf6+ Qf7 45.Qxd6+ , White wins the whole house.}) 35. Rg3+ Bg4 {Black avoids mate, but the position is hopeless.} (35... Kf7 36. Qxh5+ {leads to direct checkmate.}) 36. Qxh5 $1 {Simple, but it's aesthetically pleasing to finish a combination with such a quiet little move.} Nxe4 {Now both captures win.} 37. Qxg4+ (37. Rxg4+ Ng5 38. Qh6 $1 Nfh7 39. Bd3) 37... Ng5 38. Ne3 $1 e4 39. Qf4 Z0 ({My opponent had had enough and resigned due to} 39... Nfh7 40. Ng4 {. I feel that this is one of my absolute favorite games to teach. There have been so many different ideas and nuances in just a single game; I hope you guys have also enjoyed it as much as I have! Outplaying such a legendary strategist like Alexander Beliavsky in his own territory made me very proud. Also, I very much remember how much I learned from him when, as a youngster, I had the privilege of playing him in the mid-90s. Yes, I lost many of those games and always felt like I got lectured...}) 1-0

