1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 Bg7 16. d5 Qe7 $5 {A very interesting handling of this position. After my game with Beliavsky, this line with 15. b3 challenging the Breyer got really popular. So, it was Black's turn to come up with an antidote. I believe it was Sasikiran who first invented this new setup. The idea looks simple, but in fact, it is the starting move of a very deep concept! First of all, Black protects the d6-pawn, so it is ready to push ...c7-c6 immediately without determining the position of the d7-knight. Then, the next step is to play ...Rec8, followed by ...a6-a5. Obviously, White will push c3-c4, so Black hopes to trade both pawns with ...b5xc4 and ...c6xd5 and install the d7-knight on c5; if Black is then even given the time to achieve ...Ba6 as well, that would be the ultra-dream! One more extra idea that Black has is to move the queen to f8, not really for defensive purposes, but much more is Black aiming at a timely ...Bg7-h6 trade of the dark-squared bishops. Strategically, a brilliant concept! The big question is how White should fight it!} ({Exactly in his previous game with the black pieces, Short already had this position (guess vs. who?). Yes, of course, it was vs. Judit Polgar in the very same tournament! In that game, he tried} 16... Qb8 {Similar idea preparing ...c7-c6 without moving the knight from d7.} 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rc8 19. Qd2 a5 20. Bd3 {when} Ba6 $5 {was interesting and instead, 20...bxc4 came a bit early. After 21.bxc4 Ba6 22.Rab1 Qc7 23.Rec1 , Black's queen in this game was quite vulnerable on b8 and later on c7, so it was a logical conclusion that why on earth is this queen placed on the queenside... 23...Bf8 24.Ne2 $14 White had things under control, and only after a lot of suffering did Nigel survive this game [/variation/38709586] Polgar, J (2728)-Short, N (2674) Wijk aan Zee 2005. �}) 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rec8 {The key position! Here, I really have to reveal something extraordinary that happened in the background, and I don't remember it ever happening before or after! At the end of the year, when preparing for Wijk aan Zee, we decided to spend a few days playing a couple of rapid training games with my second Vladislav Tkachiev for systems that are not so popular on the highest level but are actually very interesting. It was Vlad's responsibility to find those systems from the Black side vs my 1. e4. Being a great opening expert with a big liking for the Spanish opening, he selected this very system! I was heavily suffering in the first games, not exactly finding the right way to handle the position! Suddenly, everything was different from my previous vision of this middlegame. It went as far as that after the second game, I had to pick up the phone and call Arshak (my trainer and father-in-law) to help me find the right idea for this position! Normally, we would have been working together, but Arshak wanted us to enjoy our games in a quiet atmosphere, not to have any outside distractions. He was very happy to get a challenging assignment and promised to call in the evening... In the meantime, I have asked Vlad to move on to another chapter before returning to this specific variation... In the evening, my phone rang, and Arshak explained to me what he had found... A classic example of a single phone call changing everything! Honestly, Arshak's explanations have been so clear and so fascinating that instead of waiting for the next day to use it vs Vlad, I immediately went to report it to him! After going over the ideas on the board, we had the feeling that we did not need to play any more games for this variation, as I was already more than ready!} *

