18... Rec8 {The key-position! White needs to bolster the center. A single phone call with my trainer and father-in-law, Arshak, helped me find the right idea! What's the prophylactic and subtle idea I prepped and played?} 19. Rc1 $3 {Again, a super deep prophylactic move. Basically, it is very similar to 19. Qd2, but during our prep, I noticed a little finesse and wanted to pay attention to it.} ({A)} 19. Qd2 $5 {Probably Black should just transpose with} a5 20. Rac1 {, but as an illustration, I would like to show what I noticed in my preparation. After 19...bxc4 20.bxc4 cxd5 21.cxd5 Nc5 is a solid continuation, and against this setup, I wanted to have something more powerful than just some natural play like 22.Rab1 Nfd7 followed by ...a5 and ...Ba6. I see that modern engines don't care about this nuance, but I always like to pay attention to small details!}) ({B)} 19. Nh4 $6 {The aggressive idea to sacrifice the knight on f5 with Nhf5 is at first tempting (I considered it in my training games), but we should always try to be objective, and a closer look tells us that with Black's queen comfortably moving back to f8 the attack will not have a follow-up.} Qf8 20. Qd2 a5 {and if the sacrifice does not work (and it doesn't), then why did White go for Nh4?} 21. Nhf5 $2 gxf5 22. Nxf5 Kh8 {there is no follow-up, and Black should slowly win.}) 19... bxc4 {Here comes my big revelation if Black plays the earlier-mentioned plan.} (19... a5 20. Qd2 {and in case Black pushes} b4 {then White can try to simply lock the queenside and after focus with all his forces on the kingside. It is another question how easy it will be to break Black's defenses, but it is not a question Black is really interested in finding out! 20...bxc4 is the consequent way of Black's play. Black wants to establish a great outpost on c5 for his knight. 21.bxc4 cxd5 22.cxd5 Nc5 So far, so good! We both pretty quickly ended up in this position as everything went according to the plans we both envisioned... Black is only one move away from completing his perfect setup, but I had something prepared.}) 20. bxc4 cxd5 21. cxd5 Nc5 {What was I up to?} 22. Nd2 $3 {Here, I have this lovely idea. The knight is ready to be rerouted towards the queenside! In this case, it seems that, yes, it is a nice nuance, but the other option was also quite good, so what is the big deal? My answer is that yes, maybe this time both options are more or less equally possible, but in my mind, if someone wants to master my Cemento spirit, then paying attention to such details is essential!} a5 23. Nc4 Nfd7 (23... Qd8 $5) 24. Rb1 {The monster knight on c4 poses too much trouble for Black.} *

