22... Nc5 {Black is only one move away from completing his perfect setup. Arshak's brilliant concept came as a total surprise to Nigel. Can you guess the move I played here?} 23. Bd3 $3 {Usually, in the Ruy Lopez, trading a bishop for a knight is taboo, but we have to be open to the rare exceptions! Practically, Black is in a very difficult situation as he is forced to make a very tough decision! I consider this game as the reward of systematic hard work. One can never be sure when we will get the chance to use something we worked on, but if we don't do the work, the answer is pretty clear: simply never!! I also believe that the most important thing is to enjoy the working process, and if we are able to hit the jackpot as happened in this game, then that is only a bonus!} ({After} 23. Bb1 {, Black has two possible continuations. I guess my opponent most probably would have played the more natural} Nfd7 {when White anyway needs to play} 24. Bd3 $1 {, which is clearly not consistent with the previous move... Instead, 23...Ba6!? is the extravaganza, and now not 24.Qxa5 Bd3! but 24.Bxc5 dxc5! I would love to highlight that this is a very double-edged strategic position because Black gets a lot of dynamics due to the ...c5-c4 push! Typically, if in such a structure, White can set up a blockade on the light square c4. In that case, White is in great shape; otherwise, it is always tricky! 25.Qxa5? Bh6! suddenly winning material! In contrast, if 24...Rxc5 25.Rxc5 dxc5 26.Qxa5 , here White can take.}) 23... Nxd3 $1 {Biting the bullet and running with open arms into the opponent's prep was the only right way! But we all know how difficult it is to make such a decision...} ({A) Black simply can't play the normal way with} 23... Nfd7 {because after} 24. Bb5 {the white bishop will be unbearable in the long run!}) ({B)} 23... h5 $2 {Total panic played after a very long think! One can wonder how come that strong players can make mistakes after thinking for too long. The answer is pretty simple: First, you look at the natural moves, and if you convince yourself that after the normal reaction, you end up in a position that you do not like or assume that it is the opponent's preparation, then finally the confusion can take over, and one can easily make a mistake based on emotional disbalance! I believe this has happened to all of us... We'll see next how the game continued.}) 24. Rxc8+ $1 {Causing disharmony. Now, a very big question is how Black should recapture...} Bxc8 $1 {This is key, but it is so easy not to understand this over the board!} (24... Rxc8 25. Qxd3 {This is really bad now.}) 25. Qxd3 Ba6 {Where should the queen move?} 26. Qa3 $1 {Yes, this is the optimal square, putting pressure on both weaknesses, the d6 and the a5-pawns. Remember we saw this [/variation/37803576/#/20/w/0.6] in the previous game? It is very easy to panic here with Black because White's play looks super easy, occupying one of the open files with the rook, and also, the knight transfer to the queenside via Nd2 is in the air. Humanly, this looks very unpleasant to a strong player from a distance, but now the computer tells us there is no need to panic... 'Tranquilo, with precise play, we can handle any pressure'...} Z0 (26... Qd8 $1 {when} 27. Rb1 {is met by} Bf8 $1 28. Nd2 h5 {and Nd2 Bf8!} 29. Rc1 {h5! is a key sequence of engines, and somehow it is tough to find a way to confirm the advantage to the silicon beast...}) *

