29... Ba6 {Black's only practical attempt. How do we continue now?} 30. Nfxe5 $1 {Yes, this is the most powerful.} (30. Ncxe5 Bxd3 31. Nxd3 c4 {would give some chances.}) 30... Bxe5 31. Nxe5 Bxd3 (31... c4 32. Bxc4 Rxe5 33. Bxa6 Rxc1 34. Rxc1 Rxe4 {I had reached this position in my calculation, and if I had not spotted the game continuation, I might have chosen a different option. So, what did I notice when opting for 30.Nfxe5...? That's my next question for you...}) 32. Nxd3 c4 {Thanks to the pin on the c-file, White is not forced to move the knight.} 33. e5 {With a powerful duo of central pawns. It was beneficial for White to have traded the knight for the bishop.} *

