1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 {The key move of the classical Spanish setup. This move has a double purpose: 1. It prepares to occupy the center with d2-d4 in one move. The benefit of 6. Re1 compared with 6. d2-d3 (Which is mainly aimed vs. Marshall players!). 2. It secures our light-squared bishop (...Na5 was a threat!), who is the soul of the Classical Ruy Lopez!} O-O ({This is the automatic move and honestly, I have never seen anyone playing any other move here. But it makes sense to mention to those who are not yet familiar with the classical Spanish positions that we are certainly not afraid of the pin with} 8... Bg4 $2 {in fact I consider this as a huge strategical mistake. After} 9. h3 Bh5 10. d3 {Here Black is already getting into trouble! Since the center is closed, the pin is doing absolutely no harm to White; it is much more of a potential target. White has the natural Nbd2-f1-g3 maneuver coming (often well-timed g2-g4 ideas are also strong), after which Black´s h5-bishop will be completely sidelined from the battle on g6. After that, the b3-bishop will become an even bigger monster! That is the reason why no serious player plays the early 8...Bg4.}) 9. h3 {The start of the Classical Spanish. White has achieved perfect harmony. With the last move, 9. h3, we have made all the necessary preparatory moves. White is ready to play d2-d4, occupying the center without needing to worry about the annoying pin with ...Bc8-g4, which would put immediate pressure on the d4-pawn. From here on, we will be focusing on learning as many useful middlegame ideas/move orders in different variations as possible by studying my most instructive games related to this topic. One of my absolute favorite opening positions!} Nb8 {The Breyer variation is named after the legendary Hungarian player Gyula Breyer, one of the main pioneers of the Hypermodern chess Era. The Hypermodern school of chess had the completely fresh concept of not fighting for the center directly. Instead, it prioritized harmonious piece placement first (fianchettoing the bishops was a vital part of the concept) and only then challenged the opponent's center. This new approach has brought a lot of fresh wind (the spirit of the 1920s) into the world of chess, thus enriching the history of chess and the game itself. Unfortunately, he died very young, at the age of only 28, in 1921. This has been a terrible loss not only for Hungarian chess but also for the whole chess community. This variation is based on perfect harmony. Black first loses some time with his knight, but it will be beautifully regrouped to d7. Black is looking forward to challenging White´s center slowly after developing all the other pieces (...Bc8-b7, ...Rf8-e8, followed by ...Be7-f8-g7). It is known to promise a very big strategic battle with all pieces on the board. No surprise that it became one of the favorite opening variations of legendary World Champion Boris Spassky and also Magnus Carlsen on his way to the top has always loved to play it. Often, top GMs refer to any thematic ...Nc6-b8 move in any 1. e4 e5 opening as the 'Breyer spirit'!} 10. d4 {White has succeeded with his plan of pushing d2-d4 in just one move.} Nbd7 ({Now we see the main point of Black´s play. With} 10... Nbd7 {Black has a very nice way of protecting the e5-pawn, so it can keep the tension in the center and has a clear follow-up with ...Bc8-b7 targeting the e4-pawn.}) 11. Nbd2 {The knight starts its typical Spanish route, which usually consists of Nb1-d2-f1-g3.} Bb7 {Black is in time to put the e4-pawn under pressure before the d2-knight can move, so White has to react again to be able to continue the desired knight maneuver.} ({Very important to highlight how much the move order matters and why it is essential to understand what and why we are doing! It would be fatal to mix up the moves with} 11... Re8 $2 {due to the simple and typical tactic} 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6 {winning the black queen and the game.}) 12. Bc2 {White protects the e4-pawn and is ready to continue the regrouping with Nf1-g3.} Re8 {Now is the right time for this move. There are no more tricks that Black needs to pay attention to and can calmly follow his long-term strategical ideas.} 13. Nf1 {I am always a big fan if possible to reach the g3-square with my knight so that after ...Be7-f8, we will be able to protect the e4-pawn with Nf1-g3.} Bf8 {Now again the e4-pawn is under attack.} 14. Ng3 {In time to protect the e4-pawn from the best possible square. There is a special reference to it in the Classical Spanish Opening. The saying goes: The Spanish knight has parked! The reference means that after protecting the e4-pawn with the knight from g3, White is in no rush to move that piece for a longer period of time (unless we have a chance to go for an attack with Ng3-f5) and can devote the attention of what to do with the bishop from c1 as well as to see which pawn moves we want to make on the queenside like a2-a4 or b2-b3 usually leading to completely different systems.} g6 {Now we have reached the main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black has nicely regrouped his pieces and is now ready to fianchetto his dark-squared bishop to g7. (The double fianchetto is the true spirit of the Hypermodern school of chess!) The good news for White is that he has also used his time wisely and, thanks to the parked knight on g3, has things under control. Now, White has two completely different directions.} 15. b3 ({My favorite line against the Breyer. It could potentially be called the Hungarian Antidote vs. the Breyer, as both Judit Polgar and I have made quite important contributions to developing it. The reason why} 15. b3 {never got any appreciation earlier was that everyone probably wrongly assumed that} d5 {just kills it. But after the brilliant novelty by Judit in her match with Spassky when she came up with the prepared stunning piece sacrificing idea} 16. Bg5 h6 17. Bh4 {, things have dramatically changed! The point is that if Black is unable to push d6-d5 at this very moment this case, he is confronted with the White threat of going d4-d5 because, after the typical breaking move, ...c7-c6, white can cement the pawn chain by going c3-c4. Leading to a completely different type of play. Despite big efforts, Black is still searching for the best reaction to it. I would say that if a line is able to stand the test of 30 years, this speaks volumes about the 15. b3 line. My idea is to provide an unforgettable journey into the labyrinths of this fascinating system with so many different twists and turns like no other! 15.a4 Is considered the eternal main line, but somehow I was never really attracted to it, probably because 15. b3 served me extremely well, so there was no reason to change anything. 15...c5 Challenging the center. 16.d5 c4 and here we reach the absolute main tabiya of the Breyer variation. Black gets the c5-square for his knight; yes, the bishop on b7 is buried, but black has ideas like ...Ra8-b8 followed by ...Bb7-c8 regrouping. Over the years, there have been tons of different deep ideas from both sides, but I always remained on the sidelines and focused on my 15. b3 System instead. That's where my heart is!}) 15... Bg7 {The most natural move, now clearly Black is threatening to push ...d6-d5 next, if given the chance.} (15... d5 16. Bg5 $1 {The bomb! Brilliant prep by Team Judit Polgar for her match with Boris Spassky in 1993.} h6 17. Bh4 $3 {I will be covering all the amazing lines and stories behind it in a separate theoretical file! [/variation/38384139] 16.exd5 Nxd5 17.dxe5 Nxc3 18.Qd3 Nd5 19.Bg5 Qc8 $132 happened with an unclear position. Black even ended up winning this game [/variation/38709580] in Polgar, J-Beliavsky, Munich 1991 � thus confirming the assumption that 15. b3 is harmless...}) 16. d5 {I was ready to continue the theoretical discussion in this line and was curious to see what Nigel had in mind.} Qe7 $5 {A very interesting handling of this position. After my game with Beliavsky, this line with 15. b3 challenging the Breyer got really popular. So, it was Black's turn to come up with an antidote. I believe it was Sasikiran who first invented this new setup. The idea looks simple, but in fact, it is the starting move of a very deep concept! First of all, Black protects the d6-pawn, so it is ready to push ...c7-c6 immediately without determining the position of the d7-knight. Then, the next step is to play ...Rec8, followed by ...a6-a5. Obviously, White will push c3-c4, so Black hopes to trade both pawns with ...b5xc4 and ...c6xd5 and install the d7-knight on c5; if Black is then even given the time to achieve ...Ba6 as well, that would be the ultra-dream! One more extra idea that Black has is to move the queen to f8, not really for defensive purposes, but much more is Black aiming at a timely ...Bg7-h6 trade of the dark-squared bishops. Strategically, a brilliant concept! The big question is how White should fight it!} ({Exactly in his previous game with the black pieces, Short already had this position (guess vs. who?). Yes, of course, it was vs. Judit Polgar in the very same tournament! In that game, he tried} 16... Qb8 {Similar idea preparing ...c7-c6 without moving the knight from d7.} 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rc8 19. Qd2 a5 20. Bd3 {when} Ba6 $5 {was interesting and instead, 20...bxc4 came a bit early. After 21.bxc4 Ba6 22.Rab1 Qc7 23.Rec1 , Black's queen in this game was quite vulnerable on b8 and later on c7, so it was a logical conclusion that why on earth is this queen placed on the queenside... 23...Bf8 24.Ne2 $14 White had things under control, and only after a lot of suffering did Nigel survive this game [/variation/38709586] Polgar, J (2728)-Short, N (2674) Wijk aan Zee 2005. �}) 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Rec8 {The key position! Here, I really have to reveal something extraordinary that happened in the background, and I don't remember it ever happening before or after! At the end of the year, when preparing for Wijk aan Zee, we decided to spend a few days playing a couple of rapid training games with my second Vladislav Tkachiev for systems that are not so popular on the highest level but are actually very interesting. It was Vlad's responsibility to find those systems from the Black side vs my 1. e4. Being a great opening expert with a big liking for the Spanish opening, he selected this very system! I was heavily suffering in the first games, not exactly finding the right way to handle the position! Suddenly, everything was different from my previous vision of this middlegame. It went as far as that after the second game, I had to pick up the phone and call Arshak (my trainer and father-in-law) to help me find the right idea for this position! Normally, we would have been working together, but Arshak wanted us to enjoy our games in a quiet atmosphere, not to have any outside distractions. He was very happy to get a challenging assignment and promised to call in the evening... In the meantime, I have asked Vlad to move on to another chapter before returning to this specific variation... In the evening, my phone rang, and Arshak explained to me what he had found... A classic example of a single phone call changing everything! Honestly, Arshak's explanations have been so clear and so fascinating that instead of waiting for the next day to use it vs Vlad, I immediately went to report it to him! After going over the ideas on the board, we had the feeling that we did not need to play any more games for this variation, as I was already more than ready!} 19. Rc1 $3 {Again, a super deep prophylactic move. Basically, it is very similar to 19. Qd2, but during our prep, I noticed a little finesse and wanted to pay attention to it.} ({A)} 19. Qd2 $5 {Probably Black should just transpose with} a5 20. Rac1 {, but as an illustration, I would like to show what I noticed in my preparation. After 19...bxc4 20.bxc4 cxd5 21.cxd5 Nc5 is a solid continuation, and against this setup, I wanted to have something more powerful than just some natural play like 22.Rab1 Nfd7 followed by ...a5 and ...Ba6. I see that modern engines don't care about this nuance, but I always like to pay attention to small details!}) ({B)} 19. Nd2 $6 {What could be Black's reaction here?} Qf8 $1 {Here we see what I have been talking about! The ...Bg7-h6 idea is coming and Black should be perfectly fine.}) ({C)} 19. Nh4 $6 {The aggressive idea to sacrifice the knight on f5 with Nhf5 is at first tempting (I considered it in my training games), but we should always try to be objective, and a closer look tells us that with Black's queen comfortably moving back to f8 the attack will not have a follow-up.} Qf8 20. Qd2 a5 {and if the sacrifice does not work (and it doesn't), then why did White go for Nh4?} 21. Nhf5 $2 gxf5 22. Nxf5 Kh8 {there is no follow-up, and Black should slowly win.}) ({D)} 19. Nh2 {the knight goes to g4} a5 20. Ng4 bxc4 21. bxc4 cxd5 22. cxd5 Nc5 {with the typical regrouping ...Ba6 and ...Rab8.}) 19... a5 ({Here comes my big revelation if Black plays the earlier-mentioned plan with} 19... bxc4 20. bxc4 cxd5 21. cxd5 Nc5 {What was I up to?} 22. Nd2 $3 {Here, I have this lovely idea. The knight is ready to be rerouted towards the queenside! In this case, it seems that, yes, it is a nice nuance, but the other option was also quite good, so what is the big deal? My answer is that yes, maybe this time both options are more or less equally possible, but in my mind, if someone wants to master my Cemento spirit, then paying attention to such details is essential!} a5 23. Nc4 Qd8 $5 {or 23...Nfd7 24.Rb1 and the monster knight on c4 poses too much trouble for Black.}) 20. Qd2 bxc4 {This is the consequent way of Black's play. Black wants to establish a great outpost on c5 for his knight.} ({If Black pushes} 20... b4 {then White can try to simply lock the queenside and after focus with all his forces on the kingside. It is another question how easy it will be to break Black's defenses, but it is not a question Black is really interested in finding out! Important to note that here not a single minor piece has been traded, which makes Black`s position harder to play! Harder to regroup! White has two completely different type of plan here: A)} 21. Red1 {Positional approach. If} c5 22. Rf1 a4 {intending to open the a-file for counterplay.} 23. Ne1 {Aiming at the d3-square. We already know this plan from the other closed position analysed inside the Leko-Beliavsky [/variation/37803576/#/19/b/0.38.0.0] Bled 2002 game!} axb3 24. axb3 Ra2 25. Nd3 {White will prepare Bb1 to kick the rook out, and the f4-push on the kingside, while the b7-bishop is passive. Or 21...cxd5 22.cxd5 and if 22...Ba6 23.Bd3! , the light squares are collapsing on the queenside. We see another very instructive position after 22...Nc5 Black is very solid, but here White also has an important hidden plan! 23.Ra1!! Preparing a2-a3. 23...Qc7 24.Rdc1 Qb6 25.a3 Nfd7 looks solid, but White can slowly increase the pressure, while Black already stays at maximum! 26.Ra2! $14 and White will double up on the a-file and regroup with Ne1-Nd3. B) 21.Rcd1!? cxd5 What is the difference after Rcd1? 22.exd5! White is setting up some energetic play, connceted with Ng5 and f2-f4, and pressure on the central files. Again, Black's b7-bishop is passive.}) 21. bxc4 cxd5 22. cxd5 Nc5 {So far, so good! We both pretty quickly ended up in this position as everything went according to the plans we both envisioned... Black is only one move away from completing his perfect setup.} 23. Bd3 $3 {This is the brilliant idea of Arshak's concept! This came as a total surprise to Nigel. Usually, in the Ruy Lopez, trading a bishop for a knight is taboo, but we have to be open to the rare exceptions! Practically, Black is in a very difficult situation as he is forced to make a very tough decision! I consider this game as the reward of systematic hard work. One can never be sure when we will get the chance to use something we worked on, but if we don't do the work, the answer is pretty clear: simply never!! I also believe that the most important thing is to enjoy the working process, and if we are able to hit the jackpot as happened in this game, then that is only a bonus!} ({After} 23. Bb1 {, Black has two possible continuations. I guess my opponent most probably would have played the more natural} Nfd7 {when White anyway needs to play} 24. Bd3 $1 {, which is clearly not consistent with the previous move... Instead, 23...Ba6!? is the extravaganza, and now not 24.Qxa5 Bd3! but 24.Bxc5 dxc5! I would love to highlight that this is a very double-edged strategic position because Black gets a lot of dynamics due to the ...c5-c4 push! Typically, if in such a structure, White can set up a blockade on the light square c4. In that case, White is in great shape; otherwise, it is always tricky! 25.Qxa5? Bh6! suddenly winning material! In contrast, if 24...Rxc5 25.Rxc5 dxc5 26.Qxa5 , here White can take.}) 23... h5 $2 {Total panic played after a very long think! One can wonder how come that strong players can make mistakes after thinking for too long. The answer is pretty simple: First, you look at the natural moves, and if you convince yourself that after the normal reaction, you end up in a position that you do not like or assume that it is the opponent's preparation, then finally the confusion can take over, and one can easily make a mistake based on emotional disbalance! I believe this has happened to all of us... Now the big question is: is playing Be3xc5 desirable for White or not?} ({A) Black simply can't play the normal way with} 23... Nfd7 {because after} 24. Bb5 {The white bishop will be unbearable in the long run!}) ({B)} 23... Nxd3 $1 {Biting the bullet and running with open arms into the opponent's prep was the only right way! But we all know how difficult it is to make such a decision...} 24. Rxc8+ $1 {Causing disharmony. Now, a very big question is how Black should recapture...} Rxc8 25. Qxd3 {is really bad now. 24...Bxc8! is key, but it is so easy not to understand this over the board! 25.Qxd3 Ba6 Where should the queen move? 26.Qa3! Yes, this is the optimal square, putting pressure on both weaknesses, the d6 and the a5-pawns. Remember we saw this [/variation/37803576/#/20/w/0.6] in the previous game? It is very easy to panic here with Black because White's play looks super easy, occupying one of the open files with the rook, and also, the knight transfer to the queenside via Nd2 is in the air. Humanly, this looks very unpleasant to a strong player from a distance, but now the computer tells us there is no need to panic... 'Tranquilo, with precise play, we can handle any pressure'... 26...Qd8! when 27.Rb1 is met by 27...Bf8! 28.Nd2 h5 and 27.Nd2 Bf8! 28.Rc1 h5! is a key sequence of engines, and somehow it is tough to find a way to confirm the advantage to the silicon beast...}) 24. Bxc5 $1 {The answer is absolutely yes! We also know the reasons why because we have a nice light-squared blockade, so we talk about pawn weaknesses instead of potential counterchances!} dxc5 {Honestly, I was spoiled with good options here, but since Black has a clear plan with ...Ne8-d6 I did not hesitate too long on my choice... What were my tempting options?} 25. Qg5 $1 {I instantly fell in love with this move, as it makes it so difficult for Black to achieve his knight maneuver.} (25. Nf1 $5 {If 25. Qg5 did not exist; then clearly, I would have played like this.} Ne8 26. Ne3 Bh6 27. Nf5 {beautiful! Or 26...Nd6 27.Nc4 and we achieve what I have been talking about previously; if we get a blockade on the c4-square, we are happy! In this case, both of Black's bishops are only spectators, not actors!}) 25... Rc7 {Setting up a trick... Let's try to understand what Black has in mind and why the e5-pawn isn't just hanging! If we have realized Black's trick, then what is our move?} (25... Qf8 26. Nf1 Ne8 27. N1d2 Nd6 28. Rc2 {. Black's point is 26.Nxe5!? Nh7 27.Qf4 Bh6 28.Qf3 Bxc1 29.Rxc1= $13}) 26. Nf1 $1 {Exactly, let us just start our strategically winning maneuver!} ({A)} 26. Bc4 {sets up a fancy idea, but since White is happy, there is no need for us to change the character of the battle!} Ne8 27. Qxg6 $5 fxg6 28. d6+ Kf8 29. dxe7+ Kxe7 30. Nh4 Kf6 $1 {and ...Bh6. After the queen trade and the transformation of the structure, it turns out that there's no direct win for White. My advice is always not to transform the position when we have the advantage if we'not getting anything better than what we already have. This is getting murky and thus, it is unnecessary.}) ({B)} 26. Qxe5 $2 Nxd5 $1 {The e5-pawn wasn't hanging!}) 26... Rac8 27. N1d2 {I knew that after natural moves I would be very happy. That is why one always needs to look out for some kamikaze continuation from the opponent...} Ne8 {The normal move.} ({The kamikaze line I wanted to be sure to have under control was} 27... c4 {What did I calculate here? A)} 28. Nxc4 Nxd5 $3 {What a trick!} 29. exd5 Qxg5 30. Nxg5 Bxd5 {and Black gets the piece back thanks to the pin. B) 28.Rxc4! Qa3 I know that probably many moves win, but the following was my main choice during the game. 29.Nxe5 Nh7 30.Qf4 Bxe5 31.Qxe5 Qxd3 32.Rxc7 Rxc7 33.Qxc7 Qxd2 After this forced sequence, I have the lovely 34.Rb1+- and Black's position is collapsing. I was very happy about this line!}) 28. Qxe7 Rxe7 29. Nc4 {I was in time to control everything. Black has many pawn weaknesses, and the black knight was not in time to get to d6...} Ba6 {The only practical attempt. How do we continue now?} 30. Nfxe5 $1 ({Yes, this is the most powerful.} 30. Ncxe5 Bxd3 31. Nxd3 c4 {would give some chances.}) 30... Bxe5 31. Nxe5 c4 (31... Bxd3 32. Nxd3 c4 33. e5 {It was beneficial for White to have traded the knight for the bishop.}) 32. Bxc4 Rxe5 33. Bxa6 Rxc1 34. Rxc1 Rxe4 {In my calculation, I have reached this position, and if I had not spotted the game continuation, I might have chosen a different option. Because being 'just a pawn up' with Black's knight finally reaching the desired d6 square would not have been to my liking! So, what did I notice when opting for 30. Nfxe5...?} 35. f3 $1 {Winning a tempo and making sure that I will have the f2-square for my king. Besides, I am setting up a devilish trap!} (35. Rc5 Re1+ $1 36. Kh2 h4 $1 {Instructive, Black boxes White's king.} 37. Rxa5 Nd6 38. Bd3 Kf8 {and Black is fighting!}) 35... Re5 36. Rc5 $1 h4 {How to proceed?} ({A)} 36... a4 37. d6 $1) ({B)} 36... Nf6 37. Rxa5) ({C) In this line we see what I had in mind with the Kf2 idea.} 36... Nd6 37. Rxa5 h4 38. Kf2 {or 37...Re1+ 38.Kf2 Rb1 39.Bd3 Rb2+ 40.Ke3 Rxg2 41.Ra6+-}) 37. d6 $3 Z0 (37... Rxc5 38. d7 {Personally, I find this as one of the most beautiful motifs in chess! Finishing a well-played strategic game with such a beautiful tactical move is an incredible pleasure! I can only sympathize with my opponent. His choice actually was very smart, knowing that I was coming from the World Championship match where the Classical Spanish was clearly not on the agenda. In fact, the problems facing Kramnik's Petroff forced me to switch to 1. d4 during the match! If not for the incredible episode with my training games prior to the event, it could have worked very well...}) 1-0

