14... Bb7 {) Strategically, this would be quite a legitimate line if we give Black only one extra move with ...Re8 to be ready to follow with ...Bf8! The only little problem is that it is White to move, and in fact, White has a very strong response here.} 15. a4 $1 {This is the refutation of Black's concept! Black actually faces concrete problems here. Now we see why the d4-knight stays on d4 (putting pressure on the b5-pawn). Once the b5-pawn moves, that will enable White´s other knight, which is on d2, to join the party on the vulnerable c4-square. We can conclude that thanks to the timely a2-a4 move, both White's knights suddenly become very mobile!} ({A) After the 'natural'} 15. Nf1 Re8 16. Ng3 Bf8 {this is a very nice healthy classical Spanish position for Black!}) ({B) Also, going directly after the dark-squared bishop is not the spirit:} 15. Nf5 Re8 {Planning ...Bf8. After capturing the e7-bishop, Black gets a lot of activity, and the pressure against the e4-pawn makes it impossible to enjoy the benefit of the pair of bishops!}) 15... bxa4 (15... Qb6 $1 {The best move, but no fun for Black either. Later, White will get a lovely tempo with Be3...}) 16. Nf5 $1 Nc5 17. Nc4 $1 {This is the key move! We see the benefit again of 15. a4!} Bxe4 {This loses material; otherwise, the position is simply bad.} 18. Bxe4 Ncxe4 {This was played in the game [/variation/38709584] Morozevich-Grischuk Dubai Blitz Armageddon 2002.�} 19. f3 $1 d5 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Nb6 Qa7 22. Be3 {White is winning.} *

