1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 c5 {A tricky move which has a very direct purpose (to trick the opponent!) but if we know the strategical idea behind it this case we can very easily handle it. In this game, Black's idea backfired like a boomerang because I knew my stuff!} 12. Bc2 $1 {Keeping the tension and not falling into Black's strategical trap. It is also common knowledge that if we have the center (like here with pawns e4, d4 vs e5, d6), we should keep the tension as long as possible and usually only change the status quo if we gain other strategic benefits.} ({Black's idea is to provoke} 12. d5 $6 {, but why would we release the tension in the center by closing it with d4-d5 when we notice that Black´s c8-bishop would be ideally placed in that case!} c4 13. Bc2 {The only justification would be if we can get a quick b2-b3 in, but Black can stop that easily with} Qc7 $1 14. Nf1 a5 {, and this is a very interesting position for Black with powerful counterplay on the queenside. This is a dream come true for any classical Spanish player with Black.} 15. Ng3 Nc5 {Black has a clear plan on the queenside of pushing ...b4, while controlling the f5-square on the kingside.}) 12... cxd4 (12... Qc7 {we can simply ignore Black and continue with useful moves like} 13. Nf1 {or also 13.b3!? It Is typical in such positions to have the d4-d5 idea in mind when Black no longer can block us with ...c5-c4!}) 13. cxd4 exd4 (13... Bb7 {How do we typically react in such a situation?} 14. d5 $14 {If we lock that bishop out of the game, this would be a clear benefit! We will also be able to target Black´s queenside with a2-a4 with a clear advantage. After 14.Nf1 exd4 15.Nxd4 Re8 , White has some issues with the e4-pawn, and Black has the typical regrouping ...g6-...Bf8-...Bg7.}) 14. Nxd4 Bb7 {Strategically, this would be quite a legitimate line if we give Black only one extra move with ...Re8 to be ready to follow with ...Bf8! The only little problem is that it is White to move, and in fact, White has a very strong response here.} 15. a4 $1 {This is the refutation of Black's concept! Black actually faces concrete problems here. Now we see why the d4-knight stays on d4 (putting pressure on the b5-pawn). Once the b5-pawn moves, that will enable White´s other knight, which is on d2, to join the party on the vulnerable c4-square. We can conclude that thanks to the timely a2-a4 move, both White's knights suddenly become very mobile!} ({After the 'natural'} 15. Nf1 Re8 16. Ng3 Bf8 {is a very nice healthy classical Spanish position for Black!}) ({Also, going directly after the dark-squared bishop is not the spirit:} 15. Nf5 Re8 {Planning ...Bf8. After capturing the e7-bishop, Black gets a lot of activity, and the pressure against the e4-pawn makes it impossible to enjoy the benefit of the pair of bishops!} 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {with ...Rac8 and ...d5 coming, while White's pieces are clumsy, or 16...Rxe7 intending ...Rc8 and ...Qe8, with pressure on the e4-pawn.}) 15... b4 (15... bxa4 16. Nf5 $1 Nc5 17. Nc4 $1 {This is the key move! We see the benefit again of 15.a4!} Bxe4 {loses material; otherwise, the position is simply bad.} 18. Bxe4 Ncxe4 {This was played in the game [/variation/38709584] Morozevich-Grischuk Dubai Blitz Armageddon 2002.�} 19. f3 $1 d5 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Nb6 Qa7 22. Be3) (15... Qb6 $1 {The best move, but no fun for Black either. Later, White will get a lovely tempo with Be3...} 16. Nf5 {White has pressure on the a-file.} Rfe8 17. Nf1 {and Be3 is coming.}) 16. Nf5 $1 {Now Black's position is simply falling apart because he needs to waste one tempo on stopping Nd2-c4! Small but decisive nuance!} Rc8 {Necessary move, but in this case, White gets the extra tempo needed to make maximal use of the f5-knight!} (16... Re8 17. Nc4 d5 18. Ncd6 {exploits the weakness of d6.}) 17. Nf1 {Maybe I could have played better in the next moves, but it was simply impossible to choose from so many great options. Besides, I was surprised myself how big an advantage I got thanks to knowing the 15. a2-a4 finesse.} (17. Nf3 $5 {Somehow exactly this move I had not on my radar!} Re8 18. Bf4 $1) 17... Nc5 (17... Re8 18. Bf4 Ne5 19. Nxe7+ Rxe7 20. Ng3 $16 {is strategically huge for White. 18...Bf8 19.Nxd6 Bxd6 20.Bxd6 Bxe4 21.Bxe4 Nxe4 22.Bxb4! It was quite important to understand from the distance that this works, and basically calculating this line took my attention away from the other alternatives...}) 18. N1g3 (18. Bf4 {For some reason, I did not consider this move, probably I was too happy...}) 18... Re8 19. Bg5 $1 h6 (19... Bf8 20. Nh5 $1 {and the pin is annoying.}) 20. Nxe7+ {I decided to be practical. Knowing that I had an enormous advantage, I felt there was no need for fancy tactics.} (20. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 21. Nxh6+ Kf8 {What does the engine have in mind that I had missed?} 22. Bb3 $3 {Honestly, I had missed this strong computer move during the game, but actually now when I took a closer look, I noticed that Black has defensive resources.} d5 23. e5 Nfe4 24. Qh5 {22...Nxb3 23.Qxb3 with a mating threat on f7. 23...d5 How is White winning here? 24.e5 is met by 24...Ng8! but White has 24.Ngf5! and the queen is transferred to the kingside. 24...Ng8 25.Qg3 Bg5 26.Nxg8 Kxg8 27.h4+- 22...Ne6! 23.Nhf5 Rc5! 24.Qd2 Ng8 and apart of compensation there is no clarity here! Good illustration of why we don´t need to play for the galleries when we have the clearly better position!}) 20... Qxe7 21. Nf5 Qe6 22. Bxf6 Qxf6 23. Nxd6 Red8 24. e5 {Winning a healthy pawn and cementing the knight on d6 was too tempting.} Qg5 25. g3 {And I went on to win the game without much effort.} *

