1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 Bg7 16. d5 Rc8 $5 ({I have always considered this as the main move for Black with the idea to get to 'Spassky's brilliant piece sac position.' After} 16... Rc8 {, Black is ready to push ...c7-c6 because after dxc6 the pawn is no longer hanging on d6 due to Rxc6! Here are Black's alternatives:}) ({A)} 16... Bf8 $6 {This looks weird.} 17. Bg5 h6 18. Be3 c6 19. c4 a5 20. Qd2 {White got the dream in the game [/variation/38709585] Polgar, J (2595)-Spassky, B (2565) Budapest (Match/2) 1993. �}) ({B)} 16... Nb6 17. Be3 c6 $1 {Black missed the beautiful positional pawn sac idea not only in the original Polgar-Spassky game, but also one year later in the Candidates matches between Kamsky-Van der Sterren we have seen the same story! Looking at it with modern eyes, one would have real difficulty understanding how that is possible, but the explanation is rather simple: Spassky's brilliancy has blinded everyone! ( 17...Rc8 18.Qe2 c6 19.c4 is the tabiya.)} 18. dxc6 {White has no other choice.} Bxc6 19. Bxb6 Qxb6 20. Qxd6 {White has won a pawn but had to give up the dark-squared bishop! This is not my spirit!} Rad8 21. Qa3 {now} Bh6 $5 {is also a very powerful diagonal. This bishop is a monster! Bf8 and} 22. b4 {intending the thematic Bb3 is met by Bh6! and ...Bf4 putting pressure on the e4-pawn. 22.Qb2 b4! and Black has lovely compensation thanks to the dark square control. 17.Rb1!! The improvement! See the Leko-Beliavsky [/variation/37803576] game.}) ({C)} 16... Qe7 $5 {See the Leko-Short [/variation/37806095] game.}) ({D)} 16... Qb8 {was played in the game [/variation/38709586] Polgar, J-Short, Wijk aan Zee 2005. �}) 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 Nb6 $1 19. Qe2 $1 {Now by transposition we have reached back to the Polgar-Spassky game, which is the tabiya.} cxd5 20. cxd5 Nbxd5 $1 {This is a brilliant positional piece sacrifice! Even more than 30 years later, I am still under the influence of this sensational idea!} 21. exd5 Nxd5 {I can imagine the shock and sensation when this first happens to somebody!} 22. Rac1 $3 {The advantage of the engines is that they hardly get shocked, and they simply try to find the best moves under any condition...} Nxe3 $5 {Positional choice with its own tremendous nuances! Since this game was played in the early '90s, I assume that black would have opted for} (22... Nc3 23. Qd2 Nxa2 24. Ra1 Nc3 {Because, once again, only engines can evaluate this position as an advantage for White, I was never sure about this position (the brilliancy of Spassky had a special effect on me!), and only in recent years, thanks to super engines, am I willing to agree that the position is dangerous for Black if we face someone with stunningly deep preparation.}) 23. fxe3 d5 ({My intuition would say this is just unclear... Again, some extra strong moves from the engines are required so that we understand that White's chances are preferable! Actually, this position was debated in many modern correspondence games, and all of them featured the} 23... d5 {move... (In older times, my file (dating back to around 2010) simply said)}) (23... Qb6 $5 {with enough compensation and I never felt the energy to analyze positions whose look I do not like. By the way, this is still a novelty! This is a true problem of our modern times: who do we believe, our inner feelings or the silicon monster...? Now, for the sake of my first Chessable course, I continued the analysis just to have a more modern picture of the real happenings! The position is extremely rich for both sides, so for real opening fanatics, there is plenty of room left for analysis even after my work...}) 24. b4 $3 {Key move! The white bishop belongs to b3. This is the only reason why White can be potentially better!} Qd6 25. Qf2 $1 {Giving up the third pawn just like this in order to get maximum coordination!} (25. Qd2 $5 {is the other critical option, but here} Bh6 $5 {is a bit bothering.}) 25... Qxb4 26. Bb3 $1 {The logical follow-up. White will soon put pressure on f7.} *

