1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 Bg7 16. d5 Rc8 $5 ({I have always considered this as the main move for Black with the idea to get to 'Spassky's brilliant piece sac position.' After} 16... Rc8 {, Black is ready to push ...c7-c6 because after dxc6 the pawn is no longer hanging on d6 due to Rxc6!}) ({A)} 16... Bf8 $6 {This looks weird.} 17. Bg5 {Very nice little touch! Showing that Judit had excellent feeling for the position. Often in this variation we have the option to either play Bc1-g5 or Bc1-e3. Once we are really inside the position, I believe our intuition will guide us correctly. In this concrete position, it is obvious that Bg5 is the even more precise move because Black will probaly react with ...h7-h6 which, after the return of our bishop to e3, will give us the lovely extra Qd1-d2 tempo (hitting the h6-pawn!).} h6 18. Be3 c6 19. c4 a5 20. Qd2 {White got the dream in the game [/variation/38709585] Polgar, J (2595)-Spassky, B (2565) Budapest (Match/2) 1993. �}) ({B)} 16... Nb6 17. Be3 c6 $1 {Black missed the beautiful positional pawn sac idea not only in the original Polgar-Spassky game, but also one year later in the Candidates matches between Kamsky-Van der Sterren we have seen the same story! Looking at it with modern eyes, one would have real difficulty understanding how that is possible, but the explanation is rather simple: Spassky's brilliancy has blinded everyone! ( 17...Rc8 18.Qe2 c6 19.c4 is the tabiya.)} 18. dxc6 {White has no other choice.} Bxc6 19. Bxb6 Qxb6 20. Qxd6 {White has won a pawn but had to give up the dark-squared bishop! This is not my spirit!} Rad8 21. Qa3 {now} Bh6 $5 {is also a very powerful diagonal. This bishop is a monster! Bf8 and} 22. b4 {intending the thematic Bb3 is met by Bh6! and ...Bf4 putting pressure on the e4-pawn. 22.Qb2 b4! and Black has lovely compensation thanks to the dark square control. 17.Rb1!! The improvement! See the Leko-Beliavsky [/variation/37803576] game.}) ({C)} 16... Qe7 $5 {See the Leko-Short [/variation/37806095] game.}) ({D)} 16... Qb8 {was played in the game [/variation/38709586] Polgar, J-Short, Wijk aan Zee 2005. �}) 17. c4 c6 18. Be3 ({Here, obviously, the most natural move, instead of} 18. Bg5 {.}) 18... Nb6 $1 {Putting the pressure on White's pawn chain!} 19. Qe2 $1 {Now by transposition we have reached back to the Polgar-Spassky game, which is the tabiya.} (19. Bd3 {would be the ideal move, but it runs into a typical nice little Breyer tactic!} cxd5 20. cxd5 Nbxd5 $1 21. exd5 e4 {and Black is OK. Here, Black does not only win back the piece, but also both his bishops get into life!}) 19... cxd5 20. cxd5 Nbxd5 $1 {This is a brilliant positional piece sacrifice! Even more than 30 years later, I am still under the influence of this sensational idea!} 21. exd5 Nxd5 {I can imagine the shock and sensation when this first happens to somebody!} 22. Rac1 $3 {The advantage of the engines is that they hardly get shocked, and they simply try to find the best moves under any condition...} (22. b4 $5 {Judit instantly sensed the right idea, but the execution was not perfect; who could have faulted her? We are writing 1993! How should Black play here? A)} Nxb4 23. Bb3 Bd5 {A very instructive moment!} 24. Rec1 {or 24.Rac1!? ( 24.Red1? Bc4! So easy to miss, but this move should have never been allowed! Now Black got a great position in the game [/variation/38709581] Polgar, J (2595)-Spassky, B (2565) Budapest (Match/10) 1993. � Instead, after 24...Bxb3 25.axb3 , White has pressure on the a6-pawn.) 24...Bxb3 25.axb3 d5 26.Rxc8 Qxc8 27.Rc1 Qd7 28.Qd2 a5 29.Bh6 Bh8 is humanly far from clear, but if the computer says it is clearly better for White, then it is hard to argue... B) 22...Nxe3! Black missed a nice, forced line here. 23.fxe3 Bxf3! Giving up the soul humanly is never easy!! 24.gxf3 e4! The omputer is happy for Black, but actually, the position is still very tricky! 25.f4! Keeping the center closed. 25...Bxa1 26.Rxa1 Qf6 This is the point of the computer's play. Black goes for a forced double attack. 27.Rd1 Qe6 28.Bb3 Qxh3 29.Qg2 Qxg2+ 30.Kxg2 and despite the fact that Black has three pawns plus a rook vs two minor pieces, thanks to the 'Cemento construction,' White should not be worse!}) ({A classy idea was tried by Kamsky one year later with} 22. Be4 $2 Nc3 23. Bxb7 Nxe2+ 24. Nxe2 {White is planning to set up a light squared blockade with Bb7-d5, if the Black rook moves... How should Black react?} d5 $17 {yes, this classy counter-idea destroyed White's hopes in the game [/variation/38709587] Kamsky-Van der Sterren Candidates match 1994. �} 25. Bxc8 Qxc8 {with a powerful duo of central pawns fighting White's clumsy pieces. Instead, 24...Rb8 25.Bd5 allows White to set up a powerful blockade.}) 22... Nxe3 $5 {Positional choice with its own tremendous nuances!} ({Since this game was played in the early '90s, I assume that Black would have opted for} 22... Nc3 23. Qd2 Nxa2 24. Ra1 Nc3 {Because, once again, only engines can evaluate this position as an advantage for White, I was never sure about this position (the brilliancy of Spassky had a special effect on me!), and only in recent years, thanks to super engines, am I willing to agree that the position is dangerous for Black if we face someone with stunningly deep preparation. Now,} 25. Bh6 $5 Bh8 26. b4 $1 {is the other possible move order, while 26.Nh2 b4 27.Ng4 d5 28.f4 e4 29.f5 d4 $13 was the game [/variation/38709588] Shirov-Tarjan 2016. � 25.b4! Already, the young Hikaru Nakamura knew that this was the key move. Usually, young players are known to be flexible, and they always know how to use technology for maximum performance! 25...d5 and now: A) 26.Bb3 Hikaru probably knew the b4 idea and assumed it is connected with Bb3 ideas. Often, when we go along computer lines, it is better to make sure we really know what the computer has in mind; otherwise, we can easily burn ourselves! 26...d4 27.Bg5 Qd6 28.Bh6 Qf6 is the computer’s line. 26...Qe7 27.Bh6 was the game [/variation/38709589] Nakamura-Golod 2009, � and Black should play 27...f6 $132 . The computer’s suggestion is 27.Bc5 but no good player would let Black sacrifice the rook on c5 in such positions! 27...Rxc5 28.bxc5 Qxc5 29.Qe3! Again, without engines this is just unclear! Or 28...e4 29.c6!! Bxc6 30.Rxa6 Qb7 White’s rook and knight are threatened now. 31.Nd4!! Qxa6 32.Qxc3 Black’s central pawns are blockaded, and White’s rook will playo n the a- or c-file. The computer gives advantage... C'mon... B) 26.Bh6! Bh8 and in this totally crazy messy position, which we would have simply stopped analyzing prior to super engine times, the computer comes up with some unimaginable superhuman play... 27.Ra3!! The start of a very, very deep idea! I believe before the supercomputer era, it would have been impossible to come up with this. 27...d4 28.Ng5! What? One move on the left side, then one on the right and so on...? The reason why I am highlighting this is that once we see engine moves, we can somehow already try to make sense of them, but humanly often, it is just impossible to think of the sequence of moves that the computers come up with! And how often if we try to play the computer idea with a wrong move order then it already does not work!! This is one of the trickiest/most dangerous things we are facing in today's modern chess! Now the explanation is kinda: 'Aha, of course we should target the weak f7-pawn...' 28...Qd6 targeting b4. 29.Rea1!! This is some completely different planet! Again, once we see it, it is already explainable: 'Aha, we target the a6-pawn so that after Bc2-b3 Black will not have the natural ...Bb7-d5 move due to the hanging pawn on a6...' 29...Qxb4 30.Bb3 Finally, the bishop has landed on the desired diagonal. It is still way too early for White to open a bottle of Champagne... 30...Rc4! Lovely positional exchange sac, in fact already a rook sac, as we have already sacrificed a piece earlier. Black is still very much in the game! ( 30...Rc7 31.N3e4!! Incredible how beautifully all of White´s pieces are joining the battle.) 31.f3!! Without this move all of White's play would mean nothing! Very instructive how White is in no rush to collect material, and instead sticks to the approach of improving the position to the maximum! 31...f5 32.Kh1! This position is very dangerous for Black. But basically, only thanks to us knowing engines are happy here for White, can we feel really secure with White! All this was some insanely phenomenal stuff and the game is anyway only beginning...}) 23. fxe3 d5 ({My intuition would say this is just unclear... Again, some extra strong moves from the engines are required so that we understand that White's chances are preferable! Actually, this position was debated in many modern correspondence games, and all of them featured the} 23... d5 {move...}) ({In older times, my file (dating back to around 2010) simply said} 23... Qb6 $5 {with enough compensation and I never felt the energy to analyze positions whose look I do not like. By the way, this is still a novelty! This is a true problem of our modern times: who do we believe, our inner feelings or the silicon monster...? Now, for the sake of my first Chessable course, I continued the analysis just to have a more modern picture of the real happenings! The position is extremely rich for both sides, so for real opening fanatics, there is plenty of room left for analysis even after my work...} 24. Qf2 $5 {is an alternative here, but it is the main move, as we will see, with Black's pawn provoked to h6! Now there is the surprising} Bh6 $3 {with pressure on both dark-sqaured diagonals, which is annoying. By now, we know 24.b4! is standard. 24...e4 Best. 25.Nd2 d5 ( 25...Bb2 26.Nb3! Going for the blockading strategy. 26...Bxc1 27.Rxc1 Rc3 28.Nd4 Rec8 29.Qd2 White will soon play Nge2, kicking the rook out of c3. After Rf1, the bishop can move to b3 and put extra pressure on f7.) 26.Qf2 Qd6! and now it seems that White has two different options leading to completely different play. ( 26...Bb2 27.Nb3! We already know the 'cemento spirit' move! 27...Rc4 28.Ne2! Reinforcing the control of the d4 square! 28...Rec8 29.Nbd4 Qc7 30.Rf1 Insanely precise play by our silicon friend... 30...Bxc1 31.Rxc1 with a firm blockade on d4.) A) 27.Bb3 Rxc1 28.Rxc1 Qxb4 29.Ndxe4 Qe7 30.Nd2 a5! Key move! Black is aiming to break the cemento construction of the b3-bishop and I am still not convinced that White is better! If instead 30...Qxe3 31.Qxe3 Rxe3 32.Rc7 Rxg3 33.Rxb7 Rd3 34.Nf3 , White will target d5 and f7. B) 27.Nb3!? Completely different concept. 27...Qxb4 28.Nd4 Qb2! 29.Nge2 Qxa2 30.Rf1 Rc7 31.Bb3 Qa5 is a fascinating position. Black has four pawns (!) + the two bishops, but White's outpost on d4 suddenly gives White the compensation... 31.Bxe4!? Winning back one of the pawns, but it opens up the position... 31...Rd7! 32.Ra1 Qd2 33.Rad1 Qb4 34.Bc2 Qe7 35.Rd3 Rc8 36.Rfd1 with dynamic equality. White will put pressure on the d5-pawn.}) 24. b4 $3 {Key move! The white bishop belongs to b3. This is the only reason why White can be potentially better!} Qd6 (24... e4 25. Nd4 Rc3 26. Qf2 $1 Bxd4 27. exd4 Qc7 {Looks like fantastic compensation due to the strong pin, but White can handle it!} 28. Re3 $5 {Other idea of super engine might even be stronger! ( 28.Nf1 f5 29.g3! and Ne3 is coming. This is another important correspondance game!)} Rc4 29. Re2 f5 30. Nf1 f4 {How to react here with White?} 31. Rce1 $3 {intending Bb3 next.} e3 $2 {runs into White´s main idea ( 31...Kg7 32.Bb3 Rc3 33.Nh2 $16 )} 32. Nxe3 $1 fxe3 33. Rxe3 Rf8 34. Re8 $1 {or 33...Rxe3 34.Qxe3+- with terrific attack without any sacrifices! The b7-bishop is again passive.}) 25. Qf2 $1 {Giving up the third pawn just like this in order to get maximum coordination!} (25. Qd2 $5 {is the other critical option, but here} Bh6 $5 {is a bit bothering.}) 25... Qxb4 26. Bb3 $1 Rxc1 (26... Qe7 27. Rxc8 Rxc8 28. e4 $1 {The thematic idea once the bishop has reached the ideal b3-square, and now: A)} d4 $2 {How could White react here?} 29. Ng5 Qxg5 30. Qxf7+ Kh8 31. Qxb7 {White keeps the extra piece. B) 28...dxe4? What's is the tactical justification of White`s play? 29.Ng5! targeting f7 29...Qxg5 30.Qxf7+ Kh8 31.Qxb7 and the e4-pawn drops next. C) 28...Qc5 29.Qxc5 Rxc5 30.Rd1 d4 31.Ng5! Bf6 32.Bxf7+ Important that due to the fork (Ng5-e6), this works well. 32...Kh8 33.h4 h6 34.Nf3 Kg7 35.Bd5!? Such moves are my favourite! This is also Cemento spirit! White sacrifices material in order to strategically improve his position to the maximum. 35...Bxd5 36.exd5 Rxd5 37.Ne4 and suddenly, thanks to our monster knight (which was just a few moves ago our headache!) White can enjoy torturing Black in this endgame. Beautiful transformation!}) 27. Rxc1 Qe7 28. Rd1 $1 {The c-file is absolutely unimportant at the moment. The play is all around the d5-pawn and the fact that we somehow need to open up the a2-g8 diagonal.} Rd8 29. e4 $1 {All this sequence of moves is needed to finally claim the advantage. Opening up the a2-g8 diagonal is the key concept. Super impressive...} d4 {This is a giant step for White, to have forced Black to play ...d5-d4!} (29... dxe4 $2 30. Rxd8+ Qxd8 31. Ng5 $1 {Targeting f7. Always the same...} Qxg5 $2 32. Qxf7+ Kh8 {and now White doesn't take the bishop!} 33. Qg8# {or 31...Qd4 32.Nxf7+-}) 30. Qd2 $1 {Preparing Ng5.} Bf6 31. Rf1 Kg7 {Interesting question: how to evaluate? Can White play Nf3-g5 or not?} (31... Rf8 32. Qa5 Qd6 33. h4 Kg7 34. h5 Bc8 35. Rc1 {All this happened in the fantastic game [/variation/38788750] Tomilin, A (2308)-Gerhards, G (2303) ICCF email 2021. � Big respect!}) 32. Ng5 $5 {Yes, we can!} Rf8 (32... Bxg5 $2 33. Rxf7+ Qxf7 34. Qxg5 {White wins decisive material or mates Black.} Qf8 {What is the exact finishing touch?} 35. Nh5+ $1 Kh8 36. Qxe5+ {and mate is coming.}) 33. h4 h5 $14 {Bit of a sad move because now the knight remains on g5 , which should give White the better chances, but it is still very far from being obvious that White is really better in a practical game... ( 33...h6 Time for tactics! 34.Nxf7!! Rxf7 35.Bxf7 Qxf7 36.h5 $16 I always love to finish tactics with a calm little move... White will get the f5-square for the knight. The reason why I wanted to present our dear Chessable readers with all these lines is to give a feeling of what it takes on the highest level to do preparation! Objectively, it does feel like White is pressing if he knows every single detail, but things are still far from clear. This is how a World Championship level preparation could look like. Seeing this, I think we can better understand how much pressure the players are feeling when playing a classical World Championship Match! Believe me, it is brutal! Finally, we can honestly ask ourselves the question: would we be happy if all this came on board? I think the answer is often, a very big 'I AM NOT SO SURE'!} *

