1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 Bg7 16. d5 Rc8 17. c4 c6 18. Bg5 $5 {My old big hope! It was one of the finesses I had around 2010 to counter the 16...Rc8 idea, but things also got out of control here...} h6 19. Be3 Nb6 20. Qe2 (20. Rb1 Qc7 $1 {and} 21. Bd3 {will be the first stop in our journey through the differences and similarities between these positions and those with the pawn on h7. 21.dxc6 As we already know, whenever we are forced to play this move and we have no direct benefits, that means Black will have a good long-term position! 21...Bxc6 22.cxb5 axb5 23.Qd2 Kh7 24.Rbc1 Nbd7 25.Red1 Bf8 Black was perfectly fine in the game [/variation/38709590] Landa-Kamsky 2008.�}) 20... cxd5 21. cxd5 Nbxd5 22. exd5 Nxd5 23. Rac1 {We have the same Polgar-Spassky tabiya, however, with the provoked ...h7-h6 move.} *

