23. Rac1 {How should Black continue? Does the h6-pawn change anything here?} Nxe3 $1 ({First of all, now} 23... Nc3 $2 {is not an option at all due to the hanging h6-pawn! In 2010, I was very far from ruling out the ...Nd5-c3 move in the original tabiya position with pawn on h7, so this was a real temptation behind the 18.Bg5 move order.}) 24. fxe3 {Very interesting to compare the two positions with each other. Everything is the same, only here, Black`s pawn is on h6. It is fascinating that just this little detail can change the whole dynamic of the position. It turns out that if Black plays the same way as with pawn on h7, in this case, White can benefit. However, there is one concrete line where the ...h6 move benefits Black! This was enough to destroy my big hope of 18.Bg5 being the key to happiness... So, let's take a look at what we are dealing with.} e4 $1 {This anti-positional move is the problem! Again, a small detail with a very huge impact...} (24... Qb6 {'My move' is here met by} 25. Qf2 $1 {If we remember correctly, I have already highlighted that here with the pawn on h7 Black has the annoying ...Bh6 move. Now, this is impossible! ( 25.b4!? is also possible, but if we have the chance to play 25.Qf2, then it is better to do so.)} d5 26. b4 {This always looked good for White.} Bf8 27. Rf1 $1 {Setting up the pressure on the f7-pawn, and Black can't play} Bxb4 $2 {due to} 28. Nxe5 $1) (24... d5 {is another option I'll quiz you about.}) 25. Nd4 Qg5 $1 {Here this is a very important idea! This is how Black can make good use of the ...h6 move!} 26. Qg4 $1 {And here, thanks to the protected queen, Black does not need to react to Qg4, instead can go for...} Rc3 $1 {Still a novelty. I found this move/concept so beautiful and instructive. I believe that we can learn so much from the following lines!} (26... Bxd4 27. Qxg5 hxg5 {Whenever the queen trade happens on g5, with ...hxg5 Black dramatically improves the structure!} 28. exd4 b4 29. Bb1 {and here,} f5 30. Rc4 $1 {was still giving me hope to fight for advantage. Here White can put concrete problems. Instead, after 29...d5 Still a novelty. 30.Rc2! Rxc2 31.Bxc2 Rc8 32.Rc1 f5 33.Ne2 Kf7 34.Bd1 Rxc1 35.Nxc1 , I am not sure if White can really have real chances to break Black`s fortress, but it is certainly not a given that Black holds this....}) 27. Qxg5 hxg5 {Black's pawn structure improves, and what I mean by it will soon be very visible!} *

