28. Bb1 {How should Black react?} Rxe3 $3 {This is not just a simple tactic. In reality this is a positional rook sacrifice!} (28... Bxd4 $2 29. exd4 Rxg3 30. Kf2 {would win for White.}) 29. Nde2 $1 {With the idea of trapping the rook, but Black has a fantastic concept to fight it...} d5 $1 30. Kf2 (30. Nf1 Rxe2 31. Rxe2 Bd4+ 32. Kh1 Bb6 {similar spirit as the mainline.}) 30... Rxg3 $1 31. Nxg3 (31. Kxg3 d4 $1 {White's pieces can't be activated. Notice Rc7 is prevented by the check on e5.}) 31... Bd4+ $1 {I am always in love with such quiet little key moves!} 32. Kf1 Bb6 {Black has 'only' 3 pawns for the rook but has total CEMENTO! Look at those black bishops and Black's pawn structure! On the other hand, White's bishop on b1 is pretty dead, the knight has nowhere to go, the rooks have no target, and White's king is also a potential target... The quick summary is that White can't play for any advantage here!} *

