1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 Bg7 16. d5 Rc8 17. c4 c6 18. Bg5 $5 {My old big hope! It was one of the finesses I had around 2010 to counter the 16...Rc8 idea, but things also got out of control here...} h6 19. Be3 {It is pretty amazing how the 18.Bg5 h6 inclusion changes the dynamic of the position...} Nb6 20. Qe2 (20. Rb1 Qc7 $1 21. dxc6 {As we already know, whenever we are forced to play this move and we have no direct benefits, that means Black will have a good long-term position!} Bxc6 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Qd2 Kh7 24. Rbc1 Nbd7 25. Red1 Bf8 {Black was perfectly fine in the game [/variation/38709590] Landa-Kamsky 2008.� 21.Bd3 cxd5 22.cxd5 Nbxd5! Again the same typical tactical shot. 23.exd5 e4 $132}) 20... cxd5 21. cxd5 Nbxd5 22. exd5 Nxd5 {Now we have the same Polgar-Spassky tabiya, however, with the provoked ...h7-h6 move.} 23. Rac1 Nxe3 $1 ({First of all, now} 23... Nc3 $2 {is not an option at all due to the hanging h6-pawn after} 24. Qd2 Nxa2 25. Ra1 Nc3 26. Bxh6 $1 {In 2010, I was very far from ruling out the ...Nd5-c3 move in the original tabiya position with pawn on h7, so this was a real temptation behind the 18.Bg5 move order.}) 24. fxe3 {Very interesting to compare the two positions with each other. Everything is the same, only here, Black`s pawn is on h6. It is fascinating that just this little detail can change the whole dynamic of the position. It turns out that if Black plays the same way as with the pawn on h7, in this case, White can benefit. However, there is one concrete line where the ...h6 move benefits Black! This was enough to destroy my big hope of 18.Bg5 being the key to happiness... So, let's take a look at what we are dealing with.} e4 $1 {This anti-positional move is the problem! Again, a small detail with a very huge impact...} (24... Qb6 {Now} 25. b4 $5 {is possible, but if we have the chance to play 25.Qf2, then it is better to do so. 25.Qf2! If we remember correctly, I have already highlighted that here with the pawn on h7, Black has the annoying ...Bh6 move. Now, this is impossible! 25...d5 26.b4 This always looked good for White. 26...Bf8 27.Rf1! Setting up the pressure on the f7-pawn. Black can't play 27...Bxb4? due to 28.Nxe5!}) (24... d5 25. b4 $1 Qd6 26. Qd2 {Without the ...h6 move, Black had the annoying ...Bh6 idea in this position! Now again, this move is not possible...} Bf8 {( 26...e4 27.Nxe4+- )} 27. Qf2 Qxb4 28. Bb3 {Going for the thematic ideas we discussed with the pawn on h7.}) 25. Nd4 Qg5 $1 {Here this is a very important idea! This is how Black can make good use of the ...h6 move!} 26. Qg4 $1 {And here, thanks to the protected queen, Black does not need to react to Qg4, instead can go for...} Rc3 $1 {Still a novelty. I found this move/concept so beautiful and instructive. I believe that we can learn so much from the following lines!} (26... Bxd4 27. Qxg5 hxg5 {Whenever the queen trade happens on g5, with ...hxg5 Black dramatically improves the structure!} 28. exd4 b4 29. Bb1 {( 29.Bxe4 Rxc1 30.Rxc1 Bxe4 or 29.Nxe4 Bxe4 and Black wins back the piece.)} f5 30. Rc4 $1 {was still giving me hope to fight for advantage. Here White can put concrete problems.} Rxc4 31. bxc4 {with two mobile pawns. 29...d5 Still a novelty. 30.Rc2! Rxc2 31.Bxc2 Rc8 32.Rc1 f5 33.Ne2 Kf7 34.Bd1 Rxc1 35.Nxc1 I am not sure if White can really have real chances to break Black's fortress, but it is certainly not a given that Black holds this... 35...f4 36.Bg4 Next, White will prepare g2-g3. 36...a5 37.Kf2 Kf6 38.Ne2 Bc6 39.g3 with pressure on the f4-pawn. 39...f3 40.Ng1 White has set a blockade. 40...Bb5 41.Ke3 with the idea of pushing h3-h4 and gain the f4-square for the knight.}) 27. Qxg5 hxg5 {Black's pawn structure improves, and what I mean by it will soon be very visible!} 28. Bb1 (28. Nge2 Rxe3 29. Kf2 {Tactics!} Rc3 $3 {beautiful. ( 29...Bxd4 30.Nxd4 Rxe1 is also possible.)}) (28. Nde2 Rcc8 $1 {Important.} 29. Bb1 f5 30. Red1 d5 {with good compensation. After 28...Rxe3 29.Kf2 Rxg3 30.Nxg3 d5 31.b4! , we see that here White can quickly activate the bishop, which makes all the difference.}) 28... Rxe3 $3 {This is not just a simple tactic. In reality this is a positional rook sacrifice!} (28... Bxd4 $2 29. exd4 Rxg3 30. Kf2 {would win for White.}) 29. Nde2 $1 {With the idea of trapping the rook, but Black has a fantastic concept to fight it...} (29. Rxe3 Bxd4 30. Kf2 f5 {was Black's point.}) 29... d5 $1 30. Kf2 (30. Nf1 Rxe2 31. Rxe2 Bd4+ 32. Kh1 Bb6 {with a similar spirit.}) 30... Rxg3 $1 31. Nxg3 (31. Kxg3 d4 $1 {White's pieces can't be activated. Notice Rc7 is prevented by the check on e5.}) 31... Bd4+ $1 {I am always in love with such quiet little key moves!} 32. Kf1 Bb6 {Black has 'only' 3 pawns for the rook but has total CEMENTO! Look at those black bishops and Black's pawn structure! On the other hand, White's bishop on b1 is pretty dead, the knight has nowhere to go, the rooks have no target, and White's king is also a potential target... The quick summary is that White can't play for any advantage here!} 33. b4 $1 Re6 $1 {Very important move! It destroys White`s hope to jump out thanks to some tactical trick.} (33... f5 $2 {This natural move, with the attitude of let's close the eyes and go, would spoil everything!} 34. Ne2 $1 d4 {How to punish the premature pawn advances?} 35. Red1 Rd8 {How to punish Black? ( 35...d3 What is happening here? 36.Bxd3 exd3 37.Rxd3 $16 and suddenly, Black's construction is shaky... and White´s rooks are ready to be active. 37...Kf7 38.Nc3! and the knight reaches d5. Or 37...Bxg2+ 38.Kxg2 Rxe2+ 39.Kf1 Re6 40.Rd7+- threatening Rc8. Black's king is too exposed.) How to use the moment?} 36. a4 $3 {A very important move with so many benefits! A)} d3 37. Ba2+ Kf8 38. a5 $1 {Beautiful.} Be3 39. Rc7 {. B) 36...bxa4 37.Nxd4! Bxd4 38.Rc7! wins the bishop: 38...Bc8 39.Rc4! This is the reason why we forced Black to play ...b5xa4!}) (33... Kg7 $5 {is also good with a similar spirit to}) (33... Re6 $1) 34. Re2 {Defending the 2nd rank, but now White's knight is not so effective fighting the black pawns!} Kg7 $5 {Again, making one more prophylactic move before starting to push the pawns} (34... f5 {is also possible already.}) 35. Rd1 $5 {Setting up a trick...} Kf6 $1 {The king joins the action!} (35... f5 $2 36. Nxe4 $1 fxe4 37. Bxe4 dxe4 38. Rd7+ {White has destroyed Black's structure.}) 36. Nh1 {This is how my main model line went. When analyzing with engines, usually the lines can go on forever...} Ke7 $5 {The first line of engine, but Black has other options as well.} ({Humanly, the most natural move would be} 36... Ke5 {but after} 37. Nf2 {due to the pin on Black's king, White is coming with a disturbing knight check on d3!}) 37. Nf2 f5 {Finally, Black is ready to push the pawns!} 38. Bc2 d4 39. Bb3 Rd6 40. Nd3 $1 {White is making progress activating the pieces, but Black's pawns are ready to fight.} Kf6 $1 41. Nc5 Bxc5 42. bxc5 {Where does the rook go?} Rd7 $1 {Engines are always precise.} (42... Rd8 43. c6 Bxc6 44. Rc2 Bb7 45. Rc7 {or 44...Ba8 45.Rdc1 and White breaks through.}) 43. c6 $1 {Opening up the c-file is essential. Otherwise, White could end up in trouble!} (43. a4 $2 d3 44. Rb2 Ke5 45. axb5 axb5 {the black king gets active and the pawn mass is impressive. White would have to fight for survival!}) 43... Bxc6 44. Rc1 Bb7 $1 {Now, move per move, it works for Black. All of Black's remaining pieces are ideally placed, stopping any immediate entry on the c-file.} 45. Rec2 d3 46. Rc7 {Finally, White enters, but it is just one tempo too late to claim an advantage.} d2 $1 {Just in time!} 47. R1c5 d1=Q+ 48. Bxd1 Rxd1+ 49. Ke2 Rd5 $3 {The ultimate finesse! Otherwise, Black would have had to resign.} 50. Rc2 Ba8 51. Rc8 (51. Ra7 Rd8 52. Rxa6+ Ke5 $13 {can be dangerous for White. After} 53. Rxg6 {, Black has ...Bd5-...Bc4 ideas, and the black king is very strong.}) 51... Bb7 52. R8c7 {It all ends with a stunning draw by repetition. I think this analysis could be some kind of a World Record because I have analyzed a lot all my life but have never even come close to something like this! Usually, a long analysis resulted in reaching some special pawn endgame, but with so many pieces, this is something very special.} *

