1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {My favorite system.} d5 {Black would love to play like this, and for a long time, everybody was fooled, thinking that 15.b3 is not really possible because of it until Judit delivered the bomb, which put ...d6-d5 out of business for more than a decade! Polgar - Spassky Budapest (Match/8) 1993 was the game. [/variation/38709592] �} 16. Bg5 $3 {Setting up a piece sacrifice!} h6 (16... Bg7 $2 {Shakh tried a tricky idea in our blindfold game, but the gamble did not pay off, as I had been prepared for it!} 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. f4 Rxg5 {This positional exchange sac was the idea of my opponent's choice of variation; if it had been a surprise, it could have worked...}) 17. Bh4 $1 {The point of White's play!} g5 {This move is in deep crisis. However, it will be our main topic due to some amazing tactical lines!} ({I have to reveal that I was shocked now when I discovered that the so-called 'losing move'} 17... dxe4 {is probably holding for Black, according to super engines! Black has a great resource here that can eventually hold the line! More on that in the main game.}) 18. Nxg5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 Z0 ({Suddenly, young Mamedyarov in 2006 tried to resurrect the line with} 19... exd4 {against no one else than Judit! In fact, in a period of a good two weeks, he beat Judit and drew with such attacking monsters as Shirov and Grischuk! It is incredible what stories chess history can write! For a very long time, computers could not refute this line themselves! When I was highlighted that this option was not so simple in 1999, then it was the first thing that we made sure with my trainer Amador Rodriguez that we refute it no matter what the engine said! Amador made some real contributions to killing this line!}) *

