19... Rxg5 {This positional exchange sac was the idea of my opponent's choice of variation; if it had been a surprise, it could have worked... How did I counter it?} 20. fxg5 Ne8 {White needs to address the main threats of ...Bxc3 and ...Qxg5.} 21. Qf3 $1 {Key move! White wastes no time to protect both g5 or c3-pawns but goes active instead.} (21. Qd2 Be5 $5 {is what my opponent had been hoping for, while 21...b4 22.cxb4 Qd6 $132 is also good. White's structure is too loose.}) 21... b4 (21... d4 {Black has total control of the dark squares, but if we know that it is not enough according to the computer, then that helps us navigate the complications.}) (21... Qxg5 22. exd5 {Opening up the e4 square!}) 22. Rad1 Bxc3 23. Rf1 $16 {Here, White uses the f-file for the attack. Black has to protect f7 and then exd5 comes, getting access to the key e4-square.} *

