22... Re7 {No checkmate in sight, so... what was Judit's idea when she went for the piece sacrifice?} 23. e6 $1 {The beautiful point of White`s concept starting with 16.Bg5.} fxe6 (23... Rxe6 $1 {It is very instructive to highlight that this move, which is so obvious to a super engine, was probably so disliked by Spassky in 1993 that he preferred to play the losing 23...fxe6 instead. There are many explanations: One can argue that Spassky was way past his best times in 1993. Secondly, when confronted with a stunning novelty, it is very difficult to navigate over the board. Thirdly, allowing the White rook to capture back the sacrificed piece with a tempo on the 7th rank is too much to take psychologically. As far as I can understand engines do not have any of those problems...That is why we love human vs human play!} 24. Rxd7 Qf6 {At first sight, it looks obviously better for White, and in the old days, people would not really be analyzing it, but now the super engine gives it as quite drawable! Times are changing... What engines are seeing is that Black will get plenty of activity! The spoiled pawn structure on the kingside is not that weak at all. Black`s king is perfectly safe. Black`s bishop on f8 has the potential to become a great factor, and Black`s heavy pieces are ready to start participating in a possible counterattack. The fact that it has not yet been played shows us how counterintuitive it is. As long as the super engine does not point it out, the human intuition was not guiding us in this direction at all...}) 24. Ne5 $1 {Thanks to the pin, White wins back the material with a lot of interest.} Rg7 25. Rxd7 Qg5 {And here comes a very important move to seal White's advantage.} 26. Qf3 {Protecting g2 and attacking the a8-rook.} Rd8 27. Rxg7+ Qxg7 28. Re1 {White's idea worked to perfection in the game [/variation/38709592] Polgar, J - Spassky Budapest Match/8 1993. �} *

