22... Nc6 $1 {The critical position. Black puts pressure on the d4-pawn, thus making White's queen less mobile! Can you bring your queen into play? Amador found the way!} 23. Qd3 $3 {A super important move, but psychologically so difficult even to think about it, as it steps into ...Nc6-b4...That is why one needs to be prepared!} (23. Nf5 $2 Bc8 $17 {and Black will trade the buried bishop for the monster knight.}) (23. Qf3 $2 Nxd4 {is the point of Black's defense.}) 23... Nb4 24. Qf5 $5 {This was our solution with Amador Rodriguez back in 1999! Now, modern engines say that it is not important, but practically speaking I still love our old solution very much! It has a real soul! First, we invite the black bishop to apparently win a tempo with ...Bc8, but later, we take back the tempo with ...Bf5! Good old days!!} (24. Qf3 {is simpler after all if we know all the engine moves!}) 24... Bc8 25. Qf3 {White's queen has reached the ideal f3-square! It's all very logical, though the engines offer different, less human, solutions.} (25. Qf4 $5 {Engines give this now as main, but humanly this is not as clear as the computers claim.}) 25... Be7 26. Bf5 $3 Z0 ({The big point of inviting Black's bishop to c8! The knight is coming to f5 after} 26... Bxf5 27. Nxf5 {or, otherwise, Bxc8 followed by Nf5.}) *

