1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {My favorite system.} d5 {Black would love to play like this, and for a long time, everybody was fooled, thinking that 15.b3 is not really possible because of it until Judit delivered the bomb, which put ...d6-d5 out of business for more than a decade! Polgar, J-Spassky Budapest (Match/8) 1993 was the game. [/variation/38709592] �} 16. Bg5 $3 {Setting up a piece sacrifice!} h6 (16... Bg7 $2 {Shakh tried a tricky idea in our blindfold game, but the gamble did not pay off, as I had been prepared for it!} 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Rxe5 19. f4 Rxg5 {This positional exchange sac was the idea of my opponent's choice of variation; if it had been a surprise, it could have worked...} 20. fxg5 Ne8 {and now: A)} 21. Qd2 Be5 $5 {is what my opponent had been hoping for... 21...b4 22.cxb4 Qd6 $132 is also good. B) 21.Qf3! Key move! White wastes no time to protect both g5 or c3-pawns but goes active instead. 21...b4 22.Rad1 Bxc3 23.Rf1 $16 Here, White uses the f-file for the attack. 21...Qxg5 22.exd5 Opening up the e4-square! 21...d4 Black has total control of the dark squares, but if we know that it is not enough according to the computer, then that helps us navigate the complications. 22.Rad1 c5 and not 23.cxd4 Bxd4+ but 23.Ne2! and the center is falling apart. 23...Qxg5 24.cxd4 cxd4 25.Nxd4 Be5 26.Qd3 Bg3 27.Rf1 Ng7 28.b4 Rf8 29.Bb3 Bc8 30.Rxf7! and Black resigned in the game [/variation/38709591] Leko, P (2753)-Mamedyarov, S (2760) Nice Blindfold 2008. � 30...Rxf7 31.Nf3 Qe7 32.Qd8+ and White wins the house.}) 17. Bh4 $1 {The point of White's play!} g5 {This move is in deep crisis. However, it will be our main topic due to some amazing tactical lines! I have to reveal that I was shocked now when I discovered that the so-called 'losing move' 17...dxe4 is probably holding for Black, according to super engines!} (17... dxe4 $5 {According to new engines, Black has a great resource here that can eventually hold the line!} 18. Nxe4 g5 19. Nfxg5 {is not working due to} Nxe4 {, so 19.dxe5 Nxe4 20.Bxe4 Bxe4 21.Rxe4 gxh4 22.Rd4! Re7 23.e6! This is the beautiful point of White's concept starting with 16.Bg5. A) 23...fxe6 24.Ne5! Thanks to the pin, White wins back the material with a lot of interest. 24...Rg7 25.Rxd7 Qg5 with a mating threat. 26.Qf3 defends and attacks. 26...Rd8 27.Rxg7+ Qxg7 28.Re1 White's idea worked to perfection in the game [/variation/38709592] � Polgar, J-Spassky Budapest Match/8 1993. B) 23...Rxe6! It is very instructive to highlight that this move, which is so obvious to a super engine, was probably so disliked by Spassky in 1993 that he preferred to play the losing 23...fxe6 instead. There are many explanations: one can argue that Spassky was way past his best times in 1993. Secondly, when confronted with a stunning novelty, it is very difficult to navigate over the board. Thirdly, allowing the white rook to capture back the sacrificed piece with a tempo on the 7th rank is too much to take psychologically. As far as I can understand, engines do not have any of those problems...That is why we love human vs. human play! 24.Rxd7 Qf6 At first sight, it looks obviously better for White, and in the old days, people would not really be analyzing it, but now the super engine gives it as quite drawable! Times are changing... What engines are seeing is that Black will get plenty of activity! The spoiled pawn structure on the kingside is not that weak at all. Black's king is perfectly safe. Black`s bishop on f8 has the potential to become a great factor, and Black's heavy pieces are ready to start participating in a possible counterattack. The fact that it has not yet been played shows us how counterintuitive it is. As long as the super engine does not point it out, the human intuition was not guiding us in this direction at all... Since this is not a Lifetime Repertoire, I decided not to analyze this position but wanted to highlight thsi option and point you in the right direction for your analysis.}) 18. Nxg5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 exd4 {Suddenly, the young Mamedyarov in 2006 tried to resurrect the line against no one else than Judit! In fact, in a period of a good two weeks, he beat Judit and drew with such attacking monsters as Shirov and Grischuk! It is incredible what stories chess history can write! For a very long time, computers could not refute this line themselves! When I was highlighted that this option was not so simple in 1999, then it was the first thing that we made sure with my trainer Amador Rodriguez that we refute it no matter what the engine said! Amador made some real contributions to killing this line!} ({The other capture} 19... dxe4 {is simply bad:} 20. Bxe4 Bxe4 21. Rxe4 $1 {The rook is joining the attack on the 4th rank!} Be7 {( 21...Qc8 22.Rh4! I remembered it correctly! 22...exd4 23.cxd4 Bg7 24.Nf5 Nf8 25.Qf3+- gave White a winning position in the game [/variation/38719013] Sherzer, A (2500)-Lesiege, A (2485) Biel 1993. � All the white pieces are well places dangerously close to the black king.)} 22. Rh4 {and Nf5 is coming.} Nf8 {is the only move not to get checkmated, but now White can simply grab the third pawn and get a clear advantage.} 23. dxe5 Qxd1+ 24. Rxd1 N6d7 25. Bxe7 Rxe7 26. Rg4+ {followed by f4 is close to winning after both} Kh8 27. f4 {and 26...Ng6 27.f4 .}) 20. e5 $3 {The key move of White's piece sac. Now, modern engines are giving in a fraction of a second all the critical lines for which we had to work like crazy... The concept is obvious: White sacrifices the e-pawn in order to make sure that Black's b7-bishop stays buried.} (20. cxd4 dxe4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 Rxe4 {gives White nothing.}) 20... Rxe5 21. Rxe5 Nxe5 22. cxd4 {The ideal structure for White in order to get his attack going.} Nc6 $1 {The critical position. Black puts pressure on the d4-pawn, thus making White's queen less mobile!} (22... Ng6 23. Qf3 Be7 24. Nf5 {wins on the spot.}) (22... Ned7 23. Nf5 {followed by Qf3-g3 will lead to easy mate.}) 23. Qd3 $3 {A super important move, but psychologically so difficult even to think about it, as it steps into ...Nb4...That is why one needs to be prepared!} ({After the direct} 23. Nf5 $2 Bc8 $1 {, Black simply traded the buried bishop for the monster knight and won in the Polgar, J-Mamedyarov game. [/variation/38709593] �}) (23. Nh5 Be7 {and new engines spot} 24. Be3 $1 $16 {but 24.Bxf6? brings nothing... 24...Bxf6 25.Qd3 Kf8 26.Qh7 Bxd4! Not fearing ghosts! 27.Qh6+ Ke8 28.Re1+ Ne5 29.Bf5 Qd6 30.Qg5 c5 31.Nf6+ Kd8 32.Nxd5+ Ke8 33.Nf6+ Kd8 34.Nd5+ was a draw in the Shirov, A (2720)-Mamedyarov, S (2728) Moscow 2006 game. [/variation/38709595] �}) 23... Nb4 24. Qf5 $5 {This was our solution with Amador Rodriguez back in 1999! Now modern engines say that it is not important, but practically speaking I still love our old solution very much! It has a real soul! First, we invite the Black bishop to apparently win a tempo with ...Bc8, but later, we take back the tempo with Bf5! Good old days!!} (24. Qf3 {is simpler after all if we know all the engine moves!} Nxc2 25. Bxf6 Qxf6 26. Qxf6 Nxa1 {Black has a rook and two pieces for the queen and intends to follow up with ...Re8-...Re6. White could pick up the a1-knight with the queen, but there's something stronger.} 27. Nh5 $1 {There is no defense} Re8 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. Nf6 Re1+ 30. Kh2 Bd6+ 31. g3 {and mate in the next move... 24...Be7 25.Bf5! If two excellent attackers such as Grischuk and Mamedyarov missed this in their game... Well, you can see why Amador's concept is much simpler than the engine's. ( 25.Bb1 Ne4! gives Black good chances to survive. After 25...Bc8? White could play 26.Bf5!! which would have led to Amador`s winning idea. 26.Qf4 allowed 26...Kf8!! but the game went 26...Ne4 27.Bxe7 Qxe7 28.a3 . This was still winning for White, but finally Sasha missed his chance to win.) Now, 25...Nc6 runs into 26.Re1! Nxd4 27.Qe3+- Nxf5 28.Nxf5 and White is winning, so Black has to play 25...Qd6 26.Re1 Ne4 and here, according to the engine, only the two brilliant, crazy moves are winning, but it is almost impossible to find them over the board. A) 27.Bh7+!! Spectacular. 27...Kxh7 28.Qxf7+ or 27...Kf8 28.Bf4! Qf6 29.Nf5 Some other computer brilliance, but it is still pretty much unclear to a human brain... B) 27.Bd2!! Another stunner. 27...Nc6 28.Qh5+- is winning. 27...Nxd2 28.Qg4+ Kf8 29.Bh7! The point of White`s play. 29...Ke8 30.Nf5 and Black has no good defense: 30...Ne4 31.Nxd6+ Nxd6 32.h4+- and Black is paralyzed, so White just wins thanks to the h-pawn! After 31...cxd6 32.f3 , I was a bit confused because there is no direct knock-out blow, but simply the position is hopeless for Black. 32...Nf6 33.Qg5 controlling the king's escape route. 33...Kd8 34.Qg7 Nxh7 35.Qxf7 Nc6 36.Qxh7 is hopeless.}) 24... Bc8 25. Qf3 (25. Qf4 $5 {Engines give this now as main, but humanly, this is not as clear as the computers claim. A)} Be7 26. Re1 $1 {Going for a crushing attack.} Nxc2 27. Rxe7 Qxe7 28. Bxf6 Qe1+ 29. Kh2 Kf8 30. Nh5 {and there is no escape for the black king. B) 25...Bg7 26.Bf5 . Engines like 26.Bh7+!? Kxh7 27.Qh4+ Kg6 28.Nh5 … anyone interested can work this out till the end... C) 25...Qd6 26.Qh4! Bg7 27.Bf5! The famous idea of this whole line! 27...Ne4 28.Nxe4 dxe4 29.Be7 Bxf5 30.Bxd6 cxd6 Whenever I see these 3 pieces vs. queen positions, I always have doubts about how easy it is if one switches off the computer... 31.Qg5 and now not 31...Bg6 32.h4! but after 31… Be6 32.Re1 $16 , I would not dare to write winning here despite engines claiming an over 2.75 advantage...}) 25... Nxc2 (25... Be7 26. Bf5 $3 {The big point of inviting Black's bishop to c8!} Be6 {was the main defense in Amador's old file if I remember correctly. Well, it was back in 1999... ( 26...Nc6 27.Bxc8! Nxd4 28.Qf4 just wins, and 27...Rxc8 28.Nf5 Ne4 29.Bxe7 Nxe7 30.Nxe7+ Qxe7 31.Qg4+ with a double attack wins on the spot.)} 27. Re1 $1 Nc6 {How to proceed here with the attack?} 28. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 29. Rxe6 $1 {The crusher!} Nxd4 30. Qg4+ Kf8 31. Re3 Qd6 32. Bh7 Bg7 33. Nh5 {or 29...fxe6 30.Bxe6+ Kf8 31.Nf5! Beautiful coordination! In fact this was Amador´s main idea! Black is helpless to Qh5! 31...Qe8 32.Bxd5! simply wins back all the material with a lot of interest!}) 26. Bxf6 {This is technically winning.} (26. Nh5 $5 Be7 27. Nxf6+ Kg7 28. Qg3 $3 {eyeing the king. Bh4 is the threat.} Bxf6 29. Bxf6+ Kxf6 30. Qh4+ {wins the queen. 28...Bf5 29.Nh5+ Kf8 30.Bxe7+ Kxe7 ( 30...Qxe7 31.Qg7+ Ke8 32.Nf6+ Kd8 33.Qg8+ and mate.) 31.Qg5+ Kd6 would be a careless check. 31.Qe5+ Kf8 32.Rd1 is also very good, but the line still goes on...}) 26... Be7 27. Bxe7 Qxe7 28. Rc1 {Simple chess.} Ne1 (28... Nxd4 29. Qxd5 {with a double attack.}) 29. Qc3 Nxg2 30. Kxg2 $16 {Often knowing that we have an easy, practical solution helps a lot instead of trying to remember some mysterious winning lines from the computer.} *

