1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {It is important to mention two other options from Black, which are also frequently played.} a5 $5 {Popular move, which shows that Black has a lot of respect for the 15.b3 line because we cannot really call this a critical move. On the other hand, it is not so easy to prove an advantage for White against it.} ({The other option is the passive} 15... c6 {Yes, it stops White from going d4-d5, but once Black voluntarily blocks his own b7-bishop this simply gives White a much easier game. A)} 16. Bg5 {A simple choice and, in fact, is what I played in my game [/variation/38709596] � vs. Svidler already back in 1995! Vintage times! As we know already, in the long term,} h6 17. Be3 {is helping White thanks to the Qd1-d2 tempo.} Bg7 18. Qd2 {White just enjoys the tempo. The other option is skipping …h6 with 16...Bg7 17.Qd2 Qe7 As we know, the queen on e7 is Sasi’s favorite setup in many of these positions. 18.a4 Putting pressure on Black's queenside structure. B) 16.a4 Clever move order. This is anyway a useful move, and now, based on which direction Black goes, ...Qc7 or ...Bg7, we develop our bishop to e3 or g5. Engines prefer meeting 16...Bg7 with 17.Be3! ( 17.Bg5 h6 18.Be3 d5 would suddenly be a possibility which is also better for White, but engines are maximalists...) 17...Qe7 18.Qd2 Qf8 A typical defensive maneuver, but it does not challenge White's center and we should simply be happy after 19.Rad1 . If 16...Qc7 17.Bg5! Bg7 18.Qd2 , White got the perfect setup; everything is harmonious, while after 17...h6 18.Be3 , the big benefit for White in the line with 15...c7-c6 is that the b7-bishop is blocked by its own pawn; thus, the e4-pawn is not vulnerable!}) 16. a4 $1 {This is the best after all.} (16. Bd2 $5 {Psychological warfare... But we'll see that the move I wanted to stop,} b4 $3 {, was, in fact, working anyway! 16...Rb8 This move was such a relief! 17.Bd3! b4 18.Qc2 and I managed to get a nice playable position in my game [/variation/38709598] Leko-Carlsen Wijk aan Zee 2008. �}) 16... b4 17. cxb4 axb4 {With the pawn on a4, White doesn't have to worry about it, and the a1-rook can easily join the game.} 18. Bb2 Bh6 19. Bd3 $1 {Keeping the tension. The position is complex, but White has the more comfortable play. Only one really high-level game has reached this position so far, but it was also online rapid in the Esipenko-Amin 2021 game. [/variation/38718846] �} ({In most games, White released the tension here with} 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Bd3 {but there's a problem...}) *

