1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {It is important to mention two other options from Black, which are also frequently played.} a5 $5 {Popular move, which shows that Black has a lot of respect for the 15.b3 line because we cannot really call this a critical move. On the other hand, it is not so easy to prove an advantage for White against it. The other option is the passive} (15... c6 {Yes, it stops White from going d4-d5, but once Black voluntarily blocks his own b7-bishop this simply gives White a much easier game. A)} 16. Bg5 {A simple choice and, in fact, is what I played in my game [/variation/38709596] � vs. Svidler already back in 1995! Vintage times! As we know already, in the long term,} h6 17. Be3 {is helping White thanks to the Qd1-d2 tempo.} Bg7 18. Qd2 {White just enjoys the tempo.} Kh7 {. The other option is skipping …h6 with 16...Bg7 17.Qd2 Qe7 As we know, the queen on e7 is Sasi’s favorite setup in many of these positions. 18.a4 Putting pressure on Black's queenside structure. 18...Qf8 Smart plan. Black gets out of the pin and secures the kingside. The big question in these positions is when is Black threatening/or is ready with ...d6-d5. From White´s perspective, the big question is, if the threat might be real, then how to best deal with it... A1) 19.Bd3 This is often a desired move in these types of positions. White does not want to move the rook from a1 yet with the potential opening up of the a-file at the right moment in mind... 19...d5 20.dxe5 Nxe5 21.Nxe5 Rxe5 22.f4 What are Black´s options here? 22...Ree8 23.e5 should be better for White. 22...Rxg5!? A stunning positional exchange sac... 23.fxg5 Nd7 is actually not so simple. Compared with my Mamedyarov game [/variation/38397300/#/16/b/0.8] from Monaco blindfold 2008, this is a clearly improved version for Black, as d7 is a better square than e8 for the knight. White should still be better after 24.Ne2 , according to the engine, but this is not what White wanted. A2) 19.Be3! Pretty impressive how deeply Almasi has understood the position! But exactly this move is why I suddenly thought that maybe 16.a4 is more clever than 16.Bg5, but maybe I am just trying to be too deep... 19...Rac8 20.Bd3 Following the plan started with 19.Be3! 20...d5 Black wanted to do something... How to react with White now? Almasi played 21.dxe5 Nxe5 22.Nxe5 and 22...Rxe5 23.f4 was the game continuation, which transposes to 21.Nxe5, but Black could have played 22...dxe4!? What an intermezzo! So easy to simply forget about this! 23.Bxe4!! and now not 23...Nxe4? 24.Nxe4 and White’s pieces are ideally placed, controlling the c5-square. 24...Rxe5 25.Bd4 Rd8 26.Qf4+- Unpinning, with a tremendous attack. Instead, after 23...Rxe5 24.Bd4 Rd8 25.Qf4 Re6 , White's knight is not playing. 26.Bf3 c5! 27.Rxe6 fxe6 28.Be5 and the position is still unpleasant for Black, but the point is 28.Bxf6 is not winning a piece due to 28...Bxf3 exploiting the pin on the f-file. The correct capture was 21.Nxe5! Very instructive that there might be really huge differences between the two moves; one always needs to pay attention to this detail! 21...Nxe5 22.dxe5 Rxe5 (White gets again the ideal setup after 22...Nxe4 23.Bxe4 dxe4 24.Nxe4 .) 23.f4 Ree8 24.e5 locking the black bishop. 24...Nd7 25.axb5 cxb5 The black knight wants to land on c5. ( 25...axb5 26.Ra7 is even worse.) 26.b4! Fixing the structure. 26...f6 How to play with White? 27.e6!! Super impressive positional sacrifice! ( 27.exf6 Nxf6 was still better for White in the Almasi, Z (2726)-Sasikiran, K (2681) Ningbo 2011 game. [/variation/38709598] �) 27...Rxe6 28.f5 and in fact, because Black’s position is falling apart, he needs to sac the exchange, but this comes already out of desperation! 28...gxf5 29.Bxf5 with powerful pressure on the h3-c8 diagonal. 29...Re7 30.Bd4 is terrible for Black, but no solution is 28...Rxe3 29.Qxe3 Ne5 30.Bc2 with an almost decisive advantage. 30...Bh6 is the only attempt to get some activity. 31.Qb6 hitting the other bishop. The position is hopeless for Black. B) 16.a4 Clever move order. This is anyway a useful move, and now, based on which direction Black goes, ...Qc7 or ...Bg7, we develop our bishop to e3 or g5. Engines prefer meeting 16...Bg7 with 17.Be3! ( 17.Bg5 Qe7 would go back to the Almasi-Sasikiran direction. 17...h6 18.Be3 d5 would suddenly be a possibility which is also better for White, but engines are maximalists...) 17...Qe7 18.Qd2 Qf8 A typical defensive maneuver, but it does not challenge White's center, and we should simply be happy. 19.Rad1 Rad8 20.Qc1! The natural reaction for White to step out of the d-file once Rad1 has been played. Black should better just sit and wait, but having played all the useful moves, it is very difficult not to do anything... 20...d5? Breaking out with the desired ...d6-d5 move does not work for Black, and this is always a key factor in these type of positions! 21.dxe5 Nxe5 22.Nxe5 Rxe5 23.f4 is the thematic refutation. 23...Ree8 24.e5 locking the bishop. 24...Nd7 25.axb5 axb5 26.b4 with total control. Again, White meets 26...f6 with 27.e6 Rxe6 28.f5 , though this is a slightly better version for Black. B2) 16...Qc7 17.Bg5! Bg7 18.Qd2 White got the perfect setup; everything is harmonious. 18...Nf8 The knight wants to jump to e6 and kick the white bishop. 19.Bh6 Ne6 20.b4 is the typical play. White gets ready to activate the c2-bishop to b3 with lovely play. 20.Bd3!? is the other possibility. Finally, note that after 17...h6 18.Be3 , the big benefit for White in the line with 15...c7-c6 is that the b7-bishop is blocked by its own pawn; thus, the e4-pawn is not vulnerable! 18...d5 19.Nxe5 Nxe5 20.dxe5 Qxe5 21.Bd4 and here Black's bishop is missing from g7!}) 16. a4 $1 {This is the best after all.} (16. Bd2 $5 {Psychological warfare...} Rb8 {This move was such a relief!} 17. Bd3 $1 b4 18. Qc2 {and I managed to get a nice playable position in my game [/variation/38709598] Leko-Carlsen Wijk aan Zee 2008. � 16...b4!! The move I wanted to stop with my move 16.Bd2 was, in fact, working anyway! A) 17.cxb4 axb4 18.d5 Qb8! protecting the b4-pawn, as 19.Bxb4 would run into 19...Bxd5! B) 17.d5 bxc3 18.Bxc3 c6 is the dream of any Breyer. 19.dxc6 Bxc6 Black has perfect harmony. The pieces occupy ideal positions putting pressure on e4. The ...d5 push might be a future possibility. C) 17.Rc1!? and now 17...d5!? is 'Total Eldorado'. I mean, look at that pawn center! 17...bxc3 18.Bxc3 exd4! Correct timing! 19.Bxd4 Bh6! is annoying! 19.Qxd4 Bg7 20.Qd2 targets the a5-pawn, but... 20...Nc5! with good counterplay. Black's pieces are fantastic and put pressure on the e4-pawn.}) 16... b4 17. cxb4 axb4 {With the pawn on a4, White doesn't have to worry about it, and the a1-rook can easily join the game.} 18. Bb2 Bh6 19. Bd3 $1 ({Keeping the tension. The position is complex, but White has the more comfortable play. Only one really high-level game has reached this position so far, but it was also online rapid in the Esipenko-Amin 2021 game. [/variation/229376] � In most games, White released the tension here with} 19. dxe5 dxe5 20. Bd3 Nc5 $1 {The difference!} 21. Bb5 {Clearly, White was counting on this move.} c6 22. Bc4 Qxd1 23. Raxd1 Nfd7 24. Bc1 Bxc1 25. Rxc1 Ba6 $132 {is enough counterplay because White's b3-pawn is also a weakness.}) 19... exd4 {Always offers the tough question to White how best to capture back...} (19... Bf4 {was the game continuation.}) 20. Bxd4 {In my mind, taking with the bishop is the better recapture keeping more control on the central squares. It is all to play for, but I feel that White has the easier play.} *

