{We have seen in a couple of examples in my favorite Breyer system what happens when White gets the dream setup; now it is time to look at what can happen when things get out of control in a similar structure! The following game is extremely instructive.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {Please read this analysis only after looking at this game all the way to the 13th move comment! That is the best way to enjoy it to the maximum!} (3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 {The starting position of the Zaitsev Variation.} 12. a3 {I have always liked this system for White vs the Zaitsev variation and had it ready since 2012! The point of playing this system was always to understand why things are happening! The main ideas are shown in the extra informational. [/variation/37952166]}) 4. d3 {Modern chess, lot of mind games involved... First an Anti-Berlin.} d6 ({Magnus decides to go for Classical Spanish structures instead of the more popular} 4... Bc5 {, which is in the Anti-Berlin spirit.}) 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now, we reached a typical main line of the classical Spanish 6. d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 ({One of the main moves, but White also has other options such as} 10. Nf1 $5 {with slow play or}) (10. d4 $5 {when the game can get very sharp after} b5 11. Bc2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 {with tons of complications.}) 10... b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12. Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 $5 {Smart choice by Magnus! He still keeps the Zaitsev spirit for one more move. This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas (move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! One can pay a huge price, as it happened to the already very strong but still very young Alireza vs. Magnus!} 13. a3 $2 {I don't like this move and feel that it is already kind of the reason why White has lost this game! In my eyes, this is clear evidence that Alireza wanted to transpose to the 12.a3 line of the Zaitsev and got completely confused. In order to understand what I mean, it is important to get back to the Black's 3rd move and check out this informational! [/variation/37952166] Now is the perfect time to get into this fascinating topic!} (13. d5 {is the principled move as we will see later when looking at both Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914] and Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252] games.}) *

