14. d5 $2 {Already a very serious mistake! Probably, Alireza wanted to fight, but this is not the way to do it! What's Black's thematic way to challenge White's structure?} c6 15. c4 $6 {Following the plan...} (15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Nh2 {was a better way, trying to fight for equality, but it was clearly not Alireza's intention in such an early stage of the game...}) 15... Nbd7 (15... Qc7 $5 {is sometimes important, but not here when White lost a tempo on a2-a3.}) 16. a4 Qc7 17. b3 {It might look like a normal type of Spanish structure, but in fact, here, Black is the one fighting for the advantage already! I remember while following this game, I was already sure that Magnus would win this no matter how resourceful and talented Alireza was... How to proceed? Which rook belongs to c8?} Rec8 $1 {The typical move. The a8-rook will later be useful on the b-file!} 18. Ra2 {How to correctly fix the structure?} bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 $15 {This is not the typical space advantage that White enjoys! It is much more that White is full of weaknesses, and Black is in time to target them before White regroups his pieces. As they say on a high level, this is only a matter of technique... Magnus went on to win a masterfully played game, and Alireza learned a lot about what not to do in the Classical Spanish Opening from the White side!} *

