{We have seen in a couple of examples in my favorite Breyer system what happens when White gets the dream setup; now it is time to look at what can happen when things get out of control in a similar structure! The following game is extremely instructive.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {Please read this analysis only after looking at this game all the way to the 13th move comment! That is the best way to enjoy it to the maximum!} (3... a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 {The starting position of the Zaitsev Variation.} 12. a3 {I have always liked this system for White vs the Zaitsev variation and had it ready since 2012! The point of playing this system was always to understand why things are happening! The main ideas are shown in the extra informational. [/variation/37952166]}) 4. d3 {Modern chess, lot of mind games involved... First an Anti-Berlin.} d6 ({Magnus decides to go for Classical Spanish structures instead of the more popular} 4... Bc5 {, which is in the Anti-Berlin spirit.}) 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now, we reached a typical main line of the classical Spanish 6. d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 ({One of the main moves, but White also has other options such as} 10. Nf1 $5 {with slow play or}) (10. d4 $5 {when the game can get very sharp after} b5 11. Bc2 exd4 12. cxd4 Bg4 {with tons of complications.}) 10... b5 11. Bc2 {Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move.} Bb7 12. d4 {This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12. Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4.} g6 $5 {Smart choice by Magnus! He still keeps the Zaitsev spirit for one more move. This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas (move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! One can pay a huge price, as it happened to the already very strong but still very young Alireza vs. Magnus!} 13. a3 $2 {I don't like this move and feel that it is already kind of the reason why White has lost this game! In my eyes, this is clear evidence that Alireza wanted to transpose to the 12.a3 line of the Zaitsev and got completely confused. In order to understand what I mean, it is important to get back to the Black's 3rd move and check out this informational! [/variation/37952166] Now is the perfect time to get into this fascinating topic!} (13. d5 {is the principled move as we will see later when looking at both Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914] and Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252] games.}) 13... Nb8 $1 {Magnus knows his stuff!} 14. d5 $2 {And here it is, already a very serious mistake! Probably, Alireza wanted to fight, but this is not the way to do it! However, I know very well how difficult it is to settle for other moves when you know that they offer nothing...That is the reason why I had highlighted 13. a3 as the cause of trouble already!} (14. b3 Nbd7 15. Bb2 Bg7 {Black has won a big tempo saving on ...h6(!) with ...d6-d5 coming, white will have to settle for equality...}) (14. b4 Nbd7 15. Bb2 {is maybe best, but also not really an ideal Zaitsev/Breyer...} Bg7 {with easy play for Black.}) 14... c6 15. c4 $6 {Following the plan...} (15. dxc6 Bxc6 16. Nh2 {was a better way, trying to fight for equality, but it was clearly not Alireza's intention in such an early stage of the game...}) 15... Nbd7 (15... Qc7 $5 {Sometimes important, but not here when White lost a tempo on a2-a3, we will be analyzing the correct version here [/variation/37934914/#/15/b/0.4] inside the Leko-Navara game.}) 16. a4 Qc7 17. b3 {It might look like a normal type of Spanish structure, but in fact, here, Black is the one fighting for advantage already! I remember while following this game, I was already sure that Magnus would win this no matter how resourceful and talented Alireza is... How to proceed? Which rook belongs to c8?} Rec8 $1 {The typical move. The a8-rook will later be useful on the b-file!} 18. Ra2 bxc4 19. bxc4 {How to correctly fix the structure?} a5 $15 {This is not the typical space advantage that White enjoys! It is much more that White is full of weaknesses, and Black is in time to target them before White regroups his pieces. As they say on a high level, this is only a matter of technique... Magnus went on to win a masterfully played game, and Alireza learned a lot about what not to do in the Classical Spanish Opening from the White side!} 20. Nf1 Ba6 21. Ne3 Nc5 22. Nd2 cxd5 23. cxd5 Rab8 {Black got everything he could only dream about. White is paralyzed, and the space advantage is worth absolutely nothing. All of Black's pieces do a perfect job} 24. Ba3 {This move highlights how much trouble White is in. White can't do anything but wait till Black keeps on improving his position.} Qd8 $1 {I love moves like this! Black gets perfect harmony.} 25. Qf3 {How to improve Black's position?} h5 $1 {Another typical improving move. Black wants to play ...Bh6, but first makes sure to get the pawn to h5 because, in the long term, Black needs the h-pawn in action!} 26. Raa1 Bh6 {What a picturesque position. Even if I wanted to set up a more ideal position for Black, it would simply be impossible; the last remaining missing move is...} 27. Rab1 Rxb1 28. Rxb1 {Which move creates the perfect harmony in Black's camp?} Kg7 $1 {...this! The perfect harmony. The great thing about strategically overwhelming advantages is that often, with simple good moves, we can suffocate the opponent like a Boa! White is completely helpless...} 29. Nef1 {There is not much White can do...} h4 30. Ne3 Bf4 {Black keeps on improving his position, which usually will lead to White at some point will lose the nerves and even help the opponent...} 31. Nef1 Qc7 {No rush!} 32. g3 $6 {White could not tolerate Black's improving moves, wants to try something, but this only speeds up his downfall.} hxg3 33. fxg3 Bh6 {White managed to kick the bishop back but has completely ruined his pawn structure. Now Magnus has clear targets to go after} 34. h4 Qd7 $1 {Highlighting all the weaknesses in White's position.} 35. Kg2 Nxa4 {Time to cash in.} 36. Bxa4 Qxa4 37. Bxd6 Qd4 $1 {The only reason why Magnus allowed the change of structure is because he calculated that he wins by force.} 38. Qf2 Qxf2+ 39. Kxf2 Bxf1 40. Z0 ({Simple and effective. Now, White just loses a piece after} 40. Nxf1 Nxe4+ {. White resigned. Magnus has masterfully shown us what happens if Black gets the dream in the Classical Spanish!}) 0-1

