{Please read this analysis only after looking at the main game all the way to the 13th move comment! [/variation/37952165/#/13/w] That is the best way to enjoy it to the maximum!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... Nf6 4. d3 {Modern chess, lot of mind games involved... First an Anti-Berlin.} d6 {Magnus decides to go for Classical Spanish structures instead of the more popular 4...Bc5, which is in the Anti-Berlin spirit.} 5. c3 a6 6. Ba4 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 {By now, we reached a typical main line of the classical Spanish 6. d3 d6 variation...} 10. h3 {One of the main moves, but White also has other options such as 10.Nf1!? with slow play or 10.d4!? when the game can get very sharp after 10...b5 11.Bc2 exd4 12.cxd4 Bg4 with tons of complications. 10...b5 11.Bc2 Typical idea. White saves the Bb3 move. 11...Bb7 12.d4 This is now officially a clean transposition to the Zaitsev variation with 12. Bc2... One could ask: How is that possible? Well, the answer is pretty simple: White saved the extra one move on going Ba4-c2 in one go but lost the tempo back with d2-d3-d4. 12...g6!? Smart choice by Magnus! He still keeps the Zaitsev spirit for one more move. This is now a Zaitsev which turns into a Breyer. One needs to be very careful not to mix up the ideas (move orders, transpositions!) by thinking that it is the same! One can pay a huge price, as it happened to the already very strong but still very young Alireza vs. Magnus! 13.a3? I don't like this move and feel that it is already kind of the reason why White has lost this game! In my eyes, this is clear evidence that Alireza wanted to transpose to the 12. a3 line of the Zaitsev and got completely confused. In order to understand what I mean it is important to get back to the 3...a6 move comment! Now is the perfect time to get into this fascinating topic! 13.d5 is the principled move as we will see later when looking at both Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914] and Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252] games.}) 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Nbd2 Bf8 {The starting position of the Zaitsev Variation.} 12. a3 {I have always liked this system for White vs the Zaitsev variation and had it ready since 2012! The point of playing this system was always to understand why things are happening! The main idea is that after ...g6, White plays Ba2.} (12. Bc2 g6 {reaches the position we'll see in the rest of the games in this chapter.}) 12... g6 (12... h6 $1 {is clearly considered a main move in this move order, and it is now that White returns with} 13. Bc2 {Now, Black has two completely different ways to treat the position.} Nb8 {Leading to a typical Zaitsev/Breyer strategical battle with a lot of nuances and lots of theory, but with a pawn on h6, which makes it different compared with the classical Breyer! One should always keep that in mind! Also, since the e4-pawn is under pressure here, White is unable to bring his knight to g3 compared with the traditional Breyers that we have looked at! Normally, the game follows like 13...d5 leading to sharp double-edged positions where deep preparation is required by both players. 14.dxe5 Nxe5 15.Nxe5 Rxe5 16.Nf3 Re8 17.e5 Ne4 18.Bf4 is again a line worth studying deeper with White. Black is more or less fine, but it should still be more enjoyable to have the white pieces here. 14.b3 Nbd7 15.a4 d5! works well and closes the line immediately. Instead, 15.Bb2! was the key move of my setup, stopping the ...d6-d5 break. 15...g6 Usually with a complicated struggle, which I was very much looking forward to, but actually, something earth-shattering has happened here in 2022/2023. ( 15...d5? 16.Nxe5 Nxe5 17.dxe5 Rxe5 18.c4! is another difference, and if 17...Nxe4 18.Nxe4 dxe4 19.Bxe4 Bxe4 20.Rxe4 and here, thanks to the developed bishop on b2, White can simply take the pawn.) 16.a4 and now: A) 16...c6 Voluntarily closing the b7-bishop had the old classical Breyer spirit of keeping the other bishop still on f8 for the moment. 17.Bd3 Actually, when I first learned this system with White, the main attraction was that the reaction that Black mostly used with a pawn on h7 in the classical Breyer was not possible here with the pawn on h6! The otherwise popular transformation of structure with 17...exd4? is just bad due to 18.cxd4 d5 19.e5 Nh5 and now 20.e6! just wins. Instead, 17...Nh5 happened in the game [/variation/38709599] Leko-Caruana Malmö 2012. � It was an interesting fight ending in a draw! I still regret till today that I tried to be too clever with 18.g3 instead of the simpler 18.Bf1 Nf4 19.g3 Ne6 20.h4 Bg7 21.b4 with the more comfortable play for White. After 18.g3 Bg7 19.Qc2 Qb6 20.Bf1 Rac8 , the pin along the a7-g1 diagonal was practically very annoying to deal with. I was unable to pose any problems to Fabiano in the game. B) 16...Bg7! Now has a very concrete idea; otherwise, earlier this move order made no real difference! 17.Bd3 Happened also in the game [/variation/38712736] Carlsen-Firouzja, Blitz 2023!� Yes, we see it correctly; I told you that we are dealing with an important position! However, the real bomb happened in Firouzja-Le Quang Champions Chess Tour 2022, already in 2022! I am still puzzled why Alireza has not used the bomb himself... While 17...c6 18.Qc2 Nh5 19.Bf1 leads to the typical strategical fight, 17...bxa4!! is a stunner because, in 99 out of 100 cases, this move would be a big strategic mistake! Again, knowing the details matter! 18.Rxa4 d5!! Now, thanks to a spectacular tactical shot, this Breyer break works to perfection! 19.dxe5 Nxe4 20.Nxe4 dxe4 21.Bxe4 Bxe4 22.Raxe4 looks like Black has miscalculated, but... 22...Nxe5!! Amazing shot! B1) 23.Rxe5 Bxe5 24.Qxd8 Raxd8 25.Rxe5 Rxe5 26.Nxe5 Rd1+ 27.Kh2 Rd2 this double attack is the point. 28.Ba3 Rxf2 29.Bc5 Rc2 30.Bd4 c5! breaking the queenside structure was the last important detail with an easy draw in the game [/variation/38709600] Vachier Lagrave, M (2734)-Caruana, F (2795) Saint Louis 2023.� B2) 23.Qxd8 Nxf3+ 24.gxf3 Rexd8 gives White nothing. B3) 23.Nxe5 Qxd1 24.Rxd1 Rxe5 25.Rxe5 Bxe5= Thanks to White’s vulnerable queenside pawns, it is an easy draw as happened in the Firouzja, A (2778)-Le, Q (2728) Miami 2022 game. [/variation/38709601] � Actually, at this moment, this line stands well for Black, which is extremely good news for Zaitsev players! Otherwise, the 12.a3 line was really unpleasant to face.}) 13. Ba2 $1 {Due to the pressure on the f7 pawn, black is unable to do the Breyer regrouping with ...Nc6-b8-d7! This line is dangerous for Black and worth studying with White. Once we know this is the key vs. 12...g6, the mistake that happened to Firouzja can never happen to us!} Bg7 (13... Nb8 $2 {How to punish the Breyer spirit now?} 14. Ng5 $1 {Officially a novelty, but I guess everybody knows about it by now.} Re7 15. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 16. Nf3 $1 {There is no good way of stopping Nf3-g5.} Nbd7 17. Ng5 d5 18. exd5 e4 19. d6 Nd5 20. Nxf7 Kxf7 21. dxc7 Qxc7 22. Rxe4 {is simply winning for White.}) 14. b4 ({White also has quiet options like} 14. Rb1 $5 {and}) (14. Qc2 $5 {getting ready to play b2-b4 in the next move.}) 14... exd4 15. cxd4 a5 {This is something for fanatics. The last time I checked it, it was still more or less holding for Black, but it is certainly not in the Classical Spanish spirit.} 16. Ng5 d5 17. e5 {What is the justification of Black's play?} Nxd4 $1 18. Bb2 Nh5 $1 19. Nxf7 Qh4 $1 (19... Kxf7 20. Bxd4 {. All this was forced! How to grab the initiative here with White?}) 20. Re4 $3 {Brilliant touch! Some more 'madness'...} dxe4 21. Bxd4 $13 {And the game is only beginning...} *

