1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Bb7 {The Zaitsev variation usually leads to a very complex battle. It is more complicated than the Breyer and requires much more concrete opening knowledge. It is not an opening variation that can be played on autopilot. It suits players who are ready to invest a lot of time in studying all kinds of long, complicated variations with a lot of different structures. The ideas are easy to understand. Black first develops the bishop and follows it up with ...Re8.} 10. d4 Re8 {This is the real starting position of the Zaitsev variation. Black keeps the tension in the center and is planning to play ...Bf8 next. It is really fascinating that this opening variation was developed only in the 70s but by none other than Karpov`s long-time trainer, Igor Zaitsev. We can speak about a very modern and ambitious opening variation. The absolute main idea of Black is to pressure the e4-pawn as quickly as possible and not to allow White to carry out the Nb1-d2-f1-g3 maneuver, which we see in so many other Classical Spanish variations. Obviously, it comes at the cost of weakening the f7-pawn early on, but it is easy to see that White is unable to exploit it.} 11. Ng5 {This is not really an attacking move, as Black can parry the threat easily with ...Rf8. It is often used as a famous Zaitsev draw (one of the big drawbacks if we consider using it as a fighting weapon facing weaker opposition!) but repeating just once is a common strategy by players who are known to be getting into time-trouble myself included...} Rf8 12. Nf3 {White has nothing better than to retreat.} ({Important to highlight that there is the move in the King's-Gambit spirit with} 12. f4 {but Black can counter it nicely, as we'll explore in the first exercise.}) 12... Re8 13. Nbd2 {Now we continue.} Bf8 {The start of the Zaitsev tabiya. White has a very big choice here. Here, we can already see better the problem White is facing. The knight can't move to f1 due to ...exd4, and the e4-pawn will fall. That is why the absolute main moves are 12. a4, 12. a3, and 12. d5, apart from the game continuation with 12. Bc2. The reason why I am writing them as move 12 continuations is because, officially, the move repetition with Nf3-g5-f3 does not count!} 14. Bc2 {I believe that the Zaitsev Variation has come as a slight surprise, and in return, I wanted to lure my young opponent out of his main preparation with this choice. At that moment, this was not a fashionable direction and could have been called an 'old school' choice.} g6 {The same position as in Firouzja-Carlsen. [/variation/37952165/#/12/b]} 15. d5 Ne7 {During the game, when David opted for this square with his knight, I had the feeling that he was not familiar with the nuances of this type of position. By now, both of us were out of book, and the game got a real street-fight character in the next few moves...} *

