17. c4 {White is trying to consolidate their center. How can Black fight this plan?} Qc7 $1 ({More flexible move here than} 17... Nbd7 18. Nf1 Qc7 19. Be3 $1 {Now White gets the harmony he is looking for!} Rec8 20. Rc1) 18. Nf1 (18. a4 $6 {Again, be careful with such moves...} bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 $1) 18... Rc8 $1 {The point of Black's play! White is not in time to get his most desirable setup.} 19. Bd3 (19. Bg5 {Usually desirable to develop this bishop to get a quick Ra1-c1 in.} Nbd7 20. Rc1 {Yes, here White got the Rc1 move in, but it comes with a loss of a little tempo, which Black can use to his benefit} a5 $1 {This is typical Classical Spanish. The ideas often remain the same.}) (19. Ne3 Nbd7 {This position has been featured in a couple of high-level games.} 20. Bd2 a5 $1 {Again, the correct plan.}) 19... Nbd7 20. Be3 bxc4 21. bxc4 cxd5 $1 {Black only plays ...cxd5 because there is a special typical tactical follow up!} 22. cxd5 {What's Black's follow-up?} Bxd5 $1 {This is the justification.} 23. exd5 e4 $132 {And, as we know, this is just fine for Black. Black has the dark squares, which compensates for giving up the pair of bishops!} *

