17. b3 {What is the most natural move here?} Bh6 $1 {The justification of Black's play! A very typical idea when White had no time to move the knight from d2. We also get the chance to understand how different and important the kingside structure can be. The difference between having g6 or h6 in these types of positions is huge!} 18. Nf1 (18. Ba3 $5 {I knew that this was a very double-edged decision, but I felt that I was obliged to try to punish Black for putting the knight on e7! Now, when I look back, I envy my optimism to dare to think like this... As of now it looks like unnecessary risk taking... The problem is that the desire to try to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board is understandable, but the a3-bishop is kind of stuck and will cause a lot of headaches in the future. Important to highlight that if I had my pawn on a4, it would have been a completely different story, and then it would have been ideal!}) ({Now, when having a fresh look, I wondered if I already so much wanted to keep the bishops, then why did not I opted for} 18. Bb2 Rc8 19. Bd3 {Now White wants a4, but probably the move that disturbed me was} Nd7 $5 {, which is clearly stopped with 18. Ba3...}) 18... Bxc1 19. Rxc1 {Somehow, I did not believe that White can really hope for an advantage here in the long run.} cxd5 20. cxd5 Bc8 $1 {The famous regrouping in these structures! Black's only bad piece is the knight on e7; otherwise, everything is solid enough to compensate for it.} 21. Ne3 Bd7 {And Black is very solid. Even now, seeing the new comps evaluation with +0.40, I still do not feel that White has anything...} *

