21... Bc8 $6 {Consequent, but the wrong spirit! This is now a very dynamic position, so Black should have better forgotten about traditional values and treat the position as it is! A very important question: what should White do now?} 22. Bc1 $3 {I was so happy to be able to make this move; it also shows how much I regretted my impulsive emotional 18. Ba3 choice! There is also the psychological moment of the game, and from now on, I felt being in the driver's seat again!} Nf4 23. a4 $1 {Finally!} bxa4 $2 {Basically, I think that practically this was already the losing move!} ({There was still a fantastic strategic idea which could have justified the ...Bc8 concept...} 23... Rb8 $1 {with the surprising idea of} 24. axb5 Rxb5 $1 {and the active rook on b5 hitting the d5 pawn compensates for the c4-square!} 25. Nc4 f5 $1 {with counterplay.}) 24. bxa4 f5 {Yes, finally, Black has pushed ...f7-f5, but now White can simply ignore it nicely and go after the weaknesses in Black's camp.} 25. Nc4 $1 {Again the famous c4-square for the white knight!} (25. Rb1 $5) 25... fxe4 (25... Qc7 $2 26. Ncxe5 $1 {with the point} dxe5 27. d6 {.}) 26. Bxe4 Ra7 {Activating the rook along the 7th rank.} 27. Ba3 $1 {This was even stronger according to the engines, but I did not want to tempt faith by moving my bishop back to a3!} (27. Rb1 {was my choice in the game.}) (27. Ba3 $1 {when} Rf6 28. Rb1 Rc7 29. Ncxe5 {is fine for White but I was a bit worried about 27...Bxh3!? sacrifices. After 28.gxh3 Qc8 29.Nxd6 Qxh3 30.Nh2! , the bishop protects the g2-square and Qg4 is an important idea.}) *

