1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 9. h3 Bb7 {The Zaitsev variation usually leads to a very complex battle. It is more complicated than the Breyer and requires much more concrete opening knowledge. It is not an opening variation that can be played on autopilot. It suits players who are ready to invest a lot of time in studying all kinds of long, complicated variations with a lot of different structures. The ideas are easy to understand. Black first develops the bishop and follows it up with ...Re8.} 10. d4 Re8 {This is the real starting position of the Zaitsev variation. Black keeps the tension in the center and is planning to play ...Bf8 next. It is really fascinating that this opening variation was developed only in the 70s but by none other than Karpov`s long-time trainer, Igor Zaitsev. We can speak about a very modern and ambitious opening variation. The absolute main idea of Black is to pressure the e4-pawn as quickly as possible and not to allow White to carry out the Nb1-d2-f1-g3 maneuver, which we see in so many other Classical Spanish variations. Obviously, it comes at the cost of weakening the f7-pawn early on, but it is easy to see that White is unable to exploit it.} 11. Ng5 {This is not really an attacking move, as Black can parry the threat easily with Rf8. It is often used as a famous Zaitsev draw (one of the big drawbacks if we consider using it as a fighting weapon facing weaker opposition!) but repeating just once is a common strategy by players who are known to be getting into time-trouble myself included...} Rf8 12. Nf3 {White has nothing better than to retreat.} ({Important to highlight that there is the move in the Kings-Gambit spirit with} 12. f4 {but Black can counter it nicely with} exf4 13. Bxf4 Na5 $1 {Hitting the bishop.} 14. Bc2 {and now comes the point} Nd5 $3 {This has happened in one of the very first Zaitsev`s games [/variation/38709602] played in Hungary, Rajna-Zaitsev Szolnok 1975! � Black has nothing to worry about.}) 12... Re8 13. Nbd2 {Now we continue.} Bf8 {The start of the Zaitsev tabiya. White has a very big choice here. Here, we can already see better the problem White is facing. The knight can't move to f1 due to ...exd4, and the e4-pawn will fall. That is why the absolute main moves are 12. a4, 12. a3, and 12. d5, apart from the game continuation with 12. Bc2. The reason why I am writing them as move 12 continuations is because, officially, the move repetition with Nf3-g5-f3 does not count!} 14. Bc2 {I believe that the Zaitsev Variation has come as a slight surprise, and in return, I wanted to lure my young opponent out of his main preparation with this choice. At that moment, this was not a fashionable direction and could have been called an 'old school' choice.} g6 {The same position as in Firouzja-Carlsen. [/variation/37952165/#/12/b]} 15. d5 Ne7 {During the game, when David opted for this square with his knight, I had the feeling that he was not familiar with the nuances of this type of position. By now, both of us were out of book, and the game got a real street-fight character in the next few moves...} ({Usually, in this structure, Black normally goes for the following standard setup.} 15... Nb8 16. b3 c6 17. c4 {and here} Qc7 $1 {is more flexible than 17...Nbd7. ( 17...Nbd7 18.Nf1 Qc7 19.Be3! and now White gets the harmony he is looking for! 19...Rec8 20.Rc1 ) Again, White should be careful with moves like} 18. a4 $6 {due to} bxc4 19. bxc4 a5 $1 {. After 18.Nf1 , the point of Black's play is 18...Rc8! White is not in time to get his most desirable setup. A) 19.Bd3 Nbd7 20.Be3 bxc4 21.bxc4 cxd5! Black only plays ...cxd5 because there is a special typical tactical follow up! 22.cxd5 How to play with Black? 22...Bxd5! is the justification. 23.exd5 e4 $132 and, as we know, this is just fine for Black. Black has the dark squares, which compensates for giving up the pair of bishops! B) 19.Ne3 Nbd7 This position has been featured in a couple of high-level games. 20.Bd2 a5! Again, the correct plan. 21.Rc1 bxc4 22.bxc4 Nc5 23.dxc6 Bxc6 24.Nd5 Qd8 with a normal position in the Zapata-Bruzon 2003 game. [/variation/38709603] � C) 19.Bg5 Usually desirable to develop this bishop to get a quick Ra1-c1 in. 19...Nbd7 20.Rc1 Yes, here White got the Rc1 move in, but it comes with a loss of a little tempo, which Black can use to his benefit 20...a5! This is typical Classical Spanish. The ideas often remain the same. 21.Bd3 bxc4 22.bxc4 Qd8 leads to a rich middlegame with chances for both sides, while after 21.Be3 Ba6 The typical plan activating the bishop. 22.Bd3 bxc4 23.bxc4 Qd8 24.Qd2 Rab8 , Black has achieved his regrouping, and White has no good plan. 25.Ng3 After Black has placed all his pieces right, he even has a nice little idea to bother White with: 25...a4! intending to push the pawn all the way to a3 when ...Rb8-b2 will become a threat.}) 16. c4 c6 17. b3 {What is the most natural move here?} Bh6 $1 {The justification of Black's play! A very typical idea when White had no time to move the knight from d2. We also get the chance to understand how different and important the kingside structure can be. The difference between having g6 or h6 in these types of positions is huge!} 18. Ba3 $5 {I knew that this was a very double-edged decision, but I felt that I was obliged to try to punish Black for putting the knight on e7! Now, when I look back, I envy my optimism to dare to think like this... As of now it looks like unnecessary risk taking... The problem is that the desire to try to keep the dark-squared bishops on the board is understandable, but the a3-bishop is kind of stuck and will cause a lot of headaches in the future. Important to highlight that if I had my pawn on a4, it would have been a completely different story, and then it would have been ideal!} ({A)} 18. Nf1 Bxc1 19. Rxc1 {Somehow, I did not believe that White can really hope for an advantage here in the long run.} cxd5 20. cxd5 Bc8 $1 {The famous regrouping in these structures! Black's only bad piece is the knight on e7; otherwise, everything is solid enough to compensate for it.} 21. Ne3 Bd7 {and Black is very solid. Even now, seeing the new comps evaluation with +0.40, I still do not feel that White has anything...}) ({B) Now, when having a fresh look, I wondered if I already so much wanted to keep the bishops, then why did not I opt for} 18. Bb2 Rc8 19. Bd3 {Now White wants a4, but probably the move that disturbed me was} Nd7 $5 {, which is clearly stopped with 18. Ba3...}) 18... cxd5 ({One move is clearly out of question:} 18... c5 $2 {runs into the queenside break.} 19. b4 $1 cxb4 20. Bxb4 a5 21. Ba3 b4 22. Bb2 {and White gets a strategically overwhelming position with Ba4 coming, and in the long run, Black will have trouble stopping c4-c5 break.} Nd7 23. Ba4 {with pressure on the a4-e8 diagonal. Also, Nb3 is coming.}) ({I remember that I was mostly worried about what happens if Black plays the flexible} 18... Rc8 $5 {Now White has to watch out because 'Spassky's sacrifice' is very much in the air! But I had my solid answer ready with} 19. Bd3 {One needs to be alert, but once we know the motifs that we have to pay attention to, then it is not difficult anymore!} cxd5 20. cxd5 Qb6 21. Bb2 Nh5 22. a4 f5 {is total chaos, and while thinking about such scenarios, I have already regretted the 18. Ba3 move... 19.Nf1 runs into the sacrifice 19...cxd5 20.cxd5 What is the reaction for Black here? 20...Nexd5!! Boom! 21.exd5 Nxd5 Black gets tremendous activity! 22.Be4!? I felt this is practically forced. 22...Nc3 23.Bxb7 Nxd1 24.Raxd1 Rc2 and it was impossible to evaluate this position. It just felt out of control. Now the engine says 0.00, are we cleverer by this?}) 19. cxd5 Nh5 (19... Rc8 {would have still transposed to 18...Rc8 spirit.}) 20. Nf1 {Here I was relieved because I felt that my pieces were ready for any kingside attack Black might want to achieve by pushing ...f7-f5...} Rf8 {My ambitious young opponent sticks to his idea.} ({Clearly we both needed to very precisely evaluate the consequences of the immediate} 20... f5 {but there is a forced line:} 21. exf5 {and now} gxf5 $2 {is met by} 22. Nxe5 $1 {, but 21...Nxf5 22.g4! works for White! 22...Nf4 23.gxf5 Nxh3+ 24.Kg2 Nf4+ 25.Kh2 Such things are always scary, but my judgment was correct. 25...Nxd5 26.Ng3 or 25...Bxd5 26.Ng3 $14 White's knights are nicely guarding the White king, and also Black's construction is not so stable...}) (20... Rc8 $1 {This is one of those mysterious comp moves which do not match with Black's last move. which had been 19...Nh5 looking for kingside activity.}) 21. Ne3 Bc8 $6 {Consequent, but the wrong spirit! This is now a very dynamic position, so Black should have better forgotten about traditional values and treat the position as it is! A very important question, what should White do now?} ({The computer once again points out that playing} 21... Rc8 $1 {is correct. White has difficulty finding a useful move, and Black has still not given up on pushing f7-f5 when the buried bishop on b7 anyway comes to life!} 22. Bc1 f5 {and here there is a forced line which leads to draw after complications} 23. Nxf5 $5 Nxf5 24. exf5 Bxc1 25. Rxc1 gxf5 26. Nxe5 $1 {Typical motif with the hanging knight on h5.} dxe5 27. Qxh5 Qxd5 28. Qg5+ Kh8 29. Bb1 Rxc1 30. Rxc1 Rg8 31. Qf6+ Rg7 32. Qf8+ Rg8 {ends with perpetual.}) 22. Bc1 $3 {I was so happy to be able to make this move; it also shows how much I regretted my impulsive emotional 18. Ba3 choice! There is also the psychological moment of the game, and from now on, I felt being in the driver's seat again!} Nf4 23. a4 $1 {Finally! What is Black's best reaction?} bxa4 $2 {Basically, I think that practically this was already the losing move!} ({There was still a fantastic strategical idea which could have justified the ...Bc8 concept...} 23... Rb8 $1 {with the surprising idea of} 24. axb5 Rxb5 $1 {and the active rook on b5 hitting the d5-pawn compensates for the c4-square!} 25. Nc4 f5 $1 {with counterplay.}) 24. bxa4 f5 {Yes, finally, Black has pushed f7-f5, but now White can simply ignore it nicely and go after the weaknesses in Black's camp.} 25. Nc4 $1 {Again the famous c4-square for the White knight!} (25. Rb1 $5) 25... fxe4 (25... Qc7 $2 26. Ncxe5 $1 {with the point} dxe5 27. d6 {.}) 26. Bxe4 Ra7 {Activating the rook along the 7th rank.} 27. Rb1 (27. Ba3 $1 {was even stronger according to the engines, but I did not want to tempt faith by moving my bishop back to a3!} Rf6 28. Rb1 Rc7 29. Ncxe5 {is fine for White but I was a bit worried about 27...Bxh3!? sacrifices. After 28.gxh3 Qc8 29.Nxd6 Qxh3 30.Nh2! , the bishop protects the g2-square and Qg4 is an important idea.}) 27... Rc7 28. Qb3 ({The super engines are pointing out that this tactical shot was possible, which we have both seen, of course, but with the coming time trouble, it was impossible to correctly assess all the complications after} 28. Ncxe5 $3 {, as} dxe5 29. d6 Rxc1 30. Rxc1 Nf5 31. Rxc8 $1 {was not obvious at all!} Qxc8 32. d7 Qd8 33. Bxf5 gxf5 34. Nxe5 {and the engine says it is completely winning... 28...Nxh3+ 29.gxh3 Bxc1 is also a pretty confusing line as White's kingside is destroyed. 30.Nc6!! Tranquilo! This is very much the superengines' influence... 30...Nxc6 31.dxc6 Bh6 32.Bd5+ Kh8 33.Rb8! Qf6 34.Qd4! I think that after all these sequences of moves, one risks disqualification, and rightly so!! 34...Qxd4 35.Nxd4 Bg7 36.Ne6 Bxe6 37.Rxf8+ Bxf8 38.Rxe6 Be7 39.f4 Kg7 40.Kf2 Kf8 41.Re3 Bd8 42.Rb3 and Rb8 is strong.}) 28... Bf5 $2 ({In time-trouble Black misses his sudden chance!} 28... Nf5 $1 {gives excellent counterplay, and suddenly it could have been anybody's game in time-trouble. A)} 29. Nb6 {solid choice, but this is more like bailing out to secure the situation!} Nd4 30. Nxd4 exd4 31. Nxc8 Rxc8 32. Bxf4 Bxf4 33. g3 Rc3 34. Qd1 Qg5 35. Qg4 Qxg4 36. hxg4 Be5 {B) 29.Bxf4 Bxf4 30.Na5 The problem is that Black can simply ignore the c6 knight and go for an attack on the kingside 30...Qf6 31.Nc6 h5 with a rook lift to f7 or g7, supporting ...g5.}) 29. Bxf4 ({The typical psychological situation, I keep threatening with} 29. Ncxe5 {especially after my previous 28. Qb3 move, and my great opponent simply ignores it, the result of course, with little time, I felt obliged to find another solution...} Rxc1 30. Rbxc1 dxe5 31. d6+ Be6 32. dxe7 $1 {wins.}) 29... exf4 ({After} 29... Bxf4 {I was already intending to play} 30. Ncxe5 $1 {as it was clear that here are definitely no tricks!}) 30. Bxf5 Nxf5 31. Na5 $1 {This idea attracted me and was the reason why I refrained from the 28. Ncxe5 option. Now, Black is completely paralyzed, and White can quietly look forward to any time pressure. There are no chances here for any surprise! White's king is perfectly safe, while Black's king is a real target now.} Qd7 32. Nc6 Qf7 33. Re6 Rfc8 34. Rbe1 {Total domination. The rest does not need any commentary.} Bf8 35. Ng5 Qd7 36. Qf3 Ng7 37. Rf6 Re8 (37... Nh5 38. Rf7 {and the queen is trapped.}) 38. Rxe8 Qxe8 39. Rxf4 Rb7 40. Re4 Qc8 41. g4 {And Black resigned. I have brilliant personal memories from the Dresden Olympiad by winning Gold on Board 1. It was very interesting to re-live the action of this unorthodox big street fight! The Zaitsev variation always brings a lot of tension!} 1-0

