1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 d6 {A Spanish with 6. d3 d6 can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer, as we have just seen in the Firouzja-Carlsen [/variation/37952165] game.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {Basically, exactly the same moves happened, only that here, it came from a 6. d3 Spanish instead of Anti-Berlin 4. d3...} 13. d5 {Magnus knew his stuff already back in 2008 when he was just 18 years old!} Ne7 14. Nf1 $5 ({This game was played 5-6 days after my game [/variation/37934914] with Navara, so Magnus had to be well aware of it. Even though he started with 6. d3, I think he had an idea of how to play this position if it were to happen... Going for} 14. Nf1 {shows a very nice sense for finesses. It is common knowledge that in such structures, Black is breaking with ...c7-c6, and if White is to play dxc6, then after ...Bxc6, Black opens up the diagonal for his bishop and will have a nice game. So, then, why is it so impressive what Magnus has done? The answer is pretty simple, but all the more impressive: he understood the exception of the situation!}) 14... Bg7 $5 ({Black finally refrained from} 14... c6 {Clearly, Black could have played like this, but David probably realized that it might be a bit uncomfortable and decided to take a much sharper direction...} 15. Bg5 Bg7 16. dxc6 Bxc6 {, and here it is essential to understand the difference between the unusual knight position on e7 and ...Nbd7 setups! As I understand, it is all about Black being unable to break with ...d6-d5 due to the vulnerable e5-pawn!}) *

