16... Bxc6 {Here, it is essential to understand the difference between the unusual knight position on e7 and ...Nbd7 setups! As I understand, it is all about Black being unable to break with ...d6-d5 due to the vulnerable e5-pawn! Carlsen showed his class.} 17. N1h2 $3 {Just continuing playing normal chess, but with some incredible precision! It is all about keeping as much tension in the position as possible and, at the same time, making sure that the ...d6-d5 break is under perfect control.} ({Playing for the typical d5 square à la Sveshnikov spirit with} 17. Bxf6 {brings absolutely nothing because after} Bxf6 18. Ne3 h5 $132 {suddenly Black's knight is perfectly placed on e7!}) ({And making a lazy move like} 17. Qd2 {would also not do because Black is in time with} Qc7 $1 18. N1h2 {too late now.} d5 $1 {Here, Black is ready to achieve the desired ...d6-d5 break and solves the problems of the awkward e7-knight.}) 17... Qc7 (17... Ra7 $5 {Typical high-class move.} 18. Qd2 Rd7 19. a4 $1 {With little pressure. Obviously, White is more comfortable. The rook is fancy on d7 but will be missing from the a-file...}) 18. Bxf6 $1 {Now is the right time!} Bxf6 19. Ng4 Bg7 20. Bb3 $1 {And suddenly, Black´s kingside feels shaky.} *

