17... Nxd5 {Can you improve on young Carlsen's play?} 18. Bg5 $3 (18. b4 $1 {The exclamation mark is to highlight that the young Magnus Carlsen was already very well aware of the idea of how to meet Spassky's legendary piece sacrifice in the Breyer! But here, the position is very specific, and it requires supercomputer precision to find the perfect sequence!} c5 $132 {Only supercomputers are capable of coming up with something like this. This amazing move is a game-changer! 18...Nxc3 was played by Navara and wonderfully refuted by Magnus, as we'll see next.} 19. bxc5 dxc5 20. c4 Nc3 $1 21. Qxd8 Raxd8 $13 {Thanks to Black's lovely coordination, this feels like enough compensation.}) 18... Qd7 19. b4 $3 {This is entirely a completely different language...} Nxc3 (19... c5 20. bxc5 dxc5 21. c4 $1 {is easy when we see the engine's lines. Otherwise, it is a completely different story! The pin along the d-file is the key issue!}) 20. Qd2 e4 (20... Ne4 21. Bxe4 Bxe4 22. Bh6 $1 {Again, this is some incredible computer precision...}) 21. Bb3+ Kh8 22. Nd4 c5 23. bxc5 dxc5 24. Ne6 $1 Qxd2 25. Bxd2 {With advantage.} Z0 (25... Rxe6 26. Bxe6 Ne2+ 27. Rxe2 Bxa1 28. g4 $1 {Breaking Black´s pawn structure is key.}) *

