1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 d6 {A Spanish with 6. d3 d6 can easily turn into a Zaitsev/Breyer, as we have just seen in the Firouzja-Carlsen [/variation/37952165] game.} 7. c3 O-O 8. Re1 Re8 9. Nbd2 Bf8 10. h3 b5 11. Bc2 Bb7 12. d4 g6 {Basically, exactly the same moves happened, only that here, it came from a 6. d3 Spanish instead of Anti-Berlin 4. d3...} 13. d5 {Magnus knew his stuff already back in 2008 when he was just 18 years old!} Ne7 14. Nf1 $5 ({This game was played 5-6 days after my game with Navara, so Magnus had to be well aware of it. Even though he started with 6. d3, I think he had an idea of how to play this position if it were to happen... Going for} 14. Nf1 {shows a very nice sense for finesses. It is common knowledge that in such structures, Black is breaking with ...c7-c6, and if White is to play dxc6, then after ...Bxc6, Black opens up the diagonal for his bishop and will have a nice game. So, then, why is it so impressive what Magnus has done? The answer is pretty simple, but all the more impressive: he understood the exception of the situation!}) (14. b3 {would run into} c6 15. c4 Bh6 {with pressure on the d5-pawn.}) 14... Bg7 $5 ({Black finally refrained from} 14... c6 {Clearly, Black could have played like this, but David probably realized that it might be a bit uncomfortable and decided to take a much sharper direction...} 15. Bg5 Bg7 16. dxc6 Bxc6 {, and here it is essential to understand the difference between the unusual knight position on e7 and ...Nbd7 setups! As I understand, it is all about Black being unable to break with ...d6-d5 due to the vulnerable e5-pawn! A) Playing for the typical d5 square à la Sveshnikov spirit with} 17. Bxf6 {brings absolutely nothing because after} Bxf6 18. Ne3 h5 $132 {suddenly Black's knight is perfectly placed on e7! B) And making a lazy move like 17.Qd2 would also not do because Black is in time with 17...Qc7! 18.N1h2 too late now. 18...d5! Here, Black is ready to achieve the desired ...d6-d5 break and solves the problems of the awkward e7-knight. C) 17.N1h2!! Just continuing playing normal chess, but with some incredible precision! It is all about keeping as much tension in the position as possible and, at the same time, making sure that the ...d6-d5 break is under perfect control. 17...Qc7 18.Bxf6! Now is the right time! 18...Bxf6 19.Ng4 Bg7 20.Bb3! and suddenly Black´s kingside feels shaky. 17...Ra7!? Typical high class move. 18.Qd2 Rd7 19.a4! With little pressure. Obviously, White is more comfortable. The rook is fancy on d7 but will be missing from the a-file...}) 15. b3 {Now that Magnus stopped the ...Bf8-h6 idea, he is switching back to classical ideas. What are Black's options?} Nxe4 $1 {David apparently got very excited about all these piece sacrifices, which I have told him in our post-mortem.} (15... c6 16. c4 cxd5 17. cxd5 Nexd5 $2 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bd2 {or 16...Rc8 17.Ne3 $14 is simply nice for White.}) 16. Bxe4 f5 17. Bc2 (17. Ng5 fxe4 18. c4 {is a positional way of handling the situation, and the computer suggests it, but it is humanly not that impressive.} Nf5 19. Nxe4 Qd7 {I understand why Magnus preferred to go for the complications instead because, practically, this position does not look so clear. Black has both ...Nf5-d4 and also ...c7-c6 ideas... Usually, I am a big fan of the e4-square, but here with Black having the pair of bishops, one really has the feeling that this is just unclear.}) 17... Nxd5 ({Actually, Black had a very interesting other alternative with} 17... e4 $1 18. Nd4 Nxd5 {and the b3 move has weakened the c3-pawn.} 19. b4 $5 {runs into} c5 $1 $132 {, so 19.Bd2 and if now 19...c5 20.Ne2 , slowly White will get out. Black has two main options: A) 19...Qf6! with ...b5-b4 to follow. 20.Rc1 b4 There is tons of pressure on White's position. How to handle it? ( 20...c5 21.Ne2 and White plays c4.) 21.Ne2!! Cool! 21...bxc3 22.Nxc3 Nxc3 23.Bxc3 Qxc3 24.Bxe4! fxe4 25.Rxc3 Bxc3 with a total mess! I don't tink that any side can claim any advantage here, just an unbalanced dynamic equality. 26.Ne3!? The knight will come to g4 or d5. B) 19...b4 20.c4 Nc3 21.Bxc3 bxc3 looks quite interesting for Black, but White has a very strong move... 22.b4!! Clearing the b3-square for the knight to reach a5, and allowing the bishop to move to a4. What a multi-purpose move! 22...c5 ( 22...Qf6 23.Nb3! ) 23.bxc5 dxc5 24.Ne2! Qc7 25.Rb1 Rad8 26.Qc1 There is not enough compensation. White´s knights are ready to be activated. 20...Bxd4 21.cxd5 feels good for White! For example: 21...Qh4 22.Be3 or 21...Bxa1? 22.Qxa1 and the king is exposed, or 21...a5 22.Rc1 Qh4 23.Be3 Bc3 24.Bb1 Bxe1 25.Qxe1 f4 26.g3! $16 Great touch! White gets control of all the dark squares!}) 18. b4 $1 {The exclamation mark is to highlight that the young Magnus Carlsen was already very well aware of the idea of how to meet Spassky's legendary piece sacrifice in the Breyer! But here, the position is very specific, and it requires supercomputer precision to find the perfect sequence!} (18. Bg5 $3 Qd7 19. b4 $3 {This is entirely a completely different language... A)} c5 20. bxc5 dxc5 21. c4 $1 {The knight is pinned, and taking on c4 opens tha a4-e8 diagonal. It is easy when we see the engine's lines. Otherwise, it is a completely different story! The pin along the d-file is the key issue!} bxc4 22. Ne3 $3 {The brutal computer...} e4 23. Ba4 {wins too much material. After 22.Ba4 Bc6 23.Ne3!! $16 , no surprise that suddenly I did not managed to spot it during the recording... Without full concentration so easy to miss it! 23.Bxc6? Qxc6 would in fact be good for Black! B) 19...Nxc3 20.Qd2 e4 protects the c3-knight and threatens the white knight. ( 20...Ne4 21.Bxe4 Bxe4 22.Bh6! is, again, some incredible computer precision...) 21.Bb3+ Kh8 22.Nd4 c5 23.bxc5 dxc5 24.Ne6! Qxd2 25.Bxd2 with advantage: 25...Rxe6 26.Bxe6 Ne2+ 27.Rxe2 Bxa1 Breaking Black´s pawn structure is key. Ng3 is coming.}) 18... Nxc3 (18... c5 $132 {Only supercomputers are capable of coming up with something like this. This amazing move is a game-changer!} 19. bxc5 dxc5 20. c4 Nc3 $1 21. Qxd8 Raxd8 $13 {Thanks to Black's lovely coordination, this feels like enough compensation. Instead, 20...bxc4 21.Rb1 Qc7 22.Qe2! e4 23.Qxc4 exf3 24.Rd1! is complex, but White should be in the driver's seat... Rxb7 removing the defender of the d5-knight is the immediate threat.}) 19. Bb3+ d5 20. Qc2 Ne4 {How to get clarity in this wild position?} 21. Rxe4 $3 {Absolutely wonderful! I remember being extremely impressed by this game from Magnus!} fxe4 22. Ng5 ({Stronger than} 22. Qxe4 Kh8 {. White´s pieces are taking over. Suddenly, all the dynamics are in White´s favor!}) 22... a5 23. bxa5 Rxa5 24. Nxe4 {It was a short but extremely intensive middlegame battle. The rest is a matter of technique.} Kh8 25. Bg5 Qc8 26. Nf6 Rd8 27. Ne3 e4 28. Rc1 h6 29. Nxe4 dxe4 30. Bxd8 Qxd8 31. Qxc7 Qxc7 32. Rxc7 Ba6 (32... Ba8 33. Rc8+ Kh7 34. Bg8+ Kh8 35. Bd5+ {wins the bishop.}) 33. Nd5 b4 34. Ra7 Bd4 35. Ra8+ Kh7 36. Nxb4 Rf5 37. Rxa6 Rxf2 38. Rd6 Rd2+ 39. Kf1 e3 40. Rxd4 Rxd4 41. Nd5 Rd3 42. Ke1 (42. Ke2 Rd2+ 43. Kxe3 Rxg2 {. Magnus keeps the g-pawn.}) 42... h5 43. Bc4 Rd4 44. Nxe3 Kh6 45. a4 Kg5 46. a5 Kf4 47. Kf2 Rd2+ 48. Be2 Ke4 49. a6 Ra2 50. h4 {It has been an incredible joy to have re-checked this game from the young Magnus Carlsen's collection. No surprise that he soon went on to become the Nr.1 in the World rankings!} *

