{Just when we might think that slowly we know all the ideas in these types of positions, the ever-so-original Alexander Morozevich comes along and creates something completely new!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. d4 Bb7 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Bc2 ({Again, trying to use this line as a small surprise. I assumed that Alexander was expecting the} 12. a3 {variation (my last game was vs Caruana from 2012), but he was clearly ready for it.}) 12... h6 {One of the moves, but didn't I mention before that this could turn out to be simply unnecessary? So why did Alexander choose it? Usually, he always had his own ideas/conclusions...} (12... g6 {is usually the main move, which we discussed in these games: Firouzja-Carlsen [/variation/37952165] Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914] Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252]}) 13. d5 Ne7 $1 {Usually, in these structures, the knight does not go here, but being as creative-minded as Moro has always been, he has found a very deep new concept during his preparation! Even today, I am still very impressed! Black has a double purpose with this move, as we will see.} (13... Nb8 {with the pawn on h6, this feels strange!} 14. b3 c6 15. c4 {Leading to typical positions, but with the pawn on h6 instead of g6! All these small nuances make the positions unique and should be treated as such. Here, in my mind, clearly, g6 would be much more useful for Black!}) 14. b3 c6 15. c4 {Following the typical plan of cementing the center.} *

