15. c4 {Following the typical plan of cementing the center. Here, Moro surprised me with a new plan that neutralized White's play.} a5 $1 {This hit me as a surprise as I had been expecting a completely different type of play on this day. Moro has probably noticed that his old plan is risky against a well-prepared opponent and has made sure to have a reliable new plan ready.} (15... cxd5 {Always a committal move, so unless there is something concrete in mind, Black should not release the tension.} 16. cxd5 Nd7 $1 {This is the line Moro has played in the past, hoping for a double-edged play connected with the typical ...f7-f5 break. This is a very complex position, but during my prep, I noticed that thanks to engine precision, White can hope to create problems for Black, as seen in our previous exercise.}) 16. Nf1 (16. a4 $5 {I have never been a big fan of this, but again, one needs to keep an open mind... In any case, it is now one of the top choices of engines. Do you remember how critical I was of this move in the Firouzja-Carlsen game? What changes the estimation of this move is the fact that Black's knight is on e7 and is not ready to occupy the lovely c5-square!} bxc4 17. bxc4 Ba6 {with counterplay, but White has not to fear fighting this position.}) 16... a4 $1 {Very deep prep by Moro! I remember burning tons of time on the clock in search of how to play and keep an advantage, but I could not find it. Probably because it simply does not exist! Actually, Black's play is very simple. 1. He makes sure to open up files on the queenside so that he can trade the rooks. 2. Since the black knight from e7 will find a nice square on g6, there is no issue with this piece. 3. Once the rooks are traded off, Black can easily regroup his passive blocked bishop from b7 to the desired d7-square via c8.} 17. Rb1 {Trying to keep as much tension as possible, but it was just a desperate measure.} (17. Bd2 $5 axb3 18. axb3 Rxa1 19. Qxa1 Qb6 20. Ne3 Ra8 $132) (17. dxc6 $2 {Again, this move is taboo!} Nxc6 $1 18. cxb5 Nb4 19. bxa4 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 Qa5 $1 {and Black is better.}) 17... axb3 18. axb3 Qc7 {Black has solved his opening problems. Next, we'll see my last attempt.} *

