{Just when we might think that slowly we know all the ideas in these types of positions, the ever-so-original Alexander Morozevich comes along and creates something completely new!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 10. d4 Bb7 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. Bc2 ({Again, trying to use this line as a small surprise. I assumed that Alexander was expecting the} 12. a3 {variation (my last game was vs Caruana from 2012), but he was clearly ready for it.}) 12... h6 {One of the moves, but didn't I mention before that this could turn out to be simply unnecessary? So why did Alexander choose it? Usually, he always had his own ideas/conclusions...} (12... g6 {is usually the main move, which we discussed in these games: Firouzja-Carlsen [/variation/37952165] Leko-Navara [/variation/37934914] Carlsen-Navara [/variation/38038252]}) 13. d5 Ne7 $1 {Usually, in these structures, the knight does not go here, but being as creative-minded as Moro has always been, he has found a very deep new concept during his preparation! Even today, I am still very impressed! Black has a double purpose with this move, as we will see.} (13... Nb8 {with the pawn on h6, this feels strange!} 14. b3 c6 15. c4 {Leading to typical positions, but with the pawn on h6 instead of g6! All these small nuances make the positions unique and should be treated as such. Here, in my mind, clearly, g6 would be much more useful for Black!}) 14. b3 c6 15. c4 {Following the typical plan of cementing the center.} a5 $1 {This hit me as a surprise as I had been expecting a completely different type of play on this day. Moro has probably noticed that his old plan is risky against a well-prepared opponent and has made sure to have a reliable new plan ready.} (15... cxd5 {Always a committal move, so unless there is something concrete in mind, Black should not release the tension.} 16. cxd5 Nd7 $1 {This is the line Moro has played in the past, hoping for a double-edged play connected with the typical f7-f5 break. This is a very complex position, but during my prep, I noticed that thanks to engine precision, White can hope to create problems for black.} 17. a4 $1 {17.Nf1 f5! Black takes over with this typical strike. 18.exf5 Nxd5 19.b4 N7b6 20.Be4 Qd7 $15 was the game [/variation/38709604] Polgar,J-Morozevich Mainz rapid 2008.�} f5 18. b4 $1 {In fact, this strong move is still a novelty; the idea is to open up the a2-g8 diagonal.} Nf6 19. Bb3 $1 {One of those mysterious engine moves...well, when we see the move, we can easily make sense of it! Here it is, eyeing the g8 king, and thanks to small tactics, White can keep his vulnerable center together!} Kh8 20. Nh4 {with very sharp play, but I was ready for and very much looking forward to it.}) 16. Nf1 (16. a4 $5 {I have never been a big fan of this, but again, one needs to keep an open mind... In any case, it is now one of the top choices of engines. Do you remember how critical I was of this move in the Firouzja-Carlsen game? What changes the estimation of this move is the fact that Black´s knight is on e7 and is not ready to occupy the lovely c5-square!} bxc4 17. bxc4 Ba6 {with counterplay, but White has not to fear fighting this position.}) 16... a4 $1 {Very deep prep by Moro! I remember burning tons of time on the clock in search of how to play and keep an advantage, but I could not find it. Probably because it simply does not exist! Actually, Black's play is very simple. 1. He makes sure to open up files on the queenside so that he can trade the rooks. 2. Since the black knight from e7 will find a nice square on g6, there is no issue with this piece. 3. Once the rooks are traded off, Black can easily regroup his passive blocked bishop from b7 to the desired d7-square via c8.} 17. Rb1 {Trying to keep as much tension as possible, but it was just a desperate measure.} (17. Bd2 $5 axb3 18. axb3 Rxa1 19. Qxa1 Qb6 20. Ne3 Ra8 $132) (17. dxc6 $2 {Again, this move is taboo!} Nxc6 $1 18. cxb5 Nb4 19. bxa4 Nxc2 20. Qxc2 Qa5 $1 {and Black is better.}) 17... axb3 18. axb3 Qc7 19. Ne3 bxc4 (19... Ng6 $5 {was also possible, but my opponent follows his original intentions by going for the rook trades.}) 20. bxc4 Reb8 21. Bd2 (21. Nh2 Bc8) (21. Nh4 Bc8 22. Rxb8 Qxb8) 21... Bc8 {Honestly, I was pretty impressed and had given up hope of getting any advantage. All I wanted to do was to keep the game going and see what happens later...} 22. Rxb8 Qxb8 23. Qb1 $1 {An important move and was part of my strategy when opting for 22. Rxb8.} Qc7 $1 (23... Qxb1 $6 {Clearly, I was hoping for the queen trade when Black faces a rather unpleasant defensive task.} 24. Rxb1 $14) 24. Qb2 Ng6 25. Ra1 Rxa1+ 26. Qxa1 {With approximate equality. Finally, I went on to win this game in a very long endgame, but it had nothing to do with the opening. I felt that it was very important to show this opening/middlegame. It was a very impressive piece of prep by Morozevich and shows once again that chess is absolutely unlimited with ideas!} *

