1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 ({Often, when playing the Zaitsev, top players start with this move just to limit White´s options.} 9... Bb7 10. d3 $5 {is an extra Anti-Zaitsev weapon which can also arise from different Anti-Marshalls! Objectively ok for Black, but it is a big complex! 10.d4 Re8 Is the same as the game.}) 10. d4 (10. d3 Na5 11. Bc2 c5 {keeping for now the bishop on c8 is known to be much easier for Black. That is why this is not really an attractive option for White.}) 10... Bb7 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a4 ({In my most ambitious years, from 1998 to 2006, I was ready to go for the most aggressive and critical lines. Later, it became all the more difficult, with engines getting stronger and stronger. Since the Zaitsev more or less disappeared from the top-level competitions, it was not very practical to go for a huge battle if you were surprised by it. Also, who knows how many hours the opponent checked the critical positions with an engine? This was the reason why I had both} 12. a3 {and}) (12. Bc2 {systems ready, just in case.}) 12... Na5 $5 ({Back then, this came as a big surprise. In my mind, the Spanish Zaitsev was connected with the big theoretical debate after} 12... h6 13. Bc2 exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 c5 16. d5 Nd7 17. Ra3 {and here Black had two very big moves with} f5 {or 17...c4 with tons of notes without any clarity! There were an incredible number of stunning games on this topic from both sides. Better only to enter this territory if we are sure to be the better-prepared player.}) 13. Bc2 (13. Ba2 {was the other option, but I did not want to play artificial moves in a decisive last-round game at the Olympiad (we were fighting for medals!)}) *

