16... Nc4 {How to fight this powerful knight? Think about White's options!} 17. Nbd2 $1 ({This is some phenomenal idea from engine, but not necessary at all! I just wanted to highlight that even such ideas are possible. Knowing extra motifs should never harm...} 17. Nfd2 $5 {is the classical reaction.} Nb6 18. a5 Na4 19. c4 $14 {with pressure on the b5-pawn, supported by a future Bd3. Classical advantage!}) 17... Nb6 (17... Nxd2 18. Bxd2 $16 {helps White, who will put pressure on b5.}) 18. c4 $3 {Fantastic!} (18. a5 Nbd7 19. c4 Nc5 {Black frees the d7-square for the other knight, not allowing 19...bxc4 20.Nxc4 .}) 18... Nxc4 (18... bxc4 19. a5 c3 20. axb6 cxd2 {I have extra questions for you about this position.}) 19. Nxc4 bxc4 20. a5 $1 {Fixes the structure and the c4-pawn will eventually fall.} Bc8 {Black wants to activate the bad bishop, so now we have to rush to win the c4-pawn!} (20... Qc7 21. Be3 $1 Nd7 22. Qe2 {White is in no rush to take back the c4 pawn, it simply cannot run away!}) 21. Nd2 $1 Qc7 22. Re3 $1 {Also a typical rook lift on the 3rd rank.} Bd7 23. Rc3 Bb5 24. Nxc4 $1 {Winning back the pawn thanks to this little tactics.} Bxc4 25. Bd3 {Followed by 26.Bxc4 when White has the bishop pair and a nice advantage.} *

