18. c4 $1 {Everything goes according to the plans... or not! Can you find Beliavsky's good practical continuation?} Nc5 $1 {Very good practical try! Black needs to create as much tension as possible and not allow White to get the grip of the position! If we feel that our position is under strategic pressure, we always need to look for an alternative to create practical problems for our opponent and force him to calculate! Never allow your opponent to get too comfortable!} (18... bxc4 19. Bxc4 $16 {There is nothing to talk about...}) (18... b4 $2 {is a typical mistake! How do we punish? A question for you to answer in another exercise.}) 19. axb5 Qb6 $1 {This was a very good reaction. Some sample lines:} (19... axb5 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. cxb5 f5 22. Ng5 $1 {with ideas like Ne6 or Qh5.} fxe4 23. Bc4 $16 {or 22...Nxb3 23.Qxb3 h6 ( 23...fxe4 24.Rd1 $16 protects the d5-pawn before recapturing on e4.) 24.Ne6 fxe4! 25.Rd1 Rc8 26.b6+- threatening Nc7. 26...Bxd5 27.Rxd5 Rxc1+ 28.Kh2 Qa1 but the king can escape. 29.b7 Rh1+ 30.Kg3 and Black can only resign.}) ({After} 19... Qb6 {, Black can meet} 20. Rb1 {with} axb5 {and 20.Ba4 with 20...axb5 21.Bxb5 Rxa1 22.Bxe8 h6! 23.Bb5 Bc8 with some lovely compensation thanks to his piece activity and the bad bishop on b5!}) *

