16. Nxb3 {This came from 13.Ba2, but our structure is similar to that in the game. How should Black continue?} Nc4 $1 {Keeping tension in the position! White has an ugly bishop on a2, and Black should try to use that!} (16... Nxb3 $2 17. Bxb3 {is a transposition to my game!}) (16... Nd7 $5 {Also possible as happened in the Sasikiran-Predke 2018 game. [/variation/38709609] �}) 17. Nfd2 Nb6 $1 {Again, it is very important to play in the correct spirit!} 18. a5 (18. Na5 Qc7 {is just fine for Black.} 19. Nxb7 Qxb7 20. a5 Na4 21. c4 Qc7 {and the a5-pawn is weak.}) 18... Na4 19. c4 Qc7 $132 {This is a very interesting structure (for Black!)} 20. Qf3 {Setting up a nice little trap...} Reb8 $1 {Black should just stick to his positional regrouping. Some sample lines:} ({A)} 20... bxc4 $2 {falling into the devilish trap.} 21. Bb1 $3 {stunning move} cxb3 22. Rxa4 {and the situation has clarified on the queenside, which is in White's favor.}) ({B)} 20... Bc8 $5 {Also possible, but Black has to show some real precision!} 21. Ba3 $5 bxc4 {( 21...Bd7 22.Rec1 is a small but important difference now White can hope for something!)} 22. Rec1 c3 23. Bb4 Bd7 24. Bxc3 Nxc3 25. Rxc3 {First feeling would be that without the dark-squared bishop, White has nothing, but a closer look shows us that White has a grip thanks to the a5-pawn, which we can use for the Nc4-b6 idea!} Qa7 26. Nc4 Rec8 27. Nb6 Rxc3 28. Qxc3 Rb8 29. Nd2 Be7 30. Rb1 Bd8 31. Qb4 Bc7 $13 {and with computer's precision Black is just in time as usual.}) ({After} 20... Reb8 $1 {,} 21. Ba3 bxc4 $1 22. Rac1 c3 {is good for Black, and if 21.Bb1 Bc8 22.Bd3 Bd7 23.Ba3 Be8= , both sides have improved their position to the maximum, and now there is no follow-up! The desired 24.Rec1? runs into 24...b4 trapping the bishop.}) *

