22... b4 $1 {What did I have in mind here?} 23. Ba4 $3 {By playing this lovely move, I felt really happy, and my opponent cracked under the double pressure of me being happy and the position being critical!} Ba6 $2 {Cracking under pressure.} (23... Rxa4 $2 24. Qxa4 $1 {( 24.Bxc5 Qa5 protecting the rook. 25.Nb3 Qa6 )} Nxa4 25. Bxb6 Nxb6 26. Rxb4 {with pressure on the b-file.} Nd7 27. Reb1 Nc5 28. Rb5 $5 {or 28.Nb3 Na6 29.Na5 Nxb4 30.Rxb4 $16 and White captures the bishop.}) 24. Bc6 Ra7 25. Qc2 $1 {A quiet little move. Now, White gets perfect coordination!} Rc7 {Black is fighting! Black wants to survive thanks to the positional exchange sacrifice.} (25... Bb7 26. Bb5 {White won a huge tempo which is enough to decide the battle..}) 26. Rb2 $1 {Not afraid of ghosts! I am a big fan of positional exchange sacrifices, but here, I have a clear target in the b4-pawn, so Black's position will not be stable enough!} Rxc6 27. dxc6 Qxc6 28. Reb1 {The b-pawn is doomed. Let's see Beliavsky's reply next.} *

