1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Re8 ({Often, when playing the Zaitsev, top players start with this move just to limit White´s options.} 9... Bb7 10. d3 $5 {is an extra Anti-Zaitsev weapon which can also arise from different Anti-Marshalls! Objectively ok for Black, but it is a big complex! 10.d4 Re8 is the same as the game.}) 10. d4 (10. d3 Na5 11. Bc2 c5 {keeping for now the bishop on c8 is known to be much easier for Black. That is why this is not really an attractive option for White.}) 10... Bb7 11. Nbd2 Bf8 12. a4 ({In my most ambitious years, from 1998 to 2006, I was ready to go for the most aggressive and critical lines. Later, it became all the more difficult, with engines getting stronger and stronger. Since the Zaitsev more or less disappeared from the top-level competitions, it was not very practical to go for a huge battle if you were surprised by it. Also, who knows how many hours the opponent checked the critical positions with an engine? This was the reason why I had both} 12. a3 {and}) (12. Bc2 {systems ready, just in case.}) 12... Na5 $5 ({Back then, this came as a big surprise. In my mind, the Spanish Zaitsev was connected with the big theoretical debate after} 12... h6 13. Bc2 exd4 14. cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 c5 16. d5 Nd7 17. Ra3 {and here Black had two very big moves with} f5 {or 17...c4 with tons of notes without any clarity! There were an incredible number of stunning games on this topic from both sides. Better only to enter this territory if we are sure to be the better-prepared player.}) 13. Bc2 (13. Ba2 {was the other option, but I did not want to play artificial moves in a decisive last-round game at the Olympiad (we were fighting for medals!)} c5 {and now: A)} 14. b4 $2 {happened in an Ivanchuk-Beliavsky game...} cxb4 15. cxb4 Nc6 16. Qb3 {was the game [/variation/38709607] Ivanchuk-Beliavsky 2000, � and} d5 $132 {was the improvement in the game [/variation/38709608] Stellwagen-Beliavsky, 2007. � I want to highlight that this piece sacrifice 14...exd4! is also a typical motif that we need to keep in mind in such positions! Some sample lines: 15.bxa5 dxc3 $17 16.Qb3? cxd2 17.Qxf7+ Kh8 18.Ng5 dxe1=Q Black just wins by promoting the queen with check! 18...dxc1=Q?? What is wrong with this? 19.Qg8+! Nxg8 20.Nf7 always lovely... or 15.Ng5 c4 or 15.cxd4 cxb4 and there's not enough compensation! 15.d5 Nd7 $15 with ...Rc8 and ...Nc4 ideas. If 15.axb5 dxc3 16.Ng5 c4 17.Nxc4 Nxc4 18.Bxc4 d5 and only Black can be better. B) 14.d5 c4 15.b4! Only now. 15...cxb3 16.Nxb3 with a similar structure to what we will see later in the game. Now 16...Nd7!? is possible, as happened in the Sasikiran-Predke 2018 game, [/variation/38709609] � while 16...Nxb3? 17.Bxb3 is a transposition to my game! White has an ugly bishop on a2, and Black should try to use that! 16...Nc4! Keeping tension in the position! 17.Nfd2 Nb6! Again, it is very important to play in the correct spirit! 18.a5 ( 18.Na5 Qc7 is just fine for Black. 19.Nxb7 Qxb7 20.a5 Na4 21.c4 Qc7 and the a5-pawn is weak.) 18...Na4 19.c4 Qc7 $132 is a very interesting structure (for Black!) 20.Qf3 Setting up a nice little trap... B1) 20...bxc4? falling into the devilish trap. 21.Bb1!! Stunning move! 21...cxb3 22.Rxa4 and the situation has clarified on the queenside, which is in White's favor. B2) 20...Bc8!? is also possible, but Black has to show some real precision! 21.Ba3!? bxc4 ( 21...Bd7 22.Rec1 is a small but important difference now White can hope for something!) 22.Rec1 c3 23.Bb4 Bd7 24.Bxc3 Nxc3 25.Rxc3 First feeling would be that without the dark-squared bishop, White has nothing, but a closer look shows us that White has a grip thanks to the a5-pawn, which we can use for the Nc4-b6 idea! 25...Qa7 26.Nc4 Rec8 27.Nb6 Rxc3 28.Qxc3 Rb8 29.Nd2 Be7 30.Rb1 Bd8 31.Qb4 Bc7 $13 and with computer's precision Black is just in time as usual. B3) 20...Reb8! Black should just stick to his positional regrouping. 21.Ba3 bxc4! 22.Rac1 c3 is good for Black, and if 21.Bb1 Bc8 22.Bd3 Bd7 23.Ba3 Be8= , both sides have improved their position to the maximum, and now there is no follow-up! The desired 24.Rec1? runs into 24...b4 trapping the bishop.}) 13... c5 $2 {This is just wrong. My opponent treats the position just like after 12.Ba2, but now there are different rules!} (13... exd4 $1 {is the justification of 12...Na5, and indeed, it is now getting popular in the 2020s! Back at the beginning of the 2000s, this would have been a real shock... Giving up the center just like this without any real concrete benefit...} 14. cxd4 b4 $1 {This is the justification! Suddenly, the knight on a5 is a beautifully placed piece!} 15. e5 dxe5 $1 16. dxe5 Nd7 $132 {is out of control! However, 15.b3 g6 16.Bb2 Bg7 $13 is a very interesting position. I believe this whole line will become quite topical as happened now in the game [/variation/38709610] Zilka-Vitiugov, 2023. �}) 14. d5 $1 {Whenever the bishop is on b7 in these types of positions, this is the first move we should look at!} c4 15. b4 $1 {I was very happy about this opportunity, blowing the queenside open and changing the character of the position.} (15. Nf1 Nd7 {gives Black what he wants with eternal counterplay due to the b3-square!} 16. Be3 Qc7 {and ...Nc5 is coming.}) 15... cxb3 16. Nxb3 {During the game, I had no idea how good my position was; I was just trying to play in the right spirit.} Nxb3 (16... Nc4 {gives White many options. With the c2-bishop White has every reason to be happy.} 17. Nfd2 $5 {is the classical reaction.} Nb6 18. a5 Na4 19. c4 $14 {with pressure on the b5-pawn, supported by a future Bd3. Classical advantage! Instead, 17.Nbd2!! is some phenomenal idea from engine, but not necessary at all! I just wanted to highlight that even such ideas are possible. Knowing extra motifs should never harm... 17...Nxd2 18.Bxd2 $16 helps White, who will put pressure on b5. 17...Nb6 18.c4!! fantastic! ( 18.a5 Nbd7 19.c4 Nc5 freeing the d7-square for the other knight, and not allowing 19...bxc4 20.Nxc4 ) A) 18...Nxc4 19.Nxc4 bxc4 20.a5! fixes the structure and the c4-pawn will eventually fall. 20...Bc8 Black wants to activate the bad bishop, so now we have to rush to win the c4-pawn! (If 20...Qc7 21.Be3! Nd7 22.Qe2 , White is in no rush to take back the c4-pawn; it simply cannot run away! Rc1, Ba4, and Nd2-Nb1 are thematic ideas.) 21.Nd2! Qc7 22.Re3! Also a typical rook lift on the 3rd rank. 22...Bd7 23.Rc3 Bb5 24.Nxc4! winning back the pawn thanks to this little tactics. 24...Bxc4 25.Bd3 and White will capture the pinned bishop and put pressure on the a6-pawn. B) 18...bxc4 19.a5 c3 trading the knights. 20.axb6 cxd2 21.Nxd2! Qxb6 22.Nc4 We already know what it means when a White knight appears on c4 in all these structures. 22...Qc7 23.Na5 $16 It does not matter that Black is a pawn up! It is much more important that thanks to the open files and open diagonals + the monster knight on a5 eyeing the c6-square, Black is in a lot of trouble. 23.Qe2 would allow 23...a5! and ...Ba6.}) 17. Bxb3 Nd7 (17... Qc7 18. Bd2 Nd7 19. c4 $1 {Thanks to this energetic push, Black is just a bit slow...} bxc4 20. Rc1 Nc5 21. Bxc4 Bc8 22. Be3 $16 {Black is unable to keep the c5-square for his knight. 18...Reb8 happened in a recent game [/variation/38709611] Sychev-Artemiev in 2022.� 19.c4! was again the way to proceed with a clear advantage. Black is forced to react because after 19...Bc8? 20.axb5 axb5 21.Rxa8 Rxa8 22.cxb5+- simply wins a pawn, but 19...bxc4 20.Rc1 Bc8 21.Bxc4 $16 is also good for White. The a6-pawn is weak.}) 18. c4 $1 {Everything goes according to the plans...} Nc5 $1 {Very good practical try! Black needs to create as much tension as possible and not allow White to get the grip of the position! If we feel that our position is under strategic pressure, we always need to look for an alternative to create practical problems for our opponent and force him to calculate! Never allow your opponent to get too comfortable!} (18... bxc4 19. Bxc4 $16 {There is nothing to talk about...}) (18... b4 $2 {If Black could make one more move, then it would be fantastic, but it is now White to move!! How do we react?} 19. a5 $1 {Yes, the b4-pawn gets isolated and can't be protected in the long term. We also get access to the a4-square! ( 19.Bd2? allows 19...a5 and strategically Black is winning!)} Nc5 20. Bd2 Nd3 21. Re3 {and the b4-pawn falls, or 19...Rb8 20.Bd2 Bc8 21.Ra4 winning the pawn after 21...Nc5 22.Rxb4 Rxb4 23.Bxb4 .}) 19. axb5 Qb6 $1 {This was a very good reaction.} (19... axb5 20. Rxa8 Qxa8 21. cxb5 f5 22. Ng5 $1 {with ideas like Ne6 or Qh5. ( 22.exf5 Nxb3 23.Qxb3 Bxd5 is not so clear.)} fxe4 23. Bc4 $16 {or 22...Nxb3 23.Qxb3 h6 ( 23...fxe4 24.Rd1 $16 protects the d5-pawn before recapturing on e4.) 24.Ne6 fxe4! 25.Rd1 Rc8 26.b6+- threatening Nc7. 26...Bxd5 27.Rxd5 Rxc1+ 28.Kh2 Qa1 but the king can escape. 29.b7 Rh1+ 30.Kg3 and Black can only resign.}) 20. Rb1 (20. Ba4 axb5 $1 {( 20...Nxa4? 21.Rxa4 axb5 22.Be3!+- and White captures b5 next.)} 21. Bxb5 Rxa1 22. Bxe8 h6 $1 {with good positional compensation.} 23. Bb5 $6 Bc8 {Black has some lovely compensation. Black's pieces are active, and the bishop on b5 has no prospects!}) 20... axb5 21. Be3 (21. Bc2 {Computers give the following line with a clear advantage, but over the board, something really bothered me with this...} Ba6 {( 21...b4 22.Bd2 and the pawn is vulnerable.)} 22. Bd2 $1 Reb8 23. Qe2 {Strategically, what could be an interesting idea for Black here?} b4 $3 {When I noticed this idea during the game, I knew that I would never let this happen...} 24. Bxb4 Qxb4 25. Rxb4 Rxb4 {This is one of those positions when engines might claim an advantage, but a good player´s intuition will always believe that Black has a good play here...}) 21... Reb8 ({A)} 21... Qc7 22. Nd2 $14 {gives a small edge. Giving up the e4-pawn is psychologically never easy in the Classical Spanish, but thanks to White's activity, it is very good for White! 22.cxb5! Nxe4 23.b6 Qd7 24.Rc1 eyeing the entry point on c7. 24...Rec8 25.Qd3 threatening the knight, and here: A1) 25...Nf6 26.Rxc8 Rxc8 27.Nd2! and Black can't really do much against the simple but effective threat of Ra1-a7 after which Nc4-a5 will be deadly. A2) 25...f5? What is a lovely idea here? 26.Rc6!! Yes, thanks to tactics we can cement our rook on c6!! 26...Kh8 27.Rec1! Bxc6 28.dxc6 Rxc6 29.Qd5+- Rxc1 30.Bxc1 and the double attack on a8 and g8 decides.}) ({B)} 21... Ra3 22. Ba4 $3 {beautiful.} Rxa4 23. Qxa4 {and Black is doubly pinned.}) ({C)} 21... b4 $1 {looks like Black has counterplay with ....Ra3. Now not} 22. Re2 Qc7 {but 22.Ba4! I was hoping for this, as we will see in our game as well.. 22...Reb8 ( 22...Rxa4 23.Qxa4 Nxa4 24.Bxb6 Nxb6 25.Rxb4 is the point.) 23.Bb5 This looked so good for White during the game that we both completely missed the ideas that super engines are showing now. 23...Qc7!! The move we both missed during the game! Suddenly, there is no good way to protect the e4-pawn, and a special move-per-move battle starts (engine's territory!). 24.Nd2 During the game I was sure that this should be better for White, but now versus engines I can't prove anything... C1) 24...Ba6 25.Bc6 Bb7 26.Rxb4 Bxc6 27.Bxc5! dxc5 28.Rxb8 Rxb8 29.dxc6 $14 The knight is better than the bishop and White has the important d5-square. C2) 24...Ra2!? the b4-pawn is indirectly protected by the fork on d3. 25.Re2 Ba6! 26.Rxb4 Qa5! 27.Bxc5 dxc5 28.Rb1 Bxb5 29.cxb5 Rxb5 30.Rc1 Qa4! is a very computerish solution because if White stabilizes here, he will get a big advantage, but comp move per move holds it... 31.Qxa4 Rxa4 32.Nc4 Rbb4 33.Rec2 is almost over, but in the analysis, we are dealing with an engine! 33...g6! provokes the d5-d6 move. 34.d6 f6! and by miracle Black holds this! C3) 24...Bc8 25.Qc2 Ra3 $132 and the engine sees no way to claim an advantage! Again, the b4-pawn is safe.}) 22. Nd2 (22. Ba4 $2 Rxa4 23. Qxa4 Nxa4 24. Bxb6 Nxb6 25. Rxb5 Ba6 $1 {and ...Nd7. The direct 25...Nd7 run into 26.Reb1 Nc5 27.Nd2 and Nb3.}) (22. cxb5 $1 {Objectively, I should have been simplistic, but I clearly wanted more, and in the heat of the battle, I also felt that I had all the rights to look for more!} Qxb5 23. Nd2 Bc8 24. Bc4 Qa5 {White can press this.}) 22... b4 $1 {What did I have in mind here?} (22... bxc4 23. Bxc4 {Is a better version, White wins a tempo and this is what I wanted to get that is why I did not like 22.cxb5 so much...}) 23. Ba4 $3 {By playing this lovely move, I felt really happy, and my opponent cracked under the double pressure of me being happy and the position being critical!} Ba6 $2 {Cracking under pressure.} (23... Rxa4 $2 24. Qxa4 $1 {( 24.Bxc5 Qa5 protecting the rook. 25.Nb3 Qa6 )} Nxa4 25. Bxb6 Nxb6 26. Rxb4 {with pressure on the b-file.} Nd7 27. Reb1 Nc5 28. Rb5 $5 {or 28.Nb3 Na6 29.Na5 Nxb4 30.Rxb4 $16 and White captures the bishop.}) (23... Qc7 $3 24. Bb5 {We would have exactly landed in the lines discussed after 21...b4. Good when we don't have to fight vs. a silicon beast!}) 24. Bc6 Ra7 25. Qc2 $1 {A quiet little move. Now, White gets perfect coordination!} Rc7 {Black is fighting! Black wants to survive thanks to the positional exchange sacrifice.} (25... Bb7 26. Bb5 {White won a huge tempo which is enough to decide the battle..}) 26. Rb2 $1 {Not afraid of ghosts! I am a big fan of positional exchange sacrifices, but here, I have a clear target in the b4-pawn, so Black's position will not be stable enough!} Rxc6 27. dxc6 Qxc6 28. Reb1 b3 {Transforming the structure.} 29. Nxb3 Qxe4 (29... Nxb3 30. Rxb3 Rxb3 31. Rxb3 Qxc4 32. Rc3 Qb4 33. Rc7 {Black has no chances to survive this. With a black bishop on e6, it would be a different situation. Then, there would be hope for Cemento!}) 30. Qxe4 Nxe4 31. Na5 $1 {With a technically winning position. It was a true miracle that I did not win this game, which finally cost us the bronze medal! Certainly a total nightmare... Luckily, we won two silver medals later on in 2002 Bled and Tromsö 2014, which helped to heal the wounds...} *

