{Now we will take a look at a few examples where, from a Breyer or Zaitsev, Black decides to take the fight towards Spanish/Benoni structures.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 (11... Re8 $2 {Just making sure that we never forget this...} 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6 {and the queen is lost!}) 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {I always love to see this system being played by other top players!} exd4 $6 {I do not believe in Black's idea to turn a Classical Spanish into a Benoni structure... But let´s not forget the fact that we already know from the Breyer 'Wild Affair' [/variation/38397300/#/16/b/0.0] Theory Survey that at that time, Mamedyarov was playing a losing line... I am pretty sure that Moro was ready to bury that line once and for all, so Shakhriyar needed some emergency alternative just in case...} *

