16... c5 {Black is taking the fight towards a Benoni structure. Don't fall for his tricks and take into account the special features of the position.} 17. d5 $1 {Principled and good! The main problem of this Benoni is Black's blocked bishop on b7!} Bg7 (17... a5 {is met nicely with} 18. Bg5 $1 {Annoying! Putting pressure with the pin and inviting ...h6, which will not only weaken Black´s position but also give a Qd2 tempo.} Ba6 19. Qd2 {.}) 18. Rb1 $3 {Again, a very strong little prophylactic move! Avoiding all tricks and getting ready to develop the bishop to the ideal f4 square.} (18. Bf4 $2 Nxd5 $1 {is the devilish trick!} 19. exd5 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Qf6 $1) (18. Bb2 {runs into another trick:} Nxe4 $1 19. Bxg7 Nxg3 20. Bb2 Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Nh5 22. Qd2 Qf8 $1 23. Nh2 f5 {White has compensation, but I do not believe that it is enough for advantage. The long diagonal can be blocked with ...Nhf6.}) 18... a5 (18... Rc8 19. Bf4 Qb6 20. a4 {or 20.Qd2 with ideas like Bh6 and Nf5. If 19...Ne5 20.Nxe5 dxe5 21.Be3 Re7! This is the only justification. 22.a4 Ne8 23.axb5 axb5 24.b4!? and now if 24...c4 25.Ne2! , the knight goes to c3. 24...cxb4 25.Bd2 Rec7 26.Bd3 Nd6 27.Bxb4 Nc4 28.Ne2 Ba6 29.Nc3 $16 was the game [/variation/38709612] Leko-Jumabayev, Doha rapid 2016. �}) 19. Bf4 Qc7 20. Qd2 $1 {I like this plan more. Again, typical: once the black queen moves towards the queenside, the plan of going for Bh6 is very tempting...} ({Moro played the typical idea} 20. Bd3 $6 {but after 19...Qc7, this is the wrong plan!} Ba6 21. a4 $6 {Very logical what White is doing, but Black has exactly prepared effectively for this plan with his 19...Qc7 move! If 21.Qd2 b4 , Black gets time to create counterplay. 22.Bxa6 Rxa6 23.Bh6 Probably still slightly better for White, but I want more than this!}) *

