{Now we will take a look at a few examples where, from a Breyer or Zaitsev, Black decides to take the fight towards Spanish/Benoni structures.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nb8 10. d4 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 Bb7 (11... Re8 $2 {Just making sure that we never forget this...} 12. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 13. Ng5+ Kg8 14. Ne6 {and the queen is lost!}) 12. Bc2 Re8 13. Nf1 Bf8 14. Ng3 g6 15. b3 {I always love to see this system being played by other top players!} exd4 $6 {I do not believe in Black's idea to turn a Classical Spanish into a Benoni structure... But let´s not forget the fact that we already know from the Breyer 'Wild Affair' [/variation/38397300/#/16/b/0.0] Theory Survey that at that time, Mamedyarov was playing a losing line... I am pretty sure that Moro was ready to bury that line once and for all, so Shakhriyar needed some emergency alternative just in case...} 16. cxd4 c5 17. d5 $1 {Principled and good! The main problem of this Benoni is Black´s blocked bishop on b7!} Bg7 (17... a5 {is met nicely with} 18. Bg5 $1 {Annoying! Putting pressure with the pin and inviting ...h6, which will not only weaken Black´s position but also give a Qd2 tempo.} Ba6 19. Qd2 {.}) {What should White do here?} 18. Rb1 $3 {Again, a very strong little prophylactic move! Avoiding all tricks and getting ready to develop the bishop to the ideal f4-square.} ({A)} 18. Bf4 $2 {Is there something special here?} Nxd5 $1 {This is the devilish trick!} 19. exd5 Rxe1+ 20. Qxe1 Qf6 $1 {with a double attack.}) ({B)} 18. Bb2 {runs into another trick:} Nxe4 $1 19. Bxg7 Nxg3 20. Bb2 Rxe1+ 21. Qxe1 Nh5 22. Qd2 Qf8 $1 23. Nh2 f5 {White has compensation, but I do not believe that it is enough for advantage. The long diagonal can be blocked with ...Nhf6.}) 18... a5 (18... Rc8 19. Bf4 Qb6 20. a4 {or 20.Qd2 with ideas like Bh6 and Nf5. If 19...Ne5 20.Nxe5 dxe5 21.Be3 Re7! This is the only justification. 22.a4 Ne8 23.axb5 axb5 24.b4!? and now if 24...c4 25.Ne2! , the knight goes to c3. 24...cxb4 25.Bd2 Rec7 26.Bd3 Nd6 27.Bxb4 Nc4 28.Ne2 Ba6 29.Nc3 $16 was the game [/variation/38709612] Leko-Jumabayev, Doha rapid 2016. �}) 19. Bf4 Qc7 {Important moment! What is the best plan for White here?} 20. Bd3 $6 {Typical idea, but after 19...Qc7, this is the wrong plan!} (20. Qd2 $1 {I like this plan more. Again, typical: once the black queen moves towards the queenside, the plan of going for Bh6 is very tempting...}) 20... Ba6 21. a4 $6 {Very logical what White is doing, but Black has exactly prepared effectively for this plan with the 19..Qc7 move!} (21. Qd2 b4 {Black gets time to create counterplay.} 22. Bxa6 Rxa6 23. Bh6 {Probably still slightly better for White, but I want more than this!}) {Very interesting moment. How should Black deal now with the action on the queenside?} 21... c4 (21... bxa4 $1 22. Bxa6 Rxa6 23. bxa4 Rb6 $132 {and Black gets enough counterplay. Now that the queenside has opened up, White will not have time to create a kingside attack. Black will have his play with ...Rb6-b4, or after the trade with} 24. Rxb6 Nxb6 {, the combination of ...Nfd7 and targeting the weakness of the a4-pawn with ...Qd7 will help Black to keep the balance. Important to highlight that the white knight on g3 is suddenly far from the action!}) 22. bxc4 bxc4 23. Bc2 {Very important position! What would be the best way to play with Black?} c3 $2 {It takes only one inaccuracy, and White again gets the upper hand!} (23... Nc5 $2 {allows the break} 24. e5 $1 dxe5 25. Nxe5 $16 {Black faces concrete problems with the queen on c7...}) ({It was very important to play} 23... Ne5 $1 {immediately, not giving White time! After} 24. Nd4 Nfd7 $1 {, now the Ndf5 or Ngf5 sacrifices will not work! After Nxe5 dxe5} 25. Be3 Reb8 $132 {, Black can activate his pieces with ...Ne8-...Nd6 and ...Bf8 fighting for the b4-square. White's knight will go to c3.}) {What did Moro had in mind here?} 24. Re3 $3 {Brilliant! Moro spots his chance instantly! This is a multi-purpose move targeting the c3-pawn and setting up the powerful Nd4-f5 sacrifice!} Nb6 $6 {As often, mistakes come in bunches...} (24... Ne5 25. Nd4 Nfd7 26. Rb3 {would win the c3-pawn. What are the other benefits of the Re3 move?}) 25. Nd4 $1 Nfd7 {Why was the Re3 and Nd4 sequence so special? What is the follow-up?} 26. Ndf5 $1 {This is a typical piece sacrifice in many of the Classical Spanish positions when White is active, and Black´s pieces are far away from the kingside.} (26. Ngf5 $1 {might have been even stronger.} Be5 27. Bxe5 Nxe5 28. Qc1 $5 {Not the only good move, but a nice one!} Kh8 29. Rg3 {with terrible attack:} gxf5 30. Qg5 {threatening mate.} Ng6 31. Qf6+ Kg8 32. Nxf5 {and mate.}) 26... Be5 (26... gxf5 27. Nxf5 Ne5 28. Rg3 Ng6 29. Nxg7 Kxg7 30. Qd4+ f6 31. Rxb6 {and wins.}) 27. Nh6+ (27. Bxe5 Nxe5 28. f4 {maybe was even stronger.}) 27... Kf8 28. Bxe5 Nxe5 29. Qd4 Nbc4 30. Rxc3 Qa7 {This was still horrible. White is a healthy pawn up, but the fact that Black survived a brutal attack without getting mated helped him psychologically to defend this bad position. I can only sympathize with Moro; it was a wonderfully played game that should have resulted in victory...} *

