{This is a very special game which also perfectly fits into the topic when from a Classical Spanish we transpose into Benoni structures...} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Ng5 {As we know already, a clever tactic by time-trouble addicts!} Rf8 12. Nf3 Re8 13. Nbd2 exd4 {Around 2015, this artificially looking double-edged option started to get popular thanks to efforts by such greats as Peter Svidler and Bu Xiangzhi. For a while, Black was getting the desired results, but then came the following game (pearl) from Sasha Grischuk!} 14. cxd4 Nd7 {This is Black's idea. Black gives up the center but hopes to achieve good counterplay in the resulting Benoni structure. The plan is to play ...Na5 and ...Bf6, followed by ...c5, and play on the dark squares. Once again, the real problem is the b7-bishop!} 15. Nf1 Na5 16. Bc2 Bf6 {Now is the big question of how to proceed with White. The trick was always that White has tons of different move orders, and it is very easy to get lost in them!} *

