23. Bd2 {Luckily, in my game against Nyback in 2015, my opponent made a serious inaccuracy, giving me a chance to get a grip on the position. What would have been the best way to play for Black?} Bd4 24. Z0 ({I was very worried about this move (it is a monster bishop!), not really seeing how to play for an advantage.} 24. Be3 Bc3 {This is very annoying. Suddenly, White has trouble avoiding the move repetition. 23...Bxd2 Practically, Black should have never played like this! It just gave me the freedom I was dreaming about. 24.Qxd2 a5 25.Bd3 Ba6 26.Bxa6 Rxa6 27.f4 was the game [/variation/38709613] Leko-Nyback, Reykjavik 2015. � I felt pretty happy that I got a stable position, which I can try to press also in the approaching time-trouble. My play is easy with all the small improving moves, and I am hoping for the perfect time to push e4-e5 at some point. 25.f4!? Was more ambitious, but after spending so much time and nerves I opted for the lazier approach... 25...Qh4! This was the strong move that disturbed me. 26.Bd3 h5 and the fact that here my knight can't move to e3 was the reason why I decided on 25. Bd3 27.Nh2 Ba6 28.Nf3 Qg3! 29.Bxa6 Rxa6 $13 This queen on g3 is a very special piece causing quite some headache...}) *

