24... Bc3 25. Bf4 $3 {It is great training, so anyone who wants to can think about this moment and how to play with White! (Very difficult...) The idea gets a double exclamation mark, but the mess remains!} (25. Ngh6+ $5 gxh6 26. b4 $3 {is something from a completely different planet!!}) 25... Bxd5 (25... Bc8 $1 {stops the mating ideas.} 26. Ngh6+ $2 gxh6 27. Qg4+ Kh8 {just wins for Black, and after 26.Nxd6 Bxe1 27.Qxe1 d2!! , the fun continues, but I will let everyone analyze it further if interested. The lines are impressive but simply never-ending... I think we can agree that my assessment that the position after 19...Nce5 is really critical probably stands!}) (25... Bxe1 $2 26. Ngh6+ $3 {Beautiful tactical shot!} Kf8 27. Bxd6+ {or 26...Kh8 27.Nxf7+ are winning. 26...gxh6 27.Qg4++- leads to mate.}) 26. Ngh6+ $3 {Again!} gxh6 27. Qg4+ Kh8 28. exd5 {Black's position is falling apart.} h5 (28... Qf6 29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Nxd6 Rd8 31. Rc1 $1 {The final touch!} b4 32. Rxc3 bxc3 33. Be5 Qxe5 34. Nxf7#) 29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. Qf3 Qe2 31. Nxd6 Qxf3 32. gxf3 {With a great endgame for White, which is especially easy to understand when we have access to the engine's evaluation! It turns out that the d3-pawn is a big weakness...} *

