{This is a very special game which also perfectly fits into the topic when from a Classical Spanish we transpose into Benoni structures...} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Ng5 {As we know already, a clever tactic by time-trouble addicts!} Rf8 12. Nf3 Re8 13. Nbd2 exd4 {Around 2015, this artificially looking double-edged option started to get popular thanks to efforts by such greats as Peter Svidler and Bu Xiangzhi. For a while, Black was getting the desired results, but then came the following game (pearl) from Sasha Grischuk!} 14. cxd4 Nd7 {This is Black's idea. Black gives up the center but hopes to achieve good counterplay in the resulting Benoni structure. The plan is to play ...Na5 and ...Bf6, followed by ...c5, and play on the dark squares. Once again, the real problem is the b7-bishop!} 15. Nf1 Na5 16. Bc2 Bf6 {Now is the big question of how to proceed with White. The trick was always that White has tons of different move orders, and it is very easy to get lost in them!} 17. Ng3 $1 {I give the exclamation mark because of the deep concept that Grischuk had in mind by playing this knight move right away! The first reaction could easily be like, why do we force or provoke ...g6, which seems to be very useful for Black? The next question is: Why do we want our knight on g3?} (17. Rb1 {In these types of positions, this is an obligatory move. However, the question is always: when is the perfect moment for it? I offer you some analysis and a story from one of my games here. [/variation/38682148]}) 17... g6 18. Rb1 $1 {Here it comes!} c5 19. d5 Nc4 20. Nh2 $1 {I believe Sasha was very well prepared and knew exactly what and why he was doing it! White's idea is to keep Black's pieces hanging in the air for one move! Black has to show his card: will it be ...Bg7, ...Nde5? Not an easy choice.} (20. b3 $5 {According to my analysis from 2016, this move order is also possible, but I appreciate Grischuk's spirit of keeping things as simple as possible!} Ncb6 21. Nh2 {is basically the same, but after seeing the game I feel like one should just admire the clear vision that Grischuk had!} Bg7 22. Ng4 Ne5 23. Ne3 {20...Nce5 This move and the questions I faced in my game vs. Nyback are back again! I have opened up my soul about what went on in my mind during that game here, [/variation/38682148] so it is already understandable that I analyzed all those options in great detail. Here is some of the fruit of that work! 21.Nh2 and here engines don't appreciate 21...Bh4 , but it is again one extra option for Black. 21...c4!? When White includes b3 Nde5, he always has to be ready for this move! 22.f4 Nd3 Interesting positional pawn sacrifice. 23.Bxd3 cxd3 24.Qxd3 and now 24...h5 25.Be3 is just a healthy pawn. 24...Nc5 with pressure on the center. 25.Qf3!? Bxd5 26.Ng4 Bg7 27.f5! is also a possibility! 25.Qd2!! A very deep idea, as we will see. 25...h5 26.f5 was again one of my analysis, and now... A) 26...Bh4 27.fxg6 fxg6 28.Qh6 Qf6 29.Rf1 Qg7 This is a stunning position! What is the key move here? 30.Ng4!! Another one of my favorites... A1) 30...hxg4? 31.Qxh4+- A2) 30...Bxg3 31.Nf6++- A3) 30...Qxh6 31.Nxh6+ Kh8 32.b4 Nxe4 33.Nxe4 Rxe4 34.Nf7+ Kg8 35.Nxd6 with a technical win. B) 26...h4 What is really going on in this position? 27.Ng4!! This stunning piece sac is the point of White's play! 27...hxg3 28.fxg6 fxg6 29.Qh6!! I was shocked that Black has no defense here... 29...Bg7 30.Qxg6 Kh8 31.Bg5 Qb6 32.Kh1 Nd3 33.Rf1 Nf2+ 34.Rxf2 gxf2 35.Nf6 with mate to follow. This was my model line.}) 20... Nde5 (20... Bg7 21. b3 Ncb6 {( 21...Nce5 runs into 22.f4 and the knight is trapped.)} 22. Ng4 $1 {This move (maneuver) is the reason why Black usually places his knight on e5...} Ne5 23. Nh6+ {is now an empty shot due to} Kh8 {and there is no follow-up. 23.Ne3! Back in 2015, this was my favorite route, and I was very happy when I discovered it... 23...Bc8?! 24.f4 Ned7 25.Nef5!! was another brilliant idea I discovered while checking this line 25...gxf5 26.Nxf5 with long term attack - again the Nf5 sacrifice!}) 21. b3 Nb6 22. Bh6 {Grischuk follows his plan. Objectively, it might not be the most precise, but it worked to perfection in the game...} ({From different move orders (yes, correct, it came from 20. b3...) I had also reached this position and my main line was} 22. Rf1 $5 Bg7 23. f4 Ned7 24. Bb2 {I also had this in my repertoire ever since my game vs Tomi Nyback in 2015. As I said, already during that game, I realized that I didn't know enough about all the finesses of this position, so I really took my time to study it... White should be happy here.}) 22... Bc8 {Very natural move, but it does not stop White's idea...} ({A)} 22... Bh4 $3 {was a move that annoyed me in my prep} 23. Re3 f6 $1 {another move which was driving me crazy... Or 23.Nhf1 Bg5! 24.Bxg5 Qxg5 and suddenly White does not have the Ne2 move! This is the reason why I preferred 22. Rf1 over 22. Bh6...}) ({B) The immediate} 22... Bg5 {is met by} 23. Bxg5 Qxg5 24. Ne2 $1 {Yes, I also had 24.a4!? in my notes, but I do not want to drive all of us crazy, it is enough if I am!}) 23. Rf1 $5 {Sasha is still teasing!} ({There was no reason why White could not have pushed f4 right away, but it is a trademark of great players to take their time to prepare it to the maximum if they feel that the opponent anyway can't do anything about it...} 23. f4 Ned7 24. Qf3 {with similar ideas what we will see later in the game.}) 23... b4 {Typical idea with a5-a4 to follow, but there will not be time for counterplay...} (23... Bh4 $5 {could or should have been tried, but White has a lovely response that deserves to be pointed out! So what is White's stunning move?} 24. Nh1 $3 {Stylistically just superb! The knights are hiding for the moment, but after f2-f4, they will come to life with devastating effect!} Ra7 25. f4 Ned7 26. Nf3 Bf6 27. Nf2 {All of a sudden both knights are perfectly placed!}) 24. f4 Ned7 25. Kh1 $5 (25. e5 $5 dxe5 26. f5 $1 {was already possible according to the computer, but over the board, making sure that we are absolutely ready before going for the kill is perfectly understandable and also practical!} e4 $1 {Obviously this move disturbed White.} 27. Nxe4 Bd4+ 28. Kh1 Bb7 29. Bg5 {with a winning attack. If 28...Nxd5? , what do engines have in mind? 29.Nxc5+- lovely shot!}) 25... Ra7 {Typical move, but here it does not help at all.} (25... Bg7 $5 {was objectively better, but wasn't it what White had wanted all the way with his Ng3 move order?}) 26. Qf3 {Eyeing the f7-pawn.} Nf8 {Black protects it according to the plans.} 27. e5 $1 {Now finally, when everything was ready, Grischuk goes for the break!} dxe5 28. f5 $1 {I know it is typical, but aesthetically it is always extremely beautiful!} Bg7 {Finally, Black gives in to trade the dark-squared bishops...It shows the seriousness of the situation...} 29. Bxg7 Kxg7 {Obviously, White has many strong continuations. The choice Grischuk made signals me that he had already foreseen the beautiful mating net he went for.} 30. f6+ Kh8 31. Rbd1 $1 {Including the last piece into the game!} Rd7 {Let's try to think and understand which spectacular idea Grischuk had in mind.} 32. Qe3 $1 {The move is easy, but actually it requires extreme precision!} Nxd5 33. Rxd5 $1 {Only thanks to this sacrifice does White achieve his aim!} Rxd5 34. Qh6 Ne6 {Did Sasha miss something? Black only needs ...Rg8 and ...Qf8, and the queen will be kicked out of h6! Is White really able to set up a killing threat in just two moves?} 35. Ne4 $1 Rg8 {But now what? ...Qf8 is coming...} (35... Rd4 36. Ng5 $1 {wins on the spot.}) 36. Nf3 $3 Qf8 37. Nfg5 $3 {What a fantastic finish! I am such a big fan when, with a good opening understanding, one builds up the pressure step by step and delivers such a masterpiece!} Nxg5 (37... Qxh6 38. Nxf7#) 38. Nxg5 Rg7 {The only move, but it equals resignation.} (38... Qxh6 39. Nxf7#) 39. fxg7+ Qxg7 40. Nxf7+ {And Black resigned! After spending so much time working on this variation at the end of 2015 from the White side, I was so happy to see Grischuk playing this fantastic game! Unfortunately, I never had the chance to show my new understanding of this line afterward, but it warms my heart that Sasha had! It certainly had a very negative effect on this line from the Black side...} 1-0

