17. Rb1 $5 {) In these types of positions, this is an obligatory move. However, the question is always: when is the perfect moment for it?} ({Grischuk-Alekseenko [/variation/37956740/#/17/w] went} 17. Ng3 $1 {I give the exclamation mark, because of the deep concept that Grischuk had in mind by playing this knight move right away! The first reaction could easily be like, why do we force or provoke ...g6 which seems to be very useful for Black. The next question is: Why do we want our knight on g3?}) 17... c5 18. d5 Nc4 19. b3 Nce5 {A very important position which was reached in one of my games. The reason why I very well know that this is a critical moment is that I spent some 40 minutes on my next move! After spending all that time, I decided on a move, which I would usually rule out on general grounds as a 'No move!'. Let's take a closer look at what created the confusion in my mind...} 20. N3h2 {In my mind, this is the most natural move and would automatically play it in any blitz game. We have a space advantage, so it is logical to avoid trading pieces. The problem I faced was that, of course, I knew the typical ideas of the position but had never really looked at the details, and suddenly, over the board, the possibility of Black playing the quick ...c5-c4 was a real concern. After failing to get a clear overview of the complications after 20. N3h2 c4, my choice of playing 20. Nxe5 was a real psychological torture. I hate to play a move which I find fundamentally incorrect...} (20. Nxe5 Bxe5 21. Nh2 {At least I wanted to create the impression that I know what I am doing...} b4 22. Ng4 Bc3 23. Bd2 {and here, luckily, my opponent made a serious inaccuracy, giving me a chance to get a grip on the position. What would have been the best way to play the position?} Bxd2 {Practically, Black should have never played like this! It just gave me the freedom I was dreaming about. (I was very worried about 23...Bd4! , as it is a monster bishop, and not really seeing how to play for an advantage. 24.Be3 Bc3 is very annoying, when suddenly White has trouble avoiding the move repetition.)} 24. Qxd2 a5 {and here: A)} 25. f4 $5 {was more ambitious, but after spending so much time and nerves I opted for the lazier approach...} Qh4 $1 {This was the strong move that disturbed me.} 26. Bd3 h5 {and the fact that here my knight can't move to e3 was the reason why I decided on 25. Bd3.} 27. Nh2 Ba6 28. Nf3 Qg3 $1 29. Bxa6 Rxa6 $13 {This queen on g3 is a very special piece, causing quite some headache... B) 25.Bd3 Ba6 26.Bxa6 Rxa6 27.f4 was the game [/variation/38709613] Leko-Nyback, Reykjavik 2015. � I felt pretty happy that I got a stable position, which I can try to press also in the approaching time-trouble. My play is easy with all the small improving moves, and I am hoping for the perfect time to push e4-e5 at some point.}) 20... c4 {So let's take a look at the unknown...} (20... Ng6 $5 {is another option that Black has opening up the diagonal of his dark-squared bishop.}) 21. Ne3 $5 Nd3 $1 ({This is what the computer suggested after the game and also the move I was mostly considering during the game, but the first big question is how would we be reacting to} 21... Nc5 $2 {besides, of course, there is also the other option with}) (21... Nd3 {. 21.f4? is obviously wrong as it runs into Black's main idea 21...Nd3 22.Bxd3 cxd3 with excellent counterplay. Important to note that picking up the pawn is impossible due to 23.Qxd3? Nc5 24.Qf3 Bxd5! and Black is close to winning already!}) (21... Nc5 {Isn't this a problem? The black knights are heading to the weak d3-square...} 22. bxc4 bxc4 23. Ba3 $1 {Lovely reaction by White and suddenly Black's position is falling apart! Again, just a small nuance changes everything!} Qc7 24. Bxc5 {and Black is forced to recapture with the pawn.} dxc5 25. f4 Nd3 26. Bxd3 cxd3 27. e5 Bh4 {and White has a powerful pawn center.}) 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Nf5 $1 {Great move protecting the e4-pawn and attacking the d6-collegue...} Nc5 $1 24. Ng4 $1 {Honestly, I had reached this position in my calculation, but I was absolutely not sure how to evaluate it...} Bc3 {The move that disturbed me the most over the board, especially when deciding on going or not for 20. N3h2 It is great training, so anyone who wants to can think about this moment and how to play with White! (very difficult...)} (24... Bc8 {is the other option, but not a concern from White's perspective:} 25. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {How to play with White now?} 26. Ng3 $1 {( 26.Bb2 Qg6 with dynamic equality because White is unable to stabilize the position.)} Qg6 27. Ba3 $1 Nxe4 28. Qxd3 Bf5 29. Nxf5 Qxf5 30. f3 Ng3 31. Qxf5 Nxf5 {What is the best way to push this position?} 32. Kf2 $1 {and White is pressing. After 32.Rxe8+ Rxe8 33.g4 Nd4 34.Bxd6 Nxf3+ not 35.Kf2? Nd2!-+ but 35.Kg2 , and now how to make sure that Black keeps things under control? 35...Ne1+! 36.Kg3 Nd3! Some amazing construction! 37.Rd1 Re3+! 38.Kg2 f6! The rook and the knight form a barrier, and Black will activate the king.}) (24... Nxe4 $2 25. Qxd3 {suddenly, Black's position collapses on the spot.}) 25. Bf4 $3 {The idea gets a double exclamation move, but the mess remains!} (25. Ngh6+ $5 gxh6 26. b4 $3 {is something from a completely different planet!!}) 25... Bc8 $1 {This stops the mating ideas.} (25... Bxd5 26. Ngh6+ $3 {Again!} gxh6 27. Qg4+ Kh8 28. exd5 {Black's position is falling apart. For example,} Qf6 29. Rxe8+ Rxe8 30. Nxd6 Rd8 31. Rc1 $1 {The final touch!} b4 32. Rxc3 bxc3 33. Be5 Qxe5 34. Nxf7# {Or 28...h5 29.Rxe8+ Qxe8 30.Qf3 Qe2 31.Nxd6 Qxf3 32.gxf3 with a great endgame for White, which is especially easy to understand when we have access to the engine's evaluation! It turns out that the d3-pawn is a big weakness...}) (25... Bxe1 $2 26. Ngh6+ $3 {Beautiful tactical shot!} Kf8 27. Bxd6+ {or 26...Kh8 27.Nxf7+ are winning. 26...gxh6 27.Qg4++- leads to mate.}) 26. Nxd6 (26. Ngh6+ $2 gxh6 27. Qg4+ Kh8 {just wins for Black.}) 26... Bxe1 27. Qxe1 d2 $3 {And the fun continues, but I will let everyone analyze it further if interested. The lines are impressive but simply never-ending... I think we can agree that my assessment that the position after 19...Nce5 is really critical probably stands!} *

