1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 {The golden days when the Marshall was not yet a threat when facing Fressinet! We all know what a beast Laurent has become as a decade-long Magnus Carlsen second in the Marshall/Anti-Marshall territory!} b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nd7 {At first, this is a rather strange-looking move as Black moves a developed piece once again, but it is, in fact, an important variation. It's very important not to dismiss or underestimate such lines! The most important thing is to understand what Black players want to achieve and then act accordingly. Black's main idea is pretty obvious: to place the knight on b6, and the e7-bishop will go to f6. However, even this should be divided into two different chapters because Black has two different setups. It's important to highlight that this variation entered the world stage in the 1940s when Smyslov started to play it. Quickly, many great stars followed the trend. The list is enormous: Najdorf, Ragozin, Lilienthal, Tolush, and later even Botvinnik, Tal, Petrosian, Keres, and Bronstein have tried it out. Showing that, in general, it is a fascinating regrouping that caught the attention of all the top stars of that Era.} 10. d4 {White occupies the center and waits for Black to show his cards.} Nb6 ({This is the line that was developed later at the end of the 1950s. The original intention was} 10... Bf6 {. Though} 11. a4 $1 {was putting Black under pressure, 10...Bf6 remained the main line regardless. See comments to the Leko-Pinter [/variation/37984007] game.}) 11. Nbd2 Bf6 12. Nf1 Re8 {This old forgotten line was prepared by Fressinet together with the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky, especially for this tournament! In the very first game, when Fressinet used this line, it yielded him a surprisingly easy draw vs Topalov! Only now, when preparing the material for my first ever Chessable course, did I notice that this move was favored by none other than Efim Geller in the 1960s, the most famous theoretician among the Soviet elite players.} *

