13. N1h2 {An ambitious move, trying to target the provoking f6-bishop as quickly as possible, but Fressinet had a nice counter. How did Black play?} exd4 $1 14. cxd4 Na5 15. Bc2 c5 {Black gets his desired quick counterplay.} 16. Ng4 (16. d5 Nac4 {Dream Zaitsev for Black! We will talk about these structures later in another chapter.}) 16... Bxg4 $1 {One of those very rare positions in the Spanish when this is a good trade for Black! Topalov has clearly underestimated the power of this trade.} 17. hxg4 cxd4 18. g5 Be5 19. Nxd4 g6 $1 {Black is very active; hence, White is not able to coordinate his pieces.} (19... g6 $1 20. Nf3 Bg7 21. Rb1 Rc8 22. b3 d5 $132 23. Be3 {and if already a player of Topalov's caliber offers a draw with White to the young Fressinet, then we all know what that means... This happened in the game [/variation/38709618] Topalov,V (2739)-Fressinet,L (2591) Cannes 2002. �}) *

