14. Ne3 $5 {How should Black play?} exd4 $1 {Good or bad, Black had to go for this, releasing the tension in the center.} (14... g6 $2 {I consider this natural move already as the losing mistake! We'll see how the game went.}) 15. cxd4 g6 $3 {This is a difficult move (such moves are now suggested by engines, but back then did not cross our brains...) because after Black has given up his center, he normally wants to justify it with direct counterplay! It is pretty incredible that we know what Black wants (...Nb4), and it is still not easy to prevent it nicely.} (15... Nb4 16. Bb1 c5 {We'll see next that this runs into tactical problems!}) 16. a3 $5 {During the game, certainly, I would have seriously considered this restricting move. Stopping the ...Nb4 jump is another typical reaction from White`s perspective.} (16. Qd2 $5 a5 17. b3 Nb4 18. Bb1 c5 19. Bb2 a4 {and it is not an easy position!}) (16. b3 Nb4 17. Bb1 c5 18. Bb2 a5 19. Qd2 {transposes to the 16. Qd2 move order.}) 16... a5 $1 {Incredible what kind of ideas engines are coming up with...} 17. b3 Nxd4 $3 18. Nxd4 c5 19. Bb2 d5 $3 {Something like this can only happen in modern correspondence games backed by super engines...} (19... cxd4 20. Bxd4 {is simply nice for White.}) 20. exd5 cxd4 21. Bxd4 Nxd5 $3 {The point!} (21... Nxd5 $3 22. Nxd5 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1 Bxd4 24. Rd1 Bg7 {There is no tactic to benefit, so the position will be equal.}) *

