1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 {The golden days when the Marshall was not yet a threat when facing Fressinet! We all know what a beast Laurent has become as a decade-long Magnus Carlsen second in the Marshall/Anti-Marshall territory!} b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nd7 {At first, this is a rather strange-looking move as Black moves a developed piece once again, but it is, in fact, an important variation. It's very important not to dismiss or underestimate such lines! The most important thing is to understand what Black players want to achieve and then act accordingly. Black's main idea is pretty obvious: to place the knight on b6, and the e7-bishop will go to f6. However, even this should be divided into two different chapters because Black has two different setups. It's important to highlight that this variation entered the world stage in the 1940s when Smyslov started to play it. Quickly, many great stars followed the trend. The list is enormous: Najdorf, Ragozin, Lilienthal, Tolush, and later even Botvinnik, Tal, Petrosian, Keres, and Bronstein have tried it out. Showing that, in general, it is a fascinating regrouping that caught the attention of all the top stars of that Era.} 10. d4 {White occupies the center and waits for Black to show his cards.} Nb6 ({This is the line that was developed later at the end of the 1950s. The original intention was} 10... Bf6 {. Though} 11. a4 $1 {was putting Black under pressure, 10...Bf6 remained the main line regardless. See comments to the Leko-Pinter [/variation/37984007] game.}) 11. Nbd2 Bf6 ({It is surprising, but one of the ideas Black originally tried here in the old days was the now shockingly-looking} 11... exd4 12. cxd4 {and now: A)} d5 {Honestly, I can hardly believe my eyes, but those days, the players were real pioneers who were searching and trying out all kinds of 'crazy' ideas to see how it works in practice. No surprise this idea did not survive for too long...} 13. e5 Nb4 $1 14. Nf1 Bf5 {is obviously the original idea with good counterplay, but 13.Bc2! is a very nice reaction which refuted Black's concept! 13...Be6 (After 13...dxe4 14.Bxe4 , the bishop is a monster, pressing on the two diagonals, and Qc2 is a powerful threat.) 14.e5 Qd7 Now White has two different directions, both looking good. 15.Nf1!? looks very natural, and 15.Nb3 Bf5 16.Bg5 Bb4! This is strictly the only move. 17.Re2 Rfe8 as in the game [/variation/38709616] Spassky-Tal 1959. � White is better, but this was still a fight. However, 16...Rfe8? is positional capitulation. 17.Bxe7 Rxe7 18.Rc1 Nb4 19.Nc5! Nice little trick. 19...Bxc2 20.Qd2 Qe8 21.Qxb4 and White dominated the whole board in the game [/variation/38709615] Fischer, R-Reshevsky, S Santa Monica 1966. � B) Another idea that was tested against me was 12...Nb4 but after 13.Nf1 c5 14.a3 Nc6 15.Be3! Important key move keeping the center together and stopping Black's desired ...Be7-f6 move due to the hanging c5-pawn! ( 15.d5 would be a huge strategical mistake due to 15...Ne5 16.Nxe5 dxe5 and with ...c5-c4, Black will get lovely counterplay on the queenside.) 15...Na5 16.Bc2 Nbc4 17.Bc1! This is often a typical idea in these lines. It is important to keep the center stabilized (d4, e4 pawns!). Now that the pressure is gone from the d4-pawn, we will slowly kick Black's knight back and activate our pieces with full control of the center. 17...cxd4 18.Nxd4 Bf6 19.Rb1 The opening battle has been won, and I could enjoy the rest of the game [/variation/38709614] in Leko, P (2630)-Adams, M (2685) Cap d'Agde rapid 1996. �}) 12. Nf1 {White was in time to transfer the knight to f1 in time! This is very important because, like this, White can handle the pressure on the d4-pawn without problems.} Re8 {This old forgotten line was prepared by Fressinet together with the legendary World Champion Boris Spassky, especially for this tournament! In the very first game, when Fressinet used this line, it yielded him a surprisingly easy draw vs Topalov! Only now, when preparing the material for my first ever Chessable course, did I notice that this move was favored by none other than Efim Geller in the 1960s, the most famous theoretician among the Soviet elite players.} ({I would like to mention that it is fascinating that the modern engines even here come up with some interesting suggestion} 12... a5 $5 {Is the choice of engines} 13. Bc2 a4 14. Ng3 $1 {Now sticking to standard play is good enough. 14.Ne3 Now this is too clever... 14...exd4! Now is the time to release the tension in the center. 15.cxd4 g6! with a fighting position. Black has made a lot of progress on the queenside thanks to a5-a4, and the bishop will also feel very comfortable on the long diagonal.} g6 {A) 14...exd4? 15.cxd4 g6 16.Bh6! is a huge difference now! 16...Re8 17.Rc1 B) 14...Ne7!? This is the computer´s suggestion, but if this is best, then we are not afraid of it! 15.Nh5 Ng6 16.Nxf6+ Qxf6 17.Bg5 Qe6 18.b3 h6 19.Be3 Something like this should always be better for White thanks to the pair of bishops.} 15. Bh6 $1 {is a good development for White.} Re8 16. d5 $1 {Good timing! Now, Black´s bishop will do absolutely nothing on f6, and the b5 pawn can be a potential target!}) 13. Bc2 $5 {In my quick prep before the game, I got attracted to this move as I considered it the most flexible. Never in my wildest dreams did I expect Fressinet to repeat this line. But just in case, I wanted to be ready...} ({The simplest play with} 13. Ng3 {is, of course, also possible.} g6 14. Bh6 Na5 15. Bc2 c5 {and White has different choices here with some advantage} 16. d5 {16.b3!?} Bd7 17. b3 Nb7 18. Qd2 {Should also be pleasant; this reminds us of the Chigorin variation.}) ({In the first game of this line in the event, Fressinet's surprise worked to perfection!} 13. N1h2 {An ambitious move, trying to target the provoking f6 bishop as quickly as possible, but it runs into the nice counter} exd4 $1 14. cxd4 Na5 15. Bc2 c5 {Black gets his desired quick counterplay.} 16. Ng4 {16.d5 Nac4 Dream Zaitsev for Black! We will talk about these structures later in another chapter.} Bxg4 $1 {One of those very rare positions in the Spanish when this is a good trade for Black! Topalov has clearly underestimated the power of this trade.} 17. hxg4 cxd4 18. g5 Be5 19. Nxd4 g6 $1 {Black is very active; hence, White is not able to coordinate his pieces.} 20. Nf3 Bg7 21. Rb1 Rc8 22. b3 d5 $132 23. Be3 {Black is very active; hence, White is not able to coordinate his pieces. 19...g6! 20.Nf3 Bg7 21.Rb1 Rc8 22.b3 d5 $132 23.Be3 and if already a player of Topalov's caliber offers a draw with White to the young Fressinet, then we all know what that means... This happened in the game [/variation/38709618] Topalov,V (2739)-Fressinet,L (2591) Cannes 2002. �}) 13... Bd7 ({Releasing the tension with} 13... exd4 $5 {is typical for this variation.} 14. cxd4 Nb4 15. Bb1 c5 {is the most principled way, as was played by Spassky himself. But probably due to the terrible experience that Boris had against Ljubo influenced him... A)} 16. e5 dxe5 17. dxc5 Na4 18. Be4 Qxd1 19. Rxd1 Rb8 20. c6 Be6 $1 21. a3 Bb3 22. Rd2 Nc5 {or 21.Bd2 Nd5 22.Ba5 Bd8!! holds! B) 16.Bd2!? Nc6 17.e5! I think this was also something that attracted my attention during the quick prep. 17...dxe5 18.dxc5 Nc4! ( 18...Na4 19.Be4 Bb7 20.Qc1 is almost winning already with the black knight stuck on a4!) 19.Be4 Bb7 20.Bc3 Qc7 21.b3 looks very good, but with 21...b4! Black can still fight pretty well! An interesting try is 20.Ne3!? Nxe3 21.Bxe3 Qc7 22.a4 Rad8 23.Qb1 g6 24.axb5 axb5 25.b4 $14 . C) 16.Ng3 cxd4 (If 16...Nc6 17.e5! , here this trick works very effectively! 17...dxe5 18.dxc5 $16 when the black bishop is locked and White has the Ne4-Nd6 idea.) 17.Nxd4 and here: C1) 17...Bd7!? Again, if this is the best engines can suggest, in that case White is happy. 18.Nh5 with the idea just to give up the bishop with 18...Rc8! but no old school player will ever willingly consider playing like this... C2) 17...Nc4? The idea would be smart but has a huge drawback... 18.b3 runs into 18...Qb6 , so 18.a3 and now 18...Qb6 looks in the spirit... But is it any good? 19.e5!! The answer is a very big NO!! What a trick by the legendary Ljubo! 19...Rxe5 20.Nf3! now, due to the back-rank issue, White got the upper hand in the Ljubojevic-Spassky Linares 1990 game. [/variation/38709619] � 20...Nc6 and here instead of grabbing the exchange with 21. Nxe5, 21.Ne4! would have been the real killer blow. Note that 20.axb4? would have failed due to 20...Qxd4! 21.Qxd4 Rxe1+ and ...Bxd4, but not 20...Rxe1+ 21.Qxe1 and Black has back-rank issues.}) ({Finally, after} 13... g6 14. d5 $5 {, I am not so sure where this knight moves now... 14.Bh6 $14 is also possible.}) 14. Ne3 $5 {Over the board I loved this move soo much! Obviously, I had not looked at a slow move like 13...Bd7 in my prep, but what I liked about 13. Bc2 so much is that I felt that my knight on f1 is very flexible, which is why I did not want to play the standard 13. Ng3 move.} g6 $2 {I consider this natural move already as the losing mistake! How should White proceed?} ({Good or bad, but Black had to play...} 14... exd4 $1 {Now that we already know my comments to the 12...a5-a4 plan, this is not a new motive anymore!} 15. cxd4 {and now: A)} Nb4 16. Bb1 c5 {But here again, it runs into tactical problems! How to punish Black now?} 17. e5 $1 {This is the problem. A1)} Be7 $2 18. exd6 Bxd6 19. a3 Nc6 20. dxc5 Bxc5 21. Qc2 {with a double threat on c5 and h7. A2) 17...dxe5 18.dxc5! Na4 19.a3! Nc6 and here comes the power of the knight on e3... What is the key move for White here? 20.Nd5!! Simple and effective! Suddenly, everything makes perfect sense! 20...Nxc5 ( 20...Be6 21.Nxf6+ gxf6 22.Qc2+- hitting h7 and threatening to trap the knight with b2-b3 or 21...Qxf6 22.Bg5+- and the queen is trapped.) 21.Nxf6+ gxf6 when 22.Qc2 e4! is not so clear and White should go 22.Nh4 with very strong initiative. 22...e4 23.Qh5 Re5 24.Qh6 Black has too many problems! B) 15...g6!! This is a difficult move (such moves are now suggested by engines, but back then did not cross our brains...) because after Black has given up his center, he normally wants to justify it with direct counterplay! It is pretty incredible that we know what Black wants(...Nc6-b4), and it is still not easy to prevent it nicely. 16.Qd2!? a5 17.b3 Nb4 18.Bb1 c5 19.Bb2 a4 and it is not an easy position! 16.b3 Nb4 17.Bb1 c5 18.Bb2 a5 19.Qd2 transposes to Qd2 move order. During the game, certainly, I would have seriously considered the restricting move 16.a3!? stopping the ...Nc6-b4 jump, which is another typical reaction from White`s perspective. 16...a5! incredible what kind of ideas engines are coming up with... 17.b3 and not 17...a4 18.b4 and the knight can't get activated, but 17...Nxd4!! 18.Nxd4 c5 19.Bb2 d5!! Something like this can only happen in modern correspondance games backed by super engines... ( 19...cxd4 20.Bxd4 is simply nice for White, who has a better knight and his central pawn protected.) 20.exd5 cxd4 21.Bxd4 Nxd5!! The point. 22.Nxd5 Rxe1+ 23.Qxe1 Bxd4 24.Rd1 with pressure on the d-file, but after 24...Bg7 , there is no tactic to benefit, so the position will be equal.}) 15. d5 $1 {It is time to close the center, thus making the f6 bishop dead! Also Black has no good square for his knights plus there is one more factor...} (15. Ng4 {would destroy all the spirit I had been playing for!} Bxg4 $1 16. hxg4 exd4 $1 17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Bb1 c5 $132 {Now Black is ready for counterplay.}) 15... Na5 {How to continue?} 16. Ng4 $1 {Yes, after ...g7-g6 has been played, we can go after Black´s king!} Bg7 {I already had something very special in mind! What could that be?} (16... Bxg4 17. hxg4 {and the g5 push is a new idea.}) 17. Nh6+ $1 {Yes, this is it! We see some very special motifs here.} Kf8 {Whenever Black has to make an ugly move like this against the Nh6 check (the same applies to ...Nh3 check vs. White's king), then one needs to look out for special ideas...! How do we continue the initiative?} 18. b3 $1 {Yes, first, we ensure that Black is completely paralyzed on the queenside! We can take this luxury because Black has no good moves. Besides, we are also preparing some devilish threats.} Nb7 (18... c6 19. Qd2 $1) 19. h4 $1 {Typical.} c6 {Now comes the real point, which I had been playing for! What is the devilish move?} 20. Qd2 $3 {This a very special move which completely destroys Black.} f6 {Strategic capitulation...} (20... cxd5 21. Ng5 $1 {is the killer.} Bxh6 22. Nxh7+ {and Qxh6.}) 21. h5 g5 22. dxc6 Bxc6 23. Nf5 {The rest is a matter of technique. Black's position is full of weaknesses.} Kg8 24. Ba3 Bf8 25. Rad1 Bd7 $1 26. Ne3 (26. Nxd6 $2 Nxd6 27. Bxd6 Bg4 $1) 26... Be6 27. Nh2 $1 Qc7 (27... Rc8 28. Nhg4) 28. Nhg4 Qf7 29. Qe2 Rac8 30. Qf3 Nd7 31. Nd5 Kh8 {Black sacrifices a pawn to hope for some life.} 32. Ngxf6 g4 (32... Nxf6 33. Qxf6+ Qxf6 34. Nxf6 Red8 35. Rd3 {or 35.Nd5 Bxd5 36.exd5 Rxc3 37.Bf5}) 33. Nxg4 Qxh5 34. Nh2 (34. Nge3 Qxf3 35. gxf3 {with two strong knights. Black's bishop will find activity on h6.}) 34... Qxf3 35. Nxf3 Bxd5 36. exd5 Rxc3 37. Bf5 {I was very much attracted to this idea.} Nf6 38. Ng5 $1 a5 (38... Rc7 39. f4 $5) 39. Bb2 Rc5 (39... Rc7 40. f4) 40. f4 ({There was a beautiful tactical idea, but on move 40, I was taught not to try to be fancy!} 40. Ne6 $1 Rxd5 41. Rxd5 Nxd5 42. Nxf8 Ne7 {42...Rxf8 43.Be4+-} 43. Be6 $3 Rxf8 44. Rxe5) 40... Nxd5 41. Bd4 $5 {One of many wins.} Nc3 (41... Nxf4 42. Bxc5 Nxc5 43. Nf7+ Kg7 44. Nxd6) 42. Bxc5 Nxc5 (42... Nxd1 43. Bd4 $1 {I think this idea influenced my choice.}) 43. Rd2 e4 44. Nf7+ Kg7 45. Nxd6 Bxd6 46. Rxd6 Nxa2 47. Rd5 Nxb3 48. Rxb5 a4 49. Rb7+ Kf6 50. Bxh7 Nc3 51. g4 Nd4 52. Kf2 e3+ $1 53. Kg2 (53. Rxe3 $4 Nd1+) 53... e2 (53... Nd5 54. g5+ Ke6 55. Kg3) (53... Nce2 54. g5+ Ke6 55. Rf1) 54. Rd7 $1 1-0

