1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nd7 10. d4 Bf6 {The official main line of the 9...Nd7 variation. Black immediately puts pressure on the d4-pawn, hindering the typical Nbd2 development, but in this case, White has time to do something else...} 11. a4 $1 {White immediately goes after the vulnerable black queenside and uses the fact that Black has not had time to place the knight on b6 yet!} Na5 {Total sideline based on surprise value, but it was not a surprise anymore as Pinter had already played it vs. Almasi earlier in the tournament!} (11... Bb7 {was always considered the main line of this variation with 9...Nd7/10...Bf6. Black's bishops are now ready to fight against White's center, so it is pretty obvious how White should deal with this.} 12. d5 $1 {Yes, the time has come to close the center and shut both Black`s bishops down. See the main game [/variation/37984007] for more details.}) 12. Bc2 {We'll see it is very important to understand what Black has in mind! Once we know that, finding the right antidote is much easier!} *

