12. axb5 {Again, it is very important to understand the difference between the move orders. It almost seems like it doesn't matter when to include the axb5 exchange, but in fact, there are big differences! How to play?} axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. d5 {Now, Black has an important idea.} (14. Na3 b4 $1 {is just good for Black.}) 14... Na5 $1 15. Bc2 Nc4 $1 {This move is now possible and was successfully played by Karpov vs. Kasparov in their World Championship match in 1990!} 16. b3 (16. Qe2 $5 {was a better try, but} Qa2 {clearly disturbed Garry.}) 16... Ncb6 17. Na3 Ba6 {Now Black has a much more harmonious setup.} 18. Nh2 c6 19. dxc6 Qxc6 {Black has solved all his opening problems. I have included a couple of moves just to enjoy the way both sides maneuvered their pieces.} (19... Qxc6 20. Bd2 Be7 $1 21. Ng4 Ra8 22. Ne3 Nf6 23. Nf5 Bf8 24. Bg5 Nbd7 {Perfect harmony for Black in the Kasparov, G (2800)-Karpov, A (2730) Lyon/New York 1990 game. [/variation/38709620] �}) *

