14... Qxa8 {Here, the situation is different. What's White's important idea?} 15. Na3 $1 {This is the key move! White threatens the b5-pawn before Black is able to coordinate his forces.} c6 $5 {Black tries to play for activity by sacrificing the d6-pawn.} (15... Ba6 {This is the traditional way, but it has also been established as suffering for Black if White knows his stuff. However, there are many things happening, so it is very important to be familiar with the ideas.}) 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Qxd6 {White wins a pawn, but Black has his own ideas.} Nc8 $1 {Going for direct play.} 18. Qd1 Nc5 19. Bd5 $1 Nd6 {Black is putting all his power into pressuring the e4-pawn. How should White react?} (19... Nxe4 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 21. Qd3 {hitting e4 and b5.} Ncd6 22. Nxb5 {.}) 20. Bxc6 Qxc6 {And now, a lovely move.} 21. Nc2 $1 {Giving back the pawn but securing the advantage! This is a wonderful way of transforming one advantage into another!} Z0 (21... Ndxe4 22. Nb4 Qe6 {Now White has different good options, but the engine's suggestion is the most powerful.} 23. Qc2 Nd6 24. Nd4 $1 {exploiting the pin.} Qd7 25. Ndc6 Qe6 26. Rd1 {Followed by Be3 and a battery on the d-file using the control of the d5-square. Impressive how strong engines are... 21.Qd5 Qxd5 22.exd5 Here White loses the control. 22...Nd3 23.Rd1 e4 24.Ne1 Nxc1 25.Rxc1 b4 or a similar line 22...b4!? 23.cxb4 Nd3 24.Rd1 e4 . The black knight on d6 is an important piece.}) *

