12... Bb7 {) Again, it is very important to understand what Black has in mind! Once we know that, finding the right antidote is much easier!} 13. d5 $1 {Again, the same idea. We are shutting down both bishops and using the moment Black needs to lose a tempo to prepare ...c6 due to the hanging d6-pawn!} ({In the first game with this line, my opponent achieved a very easy draw by demonstrating the main idea of Black's setup.} 13. Nbd2 {We'll see it next.}) 13... Be7 {Black wants ...c6. How do we get ready for it?} (13... Nc4 {is the move that we have already discussed as being the key for Black when White everything was traded with axb5 earlier. Now, it is a different story! Again, the small nuances...} 14. b3 Ncb6 {and here comes the point.} 15. a5 $1 {kicking the knight into passivity.} Nc8 16. c4 $1 {Total domination.}) 14. Na3 $1 {By creating another problem.} c6 {What did we achieve with the Na3 move?} 15. b4 $1 {Yes, the answer is simple: we can destroy Black's pawn structure!} Nc4 16. Nxc4 ({Or} 16. dxc6 Bxc6 17. Nxc4) 16... bxc4 17. dxc6 {Often, such structures are better for White but still complex, but here, this is a very bad version for Black! White even has a golden opportunity to get the absolute maximum out of this position... We'll see how in another puzzle.} *

