1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Nd7 10. d4 Bf6 {The official main line of the 9...Nd7 variation. Black immediately puts pressure on the d4-pawn, hindering the typical Nbd2 development, but in this case, White has time to do something else...} 11. a4 $1 {White immediately goes after the vulnerable black queenside and uses the fact that Black has not had time to place the knight on b6 yet!} Na5 {Total sideline based on surprise value, but it was not a surprise anymore as Pinter has already played it vs. Almasi earlier in the tournament!} (11... Bb7 {was always considered the main line of this variation with 9...Nd7/10...Bf6. Black's bishops are now ready to fight against White's center, so it is pretty obvious how White should deal with this.} 12. d5 $1 {Yes, the time has come to close the center and shut both Black's bishops down.} Na5 13. Bc2 {transposes to the game. 12...Ne7 Actually, here, White has to know well what to do, but he has already achieved that the black knight had to retreat to e7! 13.axb5 axb5 14.Rxa8 Qxa8 15.Na3! This is the key move! White threatens the b5-pawn before Black is able to coordinate his forces. A) 15...Ba6 This is the traditional way, but it has also been established as suffering for Black if White knows his stuff. However, there are many things happening, so it is very important to be familiar with the ideas. A1) 16.Nc2 is not the right way. 16...Nc5 17.Nb4 Nxb3 18.Qxb3 Bc8 intending ...Bd7 and ...Qb7, or 18...Bb7 preparing ...c6. A2) There is also another interesting option with 16.Be3!? Nc5 17.Bc2 c6 18.b4 Nd7 19.dxc6 Qxc6 Now it is all about tempo, tempo play. 20.Qd3 Rc8 21.Rd1 White is better, but Black can probably survive with the engine's help. 21...Qxc3! with the point 22.Qxc3 Rxc3 23.Rxd6 Bc8! . After 22.Qxd6 Qxa3 23.Qxd7 h6 , the line still continues, but this is another story.... Surprisingly, 16...Rb8 17.Qd2 Qb7 18.Ra1! is very good for White. If 18...b4? , Black achieves the desired break, but here it only leads to more trouble. 19.cxb4 Qxb4 20.Qxb4 Rxb4 21.Nd2! A silent killer! All of a sudden, the c7-pawn and the weak queenside squares become too vulnerable. 21...Bd3 22.Rc1 Rb7 23.Bc4! Bxc4 24.Ndxc4 and Na5 is coming. The c7-pawn is a problem for Black. 18...Ra8 No need for the fancy 19.Bc2!? , as 19.Nc2 is good enough. 19...Nc5 20.Bxc5! dxc5 21.Ne3! and the knight will jump to g4. From there, it will put pressure on the f6 bishop and the e5-pawn. A3) 16.Nh2!? It is common knowledge that this is the key move in this line. However, when checking with new super engines, things are again different from how we thought about them earlier. 16...Ng6 17.Ng4 Hitting the bishop gives us a big tempo; at least that was the deep knowledge that we had! (Actually, now the engine suggests another way with 17.Ba2!? This is one of those super-clever prophylactic moves that only computers can think of... Now 17...Rb8?! 18.Nc2! is strong, and 17...Qd8 is met by some very deep play by engines... 18.Nf3! The idea is obvious: Black was threatening to trade the dark-squared bishops with ...Bf6-g5. Suddenly, the engine claims that White has everything under control and should be happy.) 17...Be7 18.Ne3!! Amazing, the knight journey continues! 18...Rb8 19.Nec2!! I find this knight route so incredibly beautiful. 19...Nc5 20.Nb4 and if 20...Nxb3 21.Qxb3 White has pressure on the queenside thanks to Nc6 ideas. 20...Bc8 21.Nc6 Rb6 22.Bc2 Bd7 23.b4 Nb7 24.Be3 Rxc6 25.dxc6 Bxc6 26.Bc1 is the legendary Dominguez-Svidler game [/variation/38709621] from 2015. � Honestly, I remember that we discussed this incredible knight maneuver with Zoltan Almasi already back in the 96-97 period! Engine plays spoiler and claims it is not so bad after 18...Bg5! Here is a logical, high-quality model line. 19.Qg4 Qd8 20.Bc2 Bf4! and it is not so simple. 21.g3 Nf6 22.Qf3 Bxe3 23.Bxe3 Qc8 24.h4 h5 25.Bb1 Ng4 26.Nc2 Qa8 27.Nb4 Bc8 28.Bd2 f5 29.exf5 Ne7 $132 . B) Black has also tried to play for activity by sacrificing the d6-pawn with 15...c6!? 16.dxc6 Bxc6 17.Qxd6 White wins a pawn, but Black has his own ideas. 17...Nc8! Going for direct play. 18.Qd1 Nc5 19.Bd5! Nd6 How should White react to it? ( 19...Nxe4 20.Bxc6 Qxc6 21.Qd3 hitting e4 and b5. 21...Ncd6 22.Nxb5 .) 20.Bxc6 Qxc6 and now the lovely 21.Nc2! giving back the pawn, but securing the advantage!This is a wonderful way of transforming one advantage into another! 21...Ndxe4 22.Nb4 Qe6 Now White has different good options, but the engine's suggestion is the most powerful. 23.Qc2 Nd6 24.Nd4! exploiting the pin. 24...Qd7 25.Ndc6 Qe6 26.Rd1 Followed by Be3 and a battery on the d-file using the control of the d5-square. Impressive how strong engines are... Instead, after 21.Qd5 Qxd5 22.exd5 , White loses the control. 22...Nd3 23.Rd1 e4 24.Ne1 Nxc1 25.Rxc1 b4 or a similar line 22...b4!? 23.cxb4 Nd3 24.Rd1 e4 . The black knight on d6 is an important piece. Again, it is very important to understand the difference between the move orders. It almost looks like it doesn't matter when to include the axb5 exchange, but in fact, it has big differences! 12.axb5 axb5 13.Rxa8 Qxa8 14.Na3 b4! is just good for Black. 14.d5 And now Black has the important idea with 14...Na5! 15.Bc2 Nc4! This move is now possible and was successfully played by Karpov vs Kasparov in their World Championship match in 1990! Now 16.Qe2!? was a better try, but 16...Qa2 clearly disturbed Garry. The game continued 16.b3 Ncb6 17.Na3 Ba6 Now Black has a much more harmonious setup. 18.Nh2 c6 19.dxc6 Qxc6 Black has solved all his opening problems. I have included a couple of moves just to enjoy the way both sides maneuvered their pieces. 20.Bd2 Be7! 21.Ng4 Ra8 22.Ne3 Nf6 23.Nf5 Bf8 24.Bg5 Nbd7 Perfect harmony for Black in the Kasparov, G (2800)-Karpov, A (2730) Lyon/New York 1990 game. [/variation/38709620] �}) 12. Bc2 Bb7 {Again, it is very important to understand what Black has in mind! Once we know that, finding the right antidote is much easier!} 13. d5 $1 {Again the same idea. We are shutting down both bishops and using the moment Black needs to lose a tempo to prepare c6 due to the hanging d6-pawn!} ({In the first game with this line, my opponent achieved a very easy draw by demonstrating the main idea of Black's setup.} 13. Nbd2 c5 $1 14. d5 {What is the thematic move for Black in these types of positions?} c4 {The famous difference! With the white pawn on a2, this would be a dream for White. With the pawn on a4, Black has things under control.} 15. b4 cxb3 16. Nxb3 Nxb3 17. Bxb3 Qc7 {Is a normal position for Black. The following moves are nice indications of how to treat these types of positions.} 18. Ba3 Nc5 19. Bc2 Rfb8 20. a5 Bc8 $1 21. Bb4 Bd7 22. Qd2 h6 23. Qe3 Rc8 24. Rec1 Qd8 25. Kh2 Rc7 26. Rg1 Rac8 27. Rac1 Qe7 28. g3 {and draw agreed in the game [/variation/38709622] Almasi,Z (2615)-Pinter,J (2590) Budapest 1997. �}) 13... Be7 {Black wants ...c7-c6. How do we get ready for it?} (13... Nc4 {is the move that we have already discussed as being the key move for Black when White traded everything with axb5 earlier. Now, it is a different story! Again, the small nuances...} 14. b3 Ncb6 {and here comes the point} 15. a5 $1 {kicking the knight into passivity} Nc8 16. c4 $1 {Total domination.}) 14. Na3 $1 {By creating another problem.} c6 {What did we achieve with the Na3 move?} 15. b4 $1 {Yes, the answer is simple: We can destroy Black's pawn structure!} Nc4 16. Nxc4 bxc4 17. dxc6 Bxc6 {Often such structures are better for White but still complex, but here this is a very bad version for Black! White even has a golden opportunity to get the absolute maximum out of this position...} 18. Nd2 $1 {Once I noticed this idea I could hardly hold my hands back! It forces Black to push d6-d5...} ({Important not to get tempted by wrong directions...} 18. Qe2 Rc8 $1 19. Qxc4 $2 {It is not in our interest to change the dynamics like this...} Bxa4 20. Qa2 Bb5 $132 {and finally Black can be happy with his structure! The b5 bishop is Cemento!}) (18. Nh2 $5 {Possible positional plan maneuvering the knight to g4 and then to e3, but the game continuation was much stronger.} Nf6 19. Ng4 {.}) 18... d5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Nf3 $1 {My concept! It is always extremely pleasing to make moves like Nf3-d2 and, in the next move, to return with Nd2-f3 after we have achieved what we wanted!} (20. Ne4 $5 {Modern engines choice...} Be6 21. Qh5 g6 {21...f5 22.Ng5 Bxg5 23.Bxg5 Qe8 24.Qxe8 Rfxe8 25.f3 25...h6 26.Bh4 g5 27.Bf2 Kf7 28.a5 is a technically winning endgame.} 22. Qh6 f6 {Humanly, this is not so clear to me, but engines as so often do not care...} 23. Be3 Qc7 24. Rad1 a5 $6 {Strategically desirable, but it runs into a beautiful refutation! How is the refutation go? 24...Rf7!?} 25. Ng5 $3 {Amazing stuff.} fxg5 26. Bxg6 $1 Nf6 27. Bxh7+ $1 {White keeps on sacrificing this bishop...} Nxh7 28. Qxe6+ Rf7 29. Rd7 {White wins. The line is pretty impressive that is why I wanted to share it, but I feel that my choice had so much more soul...}) 20... Bxf3 {This is capitulation, but Black´s position was falling apart, and obviously, the Nd2-f3-d2-f3 maneuver had its psychological effect!} ({A) After} 20... Be6 {I was planning to continue in style with} 21. Be4 $1 {21.Nxe5 Nxe5 22.Qxd8 Raxd8 23.Rxe5 Bf6 24.Re3} Rb8 {21...Rc8 22.Bb7} 22. Bd5 {This was my original plan. A1) The engine's solution is another shock... 22.Bc6!? Qc7 23.Bxd7! It is never easy to give up our soul for a pawn, but it is not only about the pawn... 23...Bxd7 24.Nxe5 White gets very quick Bf4, Qf3 with devastating developments.} Bxd5 23. Qxd5 Qc7 24. Nxe5 Nxe5 25. Bf4 $1 {was what I intended.} Rbd8 26. Bxe5 Rxd5 27. Bxc7 Bf6 28. Re3 {and White should win this easily.}) ({B) After} 20... Bc6 {White can play both} 21. Qe2 {or 21.Bf5!? and Black can´t keep his weaknesses together.}) 21. Qxf3 Qc7 {What kind of strategical move can we play?} (21... a5 {would be strategically desirable, but} 22. Rd1 $1 {and the pin decides the game on the spot.}) 22. a5 $1 {Yes, this is lovely! White fixes the queenside, all the weaknesses remain on the light squares (easy targets in the endgame!) and gives Black absolutely no hope to hold this position in the long terms.} (22. Be3 a5 $1) 22... Kh8 $5 {Black tries to prepare ...f7-f5...} 23. Ba4 {There were many other moves, but this is systematic.} Rac8 (23... Rad8 24. Qc6) (23... f5 24. Qc6 Qxc6 25. Bxc6 Rad8 26. Bb7 Nb8 27. b5 axb5 28. a6 {wins on the spot.}) 24. Qd5 Rcd8 25. Qc6 {if the endgame is winning, why not go for it?} (25. Re4 $5) 25... Qxc6 26. Bxc6 Nb8 27. Bf3 f5 $5 {Black tries something. How to deal with it?} (27... Rd3 28. Ra3 {or 28.Re3 .}) 28. Rxe5 $5 {I decided to be fancy and bite the bullet!} Bf6 29. Rxf5 Rfe8 {Going for activity.} (29... Bxc3 30. Rxf8+ Rxf8 31. Rb1 {is just hopeless.}) 30. Rxf6 $5 {Playing for the gallery!} (30. Bg5 Bxc3 31. Rc1 Rd3 32. Be2 $1) 30... Re1+ (30... gxf6 31. Be3 {just completely winning.}) 31. Kh2 gxf6 32. Bg5 $1 {The fun continues!} Re6 (32... Rxa1 33. Bxf6+ Kg8 34. Bxd8) 33. Re1 $1 {These are all the reasons why I decided on 28. Rxe5.} Rdd6 34. Rxe6 Rxe6 35. Bf4 Nd7 {White is winning in many ways, but is there something really beautiful?} (35... Re8 36. b5 axb5 37. Bxb8 Rxb8 38. a6) 36. Bd5 $1 Re2 37. Bxc4 $1 {I could not resist!} (37. Be3 Ne5 38. b5 axb5 39. a6) 37... Re4 38. Bd3 $1 Rxf4 39. Kg3 $1 {I just loved that I could win the game with such a quiet little king move, which traps Black`s rook in the center!} Ne5 40. Kxf4 Nxd3+ 41. Ke4 Nb2 42. Kd5 {And Black resigned. It was a pure pleasure to play this game! Once again, knowing the details at the very beginning helped me to get the upper hand! The rest was a matter of technique...} 1-0

