1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 {The Chigorin variation was developed immediately at the beginning of the 20th century. Probably, the temptation of moving the knight with a tempo, allowing pushing the c-pawn forward to c5, thus enabling Black to protect the vulnerable e5-pawn with ...Qc7, was the reason why it became so popular. Right now, it is considered a possibility, but it is one of those opening variations that White enjoys playing. The point is that there is no pressure on White, and by knowing the natural moves/opening ideas, White will always get a nice playable position. Of course, as with every opening variation, also here there are some important basic ideas we have to know.} 10. Bc2 c5 {Black follows his strategy.} 11. d4 {White occupies the center.} cxd4 $6 {This is quite premature, but my experienced opponent wanted to trick me with this rare forgotten line. Black is not active enough to justify releasing the tension in the center so early.} 12. cxd4 {Besides, now White will even have the Nb1-c3 option! We'll see in some critical positions how relevant this is.} *

