16... Nc4 $2 {This natural move, the idea of Black's play, is already losing! Why?} 17. Qd4 $3 {This is a winning setup! Immediately after my game, when checking the line, I also quickly reached this position and was wondering what Alexander had in mind...} Nxb2 18. Nd5 $3 (18. Bb3 {Also good, but White had missed an absolute stunner possibility} Nc4 19. Rad1 Qd7 20. Rd3 $1 {Again, the famous rook appears on the 3rd rank...} Bd8 $2 21. Nxg7 $3 {With a crushing victory in the game [/variation/38709623] Kamsky, G (2741)-Morozevich, A (2760) Thessaloniki 2013. �}) 18... Bxd5 (18... Rxc2 19. Ndxe7+ Rxe7 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qxf6 {wins.}) 19. exd5 Rxc2 {What is the tactical justification of White's play?} 20. Rxe7 $1 Rxe7 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. Qxf6 $3 {Yes, it is this move that is so easy to miss from a distance! Falling into the opponent's trap is psychologically never easy...} (22. Qg4+ $2 Kf8 {loses for White.}) 22... Re1+ 23. Rxe1 Qxf6 24. Re8# {Beautiful!} *

