15... g6 {A typical move preparing ...Nh5. Here, I played an instructive and thematic reply.} 16. b4 $5 {According to modern engines, this is not so important, but in my mind, it is instructive!} (16. Nbd2 Nh5 17. b4 {In this case, Black definitely has no ...Nc4 option, but on the other hand, Nc3 will be so much better if Black retreats with the knight to b7. I took my chance to play a psychological game...} Nb7 18. a4 {, and obviously, Black is way too slow to create threats on the kingside while the house is burning on the queenside.}) 16... Nc4 $1 (16... Nb7 {was the game continuation but after} 17. Nc3 $1 {White is basically simply winning. There is no way to stop a2-a4, after which the pressure on the b5-pawn with the white knight on c3 will be unbearable.} a5 $6 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Qxa1 Qa8 21. Qb2 {and Black suffers due to the weak b5-pawn and the passive b7-knight. Another attempt is 17...Rc8 18.Qd2 Nh5 Black wants to create counterplay with ...f7-f5, but it is too slow! We'll see why in the next exercise. 18...Qc7 19.Rec1 Qb8 20.a4 Putting pressure on the queenside pawns. 20...bxa4 21.Bxa6+- Actually, the reason why I played 18. Qd2 instead of 18. Qb3 was to have this option.}) 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. Nc3 {Another typical dream structure for White. Nowadays, people might care much less about how it looks, but in the 90s, ending up in structures like this was kind of taboo! With modern eyes, it is already obvious that no matter how bad it looks, it is still much better than to retreat to b7...} *

