1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 {The Chigorin variation was developed immediately at the beginning of the 20th century. Probably, the temptation of moving the knight with a tempo, allowing pushing the c-pawn forward to c5, thus enabling Black to protect the vulnerable e5-pawn with ...Qc7, was the reason why it became so popular. Right now, it is considered a possibility, but it is one of those opening variations that White enjoys playing. The point is that there is no pressure on White, and by knowing the natural moves/opening ideas, White will always get a nice playable position. Of course, as with every opening variation, also here there are some important basic ideas we have to know.} 10. Bc2 c5 {Black follows his strategy.} 11. d4 {White occupies the center.} cxd4 $6 {This is quite premature, but my experienced opponent wanted to trick me with this rare forgotten line. Black is not active enough to justify releasing the tension in the center so early. Besides, now White will even have the Nb1-c3 option!} 12. cxd4 Bb7 $6 {This is strategically just wrong, but it is already very difficult to give good advice for Black!} (12... exd4 13. Nxd4 Re8 {and here White should just play normally instead of trying to be extra smart! I run into} 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bh4 Nd5 $132 {in my game [/variation/38718700] Leko-Morozevich, Wijk 2002. � Kamsky was well prepared against Moro´s dubious line: 14.Nc3! Bb7 15.Nf5! Immediately going after Black's throat! 15...Rc8? 16.Bg5! and here the best is 16...b4 , as it is only bad but not losing... A) 16...h6? 17.Bxf6! is a huge problem. 17...Bxf6 18.Nxd6+- winning. B) 16...Nc4? This natural move, the idea of Black's play, is already losing! 17.Qd4!! This is a winning setup! Immediately after my game, when checking the line, I also quickly reached this position and was wondering what Alexander had in mind... 17...Nxb2 18.Bb3 Also good, but White had missed an absolute stunner possibility. 18...Nc4 19.Rad1 Qd7 20.Rd3! Again, the famous rook appears on the 3rd rank... 20...Bd8? 21.Nxg7!! With a crushing victory for White in the game [/variation/38709623] Kamsky, G (2741)-Morozevich, A (2760) Thessaloniki 2013. � Kamsky missed the amazing 18.Nd5!! Bxd5 ( 18...Rxc2 19.Ndxe7+ Rxe7 20.Bxf6 gxf6 21.Qxf6+- wins.) 19.exd5 Rxc2 What is the tactical justification of White's play? 20.Rxe7! Rxe7 21.Bxf6 gxf6 and now 22.Qg4+? Kf8 loses for White, so... 22.Qxf6!! Yes, it is this move that is so easy to miss from a distance! Falling into the opponent's trap is psychologically never easy... 22...Re1+ 23.Rxe1 Qxf6 24.Re8 beautiful. Instead of Moro’s 15…Rc8, 15...Bf8 is better when 16.Bg5 h6! 17.Bh4 Rc8 18.Qd4 Re6 protecting f6 is actually pretty ok for Black, and after 16.Qf3! then 16...Rc8? 17.Bg5! is winning now with the Nh6 threat, but if 16...h6 17.Rd1! White has a nice advantage, but it is still a game.}) 13. d5 $1 {The typical refutation of the early ...Bc8-b7 move in these types of positions. This is one of those strategic things that we must first learn when d4-d5 is good, and if we know why it is good, then we also will understand when not to do it!} Bc8 14. Bd3 $1 {I wanted to be as flexible as possible!} (14. b3 $5 {is another option, fighting against the black knight.}) 14... Bd7 15. Be3 g6 {A typical move preparing ...Nh5.} (15... Rc8 16. b3 $5 {controls the c4-square and, if the knight retreats to b7 on its way to the c5-square, White will push b4 stopping it.}) (15... Nc4 16. Bxc4 bxc4 17. Nfd2 $1 Qc7 18. Na3 c3 19. Rc1 {and the c-pawn drops.}) (15... Nh5 $2 16. Nxe5 $1 {wins on the spot.}) 16. b4 $5 {According to modern engines, this is not so important, but in my mind, it is instructive!} (16. Nbd2 Nh5 17. b4 {In This case, Black definitely has no ...Nc4 option, but on the other hand, Nc3 will be so much better if Black retreats with the knight to b7. I took my chance to play a psychological game...} Nb7 18. a4 {, and obviously, Black is way too slow to create threats on the kingside while the house is burning on the queenside.}) 16... Nb7 (16... Nc4 $1 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. Nc3 {is another typical dream structure for White. Nowadays, people might care much less about how it looks, but in the 90s, ending up in structures like this was kind of taboo! With modern eyes, it is already obvious that no matter how bad it looks, it is still much better than to retreat to b7...}) 17. Nc3 $1 {Now White is basically simply winning. There is no way to stop a2-a4, after which the pressure on the b5-pawn with the white knight on c3 will be unbearable.} Rc8 (17... a5 $6 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 Rxa1 20. Qxa1 Qa8 21. Qb2 {and Black suffers due to the weak b5-pawn and the passive b7-knight.}) 18. Qd2 Nh5 {Black wants to create counterplay with ...f7-f5, but it is too slow!} (18... Qc7 19. Rec1 Qb8 20. a4 {hitting Black's queenside pawns.} bxa4 21. Bxa6 {Actually this was the reason why I played 18. Qd2 instead of 18.Qb3 to have this option.}) 19. a4 $1 Qe8 {Black tries to hang on to the b5-pawn, but when White is given free hand in such cases the question is only when does Black's position collapse...} (19... f5 20. axb5 axb5 21. Bh6 Rf7 22. Bxb5 {the b7-knight is too sad. Or 20...f4 21.Ba7 Famous! Ever since the legendary Karpov game we know that we have this square in the Spanish Chigorin...}) 20. axb5 axb5 21. Ra7 Rb8 22. Bh6 Ng7 23. Qe2 Nd8 {The reason why people often do not mind having the terrible knight on b7 in the Chigorin is that they hope to transfer it to f7 via ...Nb7-d8-f7 after ...f7-f6. However, this plan can only work with a closed queenside; if White already has a target, it will never be satisfactory!} 24. Rc1 $1 {I still remember how happy I was about this move!} (24. Nxb5 {was winning a pawn already, but I felt that this pawn was not running away...}) 24... f6 (24... f5 $2 25. exf5 gxf5 26. Nxe5 $1 dxe5 27. Qxe5 {Double attack.} Bf6 28. Qxb8 Bxc3 29. Qc7 {hitting both bishops.}) 25. Nxb5 {White could choose from different winning continuations; finally, I settled on the simplest solution. No need for fancy business.} Bxb5 (25... Rxb5 $2 26. Bxg7 Kxg7 27. Bxb5 Bxb5 28. Rxe7+ Qxe7 29. Qxb5 {.}) 26. Bxb5 Qxb5 27. Qxb5 Rxb5 28. Rxe7 Nf7 29. Bd2 {I went on to win the game. The rest was not interesting anymore.} *

