20... Qb8 {What could have been my big idea behind going 20. Qe2...?} 21. Rec1 $3 {This is the point! White has a clear plan of going Rab1 and b4, after which the b5-pawn will be very vulnerable.} (21. Rab1 {would allow Black to play} Rc8 $1 {with a solid position because now the break does not work for White.} 22. b4 $2 axb3 23. Nxb3 Nc4 $15 {This is the big difference!}) 21... Re8 (21... Rc8 $2 22. Rxc8+ {and the b5-pawn drops.}) 22. Rab1 $1 {Following the plan. Black is facing serious practical problems. Usually, in a human game, in such a situation, the defensive side gets nervous and makes a mistake...} exd4 $2 {Feels like a panic reaction!} ({A)} 22... h6 $1 {Now in 2024, my super engine says, no worries, amigo, the situation is not so bad...} 23. b4 axb3 24. Nxb3 d5 $3 {For an engine, it is easy to suggest a move like this; I guess for us mortals, many, many hours of analysis would be needed to understand that this is possible, and it even works...}) ({B)} 22... b4 $5 {To my mind, this looked like the most natural reaction. Now, White has two different options. B1)} 23. axb4 {when if} Qxb4 {, White can simply take the e5-pawn without any compensation for Black:} 24. dxe5 dxe5 25. Nxe5 Be6 26. Ndf3 {, and after 23...exd4 24.Bxd4! , the bishop can be nicely transferred. 24...Qxb4 25.Bc3 Cemento construction! 25...Qb7 26.Re1 With a very nice position. B2) 23.d5!? also looks like an interesting choice, but we need a good reaction after 23...Bd8 24.axb4!? Qxb4 25.Ne1 $14 The justification why we consider the move 24.axb4 at all!}) 23. Nxd4 {Now, breaking out did not work.} d5 (23... b4 {was the game continuation.}) 24. Bxb5 Bxb5 (24... dxe4 25. Bxd7 Nxd7 26. Nxe4 $16) 25. Qxb5 $1 Z0 ({This is very effective.} 25... dxe4 26. Qxa4 Nd5 27. b4 Nc4 28. Qb3 {with Nc6 ideas. 25.Nxb5 is not so simple. I'll challenge you to find Black's best reply in our next exercise.}) *

