23... b4 {How to play here with White?} 24. Bb5 $1 {Now Black is in a lot of trouble! After the light-squared bishops are traded off, Black only has weaknesses!} (24. Nb5 Nc6 25. axb4 $2 Rc8 $1 {and Black will recapture on b4 next.}) 24... b3 (24... Bxb5 25. Nxb5) 25. Bxd7 Nxd7 {Now White has a big choice, and the engine says that probably, objectively, I could have played better.} 26. Nf5 $1 (26. Nb5 {I wanted to focus on my standard plan. A)} Rc8 27. Nc3 {hitting a4 and intending to jump to d5.} Nc6 28. Nd5 $16 {and the knight is powerful. B) 26...Bd8 27.Nc3! Nb7 Can we take the pawn? 28.Nxa4! Yes, we can! 28...Rxa4 29.Qb5 with threats on the a4-e8 diagonal. 29...Nbc5 30.Rxc5 Qxb5 31.Rxb5+- and finally White picks up the b3-pawn. C) 26...Nc5!? Good practical choice! If the position is bad, it is a clever tactic to tempt the opponent with a pawn sac! 27.Nc3!? was the positional choice but I could not resist! 27.Nxd6 Bxd6 28.Bxc5 White has basically won a pawn for nothing, but Black's pieces at least come to life!}) 26... Bf6 27. f4 $1 {With total domination. This was very strong. Clearly, this is the chess of the 2020s...} *

