1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 O-O 8. c3 d6 $6 {Losing the psychological battle. Mickey should have stuck to his beloved Marshall! I have noticed that whenever Black over the board decides to deviate from his main weapon, Marshall, out of fear that the opponent might have prepared something special, it almost always ends badly! After all, there is a real reason why Marshall players prefer to play the Marshall...} 9. h3 Na5 {I think I can speak in everyone´s name that compared to a Marshall, the Spanish Chigorin is a very welcome gift to all of us!} 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 {Keeping the tension is considered the most reliable line for Black.} (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Bb7 13. d5 {or 12...exd4 13.Nxd4 Re8 14.Nc3 are better for White.}) 12. Nbd2 {The move that I have been using all my life.} cxd4 13. cxd4 Nc6 {By now, I believe that this is Black's most reliable line in the Chigorin. Luckily, before this game, I was still very optimistic about White's chances here. Sometimes, being an optimist is so much better than being objective... Black immediately puts the pressure on the d4-pawn.} 14. Nb3 {The absolute main line.} (14. d5 $2 {would be premature (just think of the bishop still being on c8!).} Nb4 15. Bb1 a5 16. a3 Na6 {and the typical idea of going} 17. b4 {is not working for White with the knight still being on d2!} Bd7 {White is unable to control the position} 18. Qb3 Rfc8 {( 18...axb4? Trying to trick the opponent comes flying back like a boomerang! 19.axb4 Nc5? The supposedly clever trick... 20.bxc5 Rxa1 21.c6! and it is in fact White who comes out on top!)} 19. Bb2 Nh5 $1 {Black is too active.} 20. Bd3 {Actually, this is a very instructive position! How should Black proceed here? A)} Bd8 $3 $15 {A typical idea, transferring the e7-bishop to the ideal b6-square! Also, here we see why White's bishop on b2 is so misplaced in this structure!!} 21. Rec1 Qa7 {and ...Bb6 comes. B) 20...Nf4 21.Bf1 when 21...Bd8! is still good, but less strong than a move earlier! I was only assuming 21...Qc2 during the recording, but also quickly noticed that 22.bxa5! is kinda possible for White and goes unpunished.}) (14. Nf1 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 exd4 {and White can't recapture on d4 due to the pressure on the c-file.}) 14... a5 $1 {This is the main idea of Black's play. Immediately targeting the b3-knight.} 15. Be3 {White uses the time to develop the bishop to the ideal square supporting the vulnerable d4-pawn.} a4 16. Nbd2 Nb4 {I was very happy seeing this on the board because exactly here I was looking forward to using a special plan that was not yet well known those days! Now, when taking a fresh look at my old game, I realized that the line with 16...Nb4 stands quite well with a modern touch, so objectively, it would be false to criticize this move!} ({In my practice, I had much more difficulty against the 16...Bd7 variation.} 16... Bd7 {when} 17. Bd3 {is met by} Nb4 {, and after 17.Rc1 , Black has two main options: A) 17...Qb7 18.Nf1 Rfe8 19.Ng3 Bd8 is another big line as happened in the Leko-Bologan Dortmund 2004 game [/variation/38709624] � and many other games. 20.Qe2 h6 21.dxe5! Well-timed trade! 21...Nxe5 is well met by 22.Red1 $14 and 21...dxe5 by 22.Bd3! targeting the b5-pawn and inviting Black to lose his coordination. In general, White's idea in this line is to combine pressure against the weak b5 & e5-pawns. Somewhere, White is also dreaming to use the Rc1-c5 idea! 22...Nb4 23.Bb1 Nc6 24.Red1 or 23...Bb6 24.Red1 Bxe3 25.Qxe3 is promising for White. The e5-pawn is vulnerable. B) 17...Rac8 and White has a choice: B1) 18.Bd3!? simple play. 18...Qb8 19.Qe2 putting pressure on b5. 19...Nb4 20.Bb1 Rxc1 21.Rxc1 Rc8 22.Rxc8+ Bxc8 and now a powerful little move 23.b3! There were times when I decided that next time I might just go for this simple approach and try to squeeze the maximum out of it... B2) 18.Bb1 Qb7 19.Qe2 Rc7! I remember that this idea shocked me during the game, especially with how much ease Bacrot neutralized me. Usually, in 2002, I was quite a powerful White player... 20.Nf1 (Maybe I should have tried 20.d5 , but here, Black is well coordinated for the closed center structure. 20...Nb4 21.a3 Na6 22.Bd3 Rb8 23.b4 axb3 24.Nxb3 Rxc1 25.Rxc1 Bd8 Something like this looked way too little...) 20...Rfc8 21.Rcd1 I was still ambitious. How should Black follow it up? 21...Nb4!! Fantastic idea! I had seen it coming but assumed I would find a way to deal with it. Well, finally, I did not find one! 22.dxe5 dxe5 23.Nxe5 Be6! and Black had excellent counterplay, and the game soon ended in a draw in Leko-Bacrot Cannes 2022 game. [/variation/38709625] � B3) 18.Nf1 Qb8 19.Ng3 Rfe8 20.Bb1 and now 20...Bd8!? intending to transfer the bishop to a5 is another very typical idea in this line. Instead, after 20...Na5 eyeing the thematic c4-square. 21.b3 axb3 22.axb3 h6 23.Qd3 b4 , somehow here I was unable to get something tangible in my game [/variation/38709627] with my good friend Vladimir Akopian Elista 2008. � Finally, I'll mention 19.Bb1!? I got lucky with this move in a rapid game. A) 19...Rc7? In this line, all it takes is one inaccuracy, and Black ends up in serious trouble! Now, the situation is completely different compared with my Bacrot game! 20.Qd2! Now there is no more ...Bd8-a5 problem! 20...exd4 Sad choice, a clear sign that something went wrong! ( 20...Rfc8 21.d5! Now the black knight has no good square to go. 21...Na7 22.Rxc7 Rxc7 23.Bd3 with an easy game for White. White has so many ways to improve the position while Black is doomed to passivity... 23.Nxe5!? is another typical motif that one should keep an eye on in all the Classical Spanish positions! It automatically guarantees some advantage, but here, since the position is anyway better for White, it might not be necessary to use it. 23...dxe5 24.d6 Bxd6 25.Qxd6 Nc6 26.Rc1 Ne8 27.Qd2 Be6 28.Rc5 Also with pressure.) 21.Nxd4 Nxd4 22.Bxd4 Rxc1 23.Rxc1 Rc8 How should White react here? 24.Re1! The answer is easy. We have a space advantage and chances to build a strong initiative, so we keep the pieces on the board! The c-file is completely useless here... 24...Be6 25.Ne3 Nd7 26.f4! Bf6 27.Rd1 $16 and Black was in a lot of trouble in the game [/variation/38709626] Leko-Adams Miskolc (Rapid Match) 2005. � B) 19...Bd8! 20.Ng3 h6 is a pretty solid setup. Now, Black does not need to worry about the d4-d5 idea because he can nicely regroup his knight. 21.d5 Ne7 $132 and Black will relocate the knight to g6 and the bishop to b6.}) 17. Bb1 Bd7 (17... a3 $5 18. Qb3 {protecting b2 and threatening bxa3.} axb2 19. Qxb2 {is simply good for White: Black has problems to solve on the b-file. 18...Qa5! is a rather fresh attempt, in my time this did not really exist. It is obviously computers' influence. 19.bxa3 Qxa3 20.Qxa3 Rxa3 21.dxe5 dxe5 22.Nxe5 Be6 and Black will double up on the a-file with pressure on a2.}) 18. a3 Nc6 19. Bd3 Na5 {Back then, this exact line was played with the combination of the moves played in our game.} (19... b4 $2 20. d5 {is just bad.}) ({After my game, it became common knowledge that} 19... Qb7 {is the better move, and the latest developments are quite satisfactory for Black.} 20. Qe2 Rfe8 $1 {This is one of those moves that, when a human plays it, for some reason, it will exactly not work, but when the engine does it, then it is exactly the opposite! The tactical justification is} 21. Bxb5 $2 Nxd4 $1 22. Nxd4 exd4 23. Bxd7 dxe3 24. Bxe8 exd2 $15 {and Black captures the bishop. After 21.Rac1 h6! Making all the useful moves. Now, by transposition, we have reached the MVL-Caruana game. 22.dxe5 how to recapture? A) During the recording, I highlighted why I consider 22...dxe5 strategically an inaccuracy. The engine adds the argument that now White can even take the pawn! 23.Bxb5! The engine just grabs the pawn because it works! ( 23.Bc5 Strategic concept! The computer thinks that exactly here 23...Nh5! is more or less equal. 23...Bxc5 24.Rxc5 hitting e5 and b5. 24...b4 now White gets the c4-square. 25.Qe3 $14 followed by doubling rooks on the c-file would be my model line, which is important to keep in mind! This is a good old classical fundamental knowledge! The extra knights on f3 & c6 are in White's favor!) 23...Nd4 24.Nxd4 exd4 25.Bxd7 and now if 25...dxe3? 26.Bxe8 exd2 27.Bxf7+ Kxf7 28.Qxd2+- White has won too many pawns, while 25...Qxd7 26.Bf4 d3 27.Qf3 is simply better for White. B) Now 22...Nxe5! is clearly the better recapture! With the vulnerable bishop on d3, White has no other choice than to take it, which clearly benefits Black! 23.Nxe5 ( 23.Bb1 b4 $132 enabling ...Bb5.) 23...dxe5 24.Nf3 Qb8 25.Bc5 Typical way to try to squeeze the position, but here, there is not much left to be squeezed... 25...Bxc5 26.Rxc5 b4 $132 happened in a very recent high-level blitz encounter [/variation/38709628] between MVL-Caruana St. Louis Blitz 2023! � Black succeeded in creating enough counterplay. With one extra pair of knights on d2 (white) and c6 (black), it would be a different story; then White would be happy!!}) 20. Qe2 $1 ({This is the big finesse! The point of the} 20. Qe2 {move order is that since Black´s queen will anyway have to defend the b5-pawn with ...Qb8 (otherwise Black is unable to keep both b5 & e5 weaknesses protected), then why would I compromise my rooks positions already!}) ({Instead, after playing the routine move with} 20. Rc1 Qb8 21. Qe2 Re8 {, it is not exactly clear how White can really make progress. That is exactly the reason why Black was satisfied with this line.}) 20... Qb8 {What could have been my big idea behind going 20. Qe2...?} 21. Rec1 $3 {This is the point! White has a clear plan of going Rab1 and b4, after which the b5-pawn will be very vulnerable.} (21. Rab1 {would allow Black to play} Rc8 $1 {with a solid position because now the break does not work for White} 22. b4 $2 axb3 23. Nxb3 Nc4 $15 {the big difference.}) 21... Re8 22. Rab1 $1 {Following the plan. Black is facing serious practical problems. Usually, in a human game, in such a situation, the defensive side gets nervous and makes a mistake...} exd4 $2 {Feels like a panic reaction!} ({Now in 2024, my super engine says, no worries, amigo, the situation is not so bad...} 22... h6 $1 23. b4 axb3 24. Nxb3 d5 $3 {For an engine, it is easy to suggest a move like this; I guess for us mortals, many, many hours of analysis would be needed to understand that this is possible, and it even works... A)} 25. Nxa5 dxe4 $3 {This intermezzo is essential.} 26. Bxb5 exf3 27. gxf3 Qd6 28. Nc4 Qe6 29. dxe5 Nd5 {with almost zeros... B) 25.Nxe5 dxe4 26.Bxe4 Nxb3! All these well-timing captures are only obvious to computers. 27.Rxb3 Nxe4 28.Nxd7 Qd8! 29.Nc5 Nd6! and according to the engine, Black has a good chance to hold this despite being a pawn down.}) ({To my mind,} 22... b4 $5 {looked like the most natural reaction. Now, White has two different options. A)} 23. axb4 exd4 {(If 23...Qxb4 White can simply take the e5-pawn: 24.dxe5 dxe5 25.Nxe5 Be6 26.Ndf3 without any compensation for Black.)} 24. Bxd4 $1 {Now the bishop can be nicely transferred.} Qxb4 25. Bc3 {Cemento construction!} Qb7 26. Re1 {with a very nice position. B) 23.d5!? also looks like an interesting choice, but we need a good reaction after 23...Bd8 24.axb4!? Qxb4 25.Ne1 $14 The justification why we consider the move 24.axb4 at all! White's knights will land on a3 and c4.}) 23. Nxd4 ({Targeting b5. This is more principled than} 23. Bxd4 {.}) 23... b4 (23... d5 {Breaking out did not work as well.} 24. Bxb5 Bxb5 {( 24...dxe4 25.Bxd7 Nxd7 26.Nxe4 $16 is just good for White.)} 25. Qxb5 $1 {This is very effective.} dxe4 26. Qxa4 Nd5 27. b4 Nc4 28. Qb3 {with Nc6 ideas. Worse is 25.Nxb5 Does Black have a good move here? 25...Nc4! is not so simple. For example, 26.Nc7 Qxc7 27.exd5 Nxd5 28.Rxc4 Qd7! 29.Qd3 Rad8 or 26.Nxc4 Qxb5 27.exd5 Nxd5 , which is good for Black thanks to the queenside pawn structure and the pressure on the e-file and the a6-f1 diagonal.}) {How to play here with White?} 24. Bb5 $1 {Now Black is in a lot of trouble! After the light-squared bishops are traded off, Black only has weaknesses!} (24. Nb5 Nc6 25. axb4 $2 Rc8 $1 {and Black will recapture on b4 next.}) 24... b3 (24... Bxb5 25. Nxb5) 25. Bxd7 Nxd7 {Now White has a big choice.} 26. Nb5 {I wanted to focus on my standard plan.} ({Now the engine says that probably objectively I could have played better:} 26. Nf5 $1 Bf6 27. f4 $1 {with total domination was very strong. Clearly this is the chess of the 2020s...} g6 28. Nh6+ Kg7 29. Ng4 {and Nxf6.}) 26... Nc5 $5 {Good practical choice! If the position is bad, it is a clever tactic to tempt the opponent with a pawn sac!} ({A)} 26... Rc8 27. Nc3 Nc6 28. Nd5 $16 {and the knight is powerful.}) ({B)} 26... Bd8 27. Nc3 $1 Nb7 {Can we take the pawn?} 28. Nxa4 $1 {Yes, we can!} Rxa4 29. Qb5 {with threats on the a4-e8 diagonal.} Nbc5 30. Rxc5 Qxb5 31. Rxb5 {and finally White picks up the b3-pawn.}) 27. Nxd6 {I could not resist!} (27. Nc3 $5 {was the positional choice.}) 27... Bxd6 28. Bxc5 {White has basically won a pawn for nothing, but Black's pieces at least come to life!} Bf4 (28... h6 $5) 29. Be3 {Systematic approach.} (29. Bb4 $5 {looks clever.}) 29... h6 {White is clearly better, but suddenly not so easy to convert.} 30. Rc3 (30. Rc5 Nb7 31. Rb5 $1 Bxe3 32. Qxe3 Qc7 33. Re1 Rad8 34. Nb1 $1 {is the sophisticated suggestion of our silicon friend.}) 30... Nb7 (30... Be5 31. Rc5 $1 {This was my plan.}) 31. g3 {This worked very well in the game, but against a modern engine, it would have been a serious inaccuracy...} Be5 (31... Bxe3 $1 {It looks so counter-intuitive to trade the bishops, but after the bishop trade, the Black queen can finally be activated!} 32. Qxe3 Qe5 $1 {Is an important nuance pointed out by modern engines! Suddenly, Black gets serious chances to survive.}) 32. Rd3 $1 f5 $2 {Desperado.} (32... Qc8 33. f4 $1 {would also work exactly according to plans.}) 33. Nc4 {White has perfect harmony.} Bxg3 {Mickey tries something, but it is clearly not enough.} ({A)} 33... fxe4 34. Rd7 {or 34.Rd5 Bf6 35.Nb6 Ra5 36.Nd7+-}) ({B)} 33... f4 34. Nxe5 fxe3 35. f4 {The e3-pawn will fall, and White has a fantastic knight on e5.}) 34. fxg3 Rxe4 35. Nd2 $1 {Very nice retreat!} Qxg3+ 36. Qg2 {Now it is all over.} Qxg2+ 37. Kxg2 Re6 38. Rc1 Rae8 39. Kf3 g5 40. Rc4 {This was my very first classical game victory over Adams!} 1-0

