1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 {This has always been considered one of the most classical lines in the Chigorin variation. By move order, it can also lead to the same position if Black plays} (12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bd7 {first and after} 14. Nf1 Rac8 {would transpose to the game. This move order has been played against me three times (!) by Korchnoi, Short, and Bruzon in the 2003-2005 period. Goes on to show that it really had a solid reputation. With the 12...Bd7 move order Kamsky wanted to provoke me to the extra option of closing the center with 13. d5 this is often a psychological moment.}) (12... Rd8 {. Please look at this informational [/variation/38289911] only after reading the game annotation with}) (12... Bd7 {. This is the way how you will get the most benefit!}) 13. Nf1 {By 2006 I had gained quite an experience in this line and decided to stick to my main setup and not to fall into the provocation.} ({My philosophy has always been never to blindly follow the theory but to adjust to every single new situation. My feelings during the game signaled to me that if Gata feels ready to face} 13. d5 {this case I will simply ignore it. It leads to a completely different battle where, again, one has to be familiar with all the nuances.}) 13... Rac8 {Insisting on provoking d4-d5, the answer still remains the same.} 14. Ne3 {No, thank you! This is a very nice way of defending the c2-bishop.} cxd4 15. cxd4 Nc6 {This was always the main idea for Black.} 16. d5 {Now, with the white knight on e3, this line works very nicely for White. Again, one small detail makes the whole difference!} Nb4 17. Bb1 a5 18. a3 Na6 {For the moment, this looks quite healthy for Black. White's pieces are not yet developed, and also, the knight on e3 seems to be in the way of allowing White to play normally. However, there is one very important trick in the position, which changes everything!} *

