13... c4 $1 14. Re3 $1 ({Let's see some opening subtleties first. Obviously, this is the critical reply to 13.d5; Black makes sure to guarantee counterplay and have the ...Nb7-c5 route ready for his knight. Important strategic question: In such positions, apart from the routine} 14. Nf1 {move, which other move makes sense for White?}) ({Honestly, if I had played 13. d5, it is clear that I would have chosen this move over the board. Getting ready to play b2-b4 next, White makes sure Black's counterplay is kept under control. This is another 'Cemento spirit reaction'!} 14. Nf1 Nb7 {Black is ready for queenside activity, so now it is important for White to be active on the kingside! But that's a question for another exercise!}) 14... Nb7 15. b4 $1 {Keeping the b7-knight under control.} cxb3 ({Important to note that when Black has a terrible knight on b7, then we do not have to worry about the change of structures after} 15... a5 {White can just follow up with the normal moves} 16. Nf1 {because} axb4 {is never a strategical threat} 17. cxb4 {is just great for White.}) 16. axb3 {With a big strategic battle on the queenside. However, I usually believe that in such positions, even if it is difficult, with true mastery, White should be pressing. Let's see how the game can continue.} *

