18... Na6 {Back to the game! For the moment this looks quite healthy for Black. White's pieces are not yet developed, and also, the knight on e3 seems to be in the way of allowing White to play normally. However, there is one very important trick in the position, which changes everything! What is it?} 19. b4 $1 {This is the key move of the classical line. I remember how happy I was when I learned about it as a kid! Thanks to this lovely trick, White guarantees lasting pressure and makes it no fun for Black!} axb4 {It is always a big dilemma for Black should he capture on b4 or to keep the tension.} ({Back in 1993 I already had a big theoretical duel when my opponent kept the tension for too long.} 19... g6 20. Bd2 $1 Nh5 21. Bd3 $1 {Typical regrouping!} Nf4 22. Bf1 {The bishop protects the kingside and eyes the b5-weakness.}) 20. axb4 Qb7 ({Of course Black can't take the pawn with} 20... Nxb4 $2 {due to} 21. Bd2 {trapping the knight. Here, we can see how important that knight on e3 is!} Qc5 22. Qb3 {winning the piece.}) 21. Bd2 $1 {Nicely protecting the b4-pawn and stopping any entry square on the c-file.} Bd8 {Very logical to transfer the bishop immediately to b6, but this plan has a serious drawback. It leaves Black's kingside vulnerable!} ({I had a very interesting game with Nigel Short when he opted for a completely different plan with} 21... g6 $5 22. Bd3 Nh5 {Typical idea in these types of positions. Black grabs space but also weakens the kingside.} 23. Ra3 $5 {Just in case getting ready to activate the rook on the 3rd rank.} Nc7 24. Ng4 Ra8 25. Rc3 {I had the upper hand, but later it got out of control and the game [/variation/38709633] Leko-Short Budapest 2003 � ended in a big fighting draw.}) 22. Bd3 $1 {Both bishops are perfectly placed. One protects the b4-pawn, the other one targets b5, and they also cover all the entry squares on the c-file.} *

