26... Nc7 $5 {This is an interesting practical decision. My opponent knows that his position is close to collapse and tries to tempt me to win a pawn but to do so, I would need to give up my dark-squared bishop! How would you play?} 27. Ne3 $1 {Yes, we say no, thanks for the temptation!} (27. Bxg5 hxg5 28. Qxg5 Ne8 {White won a pawn, but Black can feel relieved. There is no real attack, but Black has long-term prospects thanks to the dark squares.}) 27... Ra8 (27... g6 {How to proceed here? That's a future question for you!}) 28. Nef5 $1 Rxa1 {Again, White can win a pawn or look further.} 29. Ne7+ $1 {This is a lovely intermezzo! I was calculating many beautiful lines and could not resist.} (29. Rxa1 Ra8 30. Rxa8+ Qxa8 31. Nxd6 $1 {was simply winning a pawn, but suddenly Black's queen can be activated.} Qa1+ 32. Bf1 $1 {or 32.Kh2 Qd1! I did not want to allow this; besides, I had discovered so many much more interesting possibilities that this was not really on my agenda.}) 29... Kh8 {Asking for trouble, but strategically keeping the position sound.} (29... Kh7 30. Rxa1 f6 {was terribly weakening.} 31. Nhf5 Bxf5 32. Nxf5 Ne8 33. h4 Nf7 34. h5 Ng5 {This is strategically completely lost for Black due to the vulnerable light squares. White can choose whatever he wants...} 35. Rc1 {or 35.Be3!?}) 30. Rxa1 {Black's kingside is about to collapse.} *

