1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 Bd7 ({This has always been considered one of the most classical lines in the Chigorin variation. By move order, it can also lead to the same position if Black plays} 12... cxd4 13. cxd4 Bd7 {first and after} 14. Nf1 Rac8 {would transpose to the game. This move order has been played against me three times (!) by Korchnoi, Short, and Bruzon in the 2003-2005 period. Goes on to show that it really had a solid reputation. With the 12...Bd7 move order Kamsky wanted to provoke me to the extra option of closing the center with 13. d5 this is often a psychological moment. Note that 14.d5? would be completely pointless now with Black's bishop on d7 and should be considered as a clear mistake! 14...Rfc8 15.Bd3 Nb7! and the knight gets the c5-square as White can't play the desired b2-b4 due to the ...a6-a5 break.}) (12... Rd8 {. Please look at this informational [/variation/38289911] only after reading the game annotation with 12...Bd7 13. d5. This is the way how you will get the most benefit!}) 13. Nf1 {By 2006 I had gained quite an experience in this line and decided to stick to my main setup and not to fall into the provocation.} ({My philosophy has always been never to blindly follow the theory but to adjust to every single new situation. My feelings during the game signaled to me that if Gata feels ready to face} 13. d5 {this case I will simply ignore it. It leads to a completely different battle where, again, one has to be familiar with all the nuances.} c4 $1 {Obviously, this is the critical move; Black makes sure to guarantee counterplay and have the ...Nb7-c5 route ready for his knight. Important strategic question: In such positions apart from the routine 14. Nf1 move, which other move makes sense for White? 14.Nf1 Nb7 Black is ready for queenside activity, so now it is important for White to be active on the kingside! What is the most principled reaction here from White's side? 15.g4! Yes, now that the center is closed, and the knight is ready to jump to g3 immediately this is a typical reaction! ( 15.Ng3 Nc5 and nothing has changed for Black.) 15...Nc5 16.Ng3 a5 with a very messy position requiring precise knowledge, which was definitely not in my interest. 14.Re3! Honestly, if I had played 13. d5, it is clear that I would have chosen this move over the board. Getting ready to play b2-b4 next, makes sure that White keeps Black's counterplay under control. This is another 'Cemento spirit reaction'! 14...Nb7 and now White shouldn't waste a move. For example, 15.Nf1 allows 15...Nc5 16.b4 cxb3 17.axb3 a5 and Black gets his counterplay. We didn't manage to control the knight, and Re3 was pointless. Instead, the direct 15.b4! keeps the b7-knight under control, and now: A) Important to note that when Black has a terrible knight on b7, we do not have to worry about the change of structures after 15...a5 as White can just follow up with the normal move 16.Nf1 because 16...axb4 is never a strategical threat. 17.cxb4 is just great for White thanks to the 'Cemento spirit'. The knight will take the Nf1-g3-e2-c3 route, and the b4-pawn will be supported by a2-a3. Meanwhile, Black's b7-knight is passive. B) 15...cxb3 16.axb3 with a big strategical battle on the queenside, but I usually believe that in such positions, even if it is difficult, but with true mastery, White should be pressing. 16...a5 What is the justification of White's previous play? 17.b4! Yes, only like this! Otherwise, Black goes ...Nb7-c5 and enjoys his life! 17...Rfc8 And now how to best react to the new situation? 18.Nb1!! This is what I had in mind when talking about true mastery! Since now all the action is on the queenside, that is why the main priority is to place our pieces as perfectly as possible, not play 'just routine Spanish moves'! 18...axb4 is not a problem, as we can continues 19.Rxa8 Rxa8 20.cxb4 and this operation has been beneficial: the c2-bishop is not hanging, the b4-pawn dominates the black knight, and White has Rc3 ideas.}) 13... Rac8 {Insisting on provoking d4-d5, the answer still remains the same.} 14. Ne3 {No, thank you! This is a very nice way of defending the c2-bishop.} cxd4 15. cxd4 Nc6 {This was always the main idea for Black.} 16. d5 {Now, with the white knight on e3, this line works very nicely for White. Again, one small detail makes the whole difference!} Nb4 17. Bb1 a5 18. a3 Na6 {For the moment this looks quite healthy for Black. White's pieces are not yet developed, and also, the knight on e3 seems to be in the way of allowing White to play normally, but there is one very important trick in the position, which changes everything! So, what is the trick here?} 19. b4 $1 {This is the key move of the classical line. I remember how happy I was when I learned about it as a kid! Thanks to this lovely trick, White guarantees lasting pressure and makes it no fun for Black!} axb4 {It is always a big dilemma for Black should he capture on b4 or to keep the tension.} ({Back in 1993, I already had a big theoretical duel when my opponent kept the tension for too long.} 19... g6 {preparing …Nh5.} 20. Bd2 $1 Nh5 21. Bd3 $1 {Typical regrouping!} Nf4 22. Bf1 {The bishop protects the kingside and eyes the b5 weakness.} f5 {Going all in.} 23. exf5 gxf5 24. Rc1 Qb7 25. Rxc8 Qxc8 26. bxa5 $1 {Decided to take the pawn because after} Nc5 {I have the lovely} 27. Bb4 $1 e4 28. Nd4 {all this happened in my game [/variation/38709632] Leko-Lukacs Budapest 1993. � I was very proud of my opening knowledge and had also annotated this game for the legendary Chess Informant back then. I believe the fact that already, as a 13/14-year-old teenager, I was facing experienced grandmasters in the Classical Spanish in Hungary has forced me to work hard and helped me understand the lines very well from an early age. The game followed} Ncd3 29. Bxd3 Nxd3 30. Re2 f4 31. Nf1 Bh4 32. Ne6 $1 {I was very proud of this back in the day!} Bxe6 33. dxe6 {, and thanks to the pin on the e-file, Black's position has fallen apart: A)} Qxe6 34. Qxd3 {is the trick. B) 33...Nxb4 34.Rxe4! is the other trick. C) After 33...Re8 34.g3!! Rxe6 ( 34...fxg3 35.Rxe4 Nxf2 36.Rg4+! wins: 36...Nxg4 37.Qxg4 and White picks up the bishop.) 35.Rc2! Qd8 36.Qg4+ , I went on to win the game easily.}) 20. axb4 Qb7 ({Of course Black can't take the pawn with} 20... Nxb4 $2 {due to} 21. Bd2 {trapping the knight. Here, we can see how important that knight on e3 is!} Qc5 22. Qb3 {winning the piece.}) 21. Bd2 $1 {Nicely protecting the b4-pawn and stopping any entry square on the c-file.} Bd8 {Very logical to transfer the bishop immediately to b6, but this plan has a serious drawback. It leaves Black's kingside vulnerable!} ({A) I had a very interesting game with Nigel Short when he opted for a completely different plan with} 21... g6 $5 22. Bd3 Nh5 {Typical idea in these types of positions. Black grabs space but also weakens the kingside.} 23. Ra3 $5 {Just in case getting ready to activate the rook on the 3rd rank.} Nc7 24. Ng4 Ra8 25. Rc3 {I had the upper hand, but later it got out of control and the game [/variation/38709633] Leko-Short Budapest 2003 � ended in a big fighting draw.}) ({B) Probably the most solid plan is just to play} 21... Ra8 22. Bd3 Nc7 {How should White react here?} 23. Rb1 $3 {Since White has a space advantage, I believe that we can afford to temporarily give up the open a-file! White has a very clear and powerful plan to transfer the f3 knight to a5; if that knight ever reaches a5, Black will be in a lot of trouble! I would not like to be in Black's shoes here...}) 22. Bd3 $1 {Both bishops are perfectly placed. One protects the b4-pawn, the other one targets b5, and they also cover all the entry squares on the c-file.} Bb6 23. Nc2 $5 {I was very proud of this multi-purpose move during the game. First of all, it is a big surprise. Secondly, Black has to deal with the direct threat of Bd2-g5 hitting the knight on f6, which is quite awkward now that Black has transferred his bishop to b6. Another really hidden idea is something that I learned after quietly analyzing my game with Nigel at home. In this structure, there is also the stunning strategical idea of going Ne3-c2 followed by Ra1-a3 and then continuing the knight route with Nc2-a1-b3-a5!} ({My move worked to perfection in the game, but it was very funny to see that computers were not impressed and suggested that without any big strategic brilliancy, I could have just played} 23. Nh4 $5 g6 24. Qf3 $1 {I have clearly looked at this during the game, and} Nh5 $2 {is simly met by} 25. Nef5 $1 {, but 24...Bd8! disturbed me when my knight is kinda stuck and vulnerable on h4. Well, the engine comes up with the neat, simple solution of going 25.g3! and since the pawn on h3 is taboo, as 25...Bxh3? runs into 26.g4+- and the bishop is trapped, White just keeps the control and will slowly improve the position, but humanly this is not so one-sided, because Black does have the knight regrouping with 25...Nc7 26.Kh2 Nce8 followed by ...Ng7 and White might be better, but at least Black has a plan.}) 23... h6 $2 {Gata plays the routine move stopping Bg5, but this is basically already the decisive mistake! How do we punish?} ({The reason why the engine was not so impressed is that there is a stunning resource for Black in the line after} 23... Nc7 $1 24. Bg5 {What does the engine have in mind here?} Nxe4 $3 {Incredible, but engines almost always find some special way to deal with every position.} 25. Bxe4 f5 26. Bd3 e4 27. Be2 Nxd5 28. Nfd4 f4 $1 {and due to many dynamic factors, the position is completely out of control.} 29. Bg4 h6 30. Bh4 {and Black has many possibilities to continue with 0.00's.} Nc3 31. Qd2 Bxg4 32. hxg4 Qd5 {Perfect coordination!} 33. Ra6 Na4 $1 {is a stylish engine line. 24.Nh4 is clearly a playable alternative now that there is no ...Bd8, with small pressure. 24...Ra8 and now 25.Rb1!? keeping all the rooks again deserves attention, but now Black has a more active version! 25.Qf3 Rxa1 26.Rxa1 Ra8 27.Rc1 keeping one pair of rooks on the board. 27...Nce8 with a long maneuvering game ahead.}) 24. Nh4 $1 {Yes! Now, this is much stronger because we even have a clear target on the kingside.} Nh7 25. Qf3 {White is spoiled with choice.} (25. Ne3 $5) 25... Ng5 (25... Bd8 26. Nf5 Bxf5 27. Qxf5 Bg5 {Should we trade dark-squared bishops?} 28. Ne3 $1 {Keeping the bishops is even stronger.}) 26. Qg3 Nc7 $5 {Interesting practical decision. My opponent knows that his position is close to collapse and tries to tempt me to win a pawn, but by doing so, I would need to give up my dark-squared bishop!} ({After} 26... Bd8 {I planned to simply continue with} 27. Ne3 {( 27.f4 exf4 28.Bxf4 Rc3! was annoying.)} g6 28. Ng4 Bxg4 29. Qxg4 {with a clear advantage. Now that the light-squared bishop is gone, the b5-pawn is extremely vulnerable.}) 27. Ne3 $1 {Yes, we say no, thanks for the temptation!} (27. Bxg5 hxg5 28. Qxg5 Ne8 {White won a pawn, but Black can feel relieved. There is no real attack, but Black has long-term prospects thanks to the dark squares.}) 27... Ra8 ({Trying to trade all the rooks.} 27... g6 {How to proceed here?} 28. Nef5 $3 {Yes, the time has come for the decisive attack.} gxf5 29. Bxg5 hxg5 30. Qxg5+ Kh8 31. Nxf5 Bxf5 32. exf5 f6 33. Qh6+ Kg8 34. Qg6+ Kh8 35. Re4 {and mate is coming.}) (27... Ne8 28. Nef5) 28. Nef5 $1 Rxa1 29. Ne7+ $1 {This is a lovely intermezzo! I was calculating many beautiful lines and could not resist.} (29. Rxa1 Ra8 30. Rxa8+ Qxa8 31. Nxd6 $1 {was simply winning a pawn, but suddenly Black's queen can be activated} Qa1+ 32. Bf1 $1 {or 32.Kh2 Qd1! I did not want to allow this; besides, I had discovered so many much more interesting possibilities that this was not really on my agenda.}) 29... Kh8 {Asking for trouble, but strategically keeping the position sound.} (29... Kh7 30. Rxa1 f6 {terrible weakening} 31. Nhf5 Bxf5 32. Nxf5 Ne8 33. h4 Nf7 34. h5 Ng5 {is strategically completely lost for Black due to the vulnerable light squares. White can choose whatever he wants...} 35. Rc1 {or 35.Be3!?}) 30. Rxa1 Nh7 31. Qf3 $3 {Following the beautiful ideas. Practically maybe I should have just cashed in with simple measures, but I could not resist playing for the galleries... What is White threatening here?} ({A)} 31. Nhf5 $1 {was the simplest.} Ne8 {is met by} 32. Nxh6 {and after 31...Bxf5 32.Nxf5 Ne8 33.Be3 , White wins the battle on the queenside without any sacrifices.}) ({B)} 31. Bxh6 $5 gxh6 32. Nhg6+ fxg6 33. Nxg6+ Kg7 34. Nxf8+ Kxf8 35. Qg6 $3 {Some insane computer calculation.}) 31... Nf6 {Sad necessity, but there was no other way to stop the queen sacrifice on f7!} (31... Ne8 $2 32. Qxf7 $3 {Yes, this is it!} Rxf7 33. Nhg6#) (31... Be8 32. Nhf5) 32. Bxh6 Ra8 $1 {The only practical chance!} 33. Rf1 $2 {Terrible choice (the move itself is not bad), especially because at the beginning, I had some 30 minutes left and calculated for 20 minutes all the fantastic lines after the sacrifice with 33. Bxg7. All my calculations turned out to be perfectly correct, but since I knew that I was simply winning here, finally, I did not dare to trust my calculation; luckily, I won the game; otherwise, it would be really difficult to forgive myself for not trusting myself!} (33. Rxa8+ Qxa8 34. Be3 Bxe3 35. Qxe3 {White is a pawn up and has the better position. With ideas like Qb6 and the e7-knight perfectly safe, this should be winning.}) (33. Bxg7+ $3 Kxg7 {here it was very difficult to decide which knight should give a check on f5 as both look good, but both moves give extra options for Black. A)} 34. Nhf5+ Kh7 35. Rxa8 Qxa8 36. Qg3 Bxf5 37. Qh4+ $1 {wins on the spot:} Kg7 38. Nxf5+ {and Qxf6. Or 34...Kf8 35.Nxd6 Rxa1+ 36.Kh2 Kxe7 37.Nxb7 Nce8 38.Nc5 Over the board, such things never feel like +5, rook + two pieces vs. queen need to be completely winning for our human feelings... B) 34.Nef5+ and now: B1) 34...Kf8 What happens here? 35.Nxd6! Bxf2+!! This disturbed me. What is the move here? ( 35...Rxa1+ 36.Kh2 Qa7 leads to mate after 37.Qxf6 Be8 38.Ng6+ Kg8 39.Qh8 36.Kxf2? Qb6+ is winning for Black! The right path is 36.Kh2! Bxh4 37.Nxb7 Rxa1 38.Nc5 with a clear advantage, but I was not so sure about this unbalance of rook + two pieces vs. queen situation. According to the engines, this is just completely winning due to the missing coordination of Black's forces... B2) 34...Kh7 35.Rxa8 Qxa8 36.Nxd6 Kg7 37.Qg3+ Kf8 38.Qxe5 Nce8 39.Nhf5 Bxf5 40.Nxf5 Qa2 41.Qf4! and White wins. B3) 34...Bxf5 35.Nxf5+ Kf8 How is White supposed to continue here? 36.Nxd6!! Yes, again, the same motif! 36...Rxa1+ 37.Kh2 This was my dream line, which I had foreseen already when going for 29. Ne7! 37...Qa7 ( 37...Qa8 38.Qxf6 and the black queen can’t defend the mating threats. 38...Kg8 39.Qxf7+ Kh8 40.Qh5+ Kg7 41.Nf5+ Kg8 42.Qg6+ Kf8 43.Qg7+ Ke8 44.Qe7 ) 38.Qxf6 Ne8 39.Qh8+ Ke7 40.Nc8+ lovely finish, but 40.Qxe5+ mates by the way... Finally, what about this? 35...Kh7 36.Nxd6!? Rxa1+ 37.Kh2 Qa8 38.Qxf6 Qf8 39.Nxf7 was my main line with Be2-g4-f5 ideas or simply pushing the d-pawn with a beautiful win, but the prosaic 36.Rxa8 Qxa8 37.Nxd6 Nce8 38.Qf5+ Kg7 39.Qg5+ Kh7 40.Nf5 Qa7 41.Qh4+ Kg8 42.Bxb5 leaves Black in a total box.}) 33... Nce8 $1 {Now Black is in time to defend the kingside. Of course, the position is terrible; White is a pawn up after all, but now the time trouble is coming, and psychologically, I was pretty down that my dream of delivering checkmate did not materialize...} 34. Bc1 Ra1 35. Nhf5 Qc7 36. Bd2 (36. Bg5 $1 {was much stronger with a simple win.} Rxf1+ 37. Bxf1 Nh7 38. Bh4 $1 Nef6 39. Nh6 $1 Be8 40. Nc6 $1 {is again a picturesque position! Black is completely paralyzed.}) 36... Rxf1+ 37. Kxf1 g6 $1 {This cuts White's coordination.} 38. Ne3 $2 {Indecisiveness in time-trouble!} (38. Nh6 $1 Kg7 {Any special ideas here?} 39. Neg8 $3 {Wow, fancy!} Bc8 40. Nxf6 Nxf6 41. g4 {with easy win.}) 38... Kg7 $1 {Suddenly, it is objectively not easy!} 39. g4 $5 {Now, out of panic, I am trying to be aggressive. How could Black have defended his difficult position?} Nh7 $2 ({Not} 39... Kf8 {due to} 40. Nxg6+ $1 fxg6 41. g5 $16) ({Black had a golden opportunity to defend the position with the unimaginable} 39... Bxe3 $3 {Giving up the dark-squared bishop like this is something that does not cross our minds, especially not in extremely heavy time trouble! But here it has a very concrete idea... A)} 40. Qxe3 Kf8 $1 {Now it is possible} 41. Nc6 Bxc6 42. dxc6 Qxc6 {Rock solid. Despite White having the two bishops, Black is probably holding this without much trouble. B) Bxe3 Qc3! is the other concrete idea.} 43. Kg2 {Qxb4 Nc6 Qa4 looks beautiful for White, but in fact, there is no clear way to crack Black's position; the computer even goes as far as to claim the 'famous 0.00s'. 41.Qe2! Qxb4 42.Qc2! is the computer precision still asking tough questions!}) 40. Kg2 {My time trouble has finished!} Qb7 $2 {The famous move 40, played with few seconds on the clock! Black wants to play ...Bb6-d8 and feels secure enough on the kingside but runs into a very unpleasant surprise! What was the reason why 40...Qb7 was such an unlucky move?} ({The only move was} 40... Nef6 $1 {when White should play} 41. Nd1 $3 {Actually, I had this move on my radar as it controls the dark squares on the kingside, and it also enables ideas like Nd1-c3 going after the b5-pawn.}) (40... Ng5 {achieves nothing} 41. Qg3 {only helps White.}) 41. Nc4 $3 {It took me exactly 32 minutes to come up with this stunning shocker! This is one of the main reasons why I have always been and am a huge fan of classical time control. Dealing with all the emotions after the time-trouble, getting enough time after move 40 is essential! Once I managed to calm down and stopped blaming myself for all the missing winning options, suddenly it hit me that there was a golden opportunity to make up for all the previous pain!} g5 {This is equal to capitulation, but Gata did not want to give me the chance to deliver my beautiful mating idea. It is a pity...} ({A)} 41... bxc4 42. Bh6+ $3 {The key idea of the whole sacrifice!} Kxh6 43. Qxf7 {and there is no defense against mate with Qxg6.}) ({B)} 41... Bxg4 42. Bh6+ $1 {is the same} Kxh6 43. Qxf7 Bxh3+ 44. Kg3) ({C)} 41... Bd8 42. Na5 $1 Qa6 43. Nec6 {and 42...Bxa5 runs into 43.Bh6+! again! 43...Kxh6 44.Qxf7 with the same problems...}) 42. Na5 Qa8 43. Nf5+ Kf8 44. h4 Bd8 45. Nh6 f6 46. hxg5 {And Black resigned. It was a very memorable big win against the legendary Gata Kamsky, who had just played in his first super tournament after almost 10 years of break. He had a very tough time. It is true that class is permanent, but without good openings, it is impossible to survive Wijk aan Zee! In the following years, after stabilizing his repertoire then, Gata was back to business! The only thing I still can't erase from my memory is that despite the fact that the stunning 41.Nc4 move was described as the most spectacular move of the tournament. Still, I did not win the daily best game prize because the move was played when the fate of the daily prize had already been decided...} 1-0

