1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. Nbd2 {Please look at this comment only after reading the game annotation with 12...Bd7 13.d5 here. [/variation/38289909] This is the way how you will get the most benefit!} Rd8 ({Suddenly, when looking at the} 12... Bd7 13. d5 {line and discovering the Re3 idea, I had a déjà vu feeling...}) (12... Bd7 {This has always been considered one of the most classical lines in the Chigorin variation. By move order, it can also lead to the same position if Black plays} 13. Nf1 {By 2006 I had gained quite an experience in this line and decided to stick to my main setup and not to fall into the provocation. My philosophy has always been never to blindly follow the theory but to adjust to every single new situation. My feelings during the game signaled to me that if Gata feels ready to face 13.d5 this case I will simply ignore it. It leads to a completely different battle where, again, one has to be familiar with all the nuances.}) 13. d5 $1 {No tricks!} (13. Nf1 cxd4 14. cxd4 exd4 {and of course White is not forced to recapture, and} 15. Ng3 $5 {or 15.Bf4!? are possible but let me show you the crazy line 15.Nxd4 d5! 16.e5 Ne4 17.f3 Bc5!! 18.b4 Bxb4 19.fxe4 Qxe5 , with which people were scaring me when I just started out playing the Classical Spanish with White...}) 13... c4 14. Re3 $5 {I knew that I knew this idea from somewhere...} Bd7 15. b4 $1 {The idea behind Re3.} Nb7 16. a4 a5 17. axb5 Bxb5 18. Nb1 $3 {Again, the positional stunner!} Be8 19. Re1 {There was no need to correct the rook´s position just yet.} (19. Na3 $1 Nd7 20. Ba4 {was the strongest.}) 19... Nd7 20. Be3 Nb6 {So far everything was great, but here I lost control...} 21. Qd2 $1 {I should have kept the b4-pawn at all costs because it is the soul of White`s position!} (21. bxa5 Nxa5 {and Rustam went on to survive this scare in the Leko-Kasimdzhanov Yerevan 2001 game. [/variation/38709631] � Yes, Re1-e3 and Nd2-b1 ideas are El Classicos in my games! All the more it hurts that I have spoiled this game; otherwise, it could have been included in my most instructive strategical wins collection...}) 21... Rdc8 22. Rc1 $1 {A lovely move, making sure we're able to keep our structure and the b7-knight stays out of the game. Black is suffering.} *

