1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Nd7 {This line has a completely different spirit compared to all the Classical Chigorin variations we have just discussed. In a way, Black's main idea is to set up a possible Benoni-type transformation of structure with ...exd4. Let´s not forget about the fact that here, Black´s bishop is still on c8! I have often highlighted the main drawback of the Spanish/Benoni structures when that bishop gets blocked out of the game with eventual d4-d5. Always the nuances!} 12. d5 $1 {My favorite reaction. It does not allow Black to go for his spirit! This is a positional system, but what attracted my attention right from the beginning is that White's positional grip in the old main line after 13.Nbd2 f5 is based on a beautiful little tactical idea. Once I saw that, I knew deep inside that this would be love for eternity!} Nb6 13. Nbd2 (13. g4 $2 {One of those rare strategical mistakes from the legendary Bobby Fischer! This is when you are still a bit young, at the same time, already very strong and a tiny bit too ambitious! In general, the idea is impressive; White stops ...f7-f5 and is planning Nbd2-f1-g3 with great prospects. The only problem is that on the opposite side sits another legend Paul Keres...}) *

