29... Bh4 $1 {This is an active route for Black's bishop! We have to really understand the position in order to see how White should continue.} 30. Qd3 $1 {With a big advantage thanks to the pressure on the diagonal.} (30. Nd3 $6 {This logical move is in the wrong direction! I should have understood that, in fact, I should be happy trading this knight for the bishop!} Nf6 {Black succeeds with his plan! Now} 31. Nd2 $3 {was keeping the advantage according to the engine, but this is another planet... 31.Bg1 Nxe4 32.Rxe4 Bg3! Black has enough counterplay; now Black is fine. 33.axb4 axb4 34.Ra6 R5f6 35.Bf2 This shows that I was giving up hope... 35...Nd8 36.Ra8 Nf7 37.Rxf8+ with a sad draw offer which was happily accepted in the game [/variation/38709639] Leko (2749) -Kramnik (2754) Monte Carlo 2005. �}) 30... Bxf2 31. Bxf2 Nf6 $6 (31... Kh7 $5 32. Bh4 $5) 32. Ng3 $1 {The point!} Rg5 33. Qxg6 Rxg6 {And now, the final touch.} 34. h4 $1 {This is a very bad endgame with Black's misplaced pieces.} *

