1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Nd7 {This line has a completely different spirit compared to all the Classical Chigorin variations we have just discussed. In a way, Black´s main idea is to set up a possible Benoni-type transformation of structure with ...exd4. Let's not forget about the fact that here, Black's bishop is still on c8! I have often highlighted the main drawback of the Spanish/Benoni structures when that bishop gets blocked out of the game with eventual d4-d5. Always the nuances!} 12. d5 $1 {My favorite reaction. It does not allow Black to go for his spirit! This is a positional system, but what attracted my attention right from the beginning is that White's positional grip in the old main line after 13.Nbd2 f5 is based on a beautiful little tactical idea. Once I saw that, I knew deep inside that this would be love for eternity!} Nb6 13. Nbd2 (13. g4 $2 {One of those rare strategical mistakes from the legendary Bobby Fischer! This is when you are still a bit young, at the same time, already very strong and a tiny bit too ambitious! In general, the idea is impressive; White stops ...f7-f5 and is planning Nbd2-f1-g3 with great prospects. The only problem is that on the opposite side sits another legend Paul Keres...} h5 $1 {Keres punishes it immediately!} 14. Nh2 hxg4 15. hxg4 Bg5 {Suddenly, White's position is in strategic ruins!} 16. Nd2 g6 17. Ndf3 Bxc1 18. Qxc1 Kg7 {Obviously, Black is going to attack White on the kingside! White's idea has heavily backfired.} 19. Qg5 {Damage control, but the endgame is also bad...} Nb7 20. Qxd8 Rxd8 21. a4 bxa4 22. Bxa4 Nxa4 23. Rxa4 Bd7 24. Ra2 c4 $1 25. Nd2 Bb5 {happened in the game [/variation/38709634] Fischer-Keres Curacao Candidates 1962. � 19...Qxg5! was even stronger: 20.Nxg5 Nac4 hitting b2, and White has problems after 21.b3?! Na3! 22.Bd3? c4-+ due to the fork on c2, or 21.Rab1 Bd7 $17 where g4 and b2 are weak and Black has a clear plan on the queenside.}) 13... f5 {The move that Bobby wanted to stop. But objectively this leads to a lovely position for White, very much according to my liking. Since then, Black has also tried two different concepts to combat White's setup:} (13... g6 $5 {Black's principal possibility, preparing ...f7-f5. A)} 14. Nf1 $1 {The computer likes this!} f5 15. Bh6 Rf7 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Ng3 $1 {I have known this for over a decade, but during the 9 AM game, I just realized that I could hardly even know my name... From the stress of needing to wake up so early, I was basically unable to sleep the whole night. That is the real problem...} Kh8 $5 {I encourage everyone to check these lines carefully because the position is very sharp!} 18. a4 $1 {Opening up a new front should guarantee White the upper hand in this wild position. 17...e4 18.Bxe4!! is still a novelty! 18...fxe4 19.Rxe4 $16 The lines continue, but it is very promising for White. The black king is exposed. B) 14.b4 Nb7! This has been an important improvement and had been holding on nicely for Black over a decade already. ( 14...cxb4 15.cxb4 Nac4 16.Nxc4 Nxc4 17.Bb3 and Vishy improved on my game [/variation/38709636] Leko-Mamedyarov Tal Memorial 2006. � 17...Nb6?! 18.Be3 Bd7 19.Rc1 Rc8 20.Rxc8 Bxc8 21.Qc2 Bd7 22.Rc1 $16 happened in the game [/variation/38709635] Anand,V (2779)-Carlsen,M (2690) Morelia/Linares 2007 is El Classico! � 15.Nf1 f5 with total chaos in the game [/variation/38709637] Leko (2699)-Tari (2597) Italian League 2017. � I would like to ask for forgiveness for playing so badly, but at 9 AM, my head is simply not working...}) (13... Bd7 {has been played by Caruana, for example. Clearly, this whole Chigorin is not his main weapon, but sometimes, from time to time, he used it as a surprise weapon against weaker opponents. I think the following plan is very strong against 13...Bd7.} 14. b3 $1 {I am always tempted to cut those knights out of the game when I have the chance!} c4 15. b4 Nb7 {The reason why Black does not mind it is that he counts on a ...a6-a5 break. White seems to be just a tempo short to achieve the desired stability... A)} 16. a3 a5 17. Rb1 {trying to hold on to the structure does not work.} axb4 18. axb4 Na4 {with concrete problems. 18...Ra2 is also annoying. B) 16.Nf1! Very important strategical idea! 16...a5 but the reality is that there is no need to look for stability! 17.a3 axb4 18.cxb4 ...because in fact the spoiled structure with cxb4 is very good for White! The most important thing is that there is no counterplay on the queenside; the passed c-pawn goes nowhere, but White's kingside attack will slowly build up. White also has another idea, namely the positional plan of transferring one of the knights to c3! A very important strategic idea to know! 18...Na4 19.Ng3 The typical idea of regrouping the horrible b7-knight to f7 is probably the only way to play with Black. 19...Qe8 20.Be3 f6 21.Nd2! Nd8 22.Nb1!! Again, this amazing move! One should remember this idea because the c3-square in such structures is a key square for White's knight. Please remember my comment [/variation/38040050/#/16/b/0.3] from the Leko-Hansen game! 22...Nf7 23.Bxa4! Giving up the light-squared bishop is never easy, but here we know why! 23...Rxa4 24.Nc3 Ra8 25.Qb1 $16 Very nice move! Keeps an eye on f5, prepares the a3-a4 break, and, just in case, even keeps the 2nd rank open for the rook if needed (Re2-a2 shift).}) 14. exf5 Bxf5 (14... Nxd5 $2 {is bad for many reasons.} 15. Nc4 $1 {The most stylish.} Nf6 16. Nxa5 Qxa5 17. g4 $1 Bb7 18. g5 Nd7 19. Nh4 {and Black will be crushed.}) 15. Bxf5 Rxf5 16. Ne4 {Here we are! I am a big lover of the e4-knight, but the big question is whether White will be able to protect the weak d5-pawn. If the answer is yes, then we obviously have hit the jackpot!} Qe8 {A multi-purpose move, but it does not change anything on the evaluation of the line. White is simply better.} (16... Qd7 {If someone is not familiar with the line, then please take time to understand what White's beautiful idea could be!} 17. b3 $3 {This is the lovely little tactic that made me instantly fall in love with the system! Those days, it was not like we opened engines and immediately got the right answer...} Raf8 {I even today feel quite some anger that I did let this golden opportunity slip vs. Kramnik. I understand that if it had not been a blindfold game, Kramnik would not have played this line, but finally, thanks to the blindfold format, he went on to defend it without too much trouble. Looking back, I was very angry at myself for relaxing too much instead of looking for ways to make the most of my chance! ( 17...Qb7 18.c4! Yes, thanks to this trick we can defend our only weakness! 18...bxc4? 19.Bd2 suddenly traps the knight!) A)} 18. Nfg5 $5 {Already during the game, my intuition tempted me for this move, but I tried to control myself and decided to play more routinely... Why is it such a difficult choice? Well, because, in general, I do not fancy the idea of changing my 'good' knight for the 'so-called' bad bishop, but one should also be more alert. After all, only one knight can land on e4 while the 'bad' bishop is actually doing a good job protecting the weak d6-pawn and, as we will see in the game, it has even a potential route to be activated...} Bxg5 19. Bxg5 {Black's position is so much more vulnerable without the e7-bishop!} Nb7 20. Rc1 $16 {was my old move, and I think it is good enough; no need for the unhuman, mysterious 20.Bc1, which is now the top choice of the engines (no comment)} c4 21. Be3 $1 {keeps Black under check with his knight! B) 18.Nh2 Qd8 (A fresh example is 18...c4 19.Be3 Bd8 20.Re2 Nb7 21.Nf1 Qc8 22.Rb2 R5f7 23.Nfg3 $16 as in the game [/variation/38709638] Harikrishna, P (2725)-Svidler, P (2701) Struga 2021. �) 19.Nf1! Clever regrouping! 19...Qa8 20.Ne3 Rf4 21.f3 I was enjoying myself, as we will see little more than I should have... 21...Qe8 22.Bd2 Qg6 23.c4 Nb7 24.Kh1 b4! A clever idea. Black is clearly much worse, but let's not forget that this was a rapid blindfold game, so having a clear strategy is very important! Black closes down the queenside and gives up the a-file but is ready to transfer the knights to the kingside. B1) 25.a3 a5 26.Rf1!? is interesting, but I played 26.Ng4 R4f5 27.Be3 I am making logical moves. 27...Nd7 28.Re2 h5 29.Ngf2 Bh4! This is the active route I mentioned for Black's bishop! 30.Nd3?! This logical move is in the wrong direction! I should have understood that, in fact, I should be happy trading this knight for the bishop! ( 30.Qd3! gave a big advantage. 30...Bxf2 31.Bxf2 Nf6?! 32.Ng3! Rg5 33.Qxg6 Rxg6 34.h4! and this is a very bad endgame with Black's misplaced pieces.) 30...Nf6 Black succeeds with his plan! Now 31.Nd2!! was keeping the advantage according to the engine, but this is another planet... 31.Bg1 Nxe4 32.Rxe4 Bg3! Black has enough counterplay and is now fine. 33.axb4 axb4 34.Ra6 R5f6 35.Bf2 This shows that I was giving up hope... 35...Nd8 36.Ra8 Nf7 37.Rxf8+ with a sad draw offer which was happily accepted in the game [/variation/38709639] Leko (2749) -Kramnik (2754) Monte Carlo 2005. � B2) The computer highlights a powerful move here for White with 25.Rf1!! with the idea to meet 25...Nd7 with the stunning 26.g4!! Incredible that in order to make the most out of White's powerful knight on e4, White needs this g2-g4 idea. Suddenly, everything is in perfect harmony! Restricting Black's pieces is the key. Now, all the squares in Black's camp will be overloaded... If 26...Nf6 what should White do? 27.Ng3! No trade! After 26...Nd8 , not 27.Nf5 R4xf5 28.gxf5 Qxf5 and Black's knights will awake, but 27.Ng2! R4f7 , and now we see Black's problems. The pieces are cramped! 28.Qe2 Nf6 29.Ng5+- or 28...h6 29.h4! Nf6 30.Ng3! Black is in a horrible situation.}) 17. Nfg5 $1 {I learned my lesson to be open-minded!} Nb7 (17... Bxg5 {is better; one year later, I even had a game for it.} 18. Bxg5 Qg6 19. Qg4 {when Black can't take} Nxd5 $2 {due to} 20. Rad1 {, so 19...Nb7 20.Rad1 Qf7 21.b3! and now 21...Nxd5? fails to 22.Rxd5! Rxg5 23.Qxg5 Qxd5 24.Nf6+ and White wins. Instead, 21...Rf8 happened in an official blitz game, Leko-Mamedyarov Tal Memorial Blitz 2006, which was not recorded, so it is not in the database! How should White treat this position? A) 22.c4!! It could have been a perfect game! 22...bxc4 23.bxc4 Nxc4 24.Nf6+!! gxf6 25.Bc1+ Qg6 26.Qxc4+- This is completely winning according to engines because the rook on f5 is kinda trapped and the queenside is falling apart. Also, White even has Rd3-g3 ideas as well. B) 22.Bc1 Nxd5 23.Qg3 Nf6 24.Nxd6 Nxd6 25.Rxd6 Nh5 26.Qg4 Rxf2 27.Be3 Rxa2 28.Rd7 Now Black is ok, but we had very little time, and things escalated... 28...Qg6 29.Bxc5 Re8 30.Rxe5 Boom! 30...Rxg2+? Hallucination under tension. I had been in Shakhriyar's shoes, now I was the lucky one... 31.Kxg2 Qc6+ 32.Red5 and Black resigned. He had 30...Rxe5 31.Rd8+ Re8 Clearly, missing that this was possible. ( 31...Kf7? 32.Rf8 ) 32.Qxg6 hxg6 33.Rxe8+ Kh7 and Black should hold.}) 18. Ne6 {Now, this is just very bad for Black.} Qf7 19. b4 $5 {I would hate to give up the c4-square just like this, but I was tempted by seeing a forced variation.} (19. g4 $5 Qg6 20. Ng3 Rf7 21. f4 {is an interesting computer suggestion. Black's knights are terrible.}) 19... cxb4 20. cxb4 Nd8 21. Be3 Nc4 (21... Nxd5 22. Qxd5 {with a tempo on the a8-rook.}) 22. Nc7 {This is what I spotted when opting for 19.b4 .} Nxe3 (22... Rc8 23. Nxa6 {and a4 is coming.}) 23. Rxe3 Ra7 24. Rc1 {Black is completely paralyzed. I went on to win the game smoothly and got incredible applause from the 800 home crowd spectators in the Miskolc National Theater! The result was still 3:1 for Mickey, but I could feel the wind of change!!} h6 25. Rec3 Qg6 26. Rg3 Qf7 27. Rgc3 Qg6 28. Qe2 Bg5 29. R1c2 Rf4 30. f3 Rf8 31. Qf2 Rb7 32. Qg3 Kh7 33. Qg4 Rb6 34. Kh1 Rf4 35. Qd7 Rxe4 36. fxe4 Qxe4 37. Qg4 Bf4 38. Rc1 Rb7 39. a3 Qd4 40. Qf5+ Kg8 41. Qc8 Bxc1 42. Qxd8+ Kh7 43. Rxc1 Qf4 44. Rg1 1-0

